| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Outsider (Native) |
| **Hit Dice** | 9d8+36 (76 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +1 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 21 (–1 size, +1 Dex, +11 natural), touch 10, flat-footed 20 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +9/+19 |
| **Attack** | Warhammer +15 melee (2d6+9/×3) |
| **Full Attack** | Warhammer +15/+10 melee (2d6+9/×3) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./10 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Passage strike, death-touch, gate command |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 120 ft., damage reduction 10/magic, immunity to death effects, spell resistance 19, gate-bound, elemental resonance (Earth/Fire) |
| **Saves** | Fort +10, Ref +7, Will +10 |
| **Abilities** | Str 23, Dex 13, Con 19, Int 14, Wis 18, Cha 15 |
| **Skills** | Diplomacy +14, Intimidate +14, Knowledge (history) +14, Knowledge (religion) +14, Listen +16, Sense Motive +16, Spot +16, Survival +16 |
| **Feats** | Cleave, Improved Sunder, Power Attack, Weapon Focus (warhammer) |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) / Lady of Fire (Fire) — dual affinity; stone shaped by heat, the forge-gate, the threshold between states |
| **Environment** | Great River (river-gates, bridge-arches, canal locks, and portals along the Great River and its major tributaries — always at a point of transition, where water passes from one state or region to another); most commonly encountered at Eruskan-maintained river-gates |
| **Organization** | Solitary (always) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 7 |
| **Treasure** | None (but charun-guarded gates often contain offerings left by Eruskan travelers — coins, wine, worked metal) |
| **Alignment** | Always lawful neutral |
| **Advancement** | 10–18 HD (Large); 19–27 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A charun does not start fights. It finishes them. A charun is a guardian of transitions — river-gates, bridge-arches, canal locks — and it allows passage to those who approach with respect and proper intent. Travelers who pay the traditional toll (an offering of wine or worked metal left at the gate’s base) pass unmolested. Travelers who attempt to pass without acknowledgment are warned once: the charun steps into view, raises its hammer, and waits. Most intelligent creatures take the hint.

Those who press forward despite the warning face a methodical, devastating combatant. A charun opens with passage strike — a blow specifically designed to drive intruders back from the threshold it guards. It uses its gate command ability to seal the passage behind or ahead of its targets, trapping them in the gate’s kill zone. In sustained combat, a charun fights with simple, crushing efficiency: Power Attack combined with its massive Strength bonus produces hits that shatter shields and break bones.

A charun does not pursue creatures that retreat from its gate. The moment an intruder withdraws beyond the threshold boundary, the charun stops, returns to its position, and resumes its vigil. It has no ego investment in the fight. It was made to guard the gate, and when the gate is no longer threatened, it stops.

Against Dómnathar, a charun fights with cold, sustained intensity. It recognises the void-signature and treats any Deceiver that approaches its gate as an existential threat to the passage it protects. A charun will pursue a fleeing Deceiver up to 1 mile from its gate — the only exception to its non-pursuit rule.

### Special Abilities

**Passage Strike (Su):** A charun’s warhammer deals an additional 2d6 force damage against any creature that is currently within or attempting to pass through the gate, bridge, or passage the charun guards. This damage applies only within the charun’s threshold zone — a 30-foot radius centered on the gate or passage. Outside this zone, the charun’s hammer deals normal damage.

**Death-Touch (Su):** Once per day, a charun can deliver a death-touch as a melee touch attack. A creature touched must succeed on a Fortitude save (DC 18) or die instantly. This is a death effect. The save DC is Charisma-based. The death-touch is not an attack — it is a judgment. A charun uses this ability only against creatures that have committed acts of desecration at its gate (destroying the gate’s stonework, murdering a traveler within the threshold zone, or attempting to corrupt the passage with Dómnathar magic). A charun has never been recorded using death-touch against a creature that simply attempted to pass without paying toll.

**Gate Command (Su):** A charun has supernatural control over the physical passage it guards. As a standard action, it can seal a gate (as wall of stone, CL 9th), open a sealed passage, raise or lower water levels within a canal lock by up to 10 feet, or cause a bridge to become impassable (the stones shift, creating difficult terrain). These effects last as long as the charun concentrates (free action) plus 1d4 rounds. This ability only functions within 100 feet of the charun’s bonded gate.

**Gate-Bound (Ex):** A charun is permanently bonded to a specific gate, bridge, or passage. It cannot voluntarily move more than 1 mile from its gate (except when pursuing Dómnathar). If forcibly moved beyond this range, it becomes weakened (–4 Strength, –4 Constitution) until it returns. A charun’s gate is always a point of physical transition — a place where water, road, or travelers pass from one region, state, or condition to another. When a charun’s gate is destroyed, the charun fades over 1d6 months unless it bonds to a new gate within that time.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a charun registers as a heavy, dual-element presence — stone and heat, the feeling of standing near a forge built into a mountainside. The resonance is calm, immense, and entirely non-threatening as long as the detecting Kin is behaving respectfully. Kin who approach a charun-guarded gate with hostile intent report that the resonance shifts: the warmth becomes oppressive, the stone-weight presses down, and the sensation resembles “standing under a hammer that hasn’t fallen yet.”

Eruskan river-travelers recognise charun resonance instinctively — it is one of the first things Eruskan children learn about river-travel: the heavy, warm feeling at the gate means the guardian is awake and watching, and you should make your offering before you pass.

### Society

Charun are solitary guardians — native Oreka spirits that manifest at points of transition along the Great River and its tributaries. They are not summoned, constructed, or born. They appear at gates, bridges, and locks when the place itself reaches a threshold of significance — enough traffic, enough history, enough importance to generate a guardian spirit. The process takes decades and is not fully understood by any Kin culture, though Eruskan scholars have studied it extensively.

The Eruskan relationship with charun defines Eruskan river-culture. Eruskan civilization is built along the Great River, and the river-gates that control navigation, trade, and water flow are the infrastructure on which Eruskan commerce depends. Charun guard these gates. The partnership is ancient and entirely practical: the Eruskan maintain the physical gate-structures, and the charun protect them from interference, theft, and sabotage.

Eruskan culture has formalised the relationship through elaborate protocols. Offerings are standardised (a splash of wine on the gatestone, or a copper coin placed in the offering-niche — both forms date back centuries). Eruskan merchants speak to charun as they would address a respected elder: formally, briefly, and with an offering in hand. The charun do not respond verbally to routine passage — they step aside, the gate opens, and the barge passes through. Conversation happens only when something is wrong: an unusual cargo, a suspicious passenger, or a question about conditions downriver. Charun remember everything they witness at their gates, and an Eruskan harbormaster who needs information about a specific barge’s passage will visit the nearest charun and ask.

Other Kin cultures encounter charun less frequently. Pekakarlik Dwarves who trade along the Great River have adopted the Eruskan offering protocol and are accepted at charun gates without incident. Halfling river-traders do the same. Mytroan caravans that cross the river at charun-guarded bridges sometimes clash with the guardians through ignorance of the protocols — a Mytroan warrior who approaches a bridge at speed without stopping to offer is likely to meet the flat of a warhammer before anyone can explain the custom.

### Lore

Characters with ranks in Knowledge (the planes) can learn the following about charun.

**DC 17:** Charun are large, stone-skinned guardians found at river-gates and bridges along the Great River. They allow respectful passage and attack those who attempt to force their way through. Offerings of wine or worked metal are the traditional toll.

**DC 22:** Charun are native Oreka spirits that manifest spontaneously at points of significant transition. They are bonded to their specific gate and cannot move far from it. They possess a death-touch reserved for desecrators. Eruskan culture has an elaborate, centuries-old protocol for interacting with them.

**DC 27:** Charun recognise and aggressively pursue Dómnathar — the only exception to their non-pursuit behavior. They remember everything that passes their gate and can serve as witnesses to events. Their Kin-sense resonance shifts to become oppressive when they detect hostile intent. When a charun’s gate is destroyed, the spirit fades within months unless bonded to a new gate.

# CHERUFE

The caldera glows. Not from below — from across, from the thing that sits in the centre of the lava lake like a man sitting in a bath. It is made of stone. It is on fire. The stone is not burning — the fire is coming from inside, pouring through cracks in a body of black basalt that has the approximate shape of a giant, if a giant were designed by someone who thought “humanoid” was a loose suggestion rather than a requirement. Its eyes are magma. When it moves, the caldera trembles.

**Huge Elemental (Fire, Earth)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Huge Elemental (Fire, Earth) |
| **Hit Dice** | 12d8+60 (114 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +0 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), burrow 20 ft. (through stone or magma only) |
| **Armor Class** | 24 (–2 size, +16 natural), touch 8, flat-footed 24 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +9/+25 |
| **Attack** | Slam +15 melee (2d8+8 plus 2d6 fire) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 slams +15 melee (2d8+8 plus 2d6 fire) |
| **Space/Reach** | 15 ft./15 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Magma hurl, caldera eruption, burn |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 120 ft., damage reduction 10/—, immunity to fire, vulnerability to cold, elemental traits, magma body, elemental resonance (Fire/Earth) |
| **Saves** | Fort +13, Ref +4, Will +6 |
| **Abilities** | Str 27, Dex 10, Con 21, Int 8, Wis 14, Cha 11 |
| **Skills** | Listen +12, Spot +12, Survival +12 |
| **Feats** | Awesome Blow, Cleave, Great Cleave, Improved Bull Rush, Power Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of Fire (Fire) / Lord of Stone (Earth) — dual affinity, Fire dominant; the cherufe is molten earth, the place where the Lady of Fire’s domain and the Lord of Stone’s domain merge |
| **Environment** | Scorchspires (active calderas, magma chambers, volcanic vent systems, and the deep volcanic core of the Scorchspire mountain range) |
| **Organization** | Solitary |
| **Challenge Rating** | 9 |
| **Treasure** | None standard (but cherufe lairs in calderas may contain natural deposits of embersteel, fire-opals, and volcanic glass worth 2d6 × 1,000 gp to a Rarozhki smith) |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 13–18 HD (Huge); 19–24 HD (Gargantuan) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A cherufe is a territorial elemental that fights with the slow, overwhelming force of a geological event. It does not charge, rush, or use rapid tactics. It walks toward threats, hits them with fists of molten stone, and continues walking. Anything that survives the first hit gets hit again. This simplicity is not stupidity — the cherufe is playing to its strengths. Its damage reduction, massive hit points, and fire damage on every strike mean that sustained melee favors it overwhelmingly.

A cherufe opens combat with magma hurl against distant targets — lobbing balls of molten stone at ranges where its opponents feel safe. As it closes, it uses its burn ability to punish melee attackers and its Awesome Blow feat to hurl creatures into the caldera walls (or, ideally, into the lava lake). Against groups, it uses caldera eruption to reshape the battlefield, cutting off escape routes and forcing enemies toward hazards.

A cherufe’s greatest weakness is cold. Cold-based attacks bypass its damage reduction and deal 50% additional damage. A cherufe that takes significant cold damage retreats into the volcanic core, burrowing through stone to a depth where no attacker can follow. It does not emerge until it has healed, which can take days.

Cherufe do not leave their volcanic home. They are bound to the caldera and its magma system as thoroughly as a charun is bound to its gate. A cherufe that is somehow forced out of a volcanic area weakens rapidly (–2 Constitution per hour) and eventually solidifies into inert basalt.

### Special Abilities

**Magma Hurl (Ex):** As a standard action, a cherufe can tear a chunk of molten stone from its own body or the surrounding caldera and hurl it at a target within 120 feet. This is a ranged attack (+7 ranged, –2 size) that deals 3d6 bludgeoning damage plus 3d6 fire damage. The molten stone splash deals 1d6 fire damage to all creatures within 5 feet of the impact point (Reflex DC 21 negates splash). The save DC is Strength-based.

**Caldera Eruption (Su):** Once per day, a cherufe can cause a localized volcanic eruption within a 30-foot radius centered on any point within 60 feet. The ground in the area cracks, releasing jets of steam and magma. All creatures in the area take 6d6 fire damage (Reflex DC 21 half) and the area becomes difficult terrain filled with fissures, steam vents, and pools of magma that deal 2d6 fire damage per round to any creature that enters or begins its turn in them. The terrain effect lasts for 1d4+1 minutes. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Burn (Ex):** A creature struck by a cherufe’s slam attack must succeed on a DC 21 Reflex save or catch fire. Burning creatures take 2d6 fire damage per round until they spend a full-round action to extinguish the flames. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Magma Body (Ex):** A cherufe’s body is composed of semi-molten basalt. Any creature that strikes a cherufe with a natural weapon or unarmed attack takes 2d6 fire damage. Metal weapons that strike the cherufe must succeed on a DC 21 Fortitude save or lose 1 point of hardness as the heat softens the metal. The save DC is Constitution-based. Magic weapons receive their enhancement bonus on this save.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a cherufe registers as a massive, overwhelming fire-earth presence — the Lady of Fire’s domain and the Lord of Stone’s domain fused into a single, molten signature that radiates heat on a metaphysical level. Kin within 120 ft. detect the cherufe automatically and experience the resonance as physical warmth — not painful, but unmistakable, like standing next to a forge the size of a house. At 30 ft., the resonance becomes oppressive: Kin describe it as “being inside the mountain’s heartbeat.”

Rarozhki Dwarves, who are more fire-attuned than any other Kin culture, experience cherufe resonance differently — as comfort rather than oppression. A Rarozhki smith standing before a cherufe feels the resonance as a deep, familiar warmth that resonates with their own elemental identity. This affinity is why Rarozhki communities have developed the most functional relationship with cherufe of any Kin culture.

### Society

Cherufe are solitary elementals — living embodiments of the volcanic core of the Scorchspires, as much a feature of the landscape as the calderas they inhabit. Each cherufe claims a specific caldera or magma chamber as its territory and does not leave it willingly. They are not social, not communicative, and not particularly intelligent — their awareness extends primarily to their territory, their heat, and threats to both.

Rarozhki Dwarves have the closest relationship with cherufe. The Rarozhki civilization is built in and around the Scorchspires, and Rarozhki forges draw heat from the same volcanic systems that sustain cherufe. This creates an ecological overlap that could have produced constant conflict but instead produced a cautious, mutually tolerant coexistence. Rarozhki smiths who work in calderas that contain cherufe follow strict protocols: do not approach the cherufe directly, do not draw more heat from the magma than necessary, and leave offerings of worked metal at the caldera’s edge (the cherufe absorbs metal offerings into its body, which Rarozhki metallurgists believe improves the quality of the volcanic minerals deposited in the area).

The Rarozhki word for cherufe is *gorvathi* — “caldera-walker” — and Rarozhki children learn to identify cherufe resonance before they learn to identify their own parents’ resonance. This is not affection; it is survival. A Rarozhki child who cannot feel a cherufe’s approach is a child who will walk into a caldera and not walk out.

Taraf-Imro warriors in the Scorchspire foothills know of cherufe but do not enter their calderas. The Taraf-Imro consider cherufe to be the Lady of Fire’s personal guardians and treat them with the same deference they show the Emberfang Wyrms — which is to say, total avoidance unless absolutely necessary.

Eruskan and Mytroan cultures have little direct experience with cherufe, as neither people frequents the deep Scorchspires. Eruskan scholars who have studied cherufe from a distance classify them as “living volcanic events” — geological phenomena that happen to be mobile and territorial.

### Lore

Characters with ranks in Knowledge (the planes) can learn the following about cherufe.

**DC 14:** Cherufe are enormous fire-and-stone elementals found in the active calderas of the Scorchspires. They are immune to fire, devastatingly strong, and capable of hurling molten stone.

**DC 19:** Cherufe cannot survive outside volcanic environments — they weaken and eventually solidify into inert basalt. Their bodies damage weapons that strike them and burn creatures that touch them. Cold is their primary vulnerability and bypasses their significant damage reduction.

**DC 24:** Cherufe are sacred to the Rarozhki Dwarves, who maintain coexistence protocols in shared calderas. Cherufe resonance is overwhelming at close range — Rarozhki experience it as comfort while other Kin experience it as oppressive heat. They absorb offerings of worked metal into their bodies. Their calderas often contain natural deposits of embersteel and fire-opals.

# CHIMERA

Three heads. That is the first thing you register — three heads on a body that should not be able to support even one of them. The lion’s head roars. The goat’s head screams. The dragon’s head, dark-scaled and smouldering, simply opens its mouth and breathes fire across the rocks where you were standing a moment ago. The body is massive, a fusion of lion and goat with bat-wings spreading wide enough to blot out the pass behind it. It does not look like something that was designed. It looks like something that was assembled in anger and then let loose.

**Large Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 9d10+27 (76 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +1 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), fly 50 ft. (poor) |
| **Armor Class** | 19 (–1 size, +1 Dex, +9 natural), touch 10, flat-footed 18 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +9/+17 |
| **Attack** | Bite +12 melee (2d6+4) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +12 melee (2d6+4) and bite +12 melee (1d8+4) and gore +12 melee (1d8+4) and 2 claws +10 melee (1d6+2) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Breath weapon |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, scent, elemental resonance (Fire/Earth/Air) |
| **Saves** | Fort +9, Ref +7, Will +6 |
| **Abilities** | Str 19, Dex 13, Con 17, Int 4, Wis 13, Cha 10 |
| **Skills** | Hide +4 (+8 in rocky terrain), Listen +9, Spot +9 |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Hover, Iron Will, Multiattack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of Fire (Fire) dominant, with traces of Lord of Stone (Earth) and Youngest Brother (Air) — a creature of three natures, none fully integrated |
| **Environment** | Steppe-Mountain Border (the rocky highlands where the Eternal Steppe meets the Giant’s Teeth foothills; secondary presence in the Scorchspire foothills and the dry ridgelines between the Kinsweave and the Infinite Desert) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pride (2–4), or flight (5–8) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 7 |
| **Treasure** | Standard |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic evil |
| **Advancement** | 10–13 HD (Large); 14–27 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +2 |

### Combat

A chimera is chaos with wings. Its three heads operate semi-independently — each reacting to threats from its own direction, each attacking with its own rhythm — which makes the creature devastatingly effective in melee but incapable of coordinated tactics. A chimera does not plan. It charges the nearest enemy, attacks with everything it has, and keeps attacking until the target stops moving or the chimera decides to eat something else.

In combat, a chimera opens with its breath weapon from the air (if flying) or at close range (if on the ground), then closes to full attack — lion bite, goat gore, dragon bite, and claw attacks in a whirlwind of violence. Against multiple opponents, each head tends to fixate on a different target, which means a chimera fighting a group distributes its damage rather than focusing fire. This is a disadvantage against disciplined defenders but an advantage against scattered or panicking enemies.

A chimera’s flying speed is poor, and it cannot hover for more than a round without landing. It uses flight primarily for repositioning — swooping to a new angle of attack or escaping to a cliff-perch to use its breath weapon from safety. A chimera that is grounded fights with feral aggression and does not retreat unless reduced to one-quarter hit points.

Chimera prides are rare and terrifying. When multiple chimeras attack, they do not coordinate — they simply attack the same general area simultaneously, creating overlapping kill zones of fire, claws, and trampling.

### Special Abilities

**Breath Weapon (Su):** The dragon head breathes a 20-foot cone of fire, dealing 3d8 fire damage (Reflex DC 17 half). Usable every 1d4 rounds. The save DC is Constitution-based. The fire smells of sulphur and animal musk — a combination that Mytroan scouts find distinctively chimera and can identify at 200 yards downwind.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a chimera registers as a discordant, layered signature — three elemental threads that do not harmonise. The Fire signature (from the dragon head) dominates, but beneath it are traces of Earth (the lion’s predatory solidity) and Air (the goat’s high-altitude adaptation and the wings). The resonance feels unstable, like three instruments playing different songs simultaneously. Kin within 60 ft. detect the chimera automatically, and the dissonance is unpleasant — not painful, but grating, like a sound that sets teeth on edge.

Scholars debate whether chimeras are natural creatures or the products of ancient magical experimentation. The elemental dissonance supports the latter theory — no creature born of Oreka’s natural elemental fabric should carry three unintegrated affinities. Rarozhki alchemists who have examined chimera remains believe the species was created during the Age of Giants, possibly as guardian beasts that outlived their purpose and went feral.

### Society

Chimeras have no society. They are territorial predators that claim rocky highlands and attack everything that enters their range that looks edible — which, for a chimera, is most things.

Their placement at the steppe-mountain border puts them in direct conflict with both Mytroan steppe-riders and the mountain-dwelling peoples of the Giant’s Teeth. Mytroan herding communities consider chimeras the worst aerial threat on the steppe — worse than griffons (which can be driven off) and worse than rocs (which are rare). A chimera that discovers a herd of horses or cattle will return to it nightly until the herd is destroyed or relocated, and its fire breath makes corrals and wooden fencing useless as protection.

Mytroan bands deal with chimeras through organised hunts — a coordinated effort involving mounted archers, fire-resistant hide shields, and the crucial tactic of targeting the goat head first. Mytroan scouts have observed that destroying or severely injuring the goat head disrupts the chimera’s coordination; the remaining two heads fight less effectively when the middle head is gone. This technique is passed down in Mytroan hunting-songs.

Taraf-Imro warriors hunt chimeras for sport and glory. A chimera kill is considered a significant achievement — the three-headed beast requires a warrior to fight three opponents simultaneously, which the Taraf-Imro regard as the purest test of combat awareness. Taraf-Imro tradition demands that the hunter take one trophy from each head: a lion’s tooth, a goat horn, and a dragon scale, worn together as a triple-kill necklace.

Rarozhki Dwarves in the Scorchspire foothills tolerate chimera prides at a distance because the creatures keep other aerial predators out of their territory. A chimera flight that has claimed a ridge effectively clears it of griffons, hieracosphinxes, and other winged threats, which Rarozhki surface-miners consider a net benefit as long as the chimeras stay on the ridge.

### Lore

Characters with ranks in Knowledge (arcana) can learn the following about chimeras.

**DC 17:** Chimeras are three-headed flying beasts that breathe fire. They are aggressive, territorial, and attack anything that enters their domain. Each head attacks independently.

**DC 22:** The goat head appears to coordinate the other two — injuring or destroying it reduces the chimera’s combat effectiveness. Chimeras are possibly artificial creatures from the Age of Giants, as their elemental signature carries three unintegrated affinities. They will repeatedly attack the same herd until it is destroyed.

**DC 27:** Mytroan hunting doctrine targets the goat head first to disrupt coordination. Taraf-Imro warriors take triple-kill trophies from all three heads. Rarozhki alchemists believe chimeras were created as Giant-era guardian beasts. Their Kin-sense resonance is uniquely discordant — three elemental signatures that never harmonise.

# CHUUL

It rises from the shallows like a nightmare designed by committee — lobster pincers the size of shields, a segmented carapace slick with brine, and a mass of writhing tentacles where its mouth should be. Its eyes, set on short stalks, swivel independently, tracking two different targets at once. It does not look like it belongs in this water. It does not look like it belongs anywhere. It looks like something that crawled out of a place that has different rules about what shapes are acceptable.

**Large Aberration (Aquatic)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Aberration (Aquatic) |
| **Hit Dice** | 11d8+44 (93 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +7 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), swim 20 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 22 (–1 size, +3 Dex, +10 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 19 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +8/+17 |
| **Attack** | Claw +12 melee (2d6+5) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 claws +12 melee (2d6+5) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Constrict 3d6+5, improved grab, paralytic tentacles |
| **Special Qualities** | Amphibious, darkvision 60 ft., immunity to poison, breach resonance |
| **Saves** | Fort +7, Ref +6, Will +9 |
| **Abilities** | Str 20, Dex 16, Con 18, Int 10, Wis 14, Cha 5 |
| **Skills** | Hide +13, Listen +11, Spot +11, Swim +13 |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Blind-Fight, Combat Reflexes, Improved Initiative |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — chuuls are alien to Oreka’s elemental framework; see Breach Resonance |
| **Environment** | Apelian Sea (coastal shallows, tidal caves, submerged ruins along the Apelian basin); secondary presence in Tidebloom Reach (brackish tidal pools, flooded Giant ruins at Hillmeet and Foxfen) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or pack (2–5) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 7 |
| **Treasure** | 1/10th coins; 50% goods; 50% items |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic evil |
| **Advancement** | 12–16 HD (Large); 17–33 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A chuul hunts from water. It lurks in shallows or tidal pools — its carapace blending with rock and coral — and waits for prey to approach the waterline. When a creature enters reach, the chuul explodes from concealment, grabbing with both pincers and dragging the target into the water.

A chuul’s combat sequence is methodical: grab with claws, constrict to immobilise, then transfer the pinned creature to its paralytic tentacles. Once paralysed, the victim is dragged underwater and consumed at the chuul’s leisure. Against a group, a chuul grabs one target and retreats into the water with it, relying on depth and darkness to prevent rescue. Multiple chuuls coordinate simple ambushes — one attacks from the front while others approach from the flanks, cutting off retreat from the waterline.

Chuuls are intelligent enough to learn from experience. A chuul that has been driven off by a particular defensive tactic will not fall for it again. Chuuls that have encountered fire-wielding opponents will attack the torch-bearer first. Chuuls that have been hooked by fishermen destroy fishing equipment before attacking the fisher.

### Special Abilities

**Constrict (Ex):** A chuul deals 3d6+5 damage with a successful grapple check.

**Improved Grab (Ex):** To use this ability, a chuul must hit with a claw attack. It can then attempt to start a grapple as a free action without provoking an attack of opportunity. If it wins the grapple check, it establishes a hold and can constrict.

**Paralytic Tentacles (Ex):** A chuul can transfer a grappled creature of Large or smaller size from a claw to its tentacles as a move action. The tentacles grapple with the same strength as the claw. A creature grappled by tentacles must succeed on a DC 19 Fortitude save each round or be paralysed for 6 rounds. The save DC is Constitution-based. While paralysed, the creature can take no actions and is helpless. The paralysis is a toxin — the tentacles exude a neurotoxic mucus that penetrates skin on contact.

**Breach Resonance (Su):** Chuuls are not native to Oreka. They are aberrations — creatures from an alien ecology that entered through the Silence Breach or through older, smaller planar tears. On Kin-sense, a chuul registers as wrong — not void (like the Dómnathar), not distorted (like undead), not static (like goblinoids), but a signal that does not correspond to any category in the Kin-sense framework. Kin describe it as “a chord in a key that doesn’t exist” or “the feeling of hearing a language that uses sounds your mouth cannot make.”

The wrongness is not aggressive — it does not cause pain or fear — but it is deeply unsettling and unmistakable. Kin within 60 ft. detect a chuul automatically and know immediately that whatever they are sensing is not from Oreka. This makes chuuls easy to detect but psychologically disturbing to encounter, particularly for Kin who have never felt a breach-resonance before.

### Society

Chuuls have no culture, no language, and no social structure beyond the pack. They are intelligent predators operating on alien instincts in a world they did not evolve for.

The chuul population in Oreka is concentrated along the Apelian Sea coast, where the deep water and extensive tidal cave systems provide ideal habitat. Smaller populations exist in the Tidebloom Reach, particularly in the flooded Giant ruins at Hillmeet and Foxfen — two devastated settlements from the Deceivers’ War where rising water levels have created an extensive network of submerged chambers.

How chuuls arrived in Oreka is debated. The most widely accepted theory holds that they entered through the Silence Breach along with the Dómnathar host — not as members of the army, but as creatures from the same alien ecology that were swept through the planar tear and deposited in Oreka’s waters. The Dómnathar do not control chuuls and have never claimed them as servitor species. Alternative theories suggest chuuls predate the Breach entirely, having entered through smaller, older planar tears that existed in the deep Apelian basin before the Deceivers’ War.

Halfling fishing communities along the Deepwater Marches coast encounter chuuls regularly and fear them deeply. A chuul in a fishing ground can destroy a community’s livelihood in weeks — the creatures consume fish stocks, attack fishing boats, and prey on fishers at the waterline. Halfling coastal villages maintain “chuul watches” during the warm months (when chuuls are most active), with sentries monitoring the shallows for the telltale breach-resonance that signals a chuul’s presence.

Na’wasua sea-elves are the most experienced chuul fighters in Oreka. Na’wasua divers encounter chuuls in the deeper Apelian waters and have developed specific combat techniques: attacking from below (where the chuul’s ventral carapace is thinnest), targeting the tentacle-mass with slashing weapons to sever the paralytic appendages, and using coordinated teams to separate a chuul from its prey. Na’wasua consider chuuls abominations — alien intrusions into the Lady of the Sea’s domain — and kill them on sight.

### Lore

Characters with ranks in Knowledge (dungeoneering) can learn the following about chuuls.

**DC 17:** Chuuls are large, lobster-like aquatic predators with paralytic tentacles. They lurk in shallows and drag prey underwater. They are intelligent enough to learn from experience and adapt their tactics.

**DC 22:** A chuul transfers grappled victims to its tentacles, which exude a paralytic toxin. They are immune to poison. Chuuls are not native to Oreka — they are alien creatures whose Kin-sense signature registers as fundamentally wrong.

**DC 27:** Chuuls probably entered Oreka through the Silence Breach, though some scholars believe they predate the Deceivers’ War. Na’wasua sea-elves have developed specific anti-chuul techniques targeting the ventral carapace and tentacle-mass. Halfling fishing communities maintain warm-season chuul watches, and the flooded Giant ruins at Hillmeet and Foxfen harbour significant chuul populations.

# CLOAKER

The ceiling is low here, the stone damp, and the shadows beyond the torchlight are thick as wool. You almost walk under it — would have walked under it — except your companion’s torch catches a ripple of movement overhead and something that looked like a hanging sheet of dark leather opens two red eyes and a mouth full of needle-teeth and drops.

**Large Aberration**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Aberration |
| **Hit Dice** | 6d8+18 (45 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +7 |
| **Speed** | 10 ft. (2 squares), fly 40 ft. (average) |
| **Armor Class** | 19 (–1 size, +3 Dex, +7 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 16 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +4/+13 |
| **Attack** | Tail slap +8 melee (1d6+5) |
| **Full Attack** | Tail slap +8 melee (1d6+5) and bite +3 melee (1d4+2) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./10 ft. (5 ft. with bite) |
| **Special Attacks** | Engulf, moan, tail slap |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., shadow shift, breach resonance |
| **Saves** | Fort +5, Ref +5, Will +7 |
| **Abilities** | Str 21, Dex 16, Con 17, Int 14, Wis 15, Cha 15 |
| **Skills** | Hide +12, Listen +13, Move Silently +12, Spot +13 |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Combat Reflexes, Improved Initiative |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — cloakers are alien aberrations; see Breach Resonance |
| **Environment** | Underground (deep cavern systems, Dómnathar tunnel networks, Giant ruin undercrofts); most commonly encountered beneath the Kinsweave and the Infinite Desert, where deep tunnels connect natural caverns to ancient infrastructure |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or mob (3–6) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 5 |
| **Treasure** | Standard |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic neutral |
| **Advancement** | 7–9 HD (Large); 10–18 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A cloaker is an ambush predator that fights from concealment. It hangs from cavern ceilings, flattening its body against the stone until it resembles a natural rock formation or hanging leather — its Hide bonus in dim or dark environments is sufficient to fool most observers. When prey passes beneath, it drops and engulfs.

A cloaker’s primary tactic is engulf: it wraps its body around a victim, biting with its inner mouth while using its tough hide to shield itself from the victim’s allies. Striking an engulfing cloaker risks hitting the creature it has wrapped around, which forces attackers to aim carefully or accept the collateral damage. While engulfing, the cloaker uses its moan to disable other nearby creatures, preventing rescue.

If outnumbered or facing a strong party, a cloaker uses shadow shift to create illusory duplicates of itself, sowing confusion and buying time to engulf its primary target. A cloaker that is badly wounded (one-quarter hit points) releases its victim and flees upward into the cavern ceiling, using its fly speed and the darkness of the upper cavern to escape.

Cloakers are intelligent. They observe parties from concealment before attacking, identify the most vulnerable target (typically the smallest or least-armoured), and time their drop for maximum surprise. A mob of cloakers coordinates ambushes — two drop simultaneously on different targets while a third uses moan to disable the rest of the group.

### Special Abilities

**Engulf (Ex):** A cloaker can engulf a Medium or smaller creature by dropping onto it from above or by making a successful grapple check. An engulfed creature is pinned and takes 1d6+5 bludgeoning damage plus 1d4+2 bite damage per round. Attacks against the cloaker while it is engulfing deal half their damage to the engulfed creature. An engulfed creature can attempt to escape with a grapple check or an Escape Artist check (DC 17).

**Moan (Ex):** A cloaker can produce a subsonic moan as a standard action. All creatures within 60 feet must save or suffer one of the following effects (determined by the cloaker): Unnerve (Will DC 15, –2 penalty on attack and damage rolls), Fear (Will DC 15, panicked for 2 rounds), Nausea (Fortitude DC 15, nauseated for 1d4+1 rounds), or Stupor (Will DC 15, creature can take only a single move action per round for 1d4 rounds). The save DCs are Charisma-based. A cloaker can change the moan’s effect each round as a free action. This is a sonic, mind-affecting ability.

**Shadow Shift (Su):** Three times per day, a cloaker can manipulate shadows to create one of the following effects: Obscure Self (as blur, CL 6th), Shadow Images (as mirror image, CL 6th, creating 1d4+2 duplicates), or Silent Image (as the spell, CL 6th, DC 15). These effects last 6 rounds or until dismissed.

**Breach Resonance (Su):** Like chuuls, cloakers are alien to Oreka’s elemental framework. On Kin-sense, they register as fundamentally wrong — a signal that belongs to no known category. However, a cloaker’s breach-resonance is fainter and harder to detect than a chuul’s, partly because the creature actively suppresses its own signature while hunting. A cloaker hanging motionless on a cavern ceiling requires a DC 22 Kin-sense check to detect. A cloaker in motion or actively moaning is easier to detect (DC 14), as the moan resonates through the Kin-sense field as well as through the air.

### Society

Cloakers are intelligent, solitary predators of the deep underground. They have a rudimentary language (a system of subsonic moans and body-posture signals) and can communicate with each other over distances of several hundred feet through stone, using the same subsonic frequencies as their moan attack.

Cloakers in Oreka are concentrated in two types of environment: natural deep cavern systems (where they are native apex predators) and the fringes of Dómnathar tunnel networks (where they are scavengers and opportunists). The Dómnathar tolerate cloakers in the outer reaches of their tunnels for the same reason they tolerate black puddings — the creatures serve as passive security, ambushing intruders before they reach Deceiver strongholds.

Vestri Dwarves encounter cloakers in deep mining operations and regard them as one of the most dangerous tunnel hazards after Dómnathar agents and black puddings. Vestri mining protocol requires all deep-tunnel teams to include a “roof-watcher” — a team member whose sole responsibility is to scan the ceiling with a hooded lantern before the group advances. Vestri roof-watchers are trained to look for the tell-tale signs: a patch of ceiling that seems too smooth, a shadow that doesn’t move with the lantern, or a faint subsonic hum at the edge of hearing.

Pekakarlik Dwarves who maintain the Giant ruin undercrofts beneath the Infinite Desert encounter cloakers less frequently but in larger groups — the extensive, interconnected tunnel systems beneath the desert support cloaker mobs that are rare in smaller cavern networks.

### Lore

Characters with ranks in Knowledge (dungeoneering) can learn the following about cloakers.

**DC 15:** Cloakers are intelligent, manta-like creatures that hang from cavern ceilings and drop onto prey. They engulf victims in their bodies and produce a subsonic moan that induces fear, nausea, or stupor.

**DC 20:** Striking a cloaker while it is engulfing a victim deals half the damage to the victim. Cloakers can create illusory duplicates of themselves using shadow manipulation. They are intelligent enough to identify the weakest member of a group before attacking.

**DC 25:** Cloakers are alien aberrations whose Kin-sense signature registers as wrong but is actively suppressed during hunting, making motionless cloakers nearly undetectable. Vestri Dwarves use dedicated roof-watchers in deep tunnel teams. The Dómnathar tolerate cloakers in their tunnel fringes as passive security against intruders.

# CLOUD GIANT

The summit is not empty. What you took for a formation of ice-covered boulders is a chair — an enormous chair, carved from the living stone of the peak — and sitting in it is a figure thirty feet tall, wrapped in fog as though fog were a garment. Its skin is pale as glacier-melt. Its hair is white and moves in a wind that does not touch you. Its eyes, when it opens them, are the blue of a sky seen from a height where the air runs out.

**Huge Giant (Air)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Huge Giant (Air) |
| **Hit Dice** | 17d8+102 (178 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +1 |
| **Speed** | 50 ft. (10 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 25 (–2 size, +1 Dex, +12 natural, +4 chain shirt), touch 9, flat-footed 24 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +12/+32 |
| **Attack** | Gargantuan morningstar +22 melee (4d6+18) or rock +12 ranged (2d8+12) |
| **Full Attack** | Gargantuan morningstar +22/+17/+12 melee (4d6+18) or rock +12 ranged (2d8+12) |
| **Space/Reach** | 15 ft./15 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Rock throwing (range increment 140 ft.), spell-like abilities |
| **Special Qualities** | Low-light vision, oversized weapons, rock catching, scent, elemental resonance (Air), Giant remnant resonance |
| **Saves** | Fort +16, Ref +6, Will +10 |
| **Abilities** | Str 35, Dex 13, Con 23, Int 12, Wis 16, Cha 13 |
| **Skills** | Climb +20, Diplomacy +7, Intimidate +11, Listen +15, Perform (sing) +5, Spot +15 |
| **Feats** | Awesome Blow, Cleave, Great Cleave, Improved Bull Rush, Improved Overrun, Iron Will, Power Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Youngest Brother (Air) — overwhelmingly strong, the air-attunement of a creature that was shaped when the Youngest Brother’s power was undivided |
| **Environment** | Giant’s Teeth (the highest summits above the permanent snowline, cloud-wrapped peaks accessible only by climbing or flight; a handful are known to lair in the upper reaches of the Emberfangs and the northern Ashen Crown) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair (mated), or family (2 adults plus 1d4 young) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 11 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (Giant-era artifacts, worked stone, and items of enormous scale — a cloud giant’s “coin purse” contains gems and metal ingots rather than currency) |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral good |
| **Advancement** | By character class |
| **Level Adjustment** | +5 |

### Combat

Cloud giants fight with the measured confidence of creatures that have been apex beings for longer than most civilizations have existed. They do not rush, do not panic, and do not waste effort. A cloud giant opens combat by throwing rocks from its summit position — its range increment of 140 feet and its vantage point mean that approaching enemies are under bombardment long before they reach melee range.

In close combat, a cloud giant wields its morningstar with devastating power, using Awesome Blow and Improved Bull Rush to hurl enemies off cliff-edges, out of passes, or simply far enough away to resume rock throwing. Against flying opponents, a cloud giant uses its spell-like abilities (fog cloud, levitate, obscuring mist) to negate aerial advantages and force the engagement onto its terms.

Cloud giants prefer to avoid lethal combat with Kin. If attacked by a Kin party, a cloud giant will attempt to drive the attackers away rather than kill them — using intimidation, rock throws aimed at the ground near (not at) the intruders, and fog to obscure the approach. Only if the party persists past multiple warnings does a cloud giant fight to kill. Against Dómnathar, no warnings are given.

### Special Abilities

**Rock Throwing (Ex):** Range increment 140 ft. A cloud giant can hurl rocks of 60–80 pounds.

**Rock Catching (Ex):** A cloud giant can catch Small, Medium, or Large rocks (or projectiles of similar shape). A successful Reflex save (DC 15 + damage dice) allows the giant to catch the projectile.

**Oversized Weapons (Ex):** A cloud giant wields weapons one size category larger than its size (Gargantuan) without penalty.

**Spell-Like Abilities:** At will — fog cloud, levitate, obscuring mist; 1/day — control weather. Caster level 17th. These abilities reflect the cloud giant’s profound connection to the Youngest Brother’s domain.

**Giant Remnant Resonance (Su):** This is the defining Kin-sense characteristic of all true Giants. On Kin-sense, a cloud giant registers as all four elemental signatures in harmony — Earth, Fire, Water, and Air — simultaneously, balanced, and overwhelmingly powerful. The experience of detecting a Giant’s resonance is unlike anything else in Oreka. Kin within 120 ft. feel the full-element harmony as an involuntary emotional response: awe, reverence, grief, or joy, depending on the individual Kin’s temperament and cultural background.

For most Kin, detecting a Giant’s resonance is the closest they will ever come to feeling what Oreka’s elemental fabric sounded like when it was whole — before the Elemental Lords vanished, before the Giants faded, before the Shattering broke the world into fragments. The resonance carries a weight of time and loss that scholars describe as “hearing the first chord of a song that stopped being sung before you were born.”

The Air signature dominates in cloud giants specifically, but all four elements are present and in balance. This balance is what distinguishes Giant resonance from, say, a cherufe’s fire-earth fusion or a ccoa’s air-earth duality — the Giants’ resonance is not a combination but a unity.

### Society

Cloud giants are the last true Giants in Oreka — and they are barely that. The Firstborn, the original Giants shaped by all four Elemental Lords together, are gone. They faded during the Thalorien — the “stone’s sleep” — crumbling to dust over millennia as their immortal bodies finally lost coherence. What remain are their descendants: smaller, shorter-lived, less powerful, but still carrying the unmistakable four-element resonance of the Firstborn in their blood.

Cloud giants are the most isolated of the remnant Giant types. They lair on the highest peaks of the Giant’s Teeth, above the permanent snowline, in structures carved from the living stone of the mountain — chairs, platforms, shelters, and halls that are not quite architecture and not quite natural formation but something between. These structures are not Giant ruins; they are Giant homes, still occupied, still maintained by the hands that built them.

The cloud giant population in Oreka is small and declining. Current estimates (based on Vestri Dwarf observation and Orean human reports) place the total number of cloud giants in the Giant’s Teeth at fewer than forty individuals. They do not reproduce frequently — a mated pair may produce one child per century — and their numbers have been falling since the Thalorien began.

Cloud giants remember. This is their defining cultural characteristic and their greatest burden. They remember the Firstborn, the Age of Giants, the Thalorien, and the Shattering. Their oral tradition — transmitted through enormous, slow-paced songs that can last for days — preserves knowledge of the world as it was before the Kin were shaped. A cloud giant who consents to speak with a Kin scholar can provide information about the Age of Giants that no other source in Oreka can confirm or deny.

Vestri Dwarves maintain formal diplomatic relationships with individual cloud giants, visiting specific summits at appointed intervals (typically once per decade) to exchange news, trade goods (gemstones and worked metal for Giant-era knowledge), and renew non-aggression agreements. The Vestri consider these relationships among their most valuable diplomatic assets and guard the details jealously.

Orean humans in the Giant’s Teeth live in the cloud giants’ shadow — sometimes literally — and have developed a culture of deference that borders on worship. Orean communities do not climb above the snowline without invitation. When a cloud giant descends to the lower peaks (which happens rarely, usually during severe weather or when the giant needs something it cannot obtain at altitude), the nearest Orean settlement treats the event as a visitation of sacred significance.

Pekakarlik Dwarves know of cloud giants but rarely interact with them. Pekakarlik traders who cross the Giant’s Teeth give the highest peaks a wide berth and leave offerings (gemstones, worked copper) at designated cairns along the high passes — tribute to the Giants that the Pekakarlik have paid for as long as their culture has existed, and which they would consider shameful to discontinue.

### Lore

Characters with ranks in Knowledge (nature) can learn the following about cloud giants.

**DC 16:** Cloud giants are enormous, air-attuned beings that dwell on the highest mountain peaks. They can control weather, throw boulders with devastating accuracy, and prefer to drive intruders away rather than kill them.

**DC 21:** Cloud giants are the last remnants of the original Giant race. Their Kin-sense resonance carries all four elemental signatures in harmony — an experience that provokes involuntary emotional responses in detecting Kin. Fewer than forty are believed to exist in Oreka.

**DC 26:** Cloud giants remember the Age of Giants through oral tradition preserved in days-long songs. Vestri Dwarves maintain once-per-decade diplomatic visits to specific individuals. Orean humans treat cloud giant descents as sacred events. Their population is declining due to extremely low reproduction rates, and some Kin scholars fear the cloud giants will follow the Firstborn into extinction within the next millennium.

# COCKATRICE

It struts out of the tall grass like it owns the steppe — a rooster-sized creature with the body of a scrawny chicken, the wings of a bat, and a tail that ends in a scaly, serpentine point. Its feathers are patchy and iridescent, shifting between sickly green and tarnished bronze. Its eyes are beady, stupid, and mean. It looks ridiculous. Then it pecks a field-mouse and the mouse turns to stone mid-squeak, and you stop laughing.

**Small Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Small Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 5d10 (27 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +3 |
| **Speed** | 20 ft. (4 squares), fly 60 ft. (poor) |
| **Armor Class** | 14 (+1 size, +3 Dex), touch 14, flat-footed 11 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +5/–1 |
| **Attack** | Bite +9 melee (1d4–2 plus petrification) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +9 melee (1d4–2 plus petrification) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Petrification |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, elemental resonance (Earth), the Harmony |
| **Saves** | Fort +4, Ref +7, Will +2 |
| **Abilities** | Str 6, Dex 17, Con 11, Int 2, Wis 13, Cha 9 |
| **Skills** | Listen +7, Spot +7 |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Dodge, Weapon FinesseB |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) — like the basilisk, the cockatrice’s petrification is an expression of Earth dominance |
| **Environment** | The Eternal Steppe (open grasslands, scrubby hillsides, field-margins near agricultural settlements); secondary presence in the Kinsweave lowlands and along the forest-steppe border |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or flock (3–13) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 3 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always neutral |
| **Advancement** | 6–8 HD (Small); 9–15 HD (Medium) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A cockatrice is aggressive, territorial, and too stupid to be afraid. It attacks creatures many times its size without hesitation, pecking and flapping and generally behaving like the world’s most dangerous chicken. Its combat strategy, such as it is, consists of running at the nearest creature and biting it until the creature turns to stone.

A cockatrice flock is a serious hazard. Multiple cockatrices attacking simultaneously force multiple petrification saves per round, and their small size and erratic movement patterns make them difficult to target. Flocks do not coordinate — each cockatrice attacks independently and usually fixates on a different target — but the sheer volume of petrifying bites creates a dangerous situation for any group caught in the open.

Cockatrices cannot sustain flight for long periods; their poor flying speed and small wings mean they tire quickly. They fly primarily to escape melee or to close distance for an attack, landing after one or two rounds.

### Special Abilities

**Petrification (Su):** A creature hit by a cockatrice’s bite must succeed on a DC 12 Fortitude save or be permanently turned to stone. The save DC is Constitution-based. The petrification is instantaneous — there is no gradual onset as with basilisk petrification. One moment the creature is alive; the next, it is a statue. Stone to flesh reverses the effect.

A cockatrice is immune to the petrification of other cockatrices but not to basilisk petrification or other sources.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a cockatrice registers as a small, sharp earth-signature — a chip of the Lord of Stone’s resonance compressed into an aggressively compact package. The resonance is disproportionately strong for the creature’s size; Kin within 30 ft. feel a brief, stabbing pulse of earth-energy, like stepping on a sharp stone. Mytroan herders who live in cockatrice territory learn to recognise this pulse and respond by moving their herds away from the area.

**The Harmony (Su):** Cockatrices possess the Harmony and sense other cockatrices within 1 mile. Flocks use this awareness to avoid overlapping territories during nesting season and to congregate at productive hunting grounds.

### Society

Cockatrices are aggressive, stupid animals. They have no culture, no language, and no behavior more complex than eat, mate, and attack things that move.

Their ecological significance in Oreka is primarily as an agricultural hazard. On the Eternal Steppe, where Mytroan herding communities maintain large herds of horses, cattle, and sheep, a cockatrice flock that wanders into grazing land can petrify livestock at a devastating rate. Mytroan herders consider cockatrices the most annoying creature on the steppe — not the most dangerous (that honour goes to the bulette or the annis hag), but the most persistently, irritatingly destructive to the pastoral economy.

Mytroan pest-control methods for cockatrices are well-developed. The preferred technique is the “stone-circle drive”: herders on horseback encircle a cockatrice flock and drive it toward a designated killing ground — a rocky area where the flock is surrounded and dispatched with ranged weapons from horseback. The key is never to approach on foot, because a cockatrice in the grass can bite an ankle before the victim sees it coming. Mytroan children are taught to walk through tall steppe-grass by stamping their feet — the vibration drives cockatrices away.

Pekakarlik alchemists purchase cockatrice feathers and blood, which have applications in petrification-related research and in the crafting of stone to flesh scrolls. A fresh cockatrice carcass is worth 50 gp to a Pekakarlik alchemist, which has created a small but persistent trade in cockatrice hunting along the desert-steppe border.

Warg communities on the steppe tolerate cockatrices because the Wargs’ thick fur and tough hide provide some protection against the creature’s weak bite. Warg pups occasionally play with cockatrices in a way that horrifies Kin observers — batting the creatures around like toys, apparently unaffected by the petrification (Wargs have a +4 racial bonus on Fortitude saves against petrification, a fact that Kin scholars find both interesting and unexplained).

### Lore

Characters with ranks in Knowledge (arcana) can learn the following about cockatrices.

**DC 13:** Cockatrices are small, chicken-like creatures whose bite turns victims to stone instantly. They are common on the Eternal Steppe and extremely aggressive despite their small size.

**DC 18:** A cockatrice flock is far more dangerous than a solitary specimen because multiple petrification saves are required each round. They cannot sustain flight for long. Stone to flesh reverses the petrification.

**DC 23:** Cockatrices are earth-attuned, like basilisks — their petrification is an expression of the Lord of Stone’s elemental domain. Mytroan herders use horseback drives to clear flocks from grazing land. Wargs appear resistant to cockatrice petrification for unknown reasons. Pekakarlik alchemists buy cockatrice remains for petrification-related research.

# CRIOSPHINX

The creature on the ridgeline has the body of a lion — massive, tawny, heavy with muscle — and the head of a ram, curling horns spiralling out from a skull broader than a man’s chest. Its wings are folded against its flanks, eagle-feathered and enormous. It watches you approach with an expression that is neither hostile nor welcoming but evaluative, as though it is calculating something about you that you are not aware of.

**Large Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 10d10+30 (85 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +0 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), fly 60 ft. (poor) |
| **Armor Class** | 20 (–1 size, +11 natural), touch 9, flat-footed 20 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +10/+18 |
| **Attack** | Gore +14 melee (2d6+6) |
| **Full Attack** | Gore +14 melee (2d6+6) and 2 claws +11 melee (1d6+3) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Powerful charge, pounce |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, elemental resonance (Fire/Earth), the Harmony |
| **Saves** | Fort +10, Ref +7, Will +5 |
| **Abilities** | Str 23, Dex 10, Con 17, Int 10, Wis 11, Cha 11 |
| **Skills** | Intimidate +10, Listen +10, Spot +10 |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Cleave, Improved Natural Attack (gore), Power Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of Fire (Fire) / Lord of Stone (Earth) — dual affinity reflecting the forge-heat and volcanic stone of the Scorchspires |
| **Environment** | Scorchspire Foothills (rocky ridgelines, dry valleys, and exposed plateaus at the transition between the Scorchspires’ volcanic slopes and the lowland desert or steppe); secondary presence in the Giant’s Teeth foothills where dry, warm conditions prevail |
| **Organization** | Solitary |
| **Challenge Rating** | 7 |
| **Treasure** | Standard |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 11–15 HD (Large); 16–20 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A criosphinx is a brute-force predator — less intelligent and less magical than its androsphinx and gynosphinx cousins, but physically more aggressive. It charges. That is its primary tactic and the one it is best at: a criosphinx’s powerful charge delivers a devastating gore attack that can shatter shields, break ribs, and send opponents flying.

In combat, a criosphinx opens with a charge from elevation — using its wings to gain speed on a downhill run — and delivers a powerful charge gore to the largest or most heavily-armoured target. After the initial impact, it pounces, following up with claw attacks against the staggered opponent. If the first charge does not end the fight, the criosphinx withdraws to a distance, wheels, and charges again. This pattern — charge, strike, withdraw, charge — continues until the opponent is dead, crippled, or has fled.

A criosphinx does not use its flying ability in combat; its poor flying speed makes it vulnerable to ranged attacks while airborne. It flies only to reposition between charges or to escape.

Against sphinx-hunting parties, a criosphinx fights with patient aggression, using the terrain of the Scorchspire foothills to force attackers into narrow passes where its charge is most effective and their numbers count for least.

### Special Abilities

**Powerful Charge (Ex):** A criosphinx that charges deals 4d6+12 damage with its gore attack (instead of the normal 2d6+6). This devastating impact can knock opponents off their feet — in addition to the damage, the target must succeed on a DC 21 Fortitude save or be knocked prone. The save DC is Strength-based.

**Pounce (Ex):** If a criosphinx charges, it can make a full attack (including claw attacks) at the end of the charge.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a criosphinx registers as a dense, hot dual-signature — the Lady of Fire’s heat compressed into the Lord of Stone’s weight, like a forge-stone that has been heated until it glows. The resonance is aggressive but not hostile; Kin describe it as “the feeling that something very heavy and very warm is paying attention to you.” Within 60 ft., the resonance is unmistakable and impossible to misidentify — the sphinx-signature is unique in Oreka’s bestiary.

The criosphinx’s resonance is notably less complex than an androsphinx’s or gynosphinx’s. Where the greater sphinxes carry layered, nuanced signatures that communicate mood and intent, the criosphinx’s resonance is blunt and straightforward — heat, weight, attention. This simplicity reflects the criosphinx’s nature: it is not a guardian, a riddler, or a sage. It is a territorial predator with a sphinx’s body and a ram’s temperament.

**The Harmony (Su):** Criosphinxes possess the Harmony and can sense other sphinxes (of any type) within 5 miles. This awareness maintains territorial separation between sphinx species. Criosphinxes avoid androsphinxes entirely (the androsphinx is larger, stronger, and magically superior) and maintain wary distance from gynosphinxes. Two criosphinxes whose territories overlap will fight, and the loser departs.

### Society

Criosphinxes are solitary territorial predators. They claim ridgelines and plateau-tops in the Scorchspire foothills and defend them against all comers — including other criosphinxes, which they fight for territory during the annual rut.

The criosphinx occupies a specific ecological niche among Oreka’s sphinxes: it is the foothills predator, the sphinx of the lower slopes, while androsphinxes claim the high desert and gynosphinxes claim the Glass Wastes. This territorial stratification is maintained by the Harmony — each sphinx type senses the others and adjusts its territory accordingly.

Rarozhki Dwarves encounter criosphinxes at the lower slopes of the Scorchspires and have a pragmatic relationship with them. A criosphinx that has claimed a ridge near a Rarozhki settlement is a nuisance (it occasionally kills livestock and threatens lone travelers) but also a deterrent — other predators avoid criosphinx territory, and a ridgeline claimed by a sphinx is a ridgeline free of chimeras, wyverns, and hieracosphinxes. Rarozhki communities near active criosphinx territories post warning markers at the boundary and advise travelers to avoid the ridge.

Taraf-Imro warriors consider criosphinx horns among the most prestigious trophies available in the Scorchspire foothills. A criosphinx horn — massive, spiralling, and dense as stone — is worth 500 gp to a Taraf-Imro trophy-trader and considerably more as a crafting material. Taraf-Imro horn-hunts are dangerous, carefully planned affairs involving teams of warriors who use the charge-and-withdraw pattern against the sphinx itself — meeting the creature’s charge with a coordinated sidestep and striking the flanks as it passes. Casualties are expected and accepted.

Androsphinxes regard criosphinxes with mild contempt — the way a scholar might regard a particularly aggressive dog. When an androsphinx and a criosphinx’s territories intersect, the criosphinx defers immediately. This hierarchy is absolute and has never been challenged.

### Lore

Characters with ranks in Knowledge (arcana) can learn the following about criosphinxes.

**DC 17:** Criosphinxes are ram-headed sphinxes found in the Scorchspire foothills. They are aggressive territorial predators that charge with devastating force. They are less intelligent and less magical than other sphinx types.

**DC 22:** A criosphinx’s charge deals massive damage and can knock opponents prone. They maintain territorial separation from other sphinx species through the Harmony. Rarozhki communities tolerate nearby criosphinxes because they deter other predators.

**DC 27:** Criosphinx resonance is fire-earth dual-attuned but simpler than other sphinxes’ signatures — blunt heat and weight rather than layered complexity. Taraf-Imro warriors hunt them for their horns, which are valuable as trophies and crafting materials. Criosphinxes defer immediately to androsphinxes in all territorial disputes.

# CÙ SÌTH

The dog is too large. That is the first thing — it stands shoulder-height to a horse, its body lean and deep-chested, built for endurance rather than speed. Its fur is dark green, the colour of moss on old stone, and it moves through the undergrowth without disturbing a single branch. Its eyes are gold and ancient and watching you with an intelligence that no dog should possess. It does not bark. It does not growl. It simply appears at the tree-line, considers you, and waits to see what you will do.

**Large Fey**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Fey |
| **Hit Dice** | 6d6+18 (39 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +3 |
| **Speed** | 50 ft. (10 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 17 (–1 size, +3 Dex, +5 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 14 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +3/+12 |
| **Attack** | Bite +7 melee (1d8+5) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +7 melee (1d8+5) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Three barks, trip |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, scent, damage reduction 5/cold iron, spell resistance 16, fey resonance (Air/Earth), forest-step, the Harmony |
| **Saves** | Fort +5, Ref +8, Will +7 |
| **Abilities** | Str 20, Dex 17, Con 16, Int 10, Wis 15, Cha 16 |
| **Skills** | Hide +8 (+16 in forest or steppe grass), Listen +11, Move Silently +12, Spot +11, Survival +11 |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Run, Track |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Youngest Brother (Air) / Lord of Stone (Earth) — the border between wind and root, the place where forest meets grassland |
| **Environment** | Forest-Steppe Border (the transitional zone where the Great Forests thin into grassland — specifically the Pasua-claimed stretches of the western and southern forest-edge, the Kinsweave-Steppe frontier, and the wooded margins of the Twin Rivers region) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or pair |
| **Challenge Rating** | 5 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 7–12 HD (Large); 13–18 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A Cù Sìth does not hunt for food — it is a fey creature sustained by the forest itself, not by prey. It fights only to defend its territory, protect the forest-border, or carry out whatever inscrutable purpose drives it on a given night. When it fights, it fights with calculated, canine efficiency: it closes to bite range with its enormous speed, trips the target prone, and delivers follow-up bites while the target struggles to rise.

The Cù Sìth’s most feared ability is its three barks. The creature barks only when it intends to kill — and by the third bark, if the target has not escaped, it dies. Pasua border-scouts who hear the first bark know they have two choices: flee immediately, or determine why the Cù Sìth has chosen this target and intervene before the third bark falls. The barks are spaced exactly ten seconds apart — enough time to act, but only barely.

A Cù Sìth does not fight groups. If outnumbered, it uses forest-step to vanish into the undergrowth and reappear elsewhere along the border, waiting for its chosen target to separate from the group. It is patient. It has all night.

Against Dómnathar, a Cù Sìth attacks without the bark-warning — it simply strikes from the underbrush with lethal intent. Pasua rangers have observed that a Cù Sìth that detects a Deceiver void-signature becomes visibly agitated, its green fur bristling and its gold eyes narrowing to slits, before it vanishes into the trees and begins to hunt.

### Special Abilities

**Three Barks (Su):** A Cù Sìth’s bark is not a sound — it is a death-sentence delivered in three parts. As a standard action, a Cù Sìth can bark at a single target within 100 feet. The bark has the following cumulative effects:

*First Bark:* The target must succeed on a Will save (DC 16) or be shaken for 1 minute. The sound is deep, resonant, and unmistakable — every creature within 500 feet hears it and knows instinctively that it is a warning.

*Second Bark:* The target must succeed on a Will save (DC 16) or be frightened for 1 minute (upgraded from shaken if the first save was failed; replaces shaken with frightened if the first save was passed). The second bark comes exactly one round (6 seconds) after the first.

*Third Bark:* The target must succeed on a Fortitude save (DC 16) or die. A creature that succeeds takes 3d6 sonic damage and is stunned for 1 round. The third bark comes exactly one round after the second.

A Cù Sìth can bark at only one target per encounter. If the target moves beyond 100 feet before the third bark, the sequence resets and the Cù Sìth must begin again. The save DCs are Charisma-based. This is a sonic, death effect for the third bark and a sonic, mind-affecting, fear effect for the first and second.

**Trip (Ex):** A Cù Sìth that hits with a bite attack can attempt to trip the opponent (+9 check modifier) as a free action without making a touch attack or provoking an attack of opportunity. If the trip fails, the opponent cannot react to trip the Cù Sìth.

**Forest-Step (Su):** Three times per day, a Cù Sìth can step into a tree, patch of undergrowth, or area of tall grass and emerge from any similar natural cover within 500 feet, as dimension door but usable only between points of natural concealment. This ability is what makes the Cù Sìth so effective as a border-guardian — it can patrol miles of forest-edge in minutes, appearing wherever it is needed.

**Fey Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a Cù Sìth registers as a sharp, wild fey signature — wind through tall grass over deep-rooted earth, the border-zone itself given form. The resonance is beautiful and unsettling in equal measure. Kin within 60 ft. feel a pull toward the forest and a simultaneous urge to remain on the open ground — the border-tension made into sensation. The resonance strengthens dramatically at night, extending to 120 ft. and becoming impossible to ignore.

Pasua elves recognise Cù Sìth resonance immediately and react to it with a combination of reverence and caution. A Pasua scout who detects a Cù Sìth signals their party to stop, stand still, and wait — the Cù Sìth will either approach or depart, and either response tells the scout something about the border’s current state.

**The Harmony (Su):** Cù Sìth possess the Harmony and can sense other Cù Sìth within 5 miles. Mated pairs coordinate border-patrols through the Harmony, dividing their territory into sectors and alternating coverage. A Cù Sìth also senses wolves, dire wolves, worgs, and blink dogs through a broader, weaker version of the Harmony — canine creatures are Harmony-adjacent, and the Cù Sìth is aware of their presence and general emotional state within 1 mile.

### Society

Cù Sìth are fey — born of the forest-steppe border itself, expressions of the transition zone between the Great Forests and the open grassland. They are guardians, but not in the way a soldier guards a gate. A Cù Sìth guards a concept: the boundary, the threshold, the place where one thing ends and another begins. It patrols the forest-edge because the forest-edge is what it is, and it responds to threats against the border with the same instinctive ferocity that a mother wolf shows toward threats to her pups.

Pasua elves have the deepest relationship with Cù Sìth. The Pasua claim the forest-border as their primary territory, and Cù Sìth patrol the same stretches of forest-edge that Pasua scouts walk. The relationship is not domestication — a Cù Sìth cannot be tamed, commanded, or persuaded — but it is collaborative. Over centuries, Pasua border-communities have learned to read Cù Sìth behavior as intelligence: a Cù Sìth that appears at the tree-line and stares toward the steppe is signalling that something is approaching from the grassland. A Cù Sìth that barks once and stops is warning — something in the border-zone is wrong, but it is not yet a killing matter.

Pasua naming tradition treats the Cù Sìth as a rank rather than a species. Young Pasua scouts earn the title *cù-warden* when they successfully interpret a Cù Sìth’s behavior to avert a threat, and the title carries significant prestige. An experienced cù-warden can predict a Cù Sìth’s actions before they happen — reading the creature’s body language, the direction of its gaze, and the intensity of its resonance — and use that prediction to protect the community.

Mytroan steppe-riders fear the Cù Sìth more than any other creature along the border — not because it is the most dangerous (an androsphinx is stronger, a chimera is more destructive) but because the Cù Sìth is the only creature that selects a specific individual and hunts them to death. Mytroan oral tradition is emphatic: if you hear the first bark, run. If you hear the second bark, pray. If you hear the third bark, you are dead. Mytroan herders who graze their animals near the forest-edge make a point of never crossing the tree-line at night, and Mytroan mothers use the Cù Sìth as the definitive “stay away from the forest after dark” cautionary tale.

Centaur herds along the border have a neutral relationship with Cù Sìth. Both are border-creatures, both patrol the transition zone, and both are territorial without being expansionist. A centaur herd that encounters a Cù Sìth gives it distance and respect; the Cù Sìth reciprocates. Centaur legends speak of Cù Sìth as “the forest’s conscience” — the part of the forest that remembers where its boundaries are.

### Lore

Characters with ranks in Knowledge (nature) can learn the following about Cù Sìth.

**DC 15:** Cù Sìth are enormous green-furred fey hounds found along the forest-steppe border. They bark three times before killing their chosen target. If you hear the first bark, you should flee immediately.

**DC 20:** The three barks are spaced exactly one round apart — fear, greater fear, death. The Cù Sìth can only target one creature per encounter, and the target must remain within 100 feet for the sequence to complete. They can teleport between points of natural cover within 500 feet, making them nearly impossible to escape in border terrain.

**DC 25:** Cù Sìth are fey guardians of the forest-steppe boundary itself — expressions of the transition zone between ecosystems. Pasua elves read their behavior as intelligence about border-zone threats. Their resonance is a dual air-earth signature that embodies the border-tension between forest and grassland. They attack Dómnathar without their usual bark-warning.

# CULSANS

The gate stands at the river-fork where the Twin Rivers meet — two pillars of Giant-cut stone, the carvings worn smooth by centuries of water and wind. Between the pillars, a figure stands facing both directions at once. It has two faces — one looking upstream, one looking downstream — set on a single head that rotates slowly, continuously, like the hands of a clock that measures something other than time. Its body is carved from the same stone as the gate, or perhaps the gate was carved from it. It holds a key in each hand. Both keys are different. Both locks are invisible.

**Medium Outsider (Native)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Outsider (Native) |
| **Hit Dice** | 8d8+24 (60 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +4 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 22 (+4 Dex, +8 natural), touch 14, flat-footed 18 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +8/+10 |
| **Attack** | Key-strike +12 melee (1d8+2 plus dimensional lock) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 key-strikes +12 melee (1d8+2 plus dimensional lock) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Key-strike, threshold judgment, two-way gaze |
| **Special Qualities** | All-around vision, darkvision 120 ft., damage reduction 10/magic, immunity to mind-affecting effects, spell resistance 18, gate-bound, elemental resonance (Air/Water), portal sight |
| **Saves** | Fort +9, Ref +10, Will +10 |
| **Abilities** | Str 14, Dex 18, Con 17, Int 17, Wis 19, Cha 16 |
| **Skills** | Diplomacy +14, Knowledge (geography) +14, Knowledge (history) +14, Knowledge (the planes) +14, Listen +17, Search +14, Sense Motive +17, Spot +17 |
| **Feats** | Combat Reflexes, Improved Disarm, Weapon Finesse |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Youngest Brother (Air) / Lady of the Sea (Water) — dual affinity; the culsans embodies the meeting of currents, the point where rivers converge and winds cross |
| **Environment** | Great River (river-forks, confluence points, canal junctions, and crossroads along the Great River and its major tributaries — always at a point where two paths, two currents, or two directions meet); most commonly encountered at Eruskan-maintained river-forks in the Twin Rivers region |
| **Organization** | Solitary (always) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 6 |
| **Treasure** | None (but offerings of paired items — two coins, two flowers, two stones — are traditionally left at a culsans’ gate) |
| **Alignment** | Always true neutral |
| **Advancement** | 9–16 HD (Medium); 17–24 HD (Large) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A culsans does not initiate combat. It is a guardian of crossroads and confluences — places where paths diverge — and its role is to observe, judge, and occasionally intervene, not to attack. A traveler who approaches a culsans-guarded fork with honest intent passes unmolested. A traveler who lies about their destination, carries stolen goods across the threshold, or attempts to use the crossroads for purposes that would corrupt the meeting-point is stopped.

When a culsans fights, it fights with precise, dispassionate efficiency. Its key-strikes lock creatures in place, preventing dimensional escape; its two-way gaze identifies deception and hostile intent; and its threshold judgment delivers consequences proportional to the offense. A creature that lied about its destination is turned back. A creature that attempted to smuggle Dómnathar artifacts across the river-fork is struck down.

A culsans has all-around vision (it sees in every direction simultaneously through its two faces) and cannot be flanked. It uses Combat Reflexes to make attacks of opportunity against every creature that attempts to pass its threshold without acknowledgment, and Improved Disarm to strip weapons from aggressive travelers before the situation escalates.

Like charun, a culsans does not pursue beyond its threshold. The moment a creature retreats from the fork, the culsans stops. Unlike charun, a culsans does not make an exception for Dómnathar — it treats Deceivers exactly as it treats any other trespasser, with proportional judgment rather than automatic hostility. This impartiality is what defines the culsans: it does not hate the Dómnathar, it does not love the Kin, it simply guards the fork and judges all who cross.

### Special Abilities

**Key-Strike (Su):** A culsans attacks with the two keys it carries — one in each hand. Each key functions as a +2 light mace that deals 1d8+2 damage. On a hit, the target must succeed on a Will save (DC 17) or be affected by dimensional anchor for 1 minute (no teleportation, no planar travel, no dimension door). The save DC is Charisma-based. The keys are part of the culsans and cannot be disarmed, stolen, or sundered.

**Threshold Judgment (Su):** Once per round as a free action, a culsans can judge a creature within 30 feet that is attempting to cross its threshold. The culsans knows the creature’s alignment, its stated destination (if it has spoken one aloud), and whether it is carrying anything cursed, stolen, or tainted by Dómnathar magic. Based on this judgment, the culsans can issue one of the following commands, each of which functions as a spell-like ability (CL 8th):

*Pass:* The creature is allowed to cross. No mechanical effect. *Turn Back:* As command (DC 16), compelling the creature to turn around and walk away from the fork. Will negates. *Halt:* As hold person (DC 16), freezing the creature in place at the threshold. Will negates. *Strike:* The culsans delivers a melee attack with both keys simultaneously as an immediate action.

The culsans’ judgment is absolute within its threshold zone but is not infallible — it reads intent and alignment, not full history. A creature with genuinely good intentions that happens to be carrying a cursed item it doesn’t know about may be judged harshly until the misunderstanding is resolved.

**Two-Way Gaze (Su):** A culsans can see in two directions simultaneously — not merely physically (which its two faces accomplish naturally) but metaphysically. As a standard action, a culsans can gaze at a creature within 60 feet and perceive its past and its intended future simultaneously. This grants the culsans a +10 insight bonus on Sense Motive checks against the target and reveals any active disguise, illusion, or shapeshifting (functioning as true seeing, CL 8th, against the targeted creature only). The target is aware of being gazed at and feels the scrutiny as a brief, disorienting sensation of being looked at from two directions at once.

**Portal Sight (Su):** A culsans can perceive every creature and object within 500 feet of its threshold simultaneously, regardless of concealment, cover, or darkness. This awareness is passive and constant — nothing crosses the fork without the culsans knowing. This sight does not extend beyond the 500-foot radius or through significant physical barriers (more than 5 feet of solid stone).

**Gate-Bound (Ex):** A culsans is permanently bonded to a specific river-fork, crossroads, or confluence. It cannot voluntarily move more than 500 feet from its threshold. If forcibly moved beyond this range, it becomes weakened (–4 to all ability scores) until it returns. When a culsans’ threshold is destroyed — the river-fork is dammed, the crossroads is obliterated, or the confluence is diverted — the culsans fades over 1d6 months unless the threshold is restored or a new one forms within range.

**All-Around Vision (Ex):** A culsans’ two faces grant it the ability to see in all directions simultaneously. It cannot be flanked.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a culsans registers as a balanced, flowing dual-signature — the Youngest Brother’s wind and the Lady of the Sea’s current meeting at a precise point and neither dominating. The resonance feels like standing at a crossroads where two breezes blow from different directions simultaneously — a sensation of convergence, of potential, of the moment before a choice is made. Kin within 60 ft. who detect the resonance experience a brief, involuntary moment of self-reflection: a flash-awareness of whatever decision they are currently avoiding.

This resonance-effect is not a mind-affecting ability — it is a Kin-sense reaction to the metaphysical nature of the culsans, which embodies the concept of the crossroads. Kin who are genuinely undecided about something often find themselves drawn to culsans-guarded forks, seeking not guidance (the culsans does not advise) but the clarity that proximity to the threshold provides.

### Society

Culsans are solitary native spirits — born of Oreka’s elemental fabric at points where paths, currents, and choices converge. They are not created, summoned, or shaped. They appear when a crossroads or confluence achieves sufficient significance — enough traffic, enough decisions made, enough history accumulated at the meeting-point — and they remain as long as the threshold exists.

Where charun guard transitions (gates, bridges, passages from one state to another), culsans guard divergences — the places where a single path becomes two, where a river splits, where a traveler must choose. The two spirit-types are related but distinct: charun are passage-guardians, culsans are choice-guardians. They are complementary expressions of Oreka’s spiritual geography, and Eruskan culture, which has named and formalised both, treats them as a matched pair.

Eruskan river-culture treats culsans with deep respect. The Eruskan tradition of leaving paired offerings (two coins, two flowers, two small stones — always two, reflecting the fork) at culsans-guarded confluences is ancient and universal among Eruskan communities. Eruskan merchants who reach a river-fork pause, make their offering, and state their destination aloud — not because the culsans requires it, but because the Eruskan believe that speaking a decision at a crossroads makes it binding.

Eruskan scholars classify culsans and charun together as *i guardiani del fiume* — “the river-guardians” — and study them as expressions of the Great River’s spiritual ecosystem. The distinction between the two is well-understood: if the spirit guards a gate, it is charun; if the spirit guards a fork, it is culsans. The physical forms differ as well — charun are large, heavy, stone-skinned warriors, while culsans are medium-sized, two-faced observers with an emphasis on perception rather than force.

Pasua elves who encounter culsans at forest-river forks treat them with quiet acknowledgment — a Pasua scout who passes a culsans will speak their name and destination aloud, a courtesy that the Pasua adopted from Eruskan practice and now consider their own tradition.

Halfling river-traders know every culsans on their trade routes by location and temperament. Halflings have observed that individual culsans develop distinct personalities over centuries: some are lenient, allowing ambiguous travelers to pass with minimal scrutiny; others are strict, demanding clear statement of purpose from every creature that approaches the fork. Halfling captains share this intelligence with each other as a matter of professional courtesy — knowing which culsans will question you about your cargo and which will let you through with a two-copper offering saves time and anxiety.

Mytroan caravans that cross the Great River at culsans-guarded forks have learned (the hard way, over several generations of trial and error) to stop, dismount, and make their offering on foot. Culsans interpret a mounted approach at speed as a hostile action and will judge accordingly — a cultural mismatch that has caused friction between Mytroan bands and Eruskan river-communities, who consider the protocols obvious.

### Lore

Characters with ranks in Knowledge (the planes) can learn the following about culsans.

**DC 16:** Culsans are two-faced guardian spirits found at river-forks and crossroads. They observe all who approach, judge their intent, and can prevent passage. The traditional offering is a pair of small items — two coins, two flowers.

**DC 21:** A culsans can perceive a creature’s alignment, destination, and whether it carries cursed or Dómnathar-tainted items. Its key-strikes prevent dimensional travel. It guards forks rather than gates — where charun guard transitions, culsans guard choices. Eruskan culture treats them as a matched pair.

**DC 26:** Culsans embody the concept of the crossroads. Their Kin-sense resonance provokes involuntary moments of self-reflection in detecting Kin. Halfling river-traders track individual culsans’ personalities and leniency levels. They are perfectly impartial — treating Dómnathar and Kin alike based on behavior at the threshold, not on nature or allegiance.

# DARKMANTLE

The stalactite opens its eyes. That is what it looks like — a cone of wet stone hanging from the cavern ceiling suddenly sprouts two tiny, reflective eyes and unfurls a membrane of leathery skin that was folded so tightly against its body that it was invisible. Then it drops.

**Small Magical Beast**

