| **Full Attack** | Bite +18 melee (4d6+8) and 2 claws +13 melee (2d8+4) |
| **Space/Reach** | 15 ft./10 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Breath weapon, capsize, snatch |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., immunity to fire, sleep, and paralysis, low-light vision, scent, elemental resonance (Water/Fire), the Harmony |
| **Saves** | Fort +13, Ref +8, Will +9 |
| **Abilities** | Str 27, Dex 10, Con 21, Int 12, Wis 12, Cha 12 |
| **Skills** | Diplomacy +16, Hide +7 (+15 submerged), Intimidate +16, Listen +16, Search +16, Spot +16, Swim +23 |
| **Feats** | Blind-Fight, Cleave, Improved Bull Rush, Power Attack, Snatch |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) / Lady of Fire (Fire) — dual affinity; the dragon turtle is the Lady of the Sea’s domain armoured in the Lady of Fire’s heat |
| **Environment** | Kailian Sea (deep channels, submerged seamounts, and the warmer currents of the eastern Kailian basin); secondary presence in the deep Apelian Sea (rare) and at the Great River’s mouth where freshwater meets salt |
| **Organization** | Solitary |
| **Challenge Rating** | 9 |
| **Treasure** | Triple standard (accumulated on the sea floor beneath the creature’s habitual resting site — a dragon turtle’s “hoard” includes shipwrecks, lost cargo, and offerings from coastal communities) |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 13–24 HD (Huge); 25–36 HD (Gargantuan) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A dragon turtle is a territorial predator that fights with overwhelming physical force. In the water, it is functionally unstoppable — its swim speed, massive bite, and capsize ability allow it to destroy vessels, scatter crews, and consume individual swimmers at will.

A dragon turtle opens combat with its breath weapon — a 60-foot cone of superheated steam that is devastating both above and below water. After the initial blast, it capsizes any vessels in range, then targets individual creatures in the water with bite and claw attacks. Against a single large vessel, a dragon turtle rams from below, uses capsize to dump the crew, and then destroys the capsized hull at leisure.

On land, a dragon turtle is slow and awkward — 20 ft. speed, no natural cover, and vulnerability to massed ranged fire. It fights on land only if cornered or defending a nest. In water, it retreats into depth if seriously wounded, diving to levels where air-breathing pursuers cannot follow.

Dragon turtles are intelligent and can be negotiated with. A party that offers tribute (gold, gems, or worked metal) and communicates respectfully may convince a dragon turtle to allow passage through its territory. This is how most coastal communities survive in dragon turtle waters — through payment, not combat.

### Special Abilities

**Breath Weapon (Su):** 60-foot cone of superheated steam, 12d6 fire damage, Reflex DC 21 half. Usable once every 1d4 rounds. The save DC is Constitution-based. The steam is equally effective above and below water — underwater, it creates a boiling zone that damages everything in the area.

**Capsize (Ex):** A dragon turtle can attempt to capsize a vessel by ramming it as a full-round action. It makes a Strength check opposed by the pilot’s Profession (sailor) check, with a +4 bonus for each size category the vessel is larger than Huge. Dragon turtles can capsize vessels of up to Colossal size.

**Snatch (Ex):** A dragon turtle can grab a creature of Medium or smaller size with its bite attack and carry it in its jaws. A snatched creature takes bite damage each round and is considered grappled.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a dragon turtle registers as a massive, layered water-fire signature — the Lady of the Sea’s cold depth overlaid with the Lady of Fire’s volcanic heat, as though an underwater hot spring had been given a body and a mind. The resonance extends 200 ft. underwater (sound and resonance carry further in water) and is impossible to miss. Kin sailors describe it as “the sea suddenly getting heavier” — a pressure on the Kin-sense that builds as the creature approaches.

The dual affinity is unusual for an aquatic creature. Scholars believe dragon turtles originated in Oreka’s volcanic sea-vents — the places where the Lady of Fire’s magma meets the Lady of the Sea’s deep water — and that their fire immunity and steam breath are products of this volcanic origin.

**The Harmony (Su):** Dragon turtles possess the Harmony and can sense other dragon turtles within 20 miles, maintaining vast territorial separations. The Kailian Sea supports an estimated six to ten dragon turtles, each claiming hundreds of square miles of deep water.

### Society

Dragon turtles are solitary, long-lived, and territorial. They claim stretches of sea-floor — typically centred on a volcanic vent, submerged seamount, or other geological feature — and patrol them for centuries. A dragon turtle’s territory is recognised by every maritime culture in Oreka, and the boundaries are mapped as carefully as coastlines.

Vestri Dwarves who maintain port facilities along the Kailian coast have the most formalised relationship with dragon turtles. The Vestri pay annual tribute — chests of worked metal and gemstones, lowered to the sea floor at designated sites — and in return the dragon turtle allows Vestri vessels to pass through its territory unmolested. This arrangement has functioned for centuries and is considered a normal cost of maritime commerce.

Halfling fishing communities in the Apelian basin live in perpetual awareness of the rare dragon turtles that inhabit those waters. Halfling sea-lore includes extensive protocols for detecting, avoiding, and (as a last resort) negotiating with dragon turtles, all of which reduce to a single principle: do not attract attention, and if you attract attention, offer everything you can afford to lose.

Na’wasua sea-elves regard dragon turtles with the same reverent caution they show to the Tidecrown Leviathans of the River Serpent family. The Na’wasua do not pay tribute — their relationship is one of mutual avoidance, based on the Na’wasua’s ability to detect dragon turtle resonance at extreme range and navigate around the creature’s territory entirely.

Eruskan merchants consider dragon turtle tribute a line item in their shipping budgets — predictable, manageable, and preferable to the alternative.

### Lore

**DC 14 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Dragon turtles are enormous aquatic dragons that breathe superheated steam. They are territorial, intelligent, and can capsize ships. Coastal communities pay them tribute for safe passage.

**DC 19:** A dragon turtle’s breath weapon is equally effective above and below water. They can capsize vessels of nearly any size. Negotiation through tribute is the standard approach — every maritime culture in Oreka maintains formal or informal tribute arrangements.

**DC 24:** Dragon turtles are dual water-fire attuned, likely originating from volcanic sea-vents. The Kailian Sea supports six to ten individuals, each controlling hundreds of square miles. Vestri coastal ports pay annual tribute as a standard cost of maritime operations. Dragon turtle resonance extends 200 ft. underwater and is detectable long before the creature is visible.

# DRAGONNE

It crouches on the ridgeline like something that could not decide whether to be a lion or a dragon and chose both. Its body is a lion’s — massive, tawny, thick with muscle — but its head is elongated, half-snouted, with brass-coloured scales running from brow to shoulders. Enormous bat-leather wings fold along its flanks, and when it opens its mouth to roar, the sound that comes out is not a lion’s roar and not a dragon’s bellow but something between: a brassy, resonant blast that shakes the stones under your feet.

**Large Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 9d10+27 (76 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +6 |
| **Speed** | 40 ft. (8 squares), fly 30 ft. (poor) |
| **Armor Class** | 18 (–1 size, +2 Dex, +7 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 16 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +9/+17 |
| **Attack** | Bite +13 melee (2d6+4) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +13 melee (2d6+4) and 2 claws +10 melee (1d6+2) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Pounce, roar |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, scent, elemental resonance (Fire/Earth), the Harmony |
| **Saves** | Fort +9, Ref +8, Will +4 |
| **Abilities** | Str 19, Dex 15, Con 17, Int 6, Wis 12, Cha 12 |
| **Skills** | Listen +11, Spot +11 |
| **Feats** | Blind-Fight, Combat Reflexes, Improved Initiative, Track |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of Fire (Fire) / Lord of Stone (Earth) — dual affinity; the dragonne is a warm-stone predator, fire in a lion’s body |
| **Environment** | Warm Mountains and Foothills (Scorchspire foothills, southern Giant’s Teeth, dry ridgelines between the Infinite Desert and the Eternal Steppe) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or pride (3–6) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 7 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (accumulated in lairs — typically shallow caves on cliff-faces) |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 10–13 HD (Large); 14–18 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +4 |

### Combat

A dragonne is a direct, aggressive predator that relies on speed, strength, and its devastating roar. It does not use subtlety. It sees prey, it charges, it pounces. The roar — a sonic weapon as much as an intimidation display — opens combat by disabling nearby creatures, and the dragonne follows up with bite and claw attacks against staggered or prone targets.

A dragonne pride is a terrifying encounter. Multiple dragonnes roaring simultaneously create overlapping sonic zones that can leave an entire party fatigued and deafened, at which point the physical assault begins. Prides hunt cooperatively — one dragonne roars and charges from the front while another circles to pounce from a flank.

Dragonnes fly poorly and reluctantly. They use their wings primarily for short glides from cliff-tops to the valley floor — a hunting technique that combines the height advantage with a pounce on landing. Sustained flight tires them quickly.

### Special Abilities

**Pounce (Ex):** A dragonne that charges can make a full attack at the end of the charge.

**Roar (Su):** A dragonne can roar as a standard action. All creatures within 120 feet must succeed on a DC 15 Fortitude save or become fatigued. Creatures within 30 feet that fail are also deafened for 2d4 rounds. The save DC is Constitution-based. A dragonne can roar once every 1d4 rounds. The roar is not merely loud — it carries a resonant, sub-harmonic frequency that interferes with physical coordination. Creatures that have already been fatigued by one roar and fail the save against a second become exhausted.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a dragonne registers as a hot, dense fire-earth signature — less complex than a true dragon’s resonance but more intense than most magical beasts. The signature pulses with the creature’s heartbeat, creating a rhythmic warmth that accelerates before the creature attacks. Kin within 60 ft. can feel the pulse quicken in the seconds before a charge, providing a split-second warning that experienced fighters learn to read.

**The Harmony (Su):** Dragonnes possess the Harmony and can sense other dragonnes within 5 miles. Prides use this to coordinate hunting across a shared territory without visual contact.

### Society

Dragonnes have no culture. They are apex predators of the warm foothills — less intelligent than true dragons, less social than lions, but physically formidable enough that few creatures contest their territories.

Taraf-Imro warriors hunt dragonnes in the Scorchspire foothills as a test of martial prowess, ranking them between chimeras (easier) and criosphinxes (harder). The Taraf-Imro technique for dragonne hunting centres on ear-protection: warriors fill their ears with beeswax-and-leather plugs before approaching, accepting the loss of hearing in exchange for immunity to the roar’s fatiguing effects.

Rarozhki Dwarves in the lower Scorchspires consider dragonnes a routine hazard. Rarozhki caravans traveling through dragonne territory assign “roar-watchers” — guards whose sole responsibility is detecting the accelerating heartbeat-pulse on Kin-sense that precedes a charge.

Mytroan herders whose summer pastures extend into the foothills lose livestock to dragonnes annually and consider the losses an acceptable cost of using the richest grazing land.

### Lore

**DC 17 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Dragonnes are lion-dragon hybrids with a devastating sonic roar that fatigues and deafens. They pounce like lions and hunt from elevated terrain.

**DC 22:** The roar’s fatigue effect stacks — a second failed save causes exhaustion. Ear protection negates the effect. Dragonnes’ Kin-sense resonance pulses faster before they charge, providing a brief warning. Prides coordinate through the Harmony.

**DC 27:** Taraf-Imro use beeswax ear-plugs for dragonne hunts. Rarozhki caravans assign “roar-watchers” trained to read the resonance-pulse. Dragonnes are less intelligent than true dragons but share the fire-earth dual affinity common to Scorchspire predators.

# DRAUGR

The barrow-mound splits open. It has not been opened by tools — the stone capstone has been pushed aside from within, scraped along the ground by hands that are still strong after three hundred years. What climbs out is wearing the remains of Vestri plate-armour — Mithril Legion insignia still visible beneath the corrosion, the breastplate cracked where the killing blow landed. Its eyes glow the dull orange of banked forge-coals. Its beard, once braided in the Vestri warrior tradition, hangs in matted ropes. It carries a warhammer. The hammer is still good. The dwarf is not.

**Medium Undead**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Undead |
| **Hit Dice** | 6d12 (39 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +1 |
| **Speed** | 20 ft. (4 squares; reduced by armour remnants) |
| **Armor Class** | 19 (+1 Dex, +6 natural, +2 armour remnants), touch 11, flat-footed 18 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +3/+8 |
| **Attack** | Warhammer +8 melee (1d8+7) or slam +8 melee (1d6+7) |
| **Full Attack** | Warhammer +8 melee (1d8+7) and slam +3 melee (1d6+2) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Death grip, barrow stench |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., damage reduction 5/magic, undead traits, turn resistance +2, cold resistance 10, elemental resonance (corrupted Earth/Fire), Dómnathar scar |
| **Saves** | Fort +2, Ref +3, Will +7 |
| **Abilities** | Str 20, Dex 12, Con —, Int 6, Wis 14, Cha 14 |
| **Skills** | Intimidate +8, Listen +8, Spot +8 |
| **Feats** | Cleave, Power Attack, Weapon Focus (warhammer) |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Corrupted — the draugr carries a distorted echo of the Vestri Earth/Fire resonance, broken by death and further warped by the Dómnathar raising that failed to hold |
| **Environment** | Tidebloom Reach and northern Kinsweave (barrow-mounds, battlefield graves, and ruined fortifications along the route the Deceiver host marched from Hillmeet to Aldenheim — the “Dead Road”); secondary presence in the Lament of Kings perimeter |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or warband (3–8) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 5 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (the draugr carries whatever it was buried with — Mithril Legion equipment, personal effects, and occasionally items of significant historical value) |
| **Alignment** | Usually lawful neutral |
| **Advancement** | 7–12 HD (Medium) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A draugr fights like the soldier it was — disciplined, methodical, and relentless. It does not charge blindly or attack in a frenzy. It advances at a steady pace, hammer raised, and delivers crushing blows with the mechanical precision of a warrior whose muscle-memory survived death intact. Draugr warbands maintain formation — they space themselves at shield-wall intervals, cover each other’s flanks, and focus fire on the most dangerous threat. Three centuries of undeath have not erased the Mithril Legion’s training.

A draugr opens combat with barrow stench to sicken nearby enemies, then closes to melee. Its death grip — an iron-hard grapple that pins the target while the draugr crushes — is its signature tactic against armoured opponents. Against unarmoured targets, the warhammer is sufficient. A draugr does not retreat, does not surrender, and does not negotiate. It fights until it is destroyed or its enemies are dead.

Draugr are not mindless. They possess a degraded intelligence — enough to recognise tactical situations, identify Dómnathar-aligned creatures, and prioritise targets. They cannot speak, but draugr warbands communicate through hand-signals — the same Mithril Legion battle-signs they used in life, still functional after three hundred years.

Against Dómnathar, draugr become terrifyingly effective. The Dómnathar scar — the residual trace of the failed raising — gives draugr an instinctive awareness of Deceiver presence. A draugr that detects a Dómnathar void-signature drops all other targets and moves toward the Deceiver with single-minded focus.

### Special Abilities

**Death Grip (Ex):** A draugr that hits with its slam attack can attempt to grapple as a free action. On a successful grapple, the draugr pins the target with crushing force, dealing 1d6+7 bludgeoning damage per round. A creature pinned by a draugr also takes 1d4 Strength damage per round as the supernatural cold of undeath drains vitality through the grip. A DC 16 Fortitude save negates the Strength damage each round. The save DC is Charisma-based. The death grip is what Vestri burial traditions are designed to prevent — a draugr’s grip is strong enough to crack plate armour.

**Barrow Stench (Ex):** A draugr exudes the stench of death and grave-rot in a 10-foot radius. Living creatures within the area must succeed on a DC 15 Fortitude save or be sickened for 1d6+4 minutes. The save DC is Charisma-based. Creatures that succeed are immune to that draugr’s stench for 24 hours.

**Dómnathar Scar (Su):** Every draugr carries a trace of the Dómnathar magic that raised it — a faint thread of the void woven into its undead essence. This trace is not loyalty; it is the opposite. The draugr broke free of the raising, and the scar is the wound that breaking left. On Kin-sense, the scar manifests as a thin line of void-cold running through the draugr’s corrupted resonance — recognisable to any Kin who has felt Dómnathar presence before.

The scar also functions as a detection mechanism. A draugr can sense Dómnathar void-signatures within 120 feet. This awareness is instinctive and automatic — the scar resonates when a Deceiver is near, and the draugr responds with immediate, focused aggression.

**Corrupted Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a draugr registers as a broken Vestri signature — the familiar earth-fire resonance of a Vestri Dwarf, corrupted by death into something cold and grinding. It feels like the memory of a forge that has gone out: the shape of warmth is still there, but the heat is gone, replaced by a chill that aches. Beneath the corrupted Vestri signature, the thin void-thread of the Dómnathar scar runs like a crack in stone.

The resonance is painful for Vestri Dwarves to detect. Every draugr is a fallen Vestri — a member of the Mithril Legion, a brother or sister who died at Aldenheim — and detecting one means feeling a beloved cultural resonance twisted into undeath. Vestri warriors who encounter draugr report involuntary grief, anger, and a fierce protective instinct — the desire to free their kindred from the prison of undeath.

### Society

Draugr are the undead soldiers of the Mithril Legion — the Vestri Dwarf army that defended Aldenheim against the northern Deceiver host when the Twelve Kings of Man refused aid and the elven armies arrived too late.

The Mithril Legion held the mountain passes for eleven days. They died to the last dwarf — crushed by numbers, overwhelmed by Dómnathar magic, buried under the bodies of their enemies. When the five druids melted the mountain and created the Lament of Kings, the Deceiver host was destroyed — but the Mithril Legion’s dead were already gone, scattered across the battlefield in their thousands.

The Dómnathar had begun raising the Vestri dead during the siege itself — turning fallen defenders against their living comrades, a standard Deceiver tactic designed to break morale. It worked against human armies. It failed against the Vestri. Something in the Mithril Legion’s oath — their binding commitment to defend Aldenheim, sworn on the Lord of Stone and the Lady of Fire together — resisted the raising. The Dómnathar necromancers could animate the bodies, but they could not control the will. The draugr rose, stood for a moment in the ranks of the Deceiver host, and then turned on their handlers.

In the chaos of the siege’s final days, the draugr scattered. The melting of Aldenheim destroyed most of them. Some survived — walking out of the fire-storm, still carrying their warhammers, still wearing their cracked Legion armour. These draugr dispersed along the Dead Road — the route the Deceiver host had marched from Hillmeet through the Tidebloom Reach — and took up residence in the barrow-mounds and battlefield graves that line the route.

Three centuries later, draugr still patrol the Dead Road. They emerge from their barrows at night, walk the old battle-routes, and attack anything that registers as Dómnathar. They do not distinguish between Dómnathar agents, Deceiver-aligned goblinoids, and creatures that merely carry a trace of void-resonance (such as Cadı Kuşu or certain half-Dómnathar). This lack of discrimination makes them dangerous to travelers along the Dead Road who may carry Dómnathar-tainted items without knowing it.

Vestri Dwarves regard draugr with agonised reverence. The Vestri do not destroy draugr — to do so would be to kill the Mithril Legion a second time. Instead, Vestri burial-priests visit known draugr barrows annually, performing the Rite of Naming: speaking the name of each draugr aloud, reciting their rank and unit in the Legion, and asking if they wish to rest. No draugr has ever accepted. The Vestri consider the rite an obligation, not a hope — they know the draugr will not rest until the Dómnathar are gone from Oreka entirely.

Tidebloom Reach communities along the Dead Road have learned to coexist with draugr through avoidance. Settlements near barrow-mounds do not travel the road at night, do not carry Dómnathar-associated artifacts, and do not disturb the barrows. Communities that follow these rules are rarely troubled. Those that violate them — treasure-hunters who open barrows, merchants who trade in Dómnathar salvage — find the draugr less forgiving.

Pasua elves who patrol the Tidebloom forests encounter draugr occasionally and treat them with solemn respect. The Far Riders who died in the Running War fought alongside the Mithril Legion in the final days — the two forces shared the battlefield at Aldenheim. Pasua rangers who meet a draugr warband on the Dead Road step aside, speak a Pasua blessing for the fallen, and let them pass.

### Lore

**DC 15 (Knowledge [religion]):** Draugr are undead Vestri Dwarves of the Mithril Legion, the army that fell defending Aldenheim. They patrol the Dead Road and attack anything connected to the Dómnathar.

**DC 20:** The Dómnathar raised the Mithril Legion’s dead during the siege, but the Vestri warriors’ oath-binding resisted control. The draugr broke free and turned on their handlers. They can sense Dómnathar void-signatures within 120 feet. Their death grip drains Strength through supernatural cold.

**DC 25:** Vestri burial-priests perform annual Rites of Naming at draugr barrows, speaking each warrior’s name and asking if they wish to rest. None have ever accepted. Draugr warbands still use Mithril Legion hand-signals and maintain formation discipline. They do not discriminate between Dómnathar agents and creatures that merely carry void-taint, making them dangerous to unwitting travelers on the Dead Road.

# DREAD WRAITH

It comes through the wall without opening the wall. One moment the corridor is empty; the next, a shape of absolute darkness occupies the space where the torchlight ends — not shadow, because shadow is the absence of light, and this is the presence of something else. It is cold the way a blade is sharp: not a quality of the air but a quality of the thing itself, radiating outward, turning breath to frost at thirty feet. Its face — if the darkness where a face should be can be called a face — is a hollow, a void, a place where a person used to be. It reaches for you with hands that have no substance and all the weight of grief.

**Large Undead (Incorporeal)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Undead (Incorporeal) |
| **Hit Dice** | 16d12 (104 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +13 |
| **Speed** | Fly 60 ft. (good) |
| **Armor Class** | 25 (–1 size, +9 Dex, +7 deflection), touch 25, flat-footed 16 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +8/— |
| **Attack** | Incorporeal touch +16 melee touch (2d6 plus 1d8 Constitution drain) |
| **Full Attack** | Incorporeal touch +16 melee touch (2d6 plus 1d8 Constitution drain) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./10 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Constitution drain, create spawn, lifesense |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., daylight powerlessness, incorporeal traits, +4 turn resistance, undead traits, unnatural aura, undead resonance |
| **Saves** | Fort +5, Ref +14, Will +14 |
| **Abilities** | Str —, Dex 28, Con —, Int 17, Wis 18, Cha 24 |
| **Skills** | Diplomacy +13, Hide +24, Intimidate +26, Knowledge (religion) +14, Listen +25, Search +22, Sense Motive +15, Spot +25, Survival +4 (+6 following tracks) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Blind-Fight, Combat Reflexes, Improved Initiative, Improved Natural Attack (incorporeal touch), Spring Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — a dread wraith is elemental negation, a wound in the fabric where resonance used to exist |
| **Environment** | Any (found wherever sufficient death-energy has accumulated — the Lament of Kings, major battlefields of the Deceivers’ War, the ruins of Hillmeet and Foxfen, and deep Giant tombs where the Thalorien’s grief pooled into darkness) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or gang (2–5 wraiths led by 1 dread wraith) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 11 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always lawful evil |
| **Advancement** | 17–32 HD (Large) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A dread wraith is an apex incorporeal predator — faster than a horse, untouchable by nonmagical weapons, and capable of draining a creature’s life-force with a single touch. It does not ambush. It does not need to. It flies through walls, floors, and ceilings, appearing wherever its targets are least prepared, and attacks with Spring Attack — touching a target and withdrawing through solid matter before the party can respond.

A dread wraith targets the strongest-looking opponent first — not out of tactical logic, but because the strongest Constitution drain produces the most powerful spawn. It fights with cold intelligence, using its incorporeal nature to attack from unexpected angles: through the floor, through the wall behind the party’s defensive line, straight up through the ground beneath a spellcaster’s feet.

Against turn attempts, a dread wraith’s +4 turn resistance makes it difficult to affect, and it retreats through the nearest wall if a cleric’s turning threatens to succeed. It returns when the turning effect expires.

A dread wraith’s unnatural aura (60 ft., animals panicked) strips the party of mounts, animal companions, and familiars before combat begins.

### Special Abilities

**Constitution Drain (Su):** A living creature hit by a dread wraith’s incorporeal touch must succeed on a DC 25 Fortitude save or take 1d8 Constitution drain. The save DC is Charisma-based. On each successful drain, the dread wraith gains 5 temporary hit points (lasting 1 hour).

**Create Spawn (Su):** A humanoid killed by a dread wraith’s Constitution drain rises as a wraith (not a dread wraith) in 1d4 rounds. The spawn is under the dread wraith’s command. A dread wraith can control up to 12 HD of spawn.

**Lifesense (Su):** A dread wraith notices and locates living creatures within 60 feet, just as if it possessed the blindsight ability.

**Daylight Powerlessness (Ex):** A dread wraith caught in natural sunlight is helpless (it can take no actions) and flees at full speed toward the nearest darkness.

**Unnatural Aura (Su):** Animals within 60 feet of a dread wraith become panicked and remain so for as long as they are within the aura.

**Undead Resonance (Su):** A dread wraith does not merely distort the elemental fabric — it wounds it. On Kin-sense, a dread wraith registers as a hole: not the Dómnathar void (which is a suppression of resonance) but an active negation, as though something were consuming the elemental energy in its vicinity. Kin within 120 ft. feel the fabric thinning — a coldness not of temperature but of meaning, as though the world were less real in the wraith’s proximity.

The effect is deeply disturbing and impossible to mistake for anything else. Experienced Kin describe it as “the feeling that the world has a wound that is bleeding where you cannot see.” The resonance-wound extends further than most undead signatures, which is what makes dread wraiths so dangerous — they can be detected at range, but the detection itself is psychologically destabilising.

### Society

Dread wraiths are not social creatures. They are concentrations of death-energy that have achieved predatory intelligence — the undead equivalent of a storm system that has learned to hunt.

In Oreka, dread wraiths are found at sites of mass death. The Lament of Kings — the blasted plain where Aldenheim was destroyed — is the densest concentration of wraith activity in the world. The melting of the mountain killed thousands of Kin and Dómnathar alike, and the sheer volume of death-energy, combined with the permanent destabilisation of the Kin-sense fabric in the area, created conditions that sustain dread wraiths indefinitely.

The ruins of Hillmeet and Foxfen in the Tidebloom Reach harbour dread wraiths that originated during the Deceivers’ War — the massacres at these settlements produced enough concentrated death to spawn wraiths that have persisted for three centuries.

Vestri Dwarves maintain a perimeter around the Lament of Kings — the “Dead Line” — beyond which civilian travel is prohibited. Vestri Stoneguard units patrol the Dead Line and respond to wraith incursions with clerical support and magical weaponry. The Vestri consider the Lament their sacred obligation — the site where Aldenheim fell is Vestri ground, and the wraiths that haunt it are Vestri dead.

Tidebloom communities near Hillmeet and Foxfen have largely abandoned the areas closest to the ruins. Settlements that remain maintain night-watch protocols and employ at least one cleric capable of turning undead.

### Lore

**DC 16 (Knowledge [religion]):** Dread wraiths are powerful incorporeal undead that drain Constitution with a touch. Creatures killed by them rise as wraith spawn. They are helpless in natural sunlight.

**DC 21:** A dread wraith’s Constitution drain is exceptionally severe (1d8 per touch) and it targets the strongest opponents to produce the most powerful spawn. They attack through walls and floors, making conventional defensive positions useless.

**DC 26:** Dread wraiths are concentrated death-energy — found at mass-death sites including the Lament of Kings and the Deceivers’ War ruins at Hillmeet and Foxfen. Their Kin-sense resonance wounds the elemental fabric rather than merely distorting it. Vestri Stoneguard units maintain a perimeter around the Lament to contain wraith activity.

# DRYAD

She is standing inside the oak. Not behind it — inside it, her body half-merged with the bark, her skin the colour of heartwood, her hair a cascade of leaves that shift with a breeze that does not touch any other tree. Her eyes are green. Not metaphorically — green the way chlorophyll is green, the green of photosynthesis, the green of something that feeds on light. She watches you with an expression that is not human curiosity. It is the expression of a tree noticing that something is standing in its shade.

**Medium Fey**

