| **Armor Class** | 17 (+4 Dex, +3 natural), touch 14, flat-footed 13 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +2/+2 |
| **Attack** | Dagger +6 melee (1d4/19–20) or masterwork longbow +7 ranged (1d8/×3) |
| **Full Attack** | Dagger +6 melee (1d4/19–20) or masterwork longbow +7 ranged (1d8/×3) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Spell-like abilities |
| **Special Qualities** | Damage reduction 5/cold iron, tree dependent, wild empathy, elemental resonance (Earth/Water), the Harmony |
| **Saves** | Fort +3, Ref +8, Will +6 |
| **Abilities** | Str 10, Dex 19, Con 11, Int 14, Wis 15, Cha 18 |
| **Skills** | Escape Artist +11, Handle Animal +11, Hide +11, Knowledge (nature) +11, Listen +9, Move Silently +11, Ride +6, Spot +9, Survival +9 |
| **Feats** | Great Fortitude, Weapon Finesse |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) / Lady of the Sea (Water) — root and sap; the dryad is bound to the land and the water that sustains it |
| **Environment** | Great Forests (old-growth oak groves, ancient forest, anywhere a single tree has stood long enough to develop fey resonance — primarily Hasura territory, Twin Rivers old-growth, and the deeper Pasua forest-margins) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or grove (2–5) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 3 |
| **Treasure** | Standard |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic good |
| **Advancement** | By character class |
| **Level Adjustment** | +2 |

### Combat

A dryad does not fight if she can avoid it. She uses charm person to turn aggressors into allies, suggestion to redirect hostile intent, and tree stride to escape into the forest if charm fails. A dryad fights with weapons only as a last resort — when her tree is directly threatened and escape is not an option.

If forced to fight, a dryad uses her longbow from within or adjacent to her tree, taking advantage of tree-merge (stepping into the trunk for total cover, emerging to fire, stepping back in). Against axe-wielding opponents who threaten her tree, she abandons all restraint — charm attempts, entangle to root them in place, and sustained bow-fire until the threat is eliminated.

A dryad grove defending against a logging operation or a fire is a serious encounter. Multiple dryads using charm person, suggestion, and entangle simultaneously can immobilize and confuse a party while one or two dryads with bows pick off targets. The forest itself becomes the weapon.

### Special Abilities

**Spell-Like Abilities:** At will — entangle (DC 15), speak with plants, tree shape; 3/day — charm person (DC 15), deep slumber (DC 17), tree stride; 1/day — suggestion (DC 17). Caster level 6th. Save DCs are Charisma-based.

**Tree Dependent (Su):** A dryad is mystically bonded to a single, specific tree. She can move no more than 300 yards from her tree. If the tree is destroyed, the dryad dies within 4d6 hours. A dryad who spends more than 24 hours away from her tree becomes sickened until she returns.

**Wild Empathy (Ex):** A dryad can improve the attitude of an animal, functioning as a Diplomacy check. She rolls 1d20+6.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a dryad registers as a deep, quiet, earth-water signature — the Lord of Stone’s permanence filtered through the Lady of the Sea’s flow, manifesting as the feeling of standing beside a very old tree on a rainy day. The resonance is gentle, ancient, and intimately tied to the specific tree the dryad is bonded to — Kin who detect a dryad’s resonance simultaneously feel the tree’s presence, as though the two were one entity with a shared signature.

Hasura elves find dryad resonance deeply comforting — it is the forest-signature in its purest, most concentrated form. Pasua elves respect it but find the intensity slightly unnerving, as though the forest were paying too much attention.

**The Harmony (Su):** Dryads possess the Harmony and can sense other dryads within 1 mile, as well as all plant life within 500 feet. This plant-awareness allows a dryad to monitor the health of the forest surrounding her tree and detect disturbances (logging, fire, blight) before they reach her grove.

### Society

Dryads are solitary fey, each bonded to a single tree for life. Their society, such as it is, consists of loose associations between dryads whose trees grow in proximity — a grove of three to five dryads in adjacent trees who share intelligence about threats, coordinate defense, and occasionally socialise.

Hasura elves have the deepest relationship with dryads. Hasura settlements are built within the Great Forest’s canopy, and Hasura druids actively protect dryad groves as sacred sites. A Hasura community that discovers a new dryad-tree adjusts its territory to buffer the tree from any threat — logging, fire, or traffic. Hasura druids consult dryads as local experts on forest health and use dryad intelligence about plant-awareness to detect disease, blight, and unnatural disturbances.

Pasua elves respect dryads but interact with them less frequently. Pasua territory lies along the forest-edge rather than in the deep forest, and dryad groves are typically deeper than Pasua patrols range.

Tanuki in the Twin Rivers forests have a cheerful, practical relationship with dryads — Tanuki longhouses are sometimes built near dryad-trees, and the Tanuki leave gifts (polished stones, woven garlands, small clay figurines) at the base of dryad-trees as a gesture of neighbourliness. Dryads tolerate Tanuki more readily than they tolerate most non-fey, partly because Tanuki shapeshifting resonates with fey nature and partly because Tanuki never cut living wood.

### Lore

**DC 13 (Knowledge [nature]):** Dryads are tree-bound fey that can charm visitors, cause plants to entangle intruders, and step between trees. They die if their bonded tree is destroyed.

**DC 18:** A dryad cannot move more than 300 yards from her tree. She can merge with the trunk for total cover. Hasura elves protect dryad groves as sacred and consult dryads about forest health.

**DC 23:** Dryad resonance on Kin-sense is inseparable from the resonance of her bonded tree — the two register as a single entity. Dryads monitor all plant life within 500 feet through the Harmony. Tanuki build longhouses near dryad-trees for mutual benefit.

# DULLAHAN

The rider comes down the Dead Road at a gallop, and the horse beneath it is wrong — too thin, too dark, its hooves striking sparks that glow the colour of old blood. The rider sits tall in the saddle, armoured in the remnants of Far Rider scout-leather, a sword in one hand and nothing on its shoulders. Nothing. The head is gone. Where the neck ends, a ragged stump of old flesh and exposed bone meets the open air, and the air around the stump shimmers with a faint, sick light that is neither fire nor moonlight but something between. The horse screams. The rider charges.

**Medium Undead**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Undead |
| **Hit Dice** | 10d12 (65 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +6 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares); mounted 60 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 22 (+2 Dex, +7 natural, +3 armour remnants), touch 12, flat-footed 20 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +5/+10 |
| **Attack** | +1 longsword +11 melee (1d8+8/19–20) or death lash +10 melee touch (see below) |
| **Full Attack** | +1 longsword +11/+6 melee (1d8+8/19–20) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. (15 ft. with death lash) |
| **Special Attacks** | Death lash, terrifying charge, death call |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 120 ft., damage reduction 10/magic, undead traits, turn resistance +4, spell resistance 20, mounted bond, elemental resonance (corrupted Air/Earth), Dómnathar scar, see without eyes |
| **Saves** | Fort +3, Ref +5, Will +9 |
| **Abilities** | Str 20, Dex 15, Con —, Int 10, Wis 14, Cha 18 |
| **Skills** | Handle Animal +10, Intimidate +17, Listen +12, Ride +15, Spot +12, Survival +10 |
| **Feats** | Improved Initiative, Mounted Combat, Ride-By Attack, Spirited Charge, Trample |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Corrupted — the dullahan carries a twisted echo of the Far Rider’s air-earth resonance (wind-over-grassland), broken by death and scarred by Dómnathar raising |
| **Environment** | Great Forests and Eternal Steppe (the Dead Road and the old Far Rider patrol routes that stretch from the forest-steppe border through the Tidebloom Reach to the edges of the Lament of Kings; occasionally found in deep Pasua territory where Far Rider outposts once stood) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or patrol (2–4 dullahan riding together) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 7 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (Far Rider equipment, scout-leather, longswords, and occasionally items of personal or historical significance — letters, tokens, campaign medals) |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic neutral |
| **Advancement** | 11–15 HD (Medium) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A dullahan fights from horseback — always. It was a cavalryman in life and it is a cavalryman in death, and its undead mount is as much a part of it as its sword arm. A dullahan’s preferred tactic is the charge: it rides at full gallop, delivers a Spirited Charge with its longsword (triple damage with a lance, double with the sword), and uses Ride-By Attack to carry past the target without stopping.

Against groups, a dullahan charges through the formation, using Trample to damage creatures in its path, then wheels and charges again. It repeats this pattern — charge, wheel, charge — until the group is broken or the dullahan is destroyed. Between charges, it uses death lash to strike at range, the spectral whip reaching targets that thought they were safe at 15 feet.

A dullahan’s death call — a wordless scream from a throat that has no head to shape it — functions as a targeted death effect that can stop a heart. The dullahan uses this sparingly, reserving it for the most dangerous opponent or for a creature that has harmed its mount.

A dullahan patrol is one of the most dangerous encounters on the Dead Road. Two to four headless riders charging in formation, covering each other’s flanks, wheeling in unison — the Mithril Legion’s draugr fight on foot, but the dullahan fight as they lived: from the saddle, at speed, with the wind in their faces (or where their faces used to be).

Against Dómnathar, dullahan respond with the same scar-driven fury as draugr. The Dómnathar raising that failed left the same void-thread in the dullahan’s undead essence, and they sense Deceiver presence at 120 feet. A dullahan that detects Dómnathar drops all other priorities and hunts.

### Special Abilities

**Death Lash (Su):** As a standard action, a dullahan can project a lash of necrotic energy from its stump — a spectral whip that strikes as a melee touch attack with 15-foot reach. A creature struck takes 2d6 negative energy damage and must succeed on a DC 19 Fortitude save or gain 1 negative level. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Terrifying Charge (Su):** When a dullahan charges, all creatures within 30 feet of its charge path must succeed on a Will save (DC 19) or be frightened for 1d4 rounds. This is a mind-affecting fear effect. The save DC is Charisma-based. The terror is not rational — it is the primal horror of a headless rider coming at full gallop, sword raised, an empty neck-stump where a face should be.

**Death Call (Su):** Once per day, a dullahan can release a death call targeting a single creature within 60 feet. The target must succeed on a Fortitude save (DC 19) or die instantly. A creature that succeeds takes 5d6 negative energy damage. This is a death effect. The save DC is Charisma-based. The death call is a scream — raw, wordless, vibrating through the air and through the Kin-sense simultaneously. Creatures that succeed on the save still hear it in their dreams for 1d6 nights afterward.

**Mounted Bond (Su):** A dullahan is supernaturally bonded to its undead mount — a war-horse raised alongside the rider, sharing the same failed Dómnathar raising and the same broken-free will. The mount has the statistics of a heavy warhorse with the undead template (darkvision 60 ft., undead traits, DR 5/magic). The bond is absolute: a dullahan whose mount is destroyed becomes staggered (can take only a single move or standard action per round) until it bonds to a new mount (a process requiring 24 hours of proximity to an appropriate dead horse). A mount whose rider is destroyed collapses into inert bone and leather.

**See Without Eyes (Su):** A dullahan has no head, but perceives its surroundings through a supernatural awareness equivalent to blindsight 120 feet combined with darkvision 120 feet. It cannot be blinded, dazzled, or affected by gaze attacks.

**Dómnathar Scar (Su):** As with draugr, dullahan carry a void-thread from the failed raising. They sense Dómnathar void-signatures within 120 feet and respond with immediate, single-minded aggression.

**Corrupted Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a dullahan registers as a broken Far Rider signature — the air-earth resonance of wind-over-grassland, corrupted by death into something cold and rushing, like a winter gale that carries the smell of old blood. The void-thread of the Dómnathar scar runs through the corrupted resonance like a dark vein.

For Pasua elves and Mytroan steppe-riders, detecting a dullahan’s resonance is deeply personal. The Far Riders were Pasua scouts and Mytroan cavalrymen — the mounted vanguard of the Kin armies during the Running War. Their resonance, even corrupted, carries the echo of the steppe and the forest-edge. Pasua rangers who encounter dullahan patrols report hearing hoofbeats in the resonance — the ghost of a gallop that has been running for three hundred years.

### Society

Dullahan are the undead Far Riders — the elite mounted scouts who fought in the Running War, the extended campaign against the Deceiver host as it marched north through the Eternal Steppe and into the Tidebloom Reach. The Far Riders were drawn from Pasua ranger companies and Mytroan light cavalry bands, chosen for their riding skill, their knowledge of the terrain, and their willingness to operate far ahead of the main army, harrying the enemy’s flanks and disrupting supply lines.

They died in the hundreds. The Running War was a fighting retreat — the Kin armies could not stop the Deceiver host in open battle, and the Far Riders paid the highest cost, trading lives for time. Those who fell in the northern reaches — the Tidebloom, the Kinsweave, the approaches to Aldenheim — were caught by Dómnathar necromancers who raised the dead as fast as they fell.

The Dómnathar expected obedient cavalry. What they got was something else. The Far Riders’ bond with their horses — a bond that in life was cultural and emotional — in death became supernatural and unbreakable. The Dómnathar raising animated the riders and their mounts together, and the combined will of rider and horse resisted the Deceiver’s control. The dullahan rose headless (the Dómnathar raising process severs the head to break the individual’s identity, a technique that works on most humanoids) but the Far Riders were not most humanoids. Their identity was not in their faces. It was in their riding.

The dullahan broke free, scattered across the Dead Road and the old patrol routes, and have been riding ever since. They follow the paths they knew in life — forest trails, steppe tracks, the old harrying routes along the Deceiver host’s march — and they attack anything that carries the void-taint.

Pasua elves regard dullahan with the same agonised reverence the Vestri show their draugr. The Far Riders were Pasua — they rode from Pasua longhouses, they carried Pasua trail-marks, they died in Pasua service. That they are still riding, still fighting, three centuries after death, is simultaneously the proudest and most painful fact in Pasua military history.

Mytroan steppe-riders encounter dullahan patrols in the Eternal Steppe and react with fear and respect. A Mytroan band that sees a dullahan patrol approaching clears the path and waits in silence until the riders pass. Some Mytroan elders claim that a dullahan patrol will not attack a Mytroan who speaks the old cavalry call-signs — the identification phrases used during the Running War — though testing this theory requires a level of courage that most Mytroans sensibly decline.

### Lore

**DC 17 (Knowledge [religion]):** Dullahan are headless undead riders that patrol the Dead Road and old Far Rider routes. They charge with devastating mounted tactics and can kill with a wordless scream. They are bonded to undead mounts.

**DC 22:** Dullahan were Far Riders raised by Dómnathar necromancers who severed their heads to break their identity. It didn’t work — the riders’ identity was in their horsemanship, not their faces. They broke free and have been riding for three hundred years. They sense Dómnathar at 120 feet.

**DC 27:** Pasua rangers consider dullahan their fallen kindred and let patrols pass with spoken blessings. Mytroan tradition claims the old Running War call-signs can prevent a dullahan attack, though this is unconfirmed. A dullahan whose mount is destroyed is severely weakened. Their resonance carries the echo of wind-over-grassland — the ghost of the steppe they rode in life.

# DUST MEPHIT

It materialises from the air itself — or rather, from the dust in the air, drawing particles together into a shape roughly the size and temperament of an angry cat with wings. Its body is gritty, compacted sand and dust that shifts and hisses when it moves. Its eyes are two sparks of dull amber. Its voice, when it speaks (and it will speak — dust mephits never shut up), sounds like sand pouring through a crack.

**Small Outsider (Air, Earth)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Small Outsider (Air, Earth) |
| **Hit Dice** | 3d8 (13 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +7 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), fly 50 ft. (perfect) |
| **Armor Class** | 17 (+1 size, +3 Dex, +3 natural), touch 14, flat-footed 14 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +3/–1 |
| **Attack** | Claw +4 melee (1d3) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 claws +4 melee (1d3) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Breath weapon, spell-like abilities, summon mephit |
| **Special Qualities** | Damage reduction 5/magic, darkvision 60 ft., fast healing 2 (in arid/dusty environments), elemental resonance (Air/Earth) |
| **Saves** | Fort +3, Ref +6, Will +3 |
| **Abilities** | Str 10, Dex 17, Con 10, Int 6, Wis 11, Cha 15 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +8, Hide +13, Listen +6, Diplomacy +4, Move Silently +9, Spot +6 |
| **Feats** | Dodge, Improved Initiative |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Youngest Brother (Air) / Lord of Stone (Earth) — minor elemental; dust is where wind meets dry earth |
| **Environment** | The Infinite Desert (sandstorms, dust-devils, ruin interiors, dry canyon systems); secondary presence wherever arid conditions meet high winds (Scorchspire valleys, Glass Wastes, Ashen Crown leeward slopes) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or gang (3–6) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 3 |
| **Treasure** | Standard |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 4–6 HD (Small); 7–9 HD (Medium) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +3 |

### Combat

Dust mephits are nuisances, not threats — unless encountered in numbers. A single dust mephit fights by blinding opponents with its breath weapon, then darting in for claw attacks before retreating to range. A gang of dust mephits cycles this pattern continuously: one blinds, the others attack, then another blinds and the first group attacks.

Their fast healing in arid environments makes them persistent — in the Infinite Desert, a dust mephit recovers from damage almost as quickly as it is dealt, and destroying one requires sustained, focused effort. They use their flight to stay above melee range and their small size to dodge ranged attacks.

Dust mephits summon allies when pressed — usually another dust mephit, which arrives irritated and noisy. A fight with dust mephits in the desert tends to escalate as reinforcements arrive.

### Special Abilities

**Breath Weapon (Su):** 10-foot cone of grit and sand, blinding creatures for 1d4 rounds (Reflex DC 13 negates). Usable once every 1d4 rounds. The save DC is Constitution-based plus a +2 racial bonus.

**Spell-Like Abilities:** 1/day — blur, wind wall. Caster level 3rd.

**Summon Mephit (Sp):** Once per day, a dust mephit can attempt to summon another dust mephit with a 25% success rate.

**Fast Healing (Ex):** A dust mephit heals 2 hit points per round in any arid or dusty environment. This fast healing does not function in wet or humid conditions.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a dust mephit registers as a small, skittering air-earth signature — the resonance of a dust-devil, wind and dry earth spinning together. The signature is faint, chaotic, and mildly irritating — Kin describe it as “an itch you can’t quite locate.” It is easy to detect (DC 10) but difficult to take seriously, which is how dust mephits prefer it.

### Society

Dust mephits are minor elementals — intelligent, talkative, self-important, and largely harmless. They form naturally in the Infinite Desert wherever sustained wind meets dry earth in conditions of elemental resonance — sandstorms, dust-devils, and the hot, dry winds that howl through canyon systems.

They are common enough in the Infinite Desert to be considered a routine environmental feature. Pekakarlik Desert Walkers treat dust mephits the way most people treat mosquitoes — annoying, persistent, and not worth the energy to destroy unless they become actively disruptive. A Pekakarlik caravan moving through dust mephit territory designates one member as the “sand-talker” — a person whose sole job is to engage the mephits in conversation and keep them distracted while the caravan passes. Dust mephits are vain and garrulous; a sufficiently flattering listener can keep one talking for hours.

Mytroan desert caravans are less patient. Mytroan scouts drive dust mephits away with targeted bursts of water (a waterskin splash is usually sufficient — dust mephits despise moisture and flee from it).

Dust mephits occasionally form temporary alliances with more powerful desert creatures, serving as scouts or messengers in exchange for protection. Their intelligence is limited, their loyalty is nonexistent, and their information is frequently wrong, but they are fast, they can fly, and they are everywhere.

### Lore

**DC 13 (Knowledge [the planes]):** Dust mephits are small, chatty minor elementals found in the Infinite Desert. Their breath weapon blinds with grit. They heal quickly in dry environments and can summon reinforcements.

**DC 18:** Dust mephits are vain and can be distracted through flattery. They despise moisture and flee from water. Pekakarlik caravans assign a “sand-talker” to keep them occupied during passage.

# DYBBUK

The goblin stops mid-sentence. Its companions notice the silence first — Krikkit never stops talking, has not stopped talking since the day it learned Common from a halfling trader — and then they notice the eyes. Krikkit’s eyes have gone flat. Not dead. Not vacant. Full, the way a cup is full when someone has poured something different into it. The goblin’s mouth opens and a voice comes out that is not Krikkit’s voice. It is older, heavier, and it speaks Goblin with an accent that hasn’t been used in three hundred years.

**Medium Undead (Incorporeal)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Undead (Incorporeal) |
| **Hit Dice** | 6d12 (39 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +5 |
| **Speed** | Fly 30 ft. (perfect) |
| **Armor Class** | 17 (+1 Dex, +6 deflection), touch 17, flat-footed 16 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +3/— |
| **Attack** | Incorporeal touch +4 melee touch (1d4 Wisdom damage) |
| **Full Attack** | Incorporeal touch +4 melee touch (1d4 Wisdom damage) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Wisdom damage, possession, wail of the unfinished |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., incorporeal traits, +2 turn resistance, undead traits, goblinoid resonance, unfinished purpose |
| **Saves** | Fort +2, Ref +3, Will +7 |
| **Abilities** | Str —, Dex 13, Con —, Int 12, Wis 16, Cha 18 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +13, Hide +10, Intimidate +13, Listen +12, Search +10, Sense Motive +12, Spot +12 |
| **Feats** | Ability Focus (possession), Improved Initiative, Iron Will |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — goblinoid dead carry the same absence of elemental resonance as living goblinoids, but twisted by undeath into something colder |
| **Environment** | Any area with goblinoid populations (Deepwater Marches free goblin settlements, Eternal Steppe Warg communities that harbour goblins, Dómnathar tunnel fringes where goblin auxiliaries are stationed) |
| **Organization** | Solitary (always) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 5 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic neutral |
| **Advancement** | 7–12 HD (Medium) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A dybbuk does not fight in its incorporeal form if it can avoid it. It is a possessor, not a combatant — its goal is to enter a living goblinoid body and use it to complete whatever task anchors it to the world. In incorporeal form, it is vulnerable: low hit points, no damage reduction, and a touch attack that deals Wisdom damage but does not kill quickly.

When forced to fight without a host, a dybbuk uses its wail of the unfinished to stun nearby creatures, then attempts to possess the most vulnerable goblinoid in range. If no goblinoid is available, it flees through the nearest wall or floor, searching for a goblinoid community to infiltrate.

When possessing a host, a dybbuk fights with whatever the host’s body is capable of — the dybbuk retains the host’s physical statistics, equipment, and proficiencies, overlaid with the dybbuk’s mental ability scores, skills, and purpose-driven aggression. A possessed goblin warrior is a dangerous opponent because it fights without fear, without pain, and without the self-preservation instinct that normally limits goblinoid aggression.

A dybbuk does not willingly abandon a host. It must be forced out through magic (protection from evil, dispel evil) or through the host’s death. If the host dies, the dybbuk is ejected in incorporeal form and is stunned for 1 round, during which it is vulnerable.

### Special Abilities

**Wisdom Damage (Su):** A dybbuk’s incorporeal touch deals 1d4 Wisdom damage. The save DC to resist is 17 (Will negates). The damage manifests as confusion, disorientation, and the sensation of hearing a voice inside your skull that is not yours. The save DC is Charisma-based. A creature reduced to 0 Wisdom is unconscious and vulnerable to possession.

**Possession (Su):** As a full-round action, a dybbuk can attempt to possess a goblinoid creature within 5 feet. The target must succeed on a Will save (DC 19) or be possessed. The dybbuk enters the target’s body and takes control, suppressing the host’s personality and memories (but not erasing them — the host is aware of everything that happens while possessed, but cannot act). The save DC is Charisma-based and includes the +2 from Ability Focus.

A dybbuk can only possess goblinoid creatures — goblins, hobgoblins, bugbears, and almas. It cannot possess Kin, animals, or non-goblinoid humanoids. This limitation is absolute and defining: the dybbuk is a goblinoid spirit, and its possession resonates only with goblinoid physiology.

The possession lasts until the host body dies, the dybbuk is forced out by magic (protection from evil suppresses the possession for the spell’s duration; dispel evil, DC 19, ejects the dybbuk permanently), or the dybbuk voluntarily departs. A possessed creature radiates a faint aura of undeath detectable with detect undead.

**Wail of the Unfinished (Su):** Once per day, a dybbuk can release a keening wail — a sound of desperate, frustrated incompletion — that affects all creatures within 30 feet. Targets must succeed on a Will save (DC 17) or be stunned for 1 round. This is a sonic, mind-affecting effect. The save DC is Charisma-based. The wail sounds different to every listener: some hear a scream of rage, others a sob of grief, others a single word repeated in a language they don’t speak.

**Goblinoid Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a dybbuk in incorporeal form registers as wild static — the same unreadable signal produced by all goblinoid creatures — but cold, thin, and unmistakably dead. It is wild static heard through ice. A DC 16 Kin-sense check detects the dybbuk; a DC 20 check identifies it as undead rather than living goblinoid.

A dybbuk possessing a host suppresses most of the undead quality — the host reads as a normal goblinoid on casual Kin-sense, with only a faint chill in the static that might be mistaken for the host being unwell. A DC 22 Kin-sense check detects the undead presence beneath the living signal.

**Unfinished Purpose (Su):** Every dybbuk is anchored to the living world by a specific, unfulfilled task — something the goblinoid failed to complete before death. The task varies: protect a specific individual, deliver a message, find a lost object, warn a community of danger, avenge a betrayal. The dybbuk is compelled to pursue this task above all else. If the task is completed, the dybbuk is released — it simply fades, the incorporeal form dissolving into nothing as the purpose that held it unravels.

A creature that discovers a dybbuk’s unfinished purpose (through Sense Motive DC 20 against a possessed host, or through commune/speak with dead targeting the dybbuk directly) can potentially resolve the possession peacefully by helping the dybbuk complete its task. This is the preferred resolution in goblin communities that understand what a dybbuk is.

### Society

Dybbuk are the restless dead of the goblinoid peoples — spirits of goblins, hobgoblins, bugbears, and almas who died with a critical purpose unfulfilled. They are unique to goblinoid dead; no Kin race produces dybbuk, and no other non-Kin people generates them. The phenomenon is poorly understood by Kin scholars because Kin scholars have limited access to goblinoid death-customs, and the goblinoid peoples themselves treat dybbuk as a private matter — a problem within the community, to be handled by the community.

Free goblin settlements in the Deepwater Marches have the most developed tradition around dybbuk. Goblin shamans (typically adepts or low-level sorcerers) serve as *ruah-speakers* — mediators between the dybbuk and the living community. When a possession is identified, the ruah-speaker’s first task is to determine the dybbuk’s unfinished purpose through dialogue with the possessed host. If the purpose is achievable (deliver a message, return a stolen item, warn of a specific danger), the community helps complete it, and the dybbuk departs peacefully.

If the purpose is unachievable (avenge a death that occurred centuries ago, find an object that no longer exists, protect a person who is already dead), the ruah-speaker must negotiate — convincing the dybbuk that its purpose cannot be fulfilled and that continuing to possess a living host serves nothing. This negotiation is the hardest part of a ruah-speaker’s work, because a dybbuk whose purpose is unachievable is a dybbuk that will never willingly leave, and forcing it out through violence or magic condemns it to wander in incorporeal form until it finds another host.

Warg communities that harbour goblins encounter dybbuk occasionally and treat them with pragmatic tolerance. The Wargs cannot be possessed (they are not goblinoid) but their goblin dependents can, and Warg pack-leaders who discover a possession typically seek out a goblin ruah-speaker to resolve it. Some Warg oral traditions include stories of dybbuk that completed their tasks and departed peacefully — these stories are told with respect, not horror, suggesting that the Wargs view dybbuk as a natural (if inconvenient) part of goblinoid existence.

Dómnathar-aligned goblin auxiliaries produce dybbuk at a higher rate than free goblin populations — the combination of violent death, suppressed autonomy, and unfulfilled commands creates ideal conditions for dybbuk formation. Dómnathar handlers consider dybbuk a nuisance and destroy them when detected, which goblin auxiliaries resent deeply and in silence.

Kin scholars who are aware of dybbuk classify them as “purpose-bound undead” — spirits anchored by task rather than by location or emotion. The Al Karisi is bound by grief; the banshee by grief and location; the dybbuk by purpose alone. This makes dybbuk the most mobile and least predictable of Oreka’s undead — they go wherever their purpose leads, crossing regional boundaries and cultural lines without regard for the living world’s geography.

### Lore

Characters with ranks in Knowledge (religion) can learn the following about dybbuk.

**DC 15:** Dybbuk are incorporeal undead spirits that possess goblinoid creatures. They can only enter goblins, hobgoblins, bugbears, and almas. A possessed host behaves strangely — speaking in archaic dialects, pursuing unknown goals, fighting without fear.

**DC 20:** Every dybbuk is driven by an unfulfilled purpose from its life. Identifying and completing that purpose causes the dybbuk to depart peacefully. Protection from evil suppresses the possession; dispel evil ejects it permanently. Free goblin communities have ruah-speakers who mediate between dybbuk and the living.

**DC 25:** Dybbuk are unique to goblinoid dead — no other race in Oreka produces them. Dómnathar-aligned goblin populations generate dybbuk at higher rates due to violent deaths and suppressed autonomy. A dybbuk possessing a host is nearly undetectable on Kin-sense (DC 22) — it reads as a living goblinoid with a faint chill. Warg communities treat dybbuk with pragmatic tolerance rather than horror.

# DIRE ANIMALS

In the wild places of Oreka — the deep forests, the far steppe, the high mountains — there are animals that are more than animals. They are larger, stronger, fiercer, and older than anything in their species has a right to be. Their eyes carry a weight of awareness that is not quite intelligence but is more than instinct. Mytroan herders call them *büyük kan* — “great blood.” Hasura druids call them *aranduin* — “the sire-marked.” Pekakarlik naturalists call them what they are: the offspring of Paragons.

## The Paragon Connection

Dire animals in Oreka are not a separate species. They are the direct descendants of Paragons — the immortal spirit-guardians that embody the ideal of each animal species. When a Paragon mates (a rare event, occurring perhaps once in a century), the offspring is a dire animal: a creature that carries a fragment of the Paragon’s elemental resonance in its blood, expressed as greater size, enhanced physical capabilities, and a lifespan far exceeding its mundane counterpart.

A dire animal is always born to a mundane mother — the Paragon’s essence overwhelms the natural template, producing a creature that is recognisably the same species but pushed to extremes. A dire wolf born to a normal she-wolf is unmistakable from birth: larger, more aggressive, and radiating a Kin-sense signature that is stronger and more defined than any normal animal’s Harmony signal.

Dire animals are rare. Each Paragon produces at most a handful of offspring per century, and not all survive to adulthood. Their rarity is what makes them significant — a dire animal in a region signals the presence (or recent presence) of a Paragon, which in turn signals that the elemental balance in that area is stable enough to support one.

**Kin-Sense Signature:** All dire animals register on Kin-sense as enhanced versions of their mundane counterparts’ Harmony signal — the same warmth, the same species-signature, but louder, sharper, more defined. Kin who detect a dire animal’s resonance instinctively recognise it as something more than a normal beast. A DC 15 Kin-sense check identifies the “Paragon-echo” — the trace of the sire’s elemental identity running through the offspring’s signal.

**The Harmony:** Dire animals possess an amplified version of the Harmony. Where a normal wolf senses pack-mates within a few hundred feet, a dire wolf senses all wolves within 2 miles. This extended awareness makes dire animals natural pack-leaders and herd-dominants — other animals of the same species instinctively defer to them.

**Elemental Affinity:** Each dire animal carries the elemental affinity of its Paragon sire, expressed through its physiology and habitat preference. The specific affinity depends on the species and the regional Paragon that sired it.

