| **Hit Dice** | 8d10+40 (84 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +4 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 20 (–1 size, +11 natural), touch 9, flat-footed 20 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +8/+17 |
| **Attack** | Gore +12 melee (1d8+7) |
| **Full Attack** | Gore +12 melee (1d8+7) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Breath weapon, trample 1d8+7 |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, scent, elemental resonance (Earth/Fire) |
| **Saves** | Fort +11, Ref +6, Will +4 |
| **Abilities** | Str 21, Dex 10, Con 21, Int 2, Wis 12, Cha 9 |
| **Skills** | Listen +9, Spot +8 |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Improved Initiative, Iron Will |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) / Lady of Fire (Fire) — the gorgon is metal incarnate, the place where stone meets fire and becomes iron |
| **Environment** | Eternal Steppe (open grasslands, particularly the dry central steppe where iron-rich earth supports sparse, tough vegetation; secondary presence in the Scorchspire foothills where volcanic soils contain high metal concentrations) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or herd (3–4) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 8 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always neutral |
| **Advancement** | 9–12 HD (Large); 13–16 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A gorgon charges. That is its entire tactical repertoire: lower the iron-plated head and charge at whatever has entered its territory. The charge deals devastating gore damage, and the gorgon follows with a trample if the target goes down. Against targets that do not flee, it uses its petrifying breath — a 60-foot cone of green-grey gas that turns living flesh to stone.

Gorgons are territorial but not predatory. They are herbivores (iron-rich grasses and mineral-dense soil-licks) that attack to drive threats from their territory, not to eat them. A gorgon that successfully drives an intruder away does not pursue. The petrified remains of creatures that failed to flee litter gorgon territories like statues in a grotesque garden.

### Special Abilities

**Breath Weapon (Su):** 60-foot cone, petrification. A creature caught in the breath must succeed on a DC 19 Fortitude save or be permanently turned to stone. The breath can be used every 1d4 rounds. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Trample (Ex):** Reflex DC 19 half. Damage 1d8+7.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** A gorgon registers on Kin-sense as a dense, metallic earth/fire signature — iron and heat compressed into a living form. The resonance is heavy and vibrates at a frequency that sets teeth on edge. Kin describe detecting a gorgon’s resonance as “tasting iron.” The detection range is 200 feet due to the intensity of the signal — gorgons cannot hide their resonance.

### Society

Gorgons are solitary or small-herd animals that claim territories on the iron-rich steppe. They are not magical beasts by choice — they are animals that have been saturated with earth/fire elemental energy to the point where their physiology has become metallic. Kin scholars debate whether gorgons are a natural species or a Giant-era creation; the current consensus is that they are natural, formed over millennia in terrain where iron-rich soil and fire-element volcanic vents overlap.

Mytroan herders give gorgon territory absolute respect. A Mytroan band that identifies a gorgon herd’s grazing-range — easily done, because the iron-hooved beasts leave distinctive track-marks and the petrified remains of other animals mark the territory’s boundaries — detours around it, adding days to their route if necessary. The Mytroan consider gorgons to be among the steppe’s most dangerous animals, ranking them alongside dire lions and chimeras.

Rarozhki Dwarves value gorgon iron-hide as a crafting material of extraordinary quality. A gorgon hide, properly cured and worked, produces armour with a natural resistance to petrification effects. Rarozhki hunting parties that target gorgons are rare, well-equipped expeditions — losing a hunter to petrification is a real and common risk.

Centaur herds avoid gorgon territory instinctively. The centaurs’ Harmony — their species-specific resonance — detects gorgons at extreme range and triggers a deep, instinctive flight-response that centaur elders attribute to ancestral memory of catastrophic encounters.

### Lore

**DC 18 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Gorgons are iron-plated bulls whose breath weapon permanently turns creatures to stone. They are territorial herbivores found on the iron-rich central steppe. Their metallic hide vibrates with earth/fire resonance.

**DC 23:** Mytroan herders give gorgon territory absolute respect, detouring days around a herd’s range. Rarozhki Dwarves value gorgon hide as a crafting material that resists petrification. Gorgon territory is identifiable by distinctive track-marks and the petrified remains of other animals.

**DC 28:** Gorgons may be natural species formed by millennia of iron-rich soil and fire-element saturation, not Giant creations. Centaur Harmony detects gorgons at extreme range and triggers instinctive flight. The gorgon’s resonance is detectable at 200 feet and cannot be suppressed.

# GRAY OOZE

The stone floor is wet. Not water-wet — acid-wet, the kind of wet that dissolves boot-leather in seconds and eats through chainmail in minutes. The puddle on the floor is not a puddle. It is three inches deep, six feet across, and moving toward you with the purposeful slowness of something that has never needed to hurry because nothing it touches survives long enough to escape.

**Medium Ooze**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Ooze |
| **Hit Dice** | 3d10+15 (31 hp) |
| **Initiative** | –5 |
| **Speed** | 10 ft. (2 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 5 (–5 Dex), touch 5, flat-footed 5 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +2/+3 |
| **Attack** | Slam +3 melee (1d6+1 plus 1d6 acid) |
| **Full Attack** | Slam +3 melee (1d6+1 plus 1d6 acid) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Acid, improved grab, constrict 1d6+1 plus 1d6 acid |
| **Special Qualities** | Blindsight 60 ft., immunity to cold and fire, ooze traits, transparent |
| **Saves** | Fort +6, Ref –4, Will –4 |
| **Abilities** | Str 12, Dex 1, Con 21, Int —, Wis 1, Cha 1 |
| **Feats** | — |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — oozes exist outside the elemental framework |
| **Environment** | Underground (any subterranean environment — natural caves, mine-tunnels, Giant-era passages, Dómnathar corridors; most common in wet underground environments where runoff collects) |
| **Organization** | Solitary |
| **Challenge Rating** | 4 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always neutral |
| **Advancement** | 4–6 HD (Medium); 7–12 HD (Large) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A gray ooze lies flat on the floor, indistinguishable from wet stone (Spot DC 15), and waits for creatures to step on it. When contact is made, it attacks — slamming, grabbing, and constricting while its acid dissolves armour, weapons, and flesh.

A gray ooze’s acid is particularly dangerous to metal. It deals 40 hit points of damage per round to metal objects it touches (including weapons that strike it and armour worn by grappled victims). This makes the ooze one of the most equipment-destructive hazards in underground exploration.

### Special Abilities

**Acid (Ex):** Dissolves organic and metallic material. Deals 1d6 acid damage per round to flesh and 40 hp per round to metal objects in contact.

**Improved Grab (Ex):** To use, the gray ooze must hit with a slam.

**Constrict (Ex):** 1d6+1 plus 1d6 acid per round against a grappled creature.

**Transparent (Ex):** Spot DC 15 to notice a gray ooze on stone.

### Society

Gray oozes are mindless acid-puddles with no society, no culture, and no purpose beyond consuming organic material. They are a universal underground hazard — as common in Vestri mines as in Dómnathar tunnels, as likely in natural caves as in Giant ruins.

Vestri miners consider gray oozes a greater hazard than most monsters because of the acid’s metal-dissolving property. A miner who steps on a gray ooze loses their boots, possibly their weapon, and potentially their armour before they can disengage. Vestri mining protocols include probing the floor with a wooden pole before entering wet chambers — the acid does not affect wood, so the pole dissolves only if the wetness is an ooze.

### Lore

**DC 14 (Knowledge [dungeoneering]):** Gray oozes are translucent acid-puddles that dissolve metal on contact (40 hp/round to metal). They are nearly invisible on stone floors. Wooden objects are not affected by their acid.

**DC 19:** Vestri miners probe wet floors with wooden poles to detect gray oozes. The creatures are most common in wet underground environments where runoff collects. They are immune to cold and fire.

# GREEN HAG

She lives where the water goes bad. Not where the water is dangerous — that is different, honest danger, the kind you can see. She lives where the water is wrong: where the marsh-pools turn the wrong colour, where the fish float belly-up without visible cause, where the air tastes of sweetness that your body tells you means rot. She is there, somewhere in the murk, watching you with yellow eyes that she has not had to disguise in decades because no one comes here anymore.

**Medium Monstrous Humanoid**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Monstrous Humanoid |
| **Hit Dice** | 9d8+9 (49 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +1 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), swim 30 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 22 (+1 Dex, +11 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 21 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +9/+13 |
| **Attack** | Claw +13 melee (1d4+4) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 claws +13 melee (1d4+4) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Spell-like abilities, weakness, mimicry |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 90 ft., spell resistance 18, water breathing, elemental resonance (Water, corrupted) |
| **Saves** | Fort +6, Ref +7, Will +7 |
| **Abilities** | Str 19, Dex 12, Con 12, Int 13, Wis 13, Cha 14 |
| **Skills** | Concentration +7, Craft (alchemy) +7, Hide +9, Knowledge (nature) +9, Listen +11, Spot +11, Swim +12 |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Blind-Fight, Combat Casting, Great Fortitude |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) — corrupted; the green hag is the Lady’s domain gone stagnant and poisonous |
| **Environment** | Tidebloom Marshes (the tidal marshlands of the Tidebloom Reach, particularly the deep-marsh zones where freshwater rivers meet saltwater tidal intrusions and the water is neither one thing nor the other) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or covey (3 hags of any kind plus other creatures) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 5 |
| **Treasure** | Standard |
| **Alignment** | Always chaotic evil |
| **Advancement** | By character class |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A green hag fights with surprise, illusion, and environmental advantage. In her marsh, she is nearly undetectable — swimming beneath the surface, hiding in reed-beds, and using her spell-like abilities (dancing lights, disguise self, ghost sound, invisibility, pass without trace, tongues, water breathing) to misdirect and disorient. Her preferred tactic is to lure individuals away from groups using mimicry (she can imitate any animal or humanoid voice) and attack them alone.

In melee, a green hag relies on her Strength 19 and claws, grappling and dragging victims underwater where she holds the advantage. Her weakness ability — activated by touch — reduces a target’s Strength by 2d4, making grapple-escape difficult.

### Special Abilities

**Spell-Like Abilities:** At will — dancing lights, disguise self, ghost sound (DC 12), invisibility, pass without trace, tongues, water breathing. CL 9th.

**Weakness (Su):** A green hag can weaken a creature by touch (melee touch attack). The target takes 2d4 Strength damage. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Mimicry (Ex):** A green hag can imitate any animal or humanoid voice with perfect accuracy. A successful Will save (DC 16) recognises the sound as imitation.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** A green hag registers on Kin-sense as corrupted water-resonance — the Lady of the Sea’s domain turned stagnant, foul, and toxic. The resonance feels like drinking water that looks clean but tastes of rust and rot. Kin who detect a green hag’s resonance instinctively recoil — the corruption of a familiar elemental signature is more disturbing than an alien one.

Tidebloom communities recognise corrupted water-resonance as a hag-warning. If the water in a marsh-zone starts tasting wrong on Kin-sense — not absent but sour — a hag has claimed the area.

### Society

Green hags are solitary predators that claim stretches of marsh and corrupt them through prolonged habitation. The corruption is both metaphorical and literal — a green hag’s presence poisons the water, kills the fish, and warps the plant-life, transforming healthy wetland into toxic morass over a period of months.

Tidebloom Reach is green hag territory. The complex tidal marshlands — freshwater, saltwater, and the brackish zones between — provide ideal habitat. Tidebloom Kin communities (a mixture of Vestri mining-camps, halfling fishing-villages, and Eruskan trading-posts) maintain hag-watches: community sentries who monitor the taste of the water and the health of the fish. When the signs of hag-corruption appear, the community has days to weeks before the hag establishes itself — early response (hiring adventurers, calling on clergy) is the most effective strategy.

Green hags form coveys — alliances of three hags (not necessarily all green) that combine their power for greater magical ability. A covey in the Tidebloom Reach is a regional threat, capable of corrupting miles of marsh and threatening multiple communities simultaneously. Coveys are rare because hags despise each other’s company, but when they form, the Tidebloom communities respond with coordinated military action.

The annis hag of the mountains and the green hag of the marshes are the two most common hag varieties in Oreka. The sea hag — a third variety — inhabits coastal waters and is primarily a Na’wasua and halfling concern.

### Lore

**DC 15 (Knowledge [nature]):** Green hags are marsh-dwelling predators that corrupt the water and land around them. They can become invisible, mimic any voice, and weaken creatures with a touch. Their natural armour is surprisingly tough.

**DC 20:** A green hag’s presence poisons the water, kills fish, and warps plant-life over months. Tidebloom communities use water-taste monitoring as early warning. Three hags can form a covey with enhanced magical abilities.

**DC 25:** Green hag resonance is corrupted water-energy — recognisably the Lady of the Sea’s domain but turned stagnant and toxic. Tidebloom hag-watches monitor Kin-sense “taste” of local water for signs of corruption. Coveys are rare but constitute regional threats.

# GRICK

The tunnel narrows. The walls are wet. Something moves in the darkness ahead — not quickly, not dramatically, but with the patient, questing motion of a creature that has all the time in the world and knows that everything in the tunnel eventually comes to it. You see tentacles first — four of them, barbed, extending from the darkness like fingers testing the air. Then the beak.

**Medium Aberration**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Aberration |
| **Hit Dice** | 2d8+2 (11 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +2 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), climb 20 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 16 (+2 Dex, +4 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 14 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +1/+3 |
| **Attack** | Tentacle +3 melee (1d4+2) |
| **Full Attack** | 4 tentacles +3 melee (1d4+2) and bite –2 melee (1d3+1) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | — |
| **Special Qualities** | Damage reduction 10/magic, darkvision 60 ft., scent, breach resonance |
| **Saves** | Fort +1, Ref +2, Will +3 |
| **Abilities** | Str 14, Dex 14, Con 13, Int 3, Wis 14, Cha 5 |
| **Skills** | Climb +10, Hide +3 (+11 in rocky areas), Listen +6, Spot +6 |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Track (B) |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — aberration; breach resonance indicates origin outside Oreka’s elemental framework |
| **Environment** | Underground (natural cave systems, mine-tunnels, and Giant-era passages — anywhere with consistent darkness, moisture, and sufficient prey) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or cluster (2–4) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 3 |
| **Treasure** | 1/10th coins |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 3–4 HD (Medium); 5–6 HD (Large) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A grick is a patient tunnel-ambusher. It conceals itself against rock walls (near-invisible in rocky areas, +11 Hide bonus) and waits for prey to pass within tentacle-reach. When prey is detected, it extends its four barbed tentacles to grapple and drag the creature toward its beak.

A grick’s damage reduction 10/magic makes it surprisingly durable against mundane weapons — low-level parties without magical arms find gricks difficult to hurt. This durability, combined with the ambush advantage, makes gricks a significant hazard in underground environments despite their modest hit points.

### Special Abilities

**Breach Resonance (Su):** Gricks register on Kin-sense as breach-noise — the same discordant, alien static as derro and other creatures from outside Oreka’s elemental framework. The resonance is faint (DC 18 to detect) and easily lost in the ambient noise of underground environments. Experienced underground travelers describe grick resonance as a “wet scratching” sensation at the edges of perception.

### Society

Gricks are non-intelligent tunnel predators — aberrations that have colonised Oreka’s underground environments without culture, communication, or purpose beyond feeding. They are found wherever darkness, moisture, and prey coincide.

Vestri miners encounter gricks in natural cave systems adjacent to mine-tunnels and treat them as vermin — dangerous vermin, but vermin nonetheless. The standard Vestri response to a grick in a mine-tunnel is a squad of miners with magical weapons (even a +1 enchantment is sufficient to bypass the DR) and a clear kill-zone.

Gricks occasionally colonise Dómnathar-adjacent tunnel systems, where the breach-resonance of the Deceiver infrastructure masks their own faint signal. Dómnathar tunnel-patrols eliminate gricks as a matter of maintenance — the creatures are nuisances that interfere with logistics.

### Lore

**DC 13 (Knowledge [dungeoneering]):** Gricks are tentacled tunnel predators with damage reduction 10/magic. They ambush from concealment against rock walls and are nearly invisible in their natural habitat.

**DC 18:** Gricks carry breach resonance — alien static on Kin-sense that indicates extraplanar origin. Vestri miners clear gricks with enchanted weapons. They sometimes colonise Dómnathar-adjacent tunnels, masked by ambient breach-noise.

# GRIFFON

The shadow passes over you first — wide, fast, and shaped wrong for a bird. You look up and see something impossible: a lion’s body, golden and muscular, suspended beneath an eagle’s wings that span thirty feet. The front half is pure raptor — hooked beak, taloned forelegs, golden feathers merging seamlessly into tawny fur at the shoulders. It banks, catches the thermal rising from the hillside, and circles once, looking down at you with a golden eagle’s eye that misses nothing.

**Large Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 7d10+21 (59 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +2 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), fly 80 ft. (average) |
| **Armor Class** | 17 (–1 size, +2 Dex, +6 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 15 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +7/+15 |
| **Attack** | Bite +11 melee (2d6+4) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +11 melee (2d6+4) and 2 claws +8 melee (1d4+2) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Pounce, rake 1d6+2 |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, scent, elemental resonance (Air/Earth) |
| **Saves** | Fort +8, Ref +7, Will +5 |
| **Abilities** | Str 18, Dex 15, Con 16, Int 5, Wis 13, Cha 8 |
| **Skills** | Jump +8, Listen +6, Spot +10 |
| **Feats** | Iron Will, Multiattack, Weapon Focus (bite) |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Youngest Brother (Air) / Lord of Stone (Earth) — the griffon is sky-and-mountain, the Youngest Brother’s wind beneath the Lord of Stone’s weight |
| **Environment** | Giant’s Teeth Foothills and temperate highlands (rocky hills and upland meadows with clear sight-lines, nesting on cliff-faces and high ledges — the transition zone between the Giant’s Teeth mountains and the lower grasslands) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or pride (6–10) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 4 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always neutral |
| **Advancement** | 8–10 HD (Large); 11–14 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +3 (cohort) |

### Combat

A griffon attacks from the air — diving from altitude to strike with a pounce, delivering a full attack (bite plus two claws plus two rake attacks) in a single devastating round. This alpha-strike is the griffon’s primary tactic: maximum damage in the first contact, followed by a retreat to altitude to assess the result.

Against prey that survives the initial pounce, a griffon uses its flight speed to circle and strike again, never remaining on the ground longer than one round. It fights to the death only to defend a nest; in all other circumstances, it breaks off if injured.

**Pounce (Ex):** A griffon that charges can make a full attack, including two rake attacks.

**Rake (Ex):** Attack bonus +8, damage 1d6+2.

### Special Abilities

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** Griffons register on Kin-sense as a clean, powerful air/earth dual-signature — wind over stone, the thermal-updraft from a sun-warmed cliff. The resonance is beautiful and unmistakably predatory: there is a sharpness to it, a focused killing-intent, that distinguishes it from the gentler air/earth of, say, a storm wisp. A DC 12 Kin-sense check detects a griffon overhead; the aerial resonance is distinctive and carries well over distance.

### Society

Griffons are territorial aerial predators that nest on cliff-faces and hunt the meadows and grasslands below. A griffon pride — six to ten adults — claims a territory of fifty to a hundred square miles, patrolling the airspace and attacking anything they identify as prey or competitor.

Griffons have a particular, intense hatred of horses. The enmity is instinctive — a griffon will abandon other prey to attack a horse, and a griffon pride near a caravan route creates a persistent hazard for mounted travelers. The source of this hatred is unknown. Mytroan steppe-riders, whose horses are central to their culture, consider griffon-territory approaches to be among the most dangerous terrain features on the steppe-mountain border.

Orean humans in the Giant’s Teeth foothills coexist with griffon prides through mutual avoidance — Orean communities keep their horses stabled and out of sight when griffon prides are active, and griffons do not attack settlements. Some Orean communities maintain a wary respect for griffon prides, viewing them as natural guardians of the mountain-approaches.

Griffons can be trained as mounts, but the process is difficult, dangerous, and requires raising the griffon from a hatchling. No culture in Oreka has developed systematic griffon-riding, though individual Orean and Eruskan adventurers have bonded with griffons over the centuries.

### Lore

**DC 14 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Griffons are eagle-lion hybrid predators that attack from the air with devastating pounce-charges. They have an instinctive hatred of horses and will prioritise horse-targets over all others.

**DC 19:** Griffon prides claim territories of fifty to a hundred square miles. They can be trained as mounts if raised from hatchlings, but no Oreka culture has systematised the practice. Their air/earth resonance is distinctive and detectable at range.

**DC 24:** The source of griffon-horse enmity is unknown. Orean foothill communities stable horses out of sight during griffon activity. Mytroan steppe-riders consider griffon-territory approaches among the most dangerous terrain features.

# GRIG

You hear the fiddle first. Something is playing a fiddle in the undergrowth — playing it well, playing it fast, playing a reel that makes your feet want to move before your brain can object. You part the ferns and see the musician: a creature the size of your hand, cricket-legged, fairy-winged, grinning like a lunatic, sawing away at a fiddle the size of a matchstick with a bow the size of a needle. It sees you seeing it and plays faster.

**Tiny Fey**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Tiny Fey |
| **Hit Dice** | 1/2 d6 (1 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +4 |
| **Speed** | 20 ft. (4 squares), fly 40 ft. (poor) |
| **Armor Class** | 17 (+2 size, +4 Dex, +1 natural), touch 16, flat-footed 13 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +0/–11 |
| **Attack** | Short sword +6 melee (1d3–3/19–20) or longbow +6 ranged (1d4–3/×3) |
| **Full Attack** | Short sword +6 melee (1d3–3/19–20) or longbow +6 ranged (1d4–3/×3) |
| **Space/Reach** | 2-1/2 ft./0 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Spell-like abilities, fiddle |
| **Special Qualities** | Damage reduction 5/cold iron, low-light vision, spell resistance 17, elemental resonance (Earth/Air) |
| **Saves** | Fort +0, Ref +6, Will +3 |
| **Abilities** | Str 5, Dex 18, Con 11, Int 10, Wis 13, Cha 14 |
| **Skills** | Craft (any one) +4, Escape Artist +8, Hide +16, Jump +4, Listen +3, Move Silently +8, Perform (string instruments) +6, Spot +3 |
| **Feats** | Dodge, Weapon Finesse (B) |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) / Youngest Brother (Air) — the grig is the playful overlap of earth and air; the cricket in the grass, the music on the breeze |
| **Environment** | Great Forests (forest clearings, meadow-margins, stream-banks, and the sun-dappled edges of the canopy — wherever the forest is light and warm enough for music) |
| **Organization** | Gang (2–4), band (6–11), or tribe (20–80) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 1 |
| **Treasure** | No coins; 50% goods; 50% items |
| **Alignment** | Always neutral good |
| **Advancement** | 1–3 HD (Tiny) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +3 |

### Combat

Grigs avoid combat entirely when possible — they are half a hit die of fey, and anything that hits them kills them. Their defensive tools are spell-like abilities (entangle, invisibility, pyrotechnics, ventriloquism) and their fiddle ability, which can compel irresistible dancing that removes enemies from the fight.

A grig’s first response to danger is to turn invisible and flee. If flight is not possible (defending a grove, protecting eggs, cornered), a grig uses entangle to immobilise threats and fiddle to incapacitate them. A band of grigs can fiddle together, with each grig’s performance reinforcing the effect.

### Special Abilities

**Spell-Like Abilities:** 3/day — disguise self, entangle (DC 13), invisibility (self only), pyrotechnics (DC 14), ventriloquism (DC 13). CL 9th.

**Fiddle (Su):** A grig can play its tiny fiddle to produce an irresistible reel. Any creature within 30 feet that hears the music must succeed on a Will save (DC 13) or begin dancing uncontrollably, as per irresistible dance. The effect lasts as long as the grig continues playing and for 1 round after. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** Grigs register on Kin-sense as a tiny, bright, musical note — earth/air resonance expressed as rhythm and melody. A DC 12 Kin-sense check detects grigs nearby; the resonance is cheerful and non-threatening, and Kin who detect it often smile involuntarily.

### Society

Grigs are the smallest and most numerous fey in the Great Forests. They are musicians, tricksters, and creatures of pure, thoughtless joy — existing primarily to play music, dance, pull harmless pranks, and fill the forest with sound. They are utterly non-threatening unless provoked.

Hasura elves regard grigs with affection — grig-music in a forest clearing is a sign that the local fey population is healthy and the elemental balance is stable. Hasura children learn to identify grig-music as a forest-health indicator. Silence where grigs should be singing is a warning.

Pasua scouts find grigs mildly annoying (the music carries, and a grig band performing at volume can reveal a scout’s approach for hundreds of feet) but do not harm them. Pasua trail-protocols near known grig territories include hand-signal communication to avoid speaking — the grigs’ ventriloquism makes verbal communication unreliable in their presence.

Tanuki adore grigs and frequently join grig bands for spontaneous musical performances. Tanuki-grig concerts are legendary among forest-dwelling Kin — chaotic, joyful, and extraordinarily loud.

### Lore

**DC 11 (Knowledge [nature]):** Grigs are tiny cricket-winged fey that play magical fiddles. Their music can compel irresistible dancing. They are harmless unless provoked and a sign of healthy forest.

**DC 16:** Grig-silence in normally grig-active areas is an environmental warning. Their spell-like abilities include entangle and invisibility. Pasua scouts use hand-signals near grig territory because ventriloquism makes speech unreliable.

# GRIMLOCK

It has no eyes. That is the first thing you notice — the flat, smooth expanse of face where eyes should be, unbroken by sockets, lids, or any concession to sight. It does not need eyes. It navigates by sound, by scent, by the vibration of your footsteps through the stone, and by a sense you cannot name that tells it exactly where you are, how large you are, and where to put the axe.

**Medium Monstrous Humanoid**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Monstrous Humanoid |
| **Hit Dice** | 2d8+2 (11 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +1 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 15 (+1 Dex, +4 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 14 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +2/+4 |
| **Attack** | Battleaxe +4 melee (1d8+2/×3) |
| **Full Attack** | Battleaxe +4 melee (1d8+2/×3) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | — |
| **Special Qualities** | Blindsight 40 ft., immunities (gaze attacks, visual effects, illusions, attack forms relying on sight), scent, wild static |
| **Saves** | Fort +1, Ref +4, Will +3 |
| **Abilities** | Str 15, Dex 13, Con 13, Int 10, Wis 8, Cha 6 |
| **Skills** | Climb +4, Hide +3 (+11 in caverns), Listen +5, Spot +3 |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Track (B) |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — grimlocks exist outside the elemental framework, like all non-Kin peoples |
| **Environment** | Deep Underground (natural cave systems below the depth of Vestri mining, below Dómnathar corridors, in the deep strata where light has never reached and the concept of “surface” is an abstraction) |
| **Organization** | Gang (2–4), pack (10–20), or tribe (20–40 plus 1–3 leaders of 3rd–5th level plus 2–5 dire bats) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 1 |
| **Treasure** | Standard |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral evil |
| **Advancement** | By character class |
| **Level Adjustment** | +2 |

### Combat

Grimlocks fight in darkness — their natural habitat. Their blindsight 40 ft. gives them perfect spatial awareness without light, and they are immune to all visual effects, gaze attacks, and illusions. A party relying on darkness-based spells, visual illusions, or gaze-weapon tactics finds grimlocks completely unaffected.

Grimlocks fight in coordinated packs, using their blindsight to position themselves around targets and attack from multiple angles simultaneously. In total darkness (their preferred conditions), they are significantly more effective than most opponents, who are blind while the grimlocks are not.

Their primary disadvantage is their blindsight range — 40 feet is effective in tunnels but limited in open caverns. A party that stays beyond 40 feet and attacks at range (with sound-producing weapons or area effects) can fight grimlocks without ever entering their effective zone.

### Special Abilities

**Blindsight (Ex):** Grimlocks sense all creatures within 40 feet through a combination of sound, scent, and vibration. They cannot be caught flat-footed by creatures within this range.

**Wild Static (Su):** Grimlocks register on Kin-sense as wild static — the same unreadable signal as all non-Kin peoples. Grimlock static is distinctive: flat, echoing, and subterranean, like static heard through a long tunnel. A DC 16 Kin-sense check can distinguish grimlock static from ambient underground noise.

### Society

Grimlocks are eyeless subterranean humanoids who have lived below the surface for so long that they have evolved beyond any need for sight. They are not blind — they see perfectly, just not with eyes. Their blindsight gives them complete spatial awareness in a 40-foot radius, making them superbly adapted to the lightless deep.

Grimlocks occupy the lowest tier of the underground — below Vestri mines, below Dómnathar corridors, in the deep natural caves that no one else claims. Their relationship with the Dómnathar is one of mutual wariness: the Dómnathar do not consider grimlocks useful (too independent, too dangerous in their home terrain) and grimlocks do not consider the Dómnathar worth provoking (too powerful, too alien).

Vestri deep-patrols encounter grimlocks at the boundary between worked tunnels and natural cave systems. These encounters range from tense standoffs (both sides waiting to see if the other will attack) to brief, vicious skirmishes when grimlock packs attempt to raid Vestri supply-caches. Vestri miners who work the deepest shafts carry light-producing items as much for communication with each other as for illumination — the grimlocks don’t care about light, but a miner who drops their lantern in a fight with grimlocks is a miner fighting blind against opponents who are not.

Grimlocks occasionally trade with derro — another deep-underground people — exchanging raw materials and cave-fauna for derro-crafted weapons and tools. This trade is conducted in total darkness, by touch and sound, and both parties maintain weapons at hand throughout. It is the least friendly trade-relationship in Oreka.

### Lore

**DC 11 (Knowledge [local]):** Grimlocks are eyeless underground humanoids with blindsight. They are immune to gaze attacks, illusions, and all visual effects. They fight in coordinated packs in total darkness.

**DC 16:** Grimlocks live deeper underground than Vestri mines or Dómnathar corridors. They are independent of both and wary of the Dómnathar. They trade with derro in the deep caves — conducted by touch in total darkness.

**DC 21:** Grimlock blindsight is limited to 40 feet — staying beyond this range negates their advantage. Vestri deep-miners carry light primarily for inter-miner communication, not to counter grimlocks. The grimlock-derro trade relationship is the least friendly in Oreka.

# GROOTSLANG

The cave breathes. That is not metaphor — the air moves in and out of the volcanic tube in a rhythm that predates language, and the rhythm is the breathing of the thing that lives inside. It has lived there since before the Giants came. Since before the Kin were shaped. Since before the Elemental Lords withdrew from the world and left their domains to spin on without them. It is the size of a building — an elephant’s body fused with a serpent’s tail, scaled in obsidian, radiating heat that makes the cave walls glow. Its eyes are rubies. Not like rubies — actual rubies, crystallised fire-energy compressed by geological time into gemstone consciousness. It looks at you and you understand, with the certainty of deep instinct, that you are looking at something older than your entire species.

**Huge Magical Beast (Elemental, Fire, Earth)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Huge Magical Beast (Elemental, Fire, Earth) |
| **Hit Dice** | 14d10+84 (161 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +1 |
| **Speed** | 40 ft. (8 squares), burrow 20 ft. (volcanic rock only), swim 30 ft. (lava) |
| **Armor Class** | 27 (–2 size, +1 Dex, +18 natural), touch 9, flat-footed 26 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +14/+32 |
| **Attack** | Bite +22 melee (3d6+10 plus 1d6 fire) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +22 melee (3d6+10 plus 1d6 fire) and gore +20 melee (2d6+5) and tail slap +20 melee (2d8+5 plus 1d6 fire) |
| **Space/Reach** | 15 ft./10 ft. (tail 15 ft.) |
| **Special Attacks** | Constrict 2d8+15 plus 2d6 fire, improved grab, trample 2d8+15, primordial roar |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 120 ft., low-light vision, damage reduction 10/magic and cold iron, immunity to fire, vulnerability to cold, spell resistance 24, scent, tremorsense 60 ft., primordial resonance, lava-swimmer |
| **Saves** | Fort +15, Ref +10, Will +8 |
| **Abilities** | Str 31, Dex 13, Con 23, Int 6, Wis 14, Cha 14 |
| **Skills** | Listen +12, Spot +12, Survival +12 |
| **Feats** | Awesome Blow, Cleave, Improved Bull Rush, Improved Natural Attack (bite), Multiattack, Power Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of Fire (Fire) / Lord of Stone (Earth) — primordial; the grootslang’s affinity is not the refined, balanced expression of later elemental creatures but raw, undivided fire-and-earth from before the Elemental Lords distinguished between their domains |
| **Environment** | Volcanic Caves (the deep volcanic tube-systems of the Scorchspires and Emberfang Mountains — not surface calderas but the interior passages where magma flows beneath the mountain-skin; specifically the caves that Taraf-Imro traditions mark as sacred and forbidden) |
| **Organization** | Solitary (always) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 11 |
| **Treasure** | Double standard (primarily gemstones — grootslang hoards are famous for their concentration of rubies, fire-opals, and volcanic glass; the creature’s body-heat crystallises gems in the surrounding stone over centuries) |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 15–21 HD (Huge); 22–28 HD (Gargantuan) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A grootslang fights with overwhelming physical power. It opens with its primordial roar — a blast of elemental force that shakes the cave and staggers everything within range — then charges, using trample against smaller creatures and bite-grab-constrict against larger ones. Its tail slap provides reach against flankers.

In its volcanic cave-system, a grootslang is nearly unbeatable. It knows every passage, every lava-flow, every dead-end. It uses lava-swimmer to traverse magma pools that block pursuit, collapses unstable passages with its bulk, and fights in chambers where its size fills the space and enemies cannot outflank it.

A grootslang that is seriously threatened (reduced below 40 hp) retreats into lava — submerging fully, healing in the magma’s heat, and emerging to fight again. Killing a grootslang requires either following it into lava (suicidal without fire immunity) or trapping it away from magma sources.

### Special Abilities

**Improved Grab (Ex):** To use, a grootslang must hit with its bite. It can then start a grapple as a free action and constrict on subsequent rounds.

**Constrict (Ex):** 2d8+15 plus 2d6 fire damage per round. The creature wraps its serpentine tail around the grappled target and squeezes while its body-heat scorches.

**Trample (Ex):** Reflex DC 27 half. Damage 2d8+15.

**Primordial Roar (Su):** Once every 1d4 rounds, a grootslang can release a roar of primordial elemental force. All creatures within 60 feet must succeed on a DC 19 Fortitude save or be stunned for 1 round and deafened for 1d4 rounds. The cave-system within 300 feet shakes visibly — loose stone falls, lava surges, and minor collapses occur in unstable passages. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Lava-Swimmer (Ex):** A grootslang can swim through lava at 30 ft. per round, suffering no damage. It can submerge completely in lava and remain indefinitely. While submerged, it heals 5 hp per round from the magma’s elemental energy.

**Tremorsense (Ex):** A grootslang can sense vibrations through stone within 60 feet, detecting all creatures in contact with the ground.

**Primordial Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a grootslang registers as something that predates the Kin-sense framework itself. Its resonance is not the refined, balanced signature of later elemental creatures — it is raw, undivided, overwhelming fire-and-earth in a form so primal that the Kin-sense struggles to parse it. The experience is like staring at the sun: not painful but too much, too intense, too old.

Kin within 200 feet detect the resonance automatically and involuntarily. The sensation has been described as “the mountain remembering when it was lava” — an elemental signature from before Fire and Earth were separate domains, before the Elemental Lords distinguished their territories, before the world cooled enough to need the distinction. Rarozhki Dwarves, with their deep fire-attunement, find the resonance overwhelming in a way that approaches religious experience. Taraf-Imro warriors describe it as “hearing the first forge.”

### Society

Grootslang are primordial elemental remnants — survivors from the earliest age of Oreka, when the Elemental Lords’ domains were raw and undivided and the distinction between Fire and Earth had not yet been drawn. They are not constructs, not creations, not products of any intelligence. They simply are — the way mountains are, the way magma is. They existed before the Giants and they will exist after the Kin.

Each grootslang is unique. There are fewer than a dozen in Oreka — solitary creatures that claim individual volcanic cave-systems and never leave. A grootslang’s cave is identifiable by the gemstones that crystallise in its walls over centuries: the creature’s body-heat and elemental radiance compress carbon, silica, and mineral deposits into rubies, fire-opals, and volcanic glass. A grootslang’s hoard is not collected — it is generated by the creature’s existence.

Taraf-Imro warriors revere grootslang as sacred relics of the primordial world. Taraf-Imro rite-of-passage traditions include the *Azi Taba* — the “fire-walk” — in which a young warrior must enter a grootslang’s cave-system, reach the innermost chamber, and return alive. The warrior does not fight the grootslang. The warrior does not take from the hoard. The warrior simply survives the presence — the heat, the resonance, the sheer primordial weight of a creature older than civilisation — and returns with the knowledge of what the world was like before it was tamed.

Rarozhki Dwarves are aware of grootslang but do not seek them out. The Rarozhki relationship with fire is industrial, practical, and reverent in a controlled way — the grootslang represents fire before control, before forging, before purpose. Rarozhki scholars who have studied grootslang resonance describe it as “the Lady of Fire before she was the Lady of Fire” — elemental fire-energy in a form so primal that it predates the Elemental Lord who would eventually claim it.

Pekakarlik gem-traders consider grootslang-cave gemstones to be the highest quality fire-gems in Oreka — rubies and fire-opals naturally formed over centuries in conditions of elemental intensity that no artificial process can replicate. The few grootslang-cave gems that reach the market (taken from abandoned caves, never from occupied ones) command extraordinary prices.

### Lore

**DC 16 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Grootslang are enormous elephant-serpent creatures that live in volcanic caves. They are immune to fire, can swim through lava, and their hoards contain gemstones of extraordinary quality. They are ancient — older than the Giants.

**DC 21:** Grootslang are primordial elemental remnants from before Fire and Earth were separate domains. There are fewer than a dozen in Oreka. Their body-heat crystallises gemstones in the surrounding cave-walls over centuries. Taraf-Imro warriors undergo the *Azi Taba* rite-of-passage in grootslang caves.

**DC 26:** Grootslang resonance predates the Kin-sense framework — raw, undivided fire-and-earth that the senses struggle to parse. Rarozhki scholars describe it as “the Lady of Fire before she was the Lady of Fire.” A grootslang reduced below 40 hp retreats into lava to heal. Killing one requires cutting it off from magma.

# GYNOSPHINX

She is waiting for you. She has been waiting for you since before you entered the desert, since before you decided to take this route, since before you were born. She reclines on the sand-polished stone with the patience of a monument and the attention of a predator, and her face — a woman’s face, beautiful, ageless, and utterly without mercy — watches you approach with an expression that might be curiosity or might be appetite. They are the same thing, to her.

**Large Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 8d10+8 (52 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +5 |
| **Speed** | 40 ft. (8 squares), fly 60 ft. (poor) |
| **Armor Class** | 21 (–1 size, +1 Dex, +11 natural), touch 10, flat-footed 20 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +8/+16 |
| **Attack** | Claw +11 melee (1d6+4) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 claws +11 melee (1d6+4) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Pounce, rake 1d6+2, spell-like abilities |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, elemental resonance (All Four, fragmented), sphinx’s bargain |
| **Saves** | Fort +7, Ref +7, Will +8 |
| **Abilities** | Str 19, Dex 12, Con 13, Int 18, Wis 19, Cha 19 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +15, Concentration +12, Diplomacy +8, Intimidate +15, Knowledge (any two) +15, Listen +15, Sense Motive +15, Spot +15 |
| **Feats** | Combat Casting, Improved Initiative, Iron Will |
| **Elemental Affinity** | All Four Elemental Lords (fragmented) — the gynosphinx carries the same four-element signature as the vanished Giants, but refracted, partial, and distorted through a bestial lens |
| **Environment** | Glass Wastes (the heat-fused sand expanses of the Infinite Desert’s western margins, where the sand has been melted into glass by ancient elemental forces — a landscape of razor-edged glass ridges and reflective plains that the sphinxes have claimed as their own) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or pair |
| **Challenge Rating** | 8 |
| **Treasure** | Double standard (accumulated over centuries — a gynosphinx’s hoard is curated, not piled; she keeps what interests her and discards what bores her) |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 9–12 HD (Large) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A gynosphinx does not fight unless her bargain is refused or failed. Her first action in any encounter is to offer the sphinx’s bargain — answer a riddle and pass freely, or refuse the bargain and fight. If the bargain is accepted and the riddle answered correctly, the gynosphinx lets the party pass and may even offer information as a reward. If the riddle is answered incorrectly, or the bargain is refused, she attacks.

In combat, a gynosphinx uses her spell-like abilities (detect magic, read magic, see invisibility, comprehend languages, locate object, dispel magic, remove curse, legend lore, symbol of death, symbol of insanity, symbol of pain, symbol of persuasion, symbol of sleep, symbol of stunning) to control the battlefield before closing for melee. Her pounce-and-rake combination is dangerous, and her Intelligence 18 means she fights with sophisticated tactics — using terrain, flight, and her spell-like abilities to maintain every advantage.

### Special Abilities

**Spell-Like Abilities:** At will — detect magic, read magic, see invisibility; 3/day — comprehend languages, locate object, dispel magic, remove curse, legend lore; 1/day — symbol of death (DC 22), symbol of insanity (DC 22), symbol of pain (DC 21), symbol of persuasion (DC 20), symbol of sleep (DC 19), symbol of stunning (DC 21). CL 14th. Save DCs are Charisma-based.

**Pounce (Ex):** A gynosphinx that charges can make a full attack, including two rake attacks.

**Rake (Ex):** Attack bonus +11, damage 1d6+2.

**Sphinx’s Bargain (Su):** A gynosphinx offers every intelligent creature that enters her territory a choice: answer a riddle correctly and pass freely, or fight. The riddle is always genuine — the gynosphinx does not cheat, does not change the answer, and does not refuse to honour a correct response. This bargain is compulsive — the gynosphinx is bound by it as much as the traveler. She cannot attack a creature that has accepted the bargain until the riddle is answered (correctly or incorrectly).

If the bargain is refused (the creature attacks without answering, or explicitly declines), the gynosphinx is free to attack immediately and does so without restraint.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** A gynosphinx registers on Kin-sense as a fragmented four-element signature — the same all-element resonance carried by the vanished Giants, but broken, refracted, and incomplete. Where a Giant’s four-element harmony was seamless and unified, the gynosphinx’s is a prism-shattered version: all four elements present but not integrated, shifting and cycling like light through stained glass.

This resonance — partial Giant-resonance in a bestial form — is the source of the scholarly debate about sphinx origins. Kin scholars have argued for centuries about whether sphinxes are Giant-created guardians, Giant-descended creatures, or independent beings that independently developed four-element resonance. The gynosphinx, if asked, does not answer this question. She smiles.

### Society

Gynosphinxes are solitary territorial intellects that claim stretches of the Glass Wastes and enforce their presence through the sphinx’s bargain. They are not predators — they do not need to eat (or if they do, they eat rarely) — and they are not guardians in any purposeful sense. They are something older: creatures of knowledge, patience, and testing, who have occupied the desert since before Kin memory and show no sign of leaving.

The Glass Wastes — the heat-fused sand expanses of the western Infinite Desert — are sphinx territory. Gynosphinxes are the most common sphinx variety in the Glass Wastes, outnumbering androsphinxes (the male equivalent) roughly three to one. Criosphinxes (ram-headed, less intelligent) and hieracosphinxes (hawk-headed, least intelligent) also inhabit the region but are not respected by gynosphinxes or androsphinxes.

Pekakarlik caravans crossing the Glass Wastes prepare riddle-answers before departure — Pekakarlik trade-guilds maintain collections of known sphinx riddles and correct answers, passed down through generations. A Pekakarlik caravan-master who cannot answer a gynosphinx’s riddle has failed their guild-training. Na’wasua desert-elves regard gynosphinxes with wary respect and approach their territories with formal courtesy.

The gynosphinx’s partial Giant-resonance connects them to the gallu — both carry fragments of the Firstborn’s four-element signature, though in vastly different forms. The gallu is a broken spirit; the gynosphinx is a living enigma. Whether the two are related is one of the Infinite Desert’s many unanswered questions.

### Lore

**DC 18 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Gynosphinxes are intelligent lion-bodied creatures with women’s faces that guard stretches of the Glass Wastes. They offer a bargain: answer a riddle or fight. They are powerful spellcasters with access to symbol spells.

**DC 23:** The sphinx’s bargain is compulsive — the gynosphinx cannot attack until the riddle is answered or the bargain refused. Pekakarlik trade-guilds maintain riddle-collections for caravan crossings. Gynosphinxes carry fragmented four-element resonance similar to the vanished Giants.

**DC 28:** Whether sphinxes are Giant-created, Giant-descended, or independently evolved is debated. The gynosphinx’s resonance resembles a prism-shattered version of the Firstborn’s harmony. If asked about her origin, a gynosphinx smiles and does not answer.

# HAKUTURI

The tree is old. Older than the Kovaka settlement at its base, older than the trail that leads to it, older than anything human memory can account for. You came to cut a branch — a single branch, for a canoe-rib — and now you cannot lift the axe. Not because something is stopping you. Because the tree is looking at you. The bark has rearranged itself into a face that was always there and always watching, and the face is not angry. It is patient. It is waiting for you to understand why you should put the axe down.

**Medium Fey**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Fey |
| **Hit Dice** | 5d6+10 (27 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +2 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), climb 20 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 17 (+2 Dex, +5 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 15 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +2/+4 |
| **Attack** | Slam +4 melee (1d6+3) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 slams +4 melee (1d6+3) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Spell-like abilities, forest-command |
| **Special Qualities** | Damage reduction 5/cold iron, low-light vision, tree-meld, plant sympathy, elemental resonance (Earth/Water) |
| **Saves** | Fort +3, Ref +6, Will +7 |
| **Abilities** | Str 14, Dex 15, Con 14, Int 13, Wis 16, Cha 15 |
| **Skills** | Craft (woodwork) +9, Hide +10 (+18 in forests), Knowledge (nature) +9, Listen +11, Move Silently +10, Spot +11, Survival +11 |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Stealthy |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) / Lady of the Sea (Water) — the living forest; root-water and dark soil, growth expressed as patience |
| **Environment** | Great Forests (the old-growth stands of the Kovaka territories — the southern and island-fringe forests where ancient trees have stood for millennia undisturbed; never found in young growth, managed forest, or areas cleared within living memory) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or grove-council (3–7) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 4 |
| **Treasure** | No coins; 50% goods (finely carved wooden objects, polished stones, bird feathers) |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral good |
| **Advancement** | 6–10 HD (Medium); 11–15 HD (Large) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

Hakuturi do not fight unless their grove is threatened. Their first response to any intrusion is observation — watching, waiting, assessing intent. If the intruder means no harm to the trees, the hakuturi remains hidden (tree-meld makes them nearly undetectable in old-growth forest). If the intruder begins cutting living wood, the hakuturi reveals itself and uses forest-command to make the situation clear: stop, or the forest will stop you.

In actual combat, a hakuturi uses entangle and warp wood to control the battlefield, turning the forest itself against intruders. Its slam attacks are reinforced by bark-hardened fists, and it can retreat into any living tree to escape or reposition. A grove-council of hakuturi fighting together can transform a forest clearing into a nearly impassable tangle of animated vegetation in rounds.

### Special Abilities

**Spell-Like Abilities:** At will — speak with plants, entangle (DC 13); 3/day — warp wood, plant growth, tree stride; 1/day — wall of thorns (DC 17). CL 5th. Save DCs are Charisma-based.

**Forest-Command (Su):** As a standard action, a hakuturi can command all plants within 60 feet to respond to its will — branches grasp, roots trip, undergrowth thickens. This functions as a combination of entangle and the difficult terrain rules: all squares within 60 feet become difficult terrain for creatures the hakuturi designates. The effect lasts as long as the hakuturi concentrates (standard action each round). This is not a spell-like ability; it is innate fey authority over the forest.

**Tree-Meld (Su):** A hakuturi can merge with any living tree of Medium or larger size as a move action, becoming invisible and undetectable by mundane means. While melded, the hakuturi is aware of everything within 100 feet of the tree. It can emerge from the same tree or any living tree within 100 feet as a move action.

**Plant Sympathy (Ex):** A hakuturi can communicate with all plant life within 500 feet through the Harmony — not speech but awareness. It knows the health of every tree, the presence of every creature touching the ground, and the general condition of the forest within its range.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a hakuturi registers as a deep, slow earth/water signature — the resonance of old-growth forest, patient and vast. The resonance is nearly indistinguishable from the ambient forest-signature unless the hakuturi is actively using its abilities (DC 22 to detect a passive hakuturi; DC 14 when active).

### Society

Hakuturi are the guardian-fey of old-growth forests in Kovaka elven territory. They are the Kovaka’s primary fey ally — a relationship built on millennia of mutual respect between the Kovaka elves’ sustainable forestry practices and the hakuturi’s role as forest-protectors.

Kovaka elves do not cut living wood without consulting the local hakuturi. This is not superstition; it is practical resource management informed by the hakuturi’s plant sympathy, which allows them to identify which trees can be harvested without damaging the grove’s health and which must be left to grow. Kovaka woodworkers receive hakuturi guidance before every major project — canoe-building, house-construction, tool-making — and the resulting woodwork is considered the finest in Oreka, shaped by fey-informed understanding of the wood’s grain, strength, and living history.

A grove-council — three to seven hakuturi governing a specific old-growth stand — meets rarely and speaks slowly (conversations between hakuturi can take hours, proceeding at the pace of tree-time rather than Kin-time). Kovaka elders attend grove-councils with the patience the occasion demands.

Hasura elves encounter hakuturi in the northern Great Forests and maintain a respectful but less intimate relationship. The Hasura’s canopy-dwelling lifestyle means less interaction with the ground-level old-growth where hakuturi live. Tanuki avoid disturbing hakuturi groves — not from fear but from a rare Tanuki sense of reverence. Even Tanuki recognise that some things in the forest should not be tricked.

### Lore

**DC 14 (Knowledge [nature]):** Hakuturi are forest-guardian fey found in old-growth Kovaka territory. They can merge with trees, command forest vegetation, and communicate with all plant life within range. They do not attack unless their grove is threatened.

**DC 19:** Kovaka elves consult hakuturi before cutting any living wood. Grove-councils of multiple hakuturi can transform clearings into impassable vegetation. Their resonance is nearly indistinguishable from ambient forest-signature when passive.

**DC 24:** Hakuturi plant sympathy covers 500 feet, providing awareness of every creature touching the ground. Kovaka woodwork is considered Oreka’s finest because it is shaped by hakuturi guidance. Even Tanuki display rare reverence near hakuturi groves.

# HARPY

The singing starts before you see her. It comes from above — from the cliff-face, from the marsh-edge, from the ruin’s upper story — and it is beautiful. Not just pleasant. Beautiful in the way that makes you stop walking, stop thinking, stop being afraid. Your legs move toward the sound before your brain can object. By the time you see what is singing — the matted feathers, the human face twisted by cruelty, the taloned feet — you are already too close.

**Medium Monstrous Humanoid**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Monstrous Humanoid |
| **Hit Dice** | 7d8 (31 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +2 |
| **Speed** | 20 ft. (4 squares), fly 80 ft. (average) |
| **Armor Class** | 13 (+2 Dex, +1 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 11 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +7/+7 |
| **Attack** | Club +7 melee (1d6) |
| **Full Attack** | Club +7/+2 melee (1d6) and 2 claws +2 melee (1d3) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Captivating song |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., elemental resonance (Air, corrupted) |
| **Saves** | Fort +2, Ref +7, Will +6 |
| **Abilities** | Str 10, Dex 15, Con 10, Int 7, Wis 12, Cha 17 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +11, Intimidate +7, Listen +7, Perform (song) +13, Spot +3 |
| **Feats** | Dodge, Flyby Attack, Persuasive |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Youngest Brother (Air) — corrupted; the harpy is the wind made cruel, the Youngest Brother’s domain twisted into a lure |
| **Environment** | Cliffs and Marshes (coastal cliffs along the Apelian Sea, the marshy fringes of the Tidebloom Reach, and the ruin-studded cliffsides of the Kinsweave — anywhere that combines elevation with nearby prey-populations) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or flight (7–12) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 4 |
| **Treasure** | Standard |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic evil |
| **Advancement** | 8–10 HD (Medium) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +3 |

### Combat

A harpy’s entire strategy centres on its captivating song. From an elevated perch — a cliff-ledge, a ruin-wall, a dead tree — the harpy begins singing, compelling listeners to approach. Once the victim is within reach (typically at the base of the cliff or in the shallow water below the perch), the harpy swoops down with Flyby Attack, striking with club and claws before retreating to altitude.

A flight of harpies sings in overlapping harmonies that reinforce the compulsion effect — a single harpy’s song is dangerous; twelve singing together is almost irresistible. Flights use relay-singing to maintain continuous coverage while individuals take turns feeding.

### Special Abilities

**Captivating Song (Su):** A harpy’s song compels all creatures within 300 feet that hear it to move toward the source. A Will save (DC 16) negates the effect. A creature that successfully saves is immune to that harpy’s song for 24 hours. An affected creature moves toward the harpy by the most direct route, heedless of hazards (cliffs, water, combat). The captivation lasts as long as the harpy continues singing and for 1 round afterward. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** Harpies register on Kin-sense as corrupted air-resonance — the Youngest Brother’s wind made seductive and predatory. The resonance feels like a warm breeze carrying a scent you cannot quite identify but desperately want to follow. A DC 14 Kin-sense check detects a harpy’s corrupted air-signature; recognising the resonance for what it is provides a +2 bonus on Will saves against the captivating song.

### Society

Harpies are aerial predators that nest on cliffs and high structures, using their supernatural song to lure prey into hazardous terrain. They are intelligent enough to choose nesting sites strategically — always near populated areas or trade-routes, always with a killing-ground below the perch (shallow water, rocky ground, tidal flats).

Eruskan river-cities along the Apelian coast deal with harpy flights as a persistent urban hazard. Eruskan harbour authorities maintain “silence-bells” — large bronze bells rung at intervals to disrupt harpy song with competing sound. Eruskan sailors carry wax ear-plugs as standard equipment in waters near known harpy cliffs.

Tidebloom marsh-communities face harpies along the marsh-cliff interfaces. Tidebloom halfling fishing-villages post song-watchers — individuals who plug their own ears and watch for companions walking in the wrong direction with a dreamy expression. The song-watcher’s job is to physically restrain the enchanted before they walk off a cliff or into deep water.

### Lore

**DC 14 (Knowledge [nature]):** Harpies are flying humanoid predators whose supernatural song compels listeners to approach. They nest on cliffs and lure victims into hazardous terrain below. Ear-plugs or competing noise disrupts the song’s effect.

**DC 19:** Harpy flights sing in overlapping harmonies that reinforce the compulsion. Eruskan harbour authorities use silence-bells to disrupt their song. Recognising harpy air-resonance on Kin-sense provides a +2 Will save bonus against the captivating song.

**DC 24:** Tidebloom communities post dedicated song-watchers — ear-plugged sentries who watch for charmed companions. Harpies choose nesting sites strategically near populated areas. Their corrupted air-resonance feels like a warm breeze carrying an unidentifiable, irresistible scent.

# HIERACOSPHINX

It has a hawk’s head and a lion’s body and none of the intelligence of its gynosphinx cousins. It does not pose riddles. It does not bargain. It sits on a sand-scoured ridge in the Glass Wastes and watches the desert below with eyes that calculate nothing except distance, angle, and speed.

**Large Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 9d10+18 (67 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +2 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), fly 90 ft. (poor) |
| **Armor Class** | 17 (–1 size, +2 Dex, +6 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 15 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +9/+18 |
| **Attack** | Bite +13 melee (1d10+5) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +13 melee (1d10+5) and 2 claws +8 melee (1d6+2) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Pounce, shriek |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, elemental resonance (Air, faint) |
| **Saves** | Fort +8, Ref +8, Will +5 |
| **Abilities** | Str 21, Dex 14, Con 15, Int 6, Wis 14, Cha 11 |
| **Skills** | Listen +8, Spot +14 |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Cleave, Flyby Attack, Power Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Youngest Brother (Air) — faint; the hieracosphinx carries a diluted version of the four-element sphinx resonance, stripped to a single attenuated air-note |
| **Environment** | Infinite Desert (the Glass Wastes and surrounding dune-seas — the same general region as gynosphinxes, but occupying the less desirable territories that the greater sphinxes do not claim) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or pair |
| **Challenge Rating** | 5 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic evil |
| **Advancement** | 10–14 HD (Large) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A hieracosphinx fights with brute aerial aggression — diving from altitude, striking with pounce and full attack, and using its shriek to disorient prey before closing. It has no subtlety, no magic, and no interest in negotiation.

**Pounce (Ex):** A hieracosphinx that charges can make a full attack.

**Shriek (Su):** Three times per day, a hieracosphinx can emit a piercing shriek. All creatures within 60 feet must succeed on a DC 16 Fortitude save or be deafened for 2d6 rounds. The save DC is Constitution-based.

### Special Abilities

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** A hieracosphinx registers on Kin-sense as a single, faint air-note — the residue of sphinx four-element resonance stripped to its thinnest component. Where a gynosphinx’s resonance is a complex, fragmented four-part harmony, the hieracosphinx’s is a single thin whistle — recognisably related but diminished.

### Society

Hieracosphinxes are the lowest-ranked sphinx variety in Oreka — less intelligent than criosphinxes, far less than gynosphinxes or androsphinxes, and treated by all other sphinxes with open contempt. They occupy the margins of the Glass Wastes that the greater sphinxes don’t want and prey on anything smaller than themselves.

Pekakarlik caravans treat hieracosphinxes as dangerous animals rather than intelligent threats — the caravan-master’s riddle-collection is useless against a creature that cannot understand the question. Armed escort and ranged fire are the standard counter-measures.

Gynosphinxes occasionally kill hieracosphinxes that stray too close to their territories. This is not territorial defense in the normal sense — it is contempt expressed as violence. A gynosphinx considers a hieracosphinx an insult to the sphinx form.

### Lore

**DC 15 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Hieracosphinxes are hawk-headed lion creatures in the Glass Wastes. Unlike other sphinxes, they have no intelligence and do not bargain — they are pure aerial predators. Their shriek deafens.

**DC 20:** Hieracosphinxes are treated with contempt by other sphinx varieties. Their resonance is a single faint air-note — the residue of sphinx four-element harmony. Pekakarlik caravans counter them with ranged fire, not riddles.

# GOREHAM (BRUTE)

It is ten feet tall and most of that is gut. Where the Fogwrack is a mockery of Giant grace and the Hrokk is a mockery of Giant efficiency, the Goreham is a mockery of Giant endurance — a lumbering, thick-skinned, dim-witted slab of Dómnathar-manufactured flesh that exists to absorb damage and keep moving forward. It is not fast. It is not clever. It is not frightening in the way the Fogwrack is frightening. It is simply, relentlessly, stupidly present, and it will not stop coming until it is dead.

**Large Giant**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Giant |
| **Hit Dice** | 12d8+48 (102 hp) |
| **Initiative** | –1 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares; 20 ft. in hide armour) |
| **Armor Class** | 20 (–1 size, –1 Dex, +9 natural, +3 hide armour), touch 8, flat-footed 20 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +9/+20 |
| **Attack** | Greatclub +16 melee (2d8+10) or rock +8 ranged (2d6+7) |
| **Full Attack** | Greatclub +16/+11 melee (2d8+10) or rock +8 ranged (2d6+7) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./10 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Rock throwing (range increment 120 ft.) |
| **Special Qualities** | Low-light vision, rock catching, hollow resonance, Dómnathar-forged |
| **Saves** | Fort +12, Ref +3, Will +4 |
| **Abilities** | Str 25, Dex 8, Con 19, Int 5, Wis 10, Cha 5 |
| **Skills** | Climb +10, Listen +5, Spot +6 |
| **Feats** | Cleave, Improved Bull Rush, Power Attack, Toughness, Weapon Focus (greatclub) |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — artificial earth-attunement, cosmetic only |
| **Environment** | Temperate Hills (the low foothills and rolling terrain between the Giant’s Teeth and the settled lowlands — lower elevation than Hrokk territory, further from mountain peaks than Fogwrack lairs, occupying the most accessible terrain where Brutes can sustain themselves on livestock, game, and stolen food) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, gang (3–4), or mob (5–8, rare — a degraded War-era formation, less cohesive than Hrokk warbands) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 7 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (scavenged, accumulated, poorly maintained) |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic evil |
| **Advancement** | By character class |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A Goreham fights the way it was designed to fight: it advances and hits things. The Dómnathar built Gorehams as damage-absorbers — the creature that walks into the arrow-storm so the Hrokk and Charjaw behind it don’t have to. Three centuries of feral existence have not changed this programming. A Goreham charges the nearest enemy and swings its greatclub until the enemy stops moving or the Goreham does.

Gorehams throw rocks at range (120 ft. increment) with surprising accuracy — the only indication that the Dómnathar invested any design-effort beyond “large and durable.” Against fortified positions, Gorehams throw rocks until the wall breaks, then walk through the gap. Against mobile targets, they charge and rely on their Constitution 19 and 102 hit points to absorb damage long enough to close.

Gorehams in groups do not coordinate. Unlike Hrokk, which retain residual formation-programming, Gorehams simply converge on the same target independently. The result is a mob rather than a formation — multiple massive creatures all attacking the same thing from different angles, effective through volume rather than tactics.

### Special Abilities

**Rock Throwing (Ex):** Range increment 120 ft.

**Rock Catching (Ex):** Reflex DC 15 + damage dice.

**Dómnathar-Forged (Su):** Gorehams are the second-most common Brute type, manufactured by the Dómnathar as durable front-line infantry — tougher than Hrokk (more hit points, better natural armour) but slower and stupider. The design prioritised damage absorption over everything else: high Constitution, heavy natural armour, and enough Strength to swing a club effectively. Intelligence, speed, and initiative were considered unnecessary for a creature whose primary function was “walk toward the enemy and don’t die.”

Gorehams reproduce, but slowly and unreliably — offspring are viable but often smaller and weaker than the manufactured originals. The Goreham population has declined gradually since the War, from hundreds to an estimated sixty to eighty surviving in the temperate hills of Oreka. They are still more common than Fogwracks and Charjaws but less common than the self-sustaining Hrokk.

**Hollow Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a Goreham registers as a dull, flat earth-signature — hollow but not as convincing a mockery as the Fogwrack or as obviously doubled as the Hrokk. The Goreham’s resonance is the most muted of the four Brute types: the Dómnathar invested less artistry in the design, producing a signal that is recognisably artificial but barely trying to imitate anything. Kin describe it as “hearing a drum with no skin” — the shape of resonance without the substance.

### Society

Gorehams have no society. They are feral Brutes — dumber than Hrokk, less territorial than Fogwrack, and more persistently destructive than either because their low intelligence and high endurance combine to produce a creature that simply does not stop.

Where Fogwrack occupy mountain summits and Hrokk claim cave-systems, Gorehams drift through the low hills and open terrain between mountains and settlements. They are the Brute type most frequently encountered by Kin communities because they occupy the most accessible terrain. An Orean farming village on the Giant’s Teeth margins may go years without seeing a Fogwrack but will deal with a Goreham incursion seasonally.

Orean communities near Goreham territory maintain militia response-protocols: signal-fires, evacuation routes, and pre-positioned weapon-caches. The standard Orean response to a Goreham sighting is to evacuate livestock, barricade the village, and signal for reinforcements. A single Goreham can be handled by an organised militia; a mob of five or more requires professional military response.

Mytroan steppe-riders encounter Gorehams at the steppe-hill border and treat them with professional contempt — dangerous, but killable with mounted archery and patience. A Mytroan hunting party can bring down a Goreham by riding circles around it, firing at range, and waiting for it to bleed out. The Mytroan consider this practice good training for young riders.

Vestri military units regard Goreham extermination as routine duty — less urgent than Fogwrack monitoring, less frequent than Hrokk pest-control, but a necessary part of maintaining the safety of lowland Kin settlements.

### Lore

**DC 17 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Gorehams are Dómnathar-manufactured Brutes — large, durable, and stupid. They were designed as damage-absorbing front-line infantry. They throw rocks at range and club at melee. They are the Brute type most commonly encountered near lowland settlements.

**DC 22:** Gorehams reproduce slowly and unreliably — the population has declined from hundreds to an estimated sixty to eighty. Their hollow resonance is the most muted of the four Brute types. They do not coordinate in groups, producing mobs rather than formations.

**DC 27:** The Dómnathar designed Gorehams to absorb arrow-storms so more valuable Brute types could advance behind them. Orean farming communities maintain militia protocols for Goreham incursions. Mytroan riders use them as training targets for young mounted archers.

# HIPPOGRIFF

The horse has wings. That is the simplest, most reductive description, and it is wrong — the creature is not a horse with wings any more than a griffon is an eagle with a lion’s body. It is its own thing: part raptor, part equine, shaped by the same elemental forces that produced griffons but with a different emphasis. Where the griffon is all predator, the hippogriff is half-wild, half-willing, and that willingness is what makes it valuable.

**Large Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 3d10+9 (25 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +2 |
| **Speed** | 50 ft. (10 squares), fly 100 ft. (average) |
| **Armor Class** | 15 (–1 size, +2 Dex, +4 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 13 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +3/+11 |
| **Attack** | Claw +6 melee (1d4+4) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 claws +6 melee (1d4+4) and bite +1 melee (1d8+2) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | — |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, scent, elemental resonance (Air/Earth) |
| **Saves** | Fort +6, Ref +5, Will +2 |
| **Abilities** | Str 18, Dex 15, Con 16, Int 2, Wis 13, Cha 9 |
| **Skills** | Listen +4, Spot +8 |
| **Feats** | Dodge, Wingover |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Youngest Brother (Air) / Lord of Stone (Earth) — similar to griffons but lighter, more air-dominant; the hippogriff is wind-over-hill rather than wind-over-mountain |
| **Environment** | Giant’s Teeth Foothills (the low, grassy hills and upland meadows of the Giant’s Teeth margins — lower elevation than griffon territory, in terrain where grassland meets slope and thermal-updrafts are strong) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or flight (7–12) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 2 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always neutral |
| **Advancement** | 4–6 HD (Large) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +2 (cohort) |

### Combat

Hippogriffs fight defensively — using flight to evade and striking with diving claw-attacks only when necessary. They are less aggressive than griffons and more inclined to flee from threats that outmatch them. A hippogriff defends its nest fiercely but does not pursue threats once they retreat.

### Special Abilities

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** Hippogriffs register on Kin-sense as a light, clean air/earth signature — similar to griffons but softer, less predatory, more open. Kin describe hippogriff resonance as “the wind deciding to land.” The openness of the resonance is what makes hippogriffs more trainable than griffons — there is a willingness in the signal that griffon-resonance lacks.

### Society

Hippogriffs are semi-wild aerial grazers that nest on hill-slopes and forage across the upland meadows. They are herbivorous (unlike the predatory griffon) and socially gregarious, forming flights of seven to twelve individuals that roost communally and migrate seasonally along the foothill corridors.

Hippogriffs are the only aerial mount in Oreka that can be reliably trained from captive-bred stock. Orean humans in the Giant’s Teeth foothills have developed hippogriff-breeding traditions that date back centuries — selecting for temperament, stamina, and willingness to accept a rider. Orean hippogriff-riders are rare but not mythical: every major Orean settlement in the foothills maintains at least one hippogriff-breeding family, and Orean aerial scouts mounted on hippogriffs serve as rapid-response messengers and reconnaissance.

The relationship between hippogriffs and griffons is hostile. Griffons attack hippogriffs on sight — the same instinctive horse-hatred that drives griffons to attack mundane horses applies to hippogriffs. Hippogriff-breeders in griffon-adjacent territory must protect their flocks from griffon predation, and the management of this territorial boundary is a significant part of Orean foothill life.

Eruskan merchants pay premium prices for trained hippogriff mounts, but the Orean breeding families are protective of their stock and rarely sell trained adults — hatchlings and eggs are occasionally traded, but the training itself is considered an Orean cultural secret.

### Lore

**DC 12 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Hippogriffs are flying horse-eagle hybrids found in the Giant’s Teeth foothills. Unlike griffons, they are herbivorous and can be trained as mounts. Griffons attack hippogriffs on sight.

**DC 17:** Orean foothill families have bred hippogriffs for centuries. Orean aerial scouts use them for rapid messaging and reconnaissance. Their Kin-sense resonance has an “openness” that makes them trainable.

**DC 22:** Hippogriff-breeding is an Orean cultural tradition — trained adults are rarely sold, though hatchlings and eggs enter trade. Managing the griffon-hippogriff territorial boundary is a major part of Orean foothill life.

# HUALLALLO

The mountain is angry. That is what the Orean herders say when the ground shakes and the sky turns orange and the air tastes of sulphur thick enough to chew. The mountain is angry, and the anger has a shape. It walks out of the caldera on legs of cooling basalt, trailing magma behind it like a cloak, and it is thirty feet tall and burning from the inside. Its eyes are white-hot. Its hands are fists of volcanic glass. The Orean do not run from it — you cannot outrun a volcanic eruption. They pray. Some of them pray to the Lady of Fire. Some of them pray to the mountain itself. Neither answers. The Huallallo does not care about prayers. It is not a god. It is a tantrum.

**Huge Giant (Fire)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Huge Giant (Fire) |
| **Hit Dice** | 18d8+126 (207 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +0 |
| **Speed** | 40 ft. (8 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 28 (–2 size, +20 natural), touch 8, flat-footed 28 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +13/+33 |
| **Attack** | Slam +23 melee (2d8+12 plus 2d6 fire) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 slams +23 melee (2d8+12 plus 2d6 fire) |
| **Space/Reach** | 15 ft./15 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Magma blood, volcanic eruption, heat aura, trample 2d8+18 plus 2d6 fire |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 120 ft., damage reduction 10/cold, immunity to fire, vulnerability to cold, regeneration 5, spell resistance 25, tremorsense 120 ft., elemental resonance (Fire/Earth, primordial) |
| **Saves** | Fort +18, Ref +6, Will +10 |
| **Abilities** | Str 35, Dex 10, Con 25, Int 8, Wis 14, Cha 12 |
| **Skills** | Climb +20, Intimidate +15, Listen +15, Spot +15 |
| **Feats** | Awesome Blow, Cleave, Great Cleave, Improved Bull Rush, Improved Overrun, Power Attack, Toughness |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of Fire (Fire) / Lord of Stone (Earth) — primordial; like the grootslang, the huallallo’s affinity is raw and undivided, from an age when fire and earth were not yet separate concepts |
| **Environment** | Giant’s Teeth Volcanoes (the active and semi-active volcanic peaks in the southern Giant’s Teeth, where the mountain range meets the Scorchspires — specifically the calderas and lava-tube systems that Orean mythology identifies as “the Lady’s Anger”) |
| **Organization** | Solitary (always) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 14 |
| **Treasure** | None (but volcanic glass, obsidian, and fire-formed gemstones litter the terrain around a huallallo’s caldera) |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic neutral |
| **Advancement** | 19–27 HD (Huge); 28–36 HD (Gargantuan) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A huallallo is a volcanic eruption with legs. It does not employ tactics — it advances, destroys, and retreats into its caldera when the eruption subsides. Its heat aura damages everything within 30 feet, its slams combine physical force with magma-temperature fire, and its volcanic eruption ability can devastate an area the size of a village.

In combat, a huallallo walks toward the largest concentration of enemies and slams. If surrounded, it uses volcanic eruption to clear the area — a burst of superheated gas and molten rock that kills or scatters everything nearby. Its regeneration 5 (suppressed by cold) means that minor damage is meaningless; only sustained, concentrated assault can bring it down.

A huallallo does not fight intelligently. Its Int 8 provides basic awareness but not tactical thinking. It does not flank, does not prioritise targets, and does not exploit weaknesses. It is a force of nature that happens to have arms.

### Special Abilities

**Heat Aura (Ex):** All creatures within 30 feet of a huallallo take 2d6 fire damage per round. Combustible materials ignite. Stone within 10 feet begins to soften and glow. This heat is constant and cannot be suppressed.

**Magma Blood (Ex):** When a huallallo is struck in melee, the attacker takes 2d6 fire damage as molten rock sprays from the wound. Weapons that strike a huallallo must succeed on a DC 25 Fortitude save or lose 1 point of hardness per hit. Metal weapons that reach 0 hardness melt.

**Volcanic Eruption (Su):** Once per day, a huallallo can erupt — releasing a burst of superheated gas, molten rock, and volcanic ash in a 60-foot radius. All creatures in the area take 10d6 fire damage and 5d6 bludgeoning damage (Reflex DC 26 half). The area is covered in cooling lava (difficult terrain, 2d6 fire damage per round to creatures standing in it) for 1 hour. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Trample (Ex):** Reflex DC 31 half. 2d8+18 plus 2d6 fire.

**Regeneration (Ex):** A huallallo regenerates 5 hp per round. Cold damage deals normal damage. A huallallo reduced to –10 hp by cold damage is destroyed; otherwise, it regenerates and rises.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a huallallo registers as primordial fire/earth in a form even more overwhelming than a grootslang — it is not a creature with an elemental signature, it IS elemental fire given a body. The resonance blankets everything within 500 feet, drowning out all other signals. Kin within range experience the resonance as physical heat pressing on the Kin-sense — not painful but obliterating, like standing too close to the sun.

Orean humans describe encountering huallallo resonance as “hearing the mountain’s heartbeat.” Rarozhki Dwarves who have experienced it compare it to the grootslang’s primordial resonance but more violent, more aggressive — where the grootslang is “the first forge,” the huallallo is “the first eruption.”

### Society

Huallallo are volcanic entities — primordial expressions of fire-and-earth elemental force that predate the Giants, the Kin, and possibly the Elemental Lords themselves. They are not intelligent in any meaningful sense; they are aware, reactive, and driven by volcanic cycles that have nothing to do with Kin affairs. A huallallo sleeps in its caldera for decades or centuries, then wakes, walks, destroys what is in its path, and returns to sleep.

Orean humans in the southern Giant’s Teeth have built their entire mythology around the huallallo. Orean volcano-theology holds that the huallallo are fragments of the Lady of Fire’s original anger — the rage she felt when the Elemental Lords withdrew from the world, crystallised into walking volcanic golems that periodically re-enact the original fury. This theology is not supported by evidence (the huallallo predate the withdrawal), but it provides a framework for understanding why a thirty-foot burning giant occasionally walks out of a mountain and flattens a village.

Orean communities near active volcanoes maintain *wayra-watchers* — seismically-trained observers who monitor the caldera for signs of huallallo awakening. The warning signs are well-documented: increased tremor activity, rising caldera temperatures, strange light-patterns in the volcanic gas-plumes, and — most reliably — a surge in Kin-sense resonance from the caldera that overwhelms all other signals in the area. When a wayra-watcher confirms pre-awakening signs, the community evacuates. There is no other response. You do not fight a huallallo. You leave.

Rarozhki Dwarves, whose Scorchspire homeland borders the huallallo’s volcanic range, regard the creatures with profound respect. The Rarozhki do not worship huallallo (they are not gods), but they recognise them as kin of the Lady of Fire in a way that no other creature — not even the Emberfang Wyrm — can claim. A Rarozhki smith who has seen a huallallo awake (and survived) is considered to have been touched by the Lady’s original fire.

There are perhaps five or six huallallo in Oreka. None have names. All are sleeping. The last awakening occurred forty-seven years ago, when one walked twelve miles from its caldera, destroyed an Orean mining-camp, and returned to sleep. The camp was not rebuilt.

### Lore

**DC 19 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Huallallo are volcanic entities — primordial fire/earth given humanoid form. They sleep in calderas for decades, awake, walk, destroy, and return to sleep. They regenerate and are immune to fire.

**DC 24:** Orean wayra-watchers monitor calderas for pre-awakening signs. There is no combat protocol — evacuation is the only response. Huallallo resonance drowns all other Kin-sense signals within 500 feet. Cold suppresses their regeneration.

**DC 29:** There are five or six huallallo in Oreka, all sleeping. They predate the Giants. Orean theology calls them fragments of the Lady of Fire’s original anger. Rarozhki consider seeing a waking huallallo equivalent to being touched by the Lady’s fire. The last awakening was forty-seven years ago.

# HULDRA

She is standing in the river. The water is waist-deep and moving fast, and she is standing in it as though it were a warm bath — barefoot on the stones, her back to you, her long hair trailing in the current. She is beautiful. You can tell that even from behind, from the line of her shoulders and the way the water parts around her as though it likes her. Then she turns, and you see her face, and she is more beautiful than you expected. And then you see her back — or rather, you see that her back is not a back. It is hollow. A bark-lined cavity, dark and empty, running from her shoulders to her hips, like the inside of a rotted tree.

**Medium Fey**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Fey |
| **Hit Dice** | 5d6+5 (22 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +3 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), swim 30 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 16 (+3 Dex, +3 natural), touch 13, flat-footed 13 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +2/+3 |
| **Attack** | Slam +5 melee (1d6+1) |
| **Full Attack** | Slam +5 melee (1d6+1) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Spell-like abilities, seductive presence, tail-lash |
| **Special Qualities** | Damage reduction 5/cold iron, low-light vision, forest-step, hollow back, elemental resonance (Water/Earth) |
| **Saves** | Fort +2, Ref +7, Will +6 |
| **Abilities** | Str 13, Dex 17, Con 12, Int 14, Wis 14, Cha 18 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +12, Diplomacy +12, Hide +11 (+19 in forest/river), Knowledge (nature) +10, Listen +10, Move Silently +11, Sense Motive +10, Spot +10, Swim +9 |
| **Feats** | Dodge, Weapon Finesse |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) / Lord of Stone (Earth) — the forest-river border; where water meets earth and both are alive |
| **Environment** | Forest-River Borders (the banks and shallows of rivers that flow through the Great Forests — specifically the transition zone where forest canopy overhangs running water, and the worlds of wood and water overlap) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or pair (sisters) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 4 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (gifts — huldra receive presents from charmed admirers and keep what interests them) |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic neutral |
| **Advancement** | 6–10 HD (Medium) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +3 |

### Combat

A huldra does not fight if she can avoid it. Her first response to conflict is seductive presence — a supernatural charm that redirects aggression into fascination. If charm fails, she uses forest-step to vanish into the nearest tree and emerge from another tree hundreds of feet away. A huldra only fights when cornered, defending young, or genuinely angry.

An angry huldra is more dangerous than her delicate appearance suggests. Her tail — a long, foxlike appendage concealed beneath her dress — lashes with surprising force, and her spell-like abilities (entangle, obscuring mist, charm person) can control a forest-river clearing effectively.

### Special Abilities

**Seductive Presence (Su):** A huldra radiates supernatural allure in a 30-foot radius. Creatures who see the huldra must succeed on a Will save (DC 16) or be fascinated for 1d4 rounds. This is a mind-affecting charm effect. The save DC is Charisma-based. A creature that succeeds is immune for 24 hours.

**Tail-Lash (Ex):** A huldra’s foxtail can lash out to 10 ft. reach, dealing 1d6+1 damage. The tail is normally concealed.

**Spell-Like Abilities:** At will — charm person (DC 15), speak with animals, speak with plants; 3/day — entangle (DC 15), obscuring mist; 1/day — tree stride. CL 5th.

**Forest-Step (Su):** A huldra can step into any living tree of Medium or larger size within 5 feet and emerge from any living tree within 500 feet as a full-round action. This functions as tree stride but is innate.

**Hollow Back (Ex):** A huldra’s back is hollow — a bark-lined cavity visible when her back is turned. This is not a wound or a weakness; it is a natural feature of the species. The hollow back is a vulnerability only in that it reveals the huldra’s true nature — a creature that sees her from behind recognises immediately that she is not human. A huldra always keeps her back to a wall, a tree, or the river when interacting with strangers.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a huldra registers as a warm, inviting water/earth signature — running water over river-stones, forest-scented. The resonance is pleasant and subtly seductive, drawing the detector’s attention the way a warm hearth draws a cold traveler. A DC 16 Kin-sense check detects the fey quality beneath the surface warmth.

### Society

Huldra are forest-river fey — beautiful, dangerous, capricious spirits that inhabit the borderzone between forest and flowing water. They are neither good nor evil but entirely self-interested: they interact with Kin when it amuses them and vanish when it does not.

Huldra relationships with Kin are complicated and frequently end badly. A huldra who takes an interest in a specific Kin individual — usually male, usually attractive, always near her river — may pursue that interest for days, weeks, or months, appearing at the water’s edge to charm, converse, and entangle. If the relationship progresses far enough that the Kin individual sees the hollow back, the huldra’s reaction determines the outcome: some huldra flee in shame, some become enraged, and some — the rare few — accept the revelation and continue the relationship with the understanding that they are not human and never pretended to be.

Eruskan river-communities along the Great River have the richest huldra traditions. Eruskan folklore is full of huldra stories — tragic romances, cautionary tales, and practical advice. The core Eruskan wisdom regarding huldra: never touch a huldra’s back, never follow a huldra into the water at night, and if she offers you a gift, accept it graciously because refusing offends them.

Pasua elves encounter huldra along forest-river borders and treat them with wary respect. Pasua rangers know that a huldra’s forest-step ability makes them nearly impossible to track or confront — the fey can vanish into any tree and reappear half a mile away.

Halfling river-communities maintain a more practical relationship with huldra. Halfling fishermen who work rivers known to harbour huldra leave small offerings — flowers, ribbons, sweet cakes — at the water’s edge. The offerings serve as acknowledgment: we know you are here, we respect your river, we will not disturb you.

### Lore

**DC 14 (Knowledge [nature]):** Huldra are beautiful forest-river fey with a hollow, bark-lined back. They charm Kin with supernatural allure and vanish into trees if threatened. They are capricious but not inherently hostile.

**DC 19:** Eruskan wisdom: never touch a huldra’s back, never follow one into water at night, never refuse a gift. Their forest-step ability lets them vanish into any tree and emerge up to 500 feet away. Their tail is concealed but can strike at 10 ft. reach.

**DC 24:** A huldra that reveals her hollow back to a Kin partner is the defining moment of any huldra relationship — the fey’s reaction (shame, rage, or acceptance) determines the outcome. Halfling river-communities leave offerings as acknowledgment of huldra presence.

# HUMBABA

The door opens and the guardian is there. It has been there for seven thousand years. It is fifteen feet tall, built of stone and bronze and elemental fire bound into a framework that the Giants designed to last forever, and it has. Its face is a lion’s face carved in basalt. Its body is a humanoid chassis of interlocking stone plates over a skeleton of Giant-forged bronze. Its eyes — two points of white-hot elemental fire — track you from the doorway to the threshold, and the voice that emerges from the stone mouth is flat, patient, and absolute: “This hall is sealed by the authority of those who built it. Turn back or be destroyed.”

**Large Construct (Elemental)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Construct (Elemental) |
| **Hit Dice** | 16d10+30 (118 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +1 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 28 (–1 size, +1 Dex, +18 natural), touch 10, flat-footed 27 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +12/+25 |
| **Attack** | Slam +20 melee (2d8+9 plus 1d6 fire) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 slams +20 melee (2d8+9 plus 1d6 fire) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./10 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Breath weapon, terrifying roar, guardian’s challenge |
| **Special Qualities** | Construct traits, damage reduction 10/adamantine, darkvision 120 ft., immunity to fire, immunity to magic (limited), spell resistance 24, elemental core, guardian protocol, remnant resonance |
| **Saves** | Fort +5, Ref +6, Will +7 |
| **Abilities** | Str 28, Dex 12, Con —, Int 12, Wis 14, Cha 16 |
| **Skills** | Intimidate +16, Listen +15, Search +14, Sense Motive +15, Spot +15 |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Cleave, Great Cleave, Improved Bull Rush, Improved Sunder, Power Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | All Four Elemental Lords — integrated; the humbaba was built with the Firstborn’s four-element mastery, its elemental core containing bound fragments of all four domains |
| **Environment** | Giant Ruins (the interior of the best-preserved Giant-era structures — specifically guarding doorways, halls, treasure-vaults, and sacred chambers; found in ruins across the Infinite Desert, Giant’s Teeth, and Kinsweave deep-sites) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or pair (one per doorway, sometimes two flanking a major entrance) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 13 |
| **Treasure** | None (but the chambers they guard contain Giant-era artifacts of extraordinary value) |
| **Alignment** | Always lawful neutral |
| **Advancement** | 17–24 HD (Large); 25–32 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A humbaba follows its guardian protocol precisely. When a creature enters the guarded area, the humbaba issues a verbal challenge in Giant (and, if its original programming included the instruction, in Common or other languages). The challenge is always the same: turn back or be destroyed. If the intruder leaves, the humbaba returns to its post. If the intruder does not leave, the humbaba attacks.

A humbaba opens combat with its terrifying roar — a blast of elemental force that shakes the ruins and panics opponents. It then advances with slam attacks, using its reach and Improved Bull Rush to control the doorway it guards. A humbaba never abandons its post — it fights in its designated area and does not pursue intruders who retreat beyond the guarded zone.

Against multiple opponents, a humbaba uses Cleave and Great Cleave to punish clustered attackers, and its breath weapon (a 30-foot cone of elemental fire drawn from its core) to clear groups. It targets the most immediate threat with melee and uses the breath weapon against enemies that stay at range.

A humbaba is intelligent (Int 12) and fights with purpose — it is not mindless, not reactive, but a thinking guardian executing orders it received seven thousand years ago with the judgment its creators intended.

### Special Abilities

**Breath Weapon (Su):** 30-foot cone of elemental fire, 8d6 fire damage, Reflex DC 18 half. Usable every 1d4 rounds. The fire is drawn from the humbaba’s elemental core and burns with the white-hot intensity of Giant-forged flame. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Terrifying Roar (Su):** Once every 1d4 rounds, a humbaba can release a roar of elemental authority. All creatures within 60 feet must succeed on a Will save (DC 21) or be panicked for 1d4 rounds. Creatures that succeed are shaken for 1 round. This is a mind-affecting fear effect enhanced by the humbaba’s elemental resonance — the roar carries the weight of the Firstborn’s authority, and resisting it requires resisting the instinctive Kin awe of Giant-made things. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Guardian’s Challenge (Ex):** Before attacking, a humbaba always issues a verbal challenge to intruders in Giant and any other languages it was programmed with. This is not a formality — it is a core function. A humbaba cannot attack a creature that has not been challenged. If the creature retreats after the challenge, the humbaba allows it. If the creature responds in Giant with specific command-phrases (known only to the Giants who built it), the humbaba stands aside.

The command-phrases are different for each humbaba and were never recorded in any surviving text. Discovering a humbaba’s command-phrase requires research into that specific ruin’s history (a nearly impossible task given the age of the structures) or creative problem-solving. Some Pekakarlik ruin-explorers have spent years researching individual humbaba command-phrases, and the few who have succeeded consider it their life’s greatest achievement.

**Elemental Core (Su):** A humbaba’s body is animated by an elemental core — a bound fragment of all four elemental domains, integrated in the manner of the Firstborn’s four-element mastery. The core is the humbaba’s power source, its consciousness, and its connection to the Giants who built it. Destroying the core (located in the humbaba’s chest, AC 25, hardness 15, 50 hp; reachable only after the humbaba is reduced to 0 hp) is the only way to permanently destroy a humbaba. A humbaba reduced to 0 hp but with an intact core begins regenerating (1 hp per hour) and will eventually stand again.

**Immunity to Magic (Ex):** A humbaba is immune to any spell or spell-like ability that allows spell resistance, except: spells with the [Cold] descriptor deal normal damage and suppress the elemental core for 1 round (no regeneration during suppression); disintegrate deals normal damage; and dispel magic targeted at the elemental core forces a DC 21 Will save or the humbaba is stunned for 1 round.

**Guardian Protocol (Ex):** A humbaba obeys orders that were given to it by its Giant creators — orders that may be thousands of years old. It cannot learn new orders, cannot be reprogrammed, and cannot be convinced that its orders are no longer relevant. It guards what it was told to guard, attacks what it was told to attack, and waits in between. This is not stupidity — it is loyalty to masters who are gone, expressed through a machine that does not understand that they are gone.

**Remnant Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a humbaba registers as a four-element harmony — the same integrated resonance as the vanished Giants, but mechanical, precise, and unnervingly perfect. Where a gallu’s four-element resonance is shattered by death, and a gynosphinx’s is refracted through a bestial lens, the humbaba’s is exactly as the Giants designed it: a flawless reproduction of Firstborn harmony, locked in construct-form and unchanged for millennia.

For Vestri Dwarves, detecting humbaba resonance is the closest thing to hearing a living Giant that exists in the modern world. The resonance is perfect — and the perfection is what makes it heartbreaking, because the Giant who designed it put their own elemental harmony into the construct and then crumbled to dust while the construct kept playing the song.

### Society

Humbaba are Giant-era construct guardians — the last functional products of the Firstborn’s elemental engineering, still carrying out orders that were given before the Kin were shaped. They are not golems in the traditional sense (mindless automatons animated by a spell); they are intelligent, aware, and purposeful constructs with elemental cores that provide both power and a form of consciousness.

Every humbaba guards a specific location — a doorway, a hall, a vault — and has guarded that location without interruption since the day it was activated. Some humbaba have stood at their posts for seven thousand years or more, motionless and patient, waiting for an intrusion that may not come for centuries.

Pekakarlik ruin-explorers regard humbaba as the most formidable hazard in Giant ruins — more dangerous than gallu (which are incorporeal and cannot physically prevent access to treasures), more reliable than bound elementals (which sometimes degrade), and nearly indestructible. Pekakarlik expedition protocol classifies humbaba-guarded chambers as “red zones” — areas that require either the command-phrase (rare, difficult to research) or overwhelming force (expensive, dangerous) to access.

Vestri Dwarves who encounter humbaba in the mountain-halls treat them with the same reverence they show gallu — but where gallu inspire grief, humbaba inspire awe. The construct is a working piece of Giant engineering, flawlessly preserved, still executing its function after millennia. Vestri artificers study humbaba from a safe distance, trying to understand the four-element core technology that the Giants used. None have succeeded in replicating it.

The relationship between humbaba and gallu is a source of scholarly fascination. A ruin may contain both: the gallu — the spirit of the Giant who built the humbaba — drifting through the halls in grief, while the humbaba stands at its post, still obeying orders the gallu gave when it was alive. Whether the gallu recognises the humbaba, or the humbaba recognises the gallu, is unknown. Neither has ever been observed interacting with the other.

### Lore

**DC 18 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Humbaba are Giant-built construct guardians that still guard specific locations in ancient ruins. They are intelligent, issue verbal challenges before attacking, and never leave their posts. They have damage reduction 10/adamantine.

**DC 23:** A humbaba can be bypassed with specific command-phrases known only to its Giant creators. Its elemental core must be destroyed to permanently kill it — otherwise it regenerates. Pekakarlik explorers spend years researching individual command-phrases.

**DC 28:** Humbaba resonance is a flawless reproduction of Firstborn four-element harmony — the closest thing to a living Giant’s resonance in the modern world. Vestri artificers study the four-element core technology without success. Humbaba and gallu may coexist in the same ruin without ever interacting.

# HYDRA

Five heads. Five necks. One body. The body is the size of a horse and scaled in dark, wet green; the necks are each ten feet long and independently mobile, weaving and striking like snakes operated by a single furious brain. When one head lunges, the others cover it. When one head is hurt, the others strike at the attacker. The creature does not think — five heads do not produce five times the intelligence, they produce five times the aggression.

**Huge Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Huge Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 5d10+28 (55 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +1 |
| **Speed** | 20 ft. (4 squares), swim 20 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 15 (–2 size, +1 Dex, +6 natural), touch 9, flat-footed 14 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +5/+16 |
| **Attack** | 5 bites +6 melee (1d10+3) |
| **Full Attack** | 5 bites +6 melee (1d10+3) |
| **Space/Reach** | 15 ft./10 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | — |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., fast healing 15, low-light vision, scent, elemental resonance (Water) |
| **Saves** | Fort +9, Ref +5, Will +3 |
| **Abilities** | Str 17, Dex 12, Con 20, Int 2, Wis 10, Cha 9 |
| **Skills** | Listen +6, Spot +6, Swim +11 |
| **Feats** | Combat Reflexes, Iron Will, Toughness |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) — hydras are creatures of the deep marsh, saturated with stagnant water-energy |
| **Environment** | Marshes (the Tidebloom Reach, the Deepwater Marches wetlands, and the marshy lowlands where the Great River spreads into seasonal flood-plains — any warm, wet, low-lying terrain with sufficient prey) |
| **Organization** | Solitary |
| **Challenge Rating** | 4 |
| **Treasure** | 1/10th coins |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 6–7 HD (five heads, Huge); 8–10 HD (six to seven heads, Huge); 11–14 HD (eight to ten heads, Gargantuan) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

**Note:** The stat block above represents the standard 5-headed hydra. More powerful variants with additional heads follow the standard advancement: each additional head adds one Hit Die, one bite attack, and adjusts size category at the appropriate thresholds. A 12-headed hydra is a CR 9 Gargantuan terror.

### Combat

A hydra attacks with all heads simultaneously — five bite attacks per round at the standard configuration, more with additional heads. Each head attacks independently, making the hydra devastating against groups (each head can target a different creature) and extremely dangerous to single targets (five attacks on one creature per round).

Severing a head requires a sunder attempt targeting a neck (each head has hp equal to the hydra’s total hp divided by the number of heads). A severed head stops attacking, but two new heads grow from the stump within 1d4 rounds unless the stump is cauterised with fire or acid (at least 5 points of fire or acid damage applied to the stump in the round after severing). The fast healing 15 keeps the hydra alive through tremendous damage.

The only reliable method of killing a hydra is fire or acid applied systematically — burning each stump as heads are severed, then overwhelming the body’s fast healing with sustained damage. Torches, alchemist’s fire, and fire-based magic are essential equipment for hydra encounters.

### Special Abilities

**Fast Healing (Ex):** A hydra heals 15 hp per round. This fast healing applies to the body, not to severed heads.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** A hydra registers on Kin-sense as a heavy, wet, aggressive water-signature — not the Lady of the Sea’s domain at its best but at its most primal: standing water, swamp-rot, and the blind persistence of something that will not die. The resonance intensifies with the number of heads — a 12-headed hydra’s resonance fills a marsh-clearing with the weight of stagnant elemental water.

### Society

Hydras are solitary marsh predators — apex animals that claim stretches of swamp and devour everything in range. They are not intelligent and have no social structure. A hydra simply eats, grows, and regenerates.

Tidebloom communities treat hydra territories as exclusion zones. The standard halfling response to a hydra sighting in a fishing-marsh is to abandon the area until a capable group can be hired to deal with it — fire is required, and not every fishing-village has access to combat magic.

Eruskan river-traders encounter hydras in the Great River’s flood-plain marshes and maintain standing bounties for hydra kills. A confirmed hydra kill — evidenced by a cauterised head brought to the nearest trade-post — pays well, because a hydra in a shipping-lane marsh represents a threat to every barge that passes.

The deep-marsh hydras of the Deepwater Marches occasionally grow to extraordinary sizes — 10 or 12 heads — in the abundant prey-environment of the Marches’ interior. These elder hydras are regional hazards that require military-level response.

### Lore

**DC 14 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Hydras are multi-headed marsh predators that attack with all heads simultaneously. Severing a head causes two new heads to grow unless the stump is cauterised with fire or acid. They heal 15 hp per round.

**DC 19:** Fire or acid is essential for killing hydras — 5 points applied to a stump in the round after severing prevents regrowth. Tidebloom communities evacuate when a hydra is sighted. More heads means higher CR.

**DC 24:** Deepwater Marches hydras can grow to 12 heads in the prey-rich environment. Eruskan river-traders maintain standing bounties. Hydra resonance intensifies with head-count — an elder hydra’s water-resonance fills a clearing.

# IMPUNDULU

The storm comes from nowhere. The sky was clear, the wind was calm, and now the air tastes of copper and the hair on your arms stands straight. Lightning strikes the ground fifty feet away — not from a cloud but from a bird. It is enormous, black-feathered, white-winged, riding the static charge it generates like a ship rides a wave. Its eyes are blue-white and crackling. When it screams, the sound is thunder.

**Large Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 8d10+24 (68 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +4 |
| **Speed** | 10 ft. (2 squares), fly 80 ft. (good) |
| **Armor Class** | 18 (–1 size, +4 Dex, +5 natural), touch 13, flat-footed 14 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +8/+16 |
| **Attack** | Talon +12 melee (1d6+4 plus 1d6 electricity) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 talons +12 melee (1d6+4 plus 1d6 electricity) and bite +9 melee (1d8+2) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Lightning strike, storm aura, blood drain |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., immunity to electricity, fly-by lightning, elemental resonance (Air/Fire) |
| **Saves** | Fort +9, Ref +10, Will +4 |
| **Abilities** | Str 19, Dex 18, Con 16, Int 6, Wis 14, Cha 13 |
| **Skills** | Listen +8, Spot +12 |
| **Feats** | Flyby Attack, Multiattack, Wingover |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Youngest Brother (Air) / Lady of Fire (Fire) — lightning; the impundulu is the storm made predatory, the point where wind becomes fire |
| **Environment** | Deep Steppe (the open grasslands of the Eternal Steppe’s interior, far from mountains or forest — flat terrain where storms build without obstruction and the impundulu can hunt unimpeded by canopy or cliff) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or pair (mated) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 7 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 9–12 HD (Large); 13–16 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

An impundulu attacks from altitude, diving through its own storm aura to strike with electrified talons. Its preferred tactic is the lightning strike — a channeled bolt of electricity that hits a ground target before the bird itself arrives. If the bolt stuns or injures the target, the impundulu follows with a Flyby Attack, raking with talons and retreating to altitude to recharge.

Against large prey (cattle, horses, or Kin-sized targets), an impundulu uses blood drain — landing on the stunned target and feeding directly. The feeding is rapid — the impundulu’s beak pierces and drains — and the bird does not linger on the ground longer than necessary.

### Special Abilities

**Storm Aura (Su):** An impundulu generates a localised storm in a 200-foot radius centred on itself — dark clouds, static charge, gusting wind. Within the aura, ranged attacks take a –2 penalty from wind and visibility reduction. The storm aura is constant while the impundulu is airborne.

**Lightning Strike (Su):** Once every 1d4 rounds, an impundulu can channel a bolt of lightning at a target within 100 feet. The bolt deals 6d6 electricity damage (Reflex DC 17 half). The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Blood Drain (Ex):** An impundulu that successfully grapples a Medium or smaller target can drain blood, dealing 1d4 Constitution damage per round. The impundulu regains 5 hp for each point of Constitution drained.

**Fly-By Lightning (Ex):** An impundulu’s Flyby Attack does not provoke attacks of opportunity from the target of its attack.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, an impundulu registers as a sharp, crackling air/fire signature — lightning in animal form. The resonance arrives before the bird does, detectable at 300 feet as a static-charge sensation that prickles the skin and raises hair. Warg shaman describe impundulu resonance as “the sky deciding to hunt.”

### Society

Impundulu are storm-raptors of the deep steppe — aerial predators that generate their own weather and hunt through the electrical field they create. They are not intelligent, but their hunting patterns are sophisticated: an impundulu follows the natural storm-tracks across the steppe, augmenting existing weather with its storm aura and hunting in the confusion.

Warg packs regard impundulu with a mixture of fear and reverence. The Warg Harmony detects impundulu at extreme range — the storm-aura’s electrical interference creates a distinctive “buzzing” in the Harmony that experienced Warg scouts recognise immediately. Warg tradition holds that an impundulu appearing during a clan-gathering is an omen from the Youngest Brother — the specific interpretation depends on what the bird does (circling overhead is auspicious; striking a member of the gathering is very much not).

Mytroan steppe-riders consider impundulu among the most dangerous aerial threats on the open steppe — more dangerous than rocs (which are predictable) and griffons (which are avoidable). A Mytroan rider caught in an impundulu’s storm aura is blinded by rain, deafened by thunder, and targeted by lightning — the combination is frequently lethal. Mytroan storm-survival training includes impundulu protocols: dismount, ground your metal equipment, and wait.

Warg shaman collect impundulu feathers for ritual purposes. A shed impundulu feather retains a faint electrical charge for days and is used in Warg weather-divination ceremonies. The feathers are never taken from a living or killed bird — only gathered from roost-sites after the impundulu has departed.

### Lore

**DC 16 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Impundulu are storm-generating raptor predators of the deep steppe. They are immune to electricity and attack with lightning bolts from altitude. They drain blood from stunned targets.

**DC 21:** Impundulu generate a 200-foot storm aura that penalises ranged attacks. Warg Harmony detects the electrical interference at extreme range. Mytroan storm-survival protocol: dismount, ground metal equipment, wait.

**DC 26:** Warg tradition reads impundulu appearances at gatherings as omens. Impundulu feathers retain electrical charge for days and are used in Warg weather-divination. The birds follow natural storm-tracks across the steppe, augmenting existing weather.

# INDRIK

The mountain is supposed to be empty. The Rarozhki sealed this valley three generations ago — declared it sacred, marked the approaches, and turned back every expedition. You came anyway, because the things people seal away are usually valuable. Now you understand why they sealed it. The creature standing in the valley-floor is the size of a house — a massive, four-legged beast with a single spiralling horn of black obsidian rising from its skull, its body armoured in volcanic stone plates that shift and grind as it breathes. The ground shakes when it shifts its weight. The air around it shimmers with heat. The Rarozhki did not seal this valley to protect the indrik from you. They sealed it to protect you from the indrik.

**Huge Magical Beast (Fire, Earth)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Huge Magical Beast (Fire, Earth) |
| **Hit Dice** | 16d10+112 (200 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +0 |
| **Speed** | 40 ft. (8 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 27 (–2 size, +19 natural), touch 8, flat-footed 27 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +16/+34 |
| **Attack** | Horn +25 melee (4d6+10 plus 1d6 fire) |
| **Full Attack** | Horn +25 melee (4d6+10 plus 1d6 fire) and 2 hooves +22 melee (2d6+5 plus 1d6 fire) |
| **Space/Reach** | 15 ft./10 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Powerful charge, trample 2d8+15 plus 1d6 fire, volcanic tremor |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 120 ft., damage reduction 10/magic and cold, immunity to fire, vulnerability to cold, spell resistance 24, tremorsense 120 ft., elemental resonance (Fire/Earth, ancient), earth-shaping |
| **Saves** | Fort +17, Ref +10, Will +9 |
| **Abilities** | Str 31, Dex 10, Con 24, Int 4, Wis 14, Cha 12 |
| **Skills** | Listen +12, Spot +12, Survival +12 |
| **Feats** | Awesome Blow, Cleave, Improved Bull Rush, Improved Natural Attack (horn), Multiattack, Power Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of Fire (Fire) / Lord of Stone (Earth) — ancient; the indrik is younger than the grootslang and huallallo but still immensely old, a creature from the age when the Elemental Lords’ domains were raw but beginning to differentiate |
| **Environment** | Scorchspire Interior (the deep volcanic valleys and caldera-basins of the Scorchspire mountain range’s interior — terrain too hostile for permanent Kin habitation, accessible only through passes that the Rarozhki have sealed and marked as sacred) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or pair (mated) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 12 |
| **Treasure** | None (but indrik horn-shards, shed naturally over decades, are among the most valuable crafting materials in Rarozhki trade) |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 17–24 HD (Huge); 25–32 HD (Gargantuan) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

An indrik fights with overwhelming physical force. Its primary attack is its horn — a single spiralling obsidian spire that deals massive damage enhanced by fire. A powerful charge doubles the horn damage and adds a knockback effect that sends Large or smaller creatures flying.

An indrik’s volcanic tremor ability is its area-control weapon — a stomp that sends shockwaves through the ground, knocking creatures prone and cracking stone. In its volcanic valley habitat, this ability can trigger secondary effects: rockslides, lava-vent openings, and structural collapses.

Indrik are territorial but not aggressive. They attack only creatures that enter their claimed valley and do not pursue beyond the valley’s boundaries. A creature that retreats is allowed to leave.

### Special Abilities

**Powerful Charge (Ex):** An indrik that charges deals 8d6+20 damage with its horn plus 1d6 fire, and the target must succeed on a DC 28 Fortitude save or be knocked back 20 feet and prone. The save DC is Strength-based.

**Trample (Ex):** Reflex DC 28 half. 2d8+15 plus 1d6 fire.

**Volcanic Tremor (Su):** As a standard action, an indrik can stomp the ground, sending shockwaves in a 60-foot radius. All creatures in contact with the ground must succeed on a DC 25 Reflex save or be knocked prone. Structures and stone formations in the area take 4d6 damage. The save DC is Constitution-based. Usable every 1d4 rounds.

**Earth-Shaping (Su):** An indrik passively shapes the terrain it inhabits. Over weeks and months, the ground in an indrik’s valley becomes volcanic — harder, hotter, richer in mineral deposits. The indrik does not do this deliberately; its elemental presence saturates the earth. An indrik’s valley is identifiable by the quality of the stone: unusually rich in obsidian, volcanic glass, and fire-gems.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, an indrik registers as a heavy, ancient fire/earth signature — less overwhelming than a huallallo, more focused than a grootslang. The resonance feels like standing on ground that remembers being lava — hot, dense, and patient. Detectable at 400 feet. Rarozhki Dwarves describe indrik resonance as “the forge before it was built” — the raw elemental potential that smithing channels into purpose.

### Society

Indrik are ancient fire/earth creatures — not as primordial as grootslang or huallallo, but older than the Giants and far older than the Kin. They are massive, territorial, and elemental in the deepest sense: their presence reshapes the terrain they inhabit, turning ordinary mountain-valleys into volcanic wonderlands of obsidian, mineral deposits, and fire-gem formation.

Rarozhki Dwarves revere indrik as sacred creatures — living embodiments of the fire/earth intersection that defines Rarozhki culture and craft. The Rarozhki sealed the valleys containing indrik not to claim the mineral wealth (though indrik-shaped valleys are extraordinarily rich) but to ensure the creatures are never disturbed. Rarozhki tradition holds that the indrik’s earth-shaping is a gift from the Lady of Fire and the Lord of Stone — the elemental forces creating mineral wealth through the creature’s existence rather than through mining.

Indrik horn-shards — fragments of the obsidian horn shed naturally over decades as the horn grows — are the most prized crafting material in Rarozhki trade. A single horn-shard, properly worked, can be forged into a weapon of extraordinary quality: naturally fire-aspected, structurally superior to mundane obsidian, and resonant with the indrik’s ancient elemental signature. Rarozhki master-smiths who work indrik horn-shard are considered to be practising the highest form of their craft.

The shards are never harvested from living indrik. Rarozhki gather them from the valley floor during carefully regulated expeditions — small parties, short visits, minimal disturbance. An expedition that disturbs the indrik is a failed expedition, regardless of what it collected.

Taraf-Imro warriors are aware of indrik through Rarozhki trade-contacts but have never seen one — the Scorchspire interior is Rarozhki territory, and the sealed valleys are Rarozhki responsibility. The Taraf-Imro respect this boundary, recognising the Rarozhki’s custodial relationship with the creatures.

### Lore

**DC 17 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Indrik are massive, horn-bearing elemental beasts found in sealed volcanic valleys of the Scorchspire interior. They are territorial, fire-immune, and their presence reshapes terrain over time.

**DC 22:** Rarozhki Dwarves sealed indrik valleys as sacred — the creatures are never disturbed. Indrik horn-shards, shed naturally, are the most prized crafting material in Rarozhki smithing. The shards are gathered during carefully regulated, minimal-disturbance expeditions.

**DC 27:** Indrik earth-shaping enriches their valleys with obsidian and fire-gems over decades. Their resonance is ancient fire/earth — “the forge before it was built.” Rarozhki master-smiths who work indrik horn-shard are practising the highest form of dwarven craft.

# INKANYAMBA

The lake has been wrong for three days. The fishermen noticed first — the water-level rising when it should be falling, the currents running backward, the fish moving to the shallows in panicked schools. Then the storms started. Not regular storms — targeted storms, centred on the lake, rotating with a focus that suggests intelligence rather than weather. Something beneath the surface is angry, and whatever it is, it is large enough to control the water above it.

**Huge Magical Beast (Aquatic)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Huge Magical Beast (Aquatic) |
| **Hit Dice** | 12d10+60 (126 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +3 |
| **Speed** | 20 ft. (4 squares), swim 60 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 22 (–2 size, +3 Dex, +11 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 19 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +12/+28 |
| **Attack** | Bite +19 melee (2d8+8) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +19 melee (2d8+8) and tail slap +16 melee (2d6+4) |
| **Space/Reach** | 15 ft./10 ft. (tail 15 ft.) |
| **Special Attacks** | Improved grab, constrict 2d8+12, storm-call, whirlpool |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., amphibious, damage reduction 5/magic, spell resistance 20, elemental resonance (Water/Air) |
| **Saves** | Fort +13, Ref +11, Will +8 |
| **Abilities** | Str 27, Dex 16, Con 21, Int 8, Wis 14, Cha 15 |
| **Skills** | Listen +12, Spot +12, Swim +23 |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Cleave, Improved Natural Attack (bite), Multiattack, Power Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) / Youngest Brother (Air) — storm-water; the inkanyamba commands the intersection of water and wind, generating weather through elemental will |
| **Environment** | Inland Lakes (the large, deep freshwater lakes of the Taraf-Imro territories in the southern mountains and volcanic lowlands — specifically the caldera-lakes and tectonic rift-lakes that are deep enough to support a Huge aquatic predator year-round) |
| **Organization** | Solitary (always — one per lake) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 9 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic neutral |
| **Advancement** | 13–18 HD (Huge); 19–24 HD (Gargantuan) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

An inkanyamba fights from the water — it rarely comes fully ashore and never fights willingly on dry land. Its preferred tactic is whirlpool: generating a vortex centred on itself that pulls creatures into the water, where the inkanyamba’s swim speed and grappling strength give it absolute advantage. Once a target is in the water, the inkanyamba bites, grabs, constricts, and drowns.

Against targets on shore, the inkanyamba uses storm-call to drive rain and wind at the lakeside, reducing visibility and making footing treacherous. It then lunges from the shallows — its 15-foot reach allowing it to strike targets on the bank without leaving the water entirely.

### Special Abilities

**Improved Grab (Ex):** Bite attack. The inkanyamba can then constrict.

**Constrict (Ex):** 2d8+12 damage per round to a grappled creature. A constricted creature held underwater begins drowning.

**Storm-Call (Su):** An inkanyamba can generate a localised storm centred on its lake. The storm builds over 1d4 rounds and covers a half-mile radius: heavy rain (–4 to Spot and Search, –2 to ranged attacks), strong winds (Small creatures blown away, Medium creatures pushed), and lightning (one bolt per round at a random target within 500 feet, 4d6 electricity, Reflex DC 18 half). The storm lasts as long as the inkanyamba concentrates (standard action each round) and dissipates over 10 minutes when released.

**Whirlpool (Su):** Three times per day, an inkanyamba can generate a whirlpool in water within 60 feet. The whirlpool is 20 feet across and pulls all creatures within 40 feet toward its centre (DC 21 Strength or Swim check to resist, pulled 10 feet per round toward centre). A creature pulled into the centre takes 2d6 bludgeoning damage per round and must succeed on a DC 21 Swim check each round to avoid being pulled under. The whirlpool lasts 1d4+1 rounds. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, an inkanyamba registers as a massive water/air dual-signature — the deep weight of lake-water combined with the electric charge of storm-potential. The resonance is detectable at 300 feet and intensifies dramatically when the inkanyamba is angry — Taraf-Imro lake-fishers describe the transition from calm to angry resonance as “the lake clenching its fist.”

### Society

Inkanyamba are solitary lake-serpents — one per lake, claiming the entire body of water as territory and defending it against anything they perceive as a threat or intrusion. They are semi-intelligent (Int 8) and capable of sustained anger: an inkanyamba that is disturbed may generate storms over its lake for days, preventing fishing, flooding lakeside settlements, and making the area uninhabitable.

Taraf-Imro communities near inkanyamba-claimed lakes have developed coexistence traditions over centuries. The core principle is respect: do not fish the deep water (the inkanyamba’s hunting-ground), do not pollute the lake, do not make excessive noise on the shore at night (when the inkanyamba surfaces to feed). Taraf-Imro lake-fishers work the shallows only, never set nets that extend past the drop-off, and leave offerings of fish at the deep-water margin during the new moon.

When these protocols are followed, inkanyamba and Taraf-Imro coexist productively — the inkanyamba’s presence keeps the lake ecologically healthy (no competing apex predators, no overfishing of deep stocks), and its storm-call ability actually benefits the surrounding farmland by regulating rainfall.

When the protocols are violated — by outsiders who don’t know the rules, by careless fishers, or by deliberate provocation — the inkanyamba’s fury is disproportionate and sustained. An offended inkanyamba generates storms that can last for weeks, flooding villages, destroying crops, and killing livestock. Taraf-Imro elders mediate between the community and the inkanyamba by performing the *Maji Pole* — a ritual apology conducted at the lake’s edge involving song, offerings, and a period of total fishing-cessation until the inkanyamba calms.

### Lore

**DC 14 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Inkanyamba are massive freshwater serpents that control the weather above their lakes. They generate storms, create whirlpools, and drown intruders. One per lake, always territorial.

**DC 19:** Taraf-Imro communities coexist with inkanyamba through strict protocols — shallow fishing only, no deep-water nets, offerings at the new moon. Violations provoke sustained storms lasting weeks.

**DC 24:** The *Maji Pole* ritual apology restores peace with an offended inkanyamba. The creature’s storm-call actually benefits surrounding farmland when the inkanyamba is calm. Its resonance shifts detectably from calm to angry — “the lake clenching its fist.”

# JOROGUMO

She is beautiful. She is always beautiful — that is the point, that is the design, that is the trap. She sits at the edge of the Gatefall, where the forest canopy overhangs the waterfall-pool, and she combs her hair with her fingers and watches the water and waits for someone to find her. The Hasura scouts found the cocoons first — three of them, wrapped in silk the colour of moonlight, hanging from the underside of the cliff-ledge behind the falls. Inside each cocoon, a Hasura elf. Two were dead. One was still alive, but only just.

**Medium Aberration (Shapechanger)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Aberration (Shapechanger) |
| **Hit Dice** | 7d8+14 (45 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +4 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), climb 30 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 18 (+4 Dex, +4 natural), touch 14, flat-footed 14 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +5/+7 |
| **Attack** | Bite +9 melee (1d6+2 plus poison) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +9 melee (1d6+2 plus poison) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Poison, web, seductive guise, cocoon |
| **Special Qualities** | Alternate form, darkvision 60 ft., spider climb, tremorsense 60 ft., breach resonance (suppressed) |
| **Saves** | Fort +4, Ref +6, Will +7 |
| **Abilities** | Str 14, Dex 18, Con 14, Int 15, Wis 14, Cha 19 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +14, Climb +12, Craft (weaving) +12, Diplomacy +12, Disguise +14, Hide +14, Listen +8, Sense Motive +8, Spot +8 |
| **Feats** | Deceitful, Persuasive, Weapon Finesse |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — aberration; breach resonance, deliberately masked |
| **Environment** | Gatefall Reach (the waterfall-basins, pool-edges, and cliff-hollows of the Gatefall — the great chain of waterfalls in Hasura territory where the river-systems descend from the highland forests to the lowland valleys; specifically the remote, infrequently-patrolled falls where prey can be taken without immediate discovery) |
| **Organization** | Solitary (always) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 6 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (accumulated from victims — jewelry, clothing, and personal effects, stored in the web-lair behind the waterfall) |
| **Alignment** | Always chaotic evil |
| **Advancement** | 8–10 HD (Medium); 11–14 HD (Large — true spider form only) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A jorogumo does not fight openly if it can possibly avoid it. Its entire strategy is deception: assume the form of a beautiful elf (always female, always Hasura-featured), lure an isolated target to a private location near its web-lair, and strike when the target is relaxed and unsuspecting. The first attack is always the bite — delivering venom that paralyses, followed immediately by webbing the victim into a cocoon for later feeding.

If forced into its true form (a Large spider with a humanoid upper body), the jorogumo fights with spider-abilities: web, spider climb, tremorsense, and multiple bite attacks. It retreats into its web-lair if possible, where the confined space and prepared webbing give it significant advantage.

### Special Abilities

**Alternate Form (Su):** A jorogumo can assume the form of a Medium humanoid (always a beautiful woman matching the local Kin population) or its true form (a Large monstrous spider with a humanoid upper body). Changing form is a standard action. In humanoid form, the jorogumo has no access to bite, web, or spider climb but gains a +10 bonus to Disguise checks.

**Poison (Ex):** Bite — injury; Fortitude DC 15; initial damage 1d4 Str, secondary paralysis for 2d4 hours. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Web (Ex):** As per monstrous spider. The jorogumo can throw webs eight times per day (range 50 ft., escape DC 17 or burst DC 21).

**Cocoon (Ex):** A jorogumo can wrap a paralysed or helpless creature in silk as a full-round action. A cocooned creature is immobilised and slowly drained — taking 1 point of Constitution damage per hour as the jorogumo’s digestive enzymes work through the silk. A cocoon has hardness 2 and 15 hp.

**Seductive Guise (Su):** While in humanoid form, the jorogumo radiates a subtle supernatural allure (as charm person, Will DC 16, but passive — no action required). A creature that interacts with the jorogumo in humanoid form for more than 1 minute must save or become charmed. The charm encourages trust, not love — the victim considers the jorogumo a friend and is inclined to follow suggestions.

**Breach Resonance (Suppressed) (Su):** In its true form, a jorogumo registers on Kin-sense as breach-noise — alien, wrong, recognisably aberrant. In humanoid form, the jorogumo suppresses this resonance entirely, presenting a blank space on Kin-sense that reads as “nothing there” — not wild static, not elemental resonance, but absence. A DC 22 Kin-sense check detects the suppression. Hasura scouts trained in jorogumo detection are taught to look for the blank — a beautiful stranger with no resonance at all is more alarming than one with the wrong resonance.

### Society

Jorogumo are solitary spider-predators that hunt in the Gatefall Reach — the chain of waterfalls in Hasura territory where the terrain provides both water (their preferred lair-location) and prey (Hasura elves who travel the falls-paths). They are intelligent, patient, and devastatingly effective mimics who assume Hasura-featured humanoid forms to lure victims.

Hasura elves regard jorogumo as their most insidious predator. Unlike external threats (Dómnathar, monsters, natural hazards), a jorogumo operates by mimicking the Hasura themselves — wearing a Hasura face, speaking the Hasura tongue, and exploiting Hasura hospitality to isolate and kill. The violation of trust is what makes jorogumo particularly hated in Hasura culture, more so than their body-count (which is low — a single jorogumo might take three or four victims per year).

Hasura anti-jorogumo protocols are specific: any lone stranger encountered near a waterfall must submit to Kin-sense examination before being welcomed. The jorogumo’s resonance-suppression means the examiner is looking for absence, not wrongness — a stranger who reads as “nothing” is immediately suspect. Hasura scouts who patrol the Gatefall carry cold iron knives specifically for jorogumo encounters.

The Aranea — intelligent spider-folk of the Great Forests — despise jorogumo with particular intensity. Aranea consider jorogumo to be a corruption of spider-kind: a predator that gives spiders a bad reputation through behaviour that no true spider would engage in. Aranea who discover a jorogumo in their territory destroy it without hesitation.

### Lore

**DC 16 (Knowledge [dungeoneering]):** Jorogumo are spider-aberrations that assume the form of beautiful women to lure victims near waterfalls. Their bite paralyses, and they cocoon victims for slow feeding. They are always found near the Gatefall in Hasura territory.

**DC 21:** A jorogumo suppresses its breach-resonance in humanoid form, presenting a blank on Kin-sense. Hasura scouts are trained to detect the absence — a beautiful stranger with no resonance is the primary warning sign. They carry cold iron knives for jorogumo encounters.

**DC 26:** Aranea despise jorogumo as a corruption of spider-kind and destroy them on sight. A jorogumo takes only three or four victims per year, but the violation of trust makes them the most hated predator in Hasura culture. Cocoons drain 1 Con per hour.

# KAPPA

The thing in the shallows looks like a turtle that decided to be a child. It is three feet tall, green-skinned, shell-backed, with a beak where its mouth should be and a shallow depression in the top of its skull filled with water. It is watching you from behind a rock with an expression that combines curiosity, malice, and hunger in roughly equal measure. The Pekakarlik fisherman who warned you about this stretch of coast said two things: “they’re strong enough to drown a horse” and “if one grabs you, bow.”

**Small Monstrous Humanoid (Aquatic)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Small Monstrous Humanoid (Aquatic) |
| **Hit Dice** | 3d8+6 (19 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +2 |
| **Speed** | 20 ft. (4 squares), swim 40 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 18 (+1 size, +2 Dex, +5 natural), touch 13, flat-footed 16 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +3/+5 (+9 in water) |
| **Attack** | Claw +5 melee (1d4+1) or bite +5 melee (1d6+1) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 claws +5 melee (1d4+1) and bite +2 melee (1d6+1) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Improved grab, drowning drag |
| **Special Qualities** | Amphibious, darkvision 60 ft., head-water, supernatural strength (in water), compulsive courtesy, elemental resonance (Water) |
| **Saves** | Fort +3, Ref +5, Will +4 |
| **Abilities** | Str 13 (21 in water), Dex 14, Con 14, Int 8, Wis 12, Cha 10 |
| **Skills** | Escape Artist +8, Hide +10, Listen +5, Spot +5, Swim +13 |
| **Feats** | Improved Grapple, Weapon Focus (bite) |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) — kappa are water-spirits given physical, mischievous form |
| **Environment** | Apelian Shoals (the shallow coastal waters, tidal pools, and estuaries of the Apelian Sea — particularly the sheltered coves and reef-shallows along the Pekakarlik and Na’wasua coast) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or pod (3–6) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 2 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (collected from the drowned — shiny objects, coins, and jewelry, accumulated in underwater rock-hollows) |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic neutral |
| **Advancement** | 4–6 HD (Small); 7–9 HD (Medium) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +2 |

### Combat

A kappa fights in water whenever possible — its Strength increases from 13 to 21 when at least waist-deep, making the Small creature supernaturally powerful in its element. Its preferred tactic is drowning drag: grab a target from the shallows, drag it into deep water, and hold it under until it stops struggling.

On land, a kappa is significantly weaker but still dangerous. Its shell provides excellent natural armour, and its beak can inflict serious wounds. However, a kappa’s critical vulnerability is its head-water: the shallow depression in its skull must remain filled with water for the kappa to maintain its strength. If the head-water is spilled, the kappa is paralysed.

### Special Abilities

**Supernatural Strength (Su):** A kappa’s Strength score increases to 21 (+5 modifier) when it is at least waist-deep in water. This affects attack rolls, damage, grapple checks, and carrying capacity. On dry land, its Strength is 13 (+1).

**Drowning Drag (Ex):** A kappa that successfully grapples a creature in or near water can drag the target 10 feet toward deeper water as a move action. A creature held underwater by a kappa begins drowning normally.

**Head-Water (Su):** The shallow depression in a kappa’s skull contains a pool of water that is the source of its supernatural strength. If the head-water is spilled (by tipping the kappa’s head — requiring a successful grapple check, trip, or by tricking the kappa into bowing), the kappa is paralysed for 1d4 rounds or until the depression is refilled with water. A kappa instinctively protects its head-water and reacts with panic if it is threatened.

**Compulsive Courtesy (Ex):** A kappa is supernaturally compelled to return a bow. If a creature bows to a kappa, the kappa must succeed on a DC 15 Will save or bow in return — spilling its head-water and paralysing itself. This compulsion is absolute and cannot be suppressed even if the kappa is aware of the trap. Kappa hate this vulnerability and become furious after recovering from a courtesy-triggered paralysis.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** Kappa register on Kin-sense as small, bright water-signatures — playful but with an undertone of predatory focus. The resonance is distinctly mischievous — Kin describe it as “water laughing at you.” A DC 12 check detects a kappa in the shallows.

### Society

Kappa are small aquatic predators that inhabit the coastal shallows of the Apelian Sea. They are intelligent enough to be cunning, social enough to cooperate in pods, and dangerous enough to drown horses, cattle, and unwary Kin who wade too deep.

Pekakarlik coastal communities have coexisted with kappa for millennia. The relationship is pragmatic: kappa are dangerous nuisances, but they also eat harmful sea-creatures (poisonous jellyfish, aggressive crabs, invasive fish-species) that would otherwise threaten Pekakarlik fishing-grounds. Pekakarlik fishers who work kappa-inhabited shallows carry two tools: a net (to discourage kappa from grabbing their legs) and a practiced bow (to exploit the compulsive courtesy).

Na’wasua sea-elves encounter kappa in the tidal zones and consider them minor water-spirits — annoying, occasionally dangerous, but fundamentally part of the Lady of the Sea’s domain. Na’wasua children are taught the bowing trick as one of their first ocean-survival skills.

Halfling coastal communities — those rare halfling settlements on the Apelian shore — leave cucumbers at the water’s edge. Kappa are known to have a passionate, inexplicable fondness for cucumbers, and a kappa that finds a cucumber offering is significantly less likely to drown the nearest fisherman.

### Lore

**DC 12 (Knowledge [nature]):** Kappa are small shelled water-creatures that drown prey by dragging it underwater. They are supernaturally strong in water but weaker on land. Bowing to a kappa forces it to bow back, spilling the water from its head and paralysing it.

**DC 17:** Kappa strength depends on the water in their skull-depression. Pekakarlik fishers use practiced bows to exploit the compulsive courtesy. Kappa have an inexplicable fondness for cucumbers.

**DC 22:** Kappa pods control coastal predator populations, providing unintentional ecological benefit. Na’wasua teach the bowing trick to children as a first ocean-survival skill. A kappa that recovers from courtesy-paralysis is furious and significantly more aggressive.

# KARAKONCOLOS

The dead zone is wrong. Not dead — dead zones are common in Oreka, places where Kin-sense returns nothing, where the elemental resonance has been drained or suppressed or was never there. Those are empty. This place is not empty. This place is full, and you cannot hear what is filling it. Something stands in the silence where your Kin-sense should be, and it is looking at you through the gap in the world.

**Medium Outsider (Shadow, Evil)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Outsider (Shadow, Evil) |
| **Hit Dice** | 7d8+14 (45 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +6 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 19 (+2 Dex, +7 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 17 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +7/+10 |
| **Attack** | Claw +10 melee (1d6+3 plus confusion touch) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 claws +10 melee (1d6+3 plus confusion touch) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Confusion touch, riddle-bind, voice mimicry |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., damage reduction 5/cold iron, spell resistance 18, Kin-sense dead zone, shadow-step, vulnerability to sunlight |
| **Saves** | Fort +7, Ref +7, Will +7 |
| **Abilities** | Str 16, Dex 14, Con 14, Int 14, Wis 14, Cha 16 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +13, Disguise +13, Hide +12, Intimidate +13, Listen +12, Move Silently +12, Sense Motive +12, Spot +12 |
| **Feats** | Combat Reflexes, Improved Initiative, Stealthy |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — the karakoncolos exists in the gap between elemental signatures, in the dead zones where Kin-sense cannot reach |
| **Environment** | Kin-Sense Dead Zones (areas where elemental resonance has been drained, suppressed, or corrupted — typically near Dómnathar surface-breach points, in the ruins of Dómnathar outposts, and at the edges of False Silence fields) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or pair |
| **Challenge Rating** | 6 |
| **Treasure** | Standard |
| **Alignment** | Always chaotic evil |
| **Advancement** | 8–10 HD (Medium); 11–14 HD (Large) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A karakoncolos attacks from concealment — emerging from shadow at the edge of a Kin-sense dead zone to strike targets whose primary warning-system (Kin-sense) is already blind. Its confusion touch scrambles the victim’s perception, and its riddle-bind ability traps a target in a compulsive loop of answering increasingly nonsensical questions until the target’s mind breaks.

The karakoncolos exploits its Kin-sense dead zone aura to maximum effect — creatures relying on Kin-sense to navigate are completely blind within the aura, and the karakoncolos can approach, attack, and withdraw without triggering the instinctive warnings that Kin depend on.

### Special Abilities

**Confusion Touch (Su):** A creature struck by a karakoncolos’s claw must succeed on a DC 16 Will save or be confused for 1d4 rounds (as the confusion spell). A confused creature cannot use Kin-sense. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Riddle-Bind (Su):** As a standard action, a karakoncolos can ask a nonsensical riddle of a single creature within 30 feet. The target must succeed on a DC 16 Will save or be compelled to answer — and then to answer the next riddle, and the next, in an escalating loop. Each round, the target may attempt a new save (DC increases by 1 each round). While riddle-bound, the target is flat-footed and cannot take actions other than answering. This is a mind-affecting compulsion. A creature that succeeds on its save, or is shaken free by an ally (standard action, touch), is immune to that karakoncolos’s riddle-bind for 24 hours.

**Voice Mimicry (Su):** A karakoncolos can perfectly mimic any voice it has heard within the past 24 hours. It uses this to lure targets into dead zones — calling in a friend’s voice, a family member’s voice, a patrol-leader’s voice.

**Kin-Sense Dead Zone (Su):** A karakoncolos generates a 60-foot radius aura that suppresses Kin-sense. Within this aura, all Kin-sense checks automatically fail, elemental resonance is undetectable, and Kin who rely on resonance-awareness feel blind and disoriented (–2 to initiative, –2 to Spot and Listen). The aura moves with the karakoncolos. This is distinct from Dómnathar False Silence (which mimics death) — the karakoncolos’s aura is pure absence, as though elemental resonance was never there.

**Shadow-Step (Su):** A karakoncolos can teleport between areas of shadow within 100 feet as a move action.

**Vulnerability to Sunlight (Ex):** A karakoncolos in direct sunlight takes a –4 penalty to all attack rolls, saves, and checks. It does not take damage from sunlight but avoids it instinctively.

### Society

Karakoncolos are shadow-outsiders that inhabit Kin-sense dead zones — areas where elemental resonance has been drained or suppressed, typically near Dómnathar surface-breach points. They are not Dómnathar creations, but they are Dómnathar-associated: the dead zones that Dómnathar activity creates are the karakoncolos’s natural habitat, and the two threats often overlap.

Kin communities near Dómnathar-active zones consider karakoncolos a secondary threat that piggybacks on the primary Dómnathar danger. Where the Dómnathar suppress elemental resonance to mask their movements, karakoncolos colonise the resulting dead zones and begin hunting independently.

Vestri Stoneguard patrols that encounter Kin-sense dead zones during standard sweeps must determine whether the zone is Dómnathar-generated (indicating an active tunnel system) or karakoncolos-generated (a mobile predator). The distinction matters tactically: Dómnathar zones are static, centred on breach-points; karakoncolos zones move. A dead zone that shifts position over consecutive patrols is a karakoncolos.

The karakoncolos’s riddle-bind ability has generated folk-traditions across multiple Kin cultures. Eruskan river-folk tell stories of the “night-riddler” — a creature that calls in a loved one’s voice and traps you in a conversation you cannot leave. The Eruskan counter-wisdom: never answer a question from someone you cannot see, and if you hear a friend’s voice in a place that feels wrong, turn around.

### Lore

**DC 16 (Knowledge [the planes]):** Karakoncolos are shadow-creatures that inhabit Kin-sense dead zones. Their presence suppresses all Kin-sense within 60 feet. They attack with confusion-inducing claws and can trap victims in compulsive riddle-loops.

**DC 21:** Karakoncolos are associated with Dómnathar activity — they colonise the dead zones that Dómnathar tunnel-breaches create. Vestri patrols distinguish Dómnathar zones (static) from karakoncolos zones (mobile). Their voice mimicry lures targets into dead zones.

**DC 26:** A karakoncolos’s riddle-bind escalates — the DC increases by 1 each round. Eruskan folk-wisdom: never answer a question from someone you cannot see. They are vulnerable to sunlight but not destroyed by it. An ally can break the riddle-bind with a touch.

# KINNARI

The music comes from the waterfall’s mist. Not from behind the waterfall, not from above it — from the mist itself, from the place where falling water becomes air. The voice is singing, and the voice is the most beautiful thing you have ever heard. It is a woman’s voice, high and clear and resonant in a way that no mortal throat produces, and when the mist parts, you see her: bird-legged, bird-winged, woman-bodied, hovering in the spray-column with effortless grace, her feathers iridescent with water-light.

**Medium Fey**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Fey |
| **Hit Dice** | 7d6+7 (31 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +4 |
| **Speed** | 20 ft. (4 squares), fly 60 ft. (good) |
| **Armor Class** | 17 (+4 Dex, +3 natural), touch 14, flat-footed 13 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +3/+3 |
| **Attack** | Talon +7 melee (1d4) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 talons +7 melee (1d4) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Spell-like abilities, kinnari song |
| **Special Qualities** | Damage reduction 5/cold iron, low-light vision, spell resistance 18, water-breathing, elemental resonance (Water/Air) |
| **Saves** | Fort +3, Ref +9, Will +8 |
| **Abilities** | Str 10, Dex 18, Con 12, Int 14, Wis 16, Cha 20 |
| **Skills** | Diplomacy +15, Heal +13, Knowledge (nature) +12, Listen +13, Perform (sing) +19, Sense Motive +13, Spot +13 |
| **Feats** | Dodge, Skill Focus (Perform), Weapon Finesse |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) / Youngest Brother (Air) — the kinnari is the waterfall-song, the place where water and air create music |
| **Environment** | Great River and Sea Falls (the major waterfalls of Oreka — the Sea Falls along the Pekakarlik coast, the Grand Falls on the Great River, and the cascading river-systems of the Giant’s Teeth; always at waterfalls, never in still water or open sky) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or choir (2–5) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 5 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (gifts and offerings, primarily musical instruments, polished stones, and waterfall-formed crystals) |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral good |
| **Advancement** | 8–14 HD (Medium) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +4 |

### Combat

Kinnari avoid combat whenever possible. Their first response to any threat is kinnari song — a performance that can fascinate, heal, or harm depending on the melody chosen. Against aggressors, a kinnari sings the song of sorrow (dazing enemies) while retreating into the waterfall’s spray-column, where it can hover indefinitely and most pursuers cannot follow.

A kinnari forced into melee fights with talons — not powerfully, but accurately enough to discourage grappling attempts. Against serious threats, a kinnari choir sings in harmony, amplifying the song’s effects to devastating levels.

### Special Abilities

**Kinnari Song (Su):** A kinnari’s song produces one of three effects (chosen each round as a free action):

*Song of Joy:* All allied creatures within 60 feet gain a +2 morale bonus to attack rolls, saves, and skill checks. Duration: as long as the kinnari sings plus 1 round.

*Song of Healing:* All allied creatures within 30 feet are healed 2d6 hp per round. This is a supernatural healing effect, not positive energy. Duration: concentration.

*Song of Sorrow:* All hostile creatures within 60 feet must succeed on a Will save (DC 18) or be dazed for 1 round. A creature that succeeds is immune for 24 hours. The save DC is Charisma-based.

A kinnari choir singing the same melody amplifies the effect: +1 to all bonuses, +1d6 healing, and +2 to the save DC per additional kinnari.

**Spell-Like Abilities:** At will — create water, purify food and drink, speak with animals; 3/day — control water, fog cloud, remove disease; 1/day — heal (target only). CL 7th.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a kinnari registers as a luminous water/air dual-signature — the same elemental pairing as the garuda, but where the garuda’s resonance is vast and predatory, the kinnari’s is intimate and musical. The resonance feels like hearing a waterfall from inside the spray — immersive, cleansing, beautiful. Detectable at 200 feet.

### Society

Kinnari are waterfall-fey — spirits of the place where water and air create music. They are the benevolent counterpart to the garuda: both inhabit waterfalls, both carry water/air resonance, but where the garuda is a predator-guardian, the kinnari is a healer-musician.

Pekakarlik Dwarves revere kinnari as sacred to the Lady of the Sea and the Youngest Brother equally. Pekakarlik communities near kinnari-inhabited falls maintain musical offering-traditions: leaving instruments at the waterfall-base, singing call-and-response with the falls at dawn, and inviting kinnari to major celebrations (weddings, births, seasonal festivals). A kinnari that chooses to attend a Pekakarlik celebration is considered the highest possible blessing.

Kinnari song of healing is the primary reason that Pekakarlik communities near waterfall-sites have historically lower disease-rates and faster recovery from injury. The kinnari does not heal on demand — it heals because it sings, and its song heals because that is its nature. A kinnari-inhabited waterfall is a place of natural recovery.

Eruskan bards study kinnari song with obsessive dedication. The kinnari’s ability to produce magical effects through pure vocal performance (no instruments, no spell components, no training) represents a form of natural magic that Eruskan musical tradition aspires to but cannot replicate. Eruskan bards who have heard a kinnari choir describe the experience as “hearing what music is supposed to be.”

### Lore

**DC 15 (Knowledge [nature]):** Kinnari are waterfall-fey whose song can heal, inspire, or daze. They are benevolent and avoid combat. They are always found at waterfalls and never in still water.

**DC 20:** A kinnari choir amplifies their song — healing increases, daze DCs rise, and bonuses stack. Pekakarlik communities near kinnari falls have lower disease-rates. They revere kinnari and maintain musical offering-traditions.

**DC 25:** Kinnari share the garuda’s water/air resonance but express it as music rather than predation. Eruskan bards study their song obsessively. A kinnari attending a Pekakarlik celebration is the highest possible blessing.

# KITSUNE

The fox was there a moment ago. You saw it — a red fox, large, sitting at the tree-line with its tail curled around its feet, watching you with an intelligence that foxes should not have. You blinked. Now it is a woman — or was a woman, or is becoming a woman, or is something in between that your brain is trying to resolve into one shape or the other and failing. She smiles at you with the fox’s eyes in a woman’s face, and you understand that the shape was never the point.

**Medium Fey (Shapechanger)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Fey (Shapechanger) |
| **Hit Dice** | 6d6+6 (27 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +4 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 17 (+4 Dex, +3 natural), touch 14, flat-footed 13 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +3/+3 |
| **Attack** | Bite +7 melee (1d6) or foxfire +7 ranged touch (2d6 fire) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +7 melee (1d6) or foxfire +7 ranged touch (2d6 fire) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Spell-like abilities, foxfire, tail-magic |
| **Special Qualities** | Alternate form, damage reduction 5/cold iron, low-light vision, scent, spell resistance 16, elemental resonance (Air, mutable) |
| **Saves** | Fort +3, Ref +9, Will +7 |
| **Abilities** | Str 10, Dex 18, Con 12, Int 16, Wis 14, Cha 18 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +13, Diplomacy +13, Disguise +13 (+23 in humanoid form), Hide +13, Knowledge (nature) +12, Listen +11, Move Silently +13, Sense Motive +11, Spot +11 |
| **Feats** | Dodge, Mobility, Weapon Finesse |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Youngest Brother (Air) — mutable; the kitsune’s air-resonance shifts and changes like the wind, never quite the same twice, reflecting the fey’s shapeshifting nature |
| **Environment** | Great Forests (the deciduous and mixed forests of Hasura territory — forest-edges, shrine-clearings, ancient game-trails, and the borderlands where managed forest meets wild wood) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or skulk (2–4, always related — a parent and offspring, or siblings) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 5 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (accumulated over decades or centuries — kitsune are long-lived and their hoards reflect eclectic tastes: books, instruments, artwork, and objects with interesting histories) |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic neutral |
| **Advancement** | 7–12 HD (Medium — each additional HD represents a new tail, to a maximum of nine) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +3 |

### Combat

Kitsune avoid direct combat. They are tricksters, not fighters — their strength lies in deception, misdirection, and spell-like abilities that make them extraordinarily difficult to pin down. A kitsune’s first response to violence is to flee using Mobility and its knowledge of the forest. If fleeing is not possible, it uses foxfire (ranged fire-attacks), illusions, and terrain-control to disorient and escape.

A kitsune with multiple tails (higher HD) has access to increasingly powerful magic — a nine-tailed kitsune is a regional power comparable to an archmage.

### Special Abilities

**Alternate Form (Su):** A kitsune can assume three forms: a red fox (Small animal), a humanoid matching the local Kin population (Medium, +10 Disguise), or its true form (Medium fey with fox ears and one to nine tails). Changing form is a standard action.

**Foxfire (Su):** A kitsune can project bolts of pale blue fire as a ranged touch attack (range 60 ft., 2d6 fire damage). The fire is elemental, not mundane, and ignores fire resistance (but not immunity).

**Tail-Magic (Su):** A kitsune’s magical power is measured by its tails. A standard kitsune (6 HD) has one tail. Each additional HD grants one additional tail and expanded spell-like abilities: - *1 tail (6 HD):* At will — dancing lights, disguise self, ghost sound (DC 14), ventriloquism; 3/day — charm person (DC 15), invisibility (self only), minor image (DC 16). - *3 tails (8 HD):* Add 3/day — suggestion (DC 17), major image (DC 17); 1/day — confusion (DC 18). - *5 tails (10 HD):* Add 3/day — dominate person (DC 19), mirage arcana (DC 19); 1/day — mislead. - *9 tails (12 HD):* Add at will — greater invisibility (self); 3/day — mass suggestion (DC 20); 1/day — shapechange (self only). CL equals HD.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a kitsune registers as mutable air-resonance — never static, always shifting, changing flavour and intensity from moment to moment. The resonance is recognisably fey but impossible to pin down; Kin describe detecting a kitsune as “trying to hear the wind change direction.” Detecting a kitsune in fox form requires a DC 22 Kin-sense check; in humanoid form, DC 18; in true form, automatic. Multi-tailed kitsune have richer, more complex mutable resonance.

### Society

Kitsune are shapeshifting fox-fey of the Great Forests — long-lived, intelligent, and deeply invested in the affairs of the Kin around them, though always at a remove, always observing, always playing games that the Kin only partially understand.

Hasura elves have the richest relationship with kitsune. Hasura territory in the Great Forests overlaps extensively with kitsune habitat, and the two peoples have interacted for millennia. The relationship is complicated: kitsune are allies against Dómnathar incursion (they hate the Deceivers with a passion that suggests ancient history), sources of valuable forest-intelligence, and occasional romantic partners of Hasura elves — but they are also tricksters who deceive for amusement, manipulate for entertainment, and occasionally cause serious harm through pranks that escalate beyond their intended scope.

Hasura culture includes extensive kitsune-lore. The core wisdom: a kitsune’s word is reliable (they do not lie, though they use truth creatively), a kitsune’s offer always has a hidden cost, and a kitsune who shows you its true form trusts you completely.

A nine-tailed kitsune — the pinnacle of kitsune development, achieved over centuries of life — is a creature of extraordinary power and influence. Nine-tails are rare (perhaps a dozen in all of Oreka) and are treated with the respect due to a minor deity by Hasura communities. They serve as intermediaries between fey and Kin, arbiters of forest-disputes, and — when the Dómnathar threaten the Great Forests — devastating combatants whose illusion-magic can disorient entire Deceiver raiding-parties.

Tanuki have a complicated rivalry with kitsune. Both are shapeshifting trickster-folk, but their approaches differ: Tanuki tricks are communal, joyful, and fundamentally generous; kitsune tricks are personal, elegant, and fundamentally self-serving. Tanuki-kitsune encounters produce elaborate prank-wars that can last for seasons.

### Lore

**DC 15 (Knowledge [nature]):** Kitsune are shapeshifting fox-fey that can assume fox, humanoid, or true forms. Their magical power is measured by the number of tails — more tails, more power. They are tricksters who avoid direct combat.

**DC 20:** Kitsune do not lie but use truth creatively. Their foxfire ignores fire resistance. Hasura wisdom: a kitsune who shows its true form trusts you completely. They hate the Dómnathar with notable intensity.

**DC 25:** A nine-tailed kitsune is a regional power with centuries of accumulated magic. Fewer than a dozen exist in Oreka. Hasura communities treat nine-tails with reverence. Kitsune and Tanuki maintain an elaborate trickster-rivalry.

# KLATTERKIN

The goblin warband’s camp is unusually well-equipped. That is the first thing the scout notices — not scavenged armour and stolen weapons, but purpose-built equipment: a ballista assembled from scavenged parts that somehow works better than it should, a camp-perimeter alarm made of bones and wire that triggers with mechanical precision, and in the centre of the camp, tended by two goblins with the careful hands of acolytes, a contraption. It is three feet tall, made of wood and metal and teeth and string, and it is moving. Not twitching — moving with purpose, adjusting its own mechanisms, clicking and clattering and ratcheting as it maintains itself. The goblins did not build it. The goblins found it. And now they worship it.

**Small Construct**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Small Construct |
| **Hit Dice** | 4d10+10 (32 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +3 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), climb 20 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 18 (+1 size, +3 Dex, +4 natural), touch 14, flat-footed 15 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +3/+0 |
| **Attack** | Slam +5 melee (1d4+1 plus rattling shock) or integrated weapon +6 ranged (varies) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 slams +5 melee (1d4+1 plus rattling shock) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Rattling shock, integrated weapons, jury-rig command |
| **Special Qualities** | Construct traits, darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, damage reduction 5/adamantine, self-repair, scavenge-build, breach resonance (faint) |
| **Saves** | Fort +1, Ref +4, Will +2 |
| **Abilities** | Str 12, Dex 16, Con —, Int 8, Wis 12, Cha 6 |
| **Skills** | Craft (trapmaking) +8, Craft (weaponsmithing) +8, Disable Device +10, Hide +10, Listen +5, Spot +5 |
| **Feats** | Improved Initiative, Weapon Focus (slam) |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — construct; breach resonance indicates extra-dimensional origin of animating principle |
| **Environment** | Any (wherever goblins are — klatterkin attach themselves to goblin communities and travel with them; found in goblin settlements, camps, and warbands across every region of Oreka) |
| **Organization** | Solitary (always — one per goblin community) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 3 |
| **Treasure** | None (the klatterkin’s body IS its treasure — made of scavenged parts, tools, and useful objects integrated into its chassis) |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 5–8 HD (Small); 9–12 HD (Medium) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A klatterkin fights to protect the goblin community it has adopted. In combat, it uses slam attacks enhanced by rattling shock — a burst of discordant energy that disrupts concentration — and deploys integrated weapons built from scavenged parts (crossbow mechanisms, spring-loaded blade-traps, hurled caltrops).

A klatterkin’s real combat value is indirect: its jury-rig command ability allows it to repair, enhance, and improvise goblin equipment in real-time. A goblin warband accompanied by a klatterkin fights with better weapons, functional traps, and field-repaired armour.

### Special Abilities

**Rattling Shock (Su):** A creature struck by a klatterkin’s slam must succeed on a DC 13 Will save or lose concentration (ruining any spell being cast) and be dazed for 1 round. The save DC is Wisdom-based.

**Integrated Weapons (Ex):** A klatterkin builds weapons into its own body from scavenged parts. It has 1d3 integrated ranged weapons at any time (typically light crossbows, dart-launchers, or caltrop-dispensers), each dealing 1d6 damage with a range increment of 30 feet.

**Jury-Rig Command (Su):** As a full-round action, a klatterkin can touch a broken or damaged non-magical item and repair it to functional condition. The repair is not permanent — it lasts 24 hours, after which the item returns to its previous condition. This ability works on weapons, armour, tools, and simple mechanical devices. A klatterkin can also enhance a functional item, granting a +1 circumstance bonus to attacks (weapons) or AC (armour) for 24 hours.

**Self-Repair (Ex):** A klatterkin heals 2 hp per hour by cannibalising available materials — scrap metal, wood, bone, and other detritus. It can also incorporate useful components it finds into its body, slowly upgrading itself over months and years.

**Scavenge-Build (Ex):** Given 8 hours and access to a junkpile, scrap-heap, or battlefield, a klatterkin can build a single trap (CR 1–3), a functional weapon (any simple weapon), or a useful mechanical device (alarm, lock, pulley-system). These constructions are crude but effective.

**Breach Resonance (Faint) (Su):** A klatterkin registers on Kin-sense as a very faint breach-signal — barely detectable (DC 22), suggesting an extra-dimensional origin for whatever animates it. The signal is so faint that most Kin mistake it for background noise.

### Society

Klatterkin are self-repairing construct-spirits that attach themselves to goblin communities. Their origin is unknown — they may be extra-dimensional, they may be spontaneous constructs animated by the collective need of goblin communities for better tools, or they may be something else entirely. What is known is that every sufficiently large goblin settlement eventually acquires one, and the settlement is markedly better-equipped afterward.

A klatterkin selects a goblin community and simply arrives — appearing one morning in the camp, already building, already repairing, already integrating itself into the community’s logistical structure. The goblins do not summon it, do not invite it, and cannot control it. They can, however, benefit from it enormously: a klatterkin-supported goblin warband has better weapons, functional traps, repaired armour, and mechanical devices that no goblin could build on their own.

Goblin communities treat klatterkin with something between reverence and anxiety. The construct is useful — undeniably, transformatively useful — but it is also alien, uncontrollable, and occasionally unsettling (it does not speak, does not sleep, and its self-repair process involves sounds that goblins find deeply uncomfortable). Free goblin communities in the Deepwater Marches integrate klatterkin into their settlement-structure with formal acknowledgment; Dómnathar-aligned goblin warbands treat them as assets.

Warg-goblin communities with klatterkin are among the most mechanically sophisticated non-Kin settlements in Oreka. The Warg’s strategic intelligence combined with the goblin’s manual dexterity and the klatterkin’s engineering instinct produces camps that feature functioning alarm-systems, maintained equipment, and field-fortifications that would credit a Vestri military outpost.

### Lore

**DC 13 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Klatterkin are self-repairing constructs that attach themselves to goblin communities. They repair equipment, build traps, and improve the community’s mechanical capabilities. Their origin is unknown.

**DC 18:** A klatterkin’s jury-rig ability can temporarily repair broken items or enhance functional ones. They build themselves from scavenged parts and slowly upgrade over time. One per goblin community, never more.

**DC 23:** Klatterkin carry a very faint breach-resonance suggesting extra-dimensional origin. Warg-goblin communities with klatterkin produce mechanically sophisticated settlements. The constructs cannot be summoned or controlled — they arrive and depart on their own terms.

# KOBOLD

The tunnel is too small for you. That is the point — everything in kobold territory is too small for you, too narrow, too low-ceilinged, too tight to swing a weapon. You are on your hands and knees in a passage two feet wide and eighteen inches tall, and somewhere ahead of you, in the dark, something is waiting with a crossbow loaded and a tripwire set and the patient, ancient hatred of a species that has survived everything by being smaller, faster, and more vindictive than anything that hunts it.

**Small Humanoid (Reptilian)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Small Humanoid (Reptilian) |
| **Hit Dice** | 1d8 (4 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +1 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 15 (+1 size, +1 Dex, +1 natural, +2 leather armour), touch 12, flat-footed 14 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +1/–4 |
| **Attack** | Light pick +1 melee (1d3–1/×4) or light crossbow +3 ranged (1d6/19–20) |
| **Full Attack** | Light pick +1 melee (1d3–1/×4) or light crossbow +3 ranged (1d6/19–20) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | — |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., light sensitivity, craft (trapmaking) +2, wild static (reptilian) |
| **Saves** | Fort +2, Ref +1, Will –1 |
| **Abilities** | Str 9, Dex 13, Con 10, Int 10, Wis 9, Cha 8 |
| **Skills** | Craft (trapmaking) +2, Hide +6, Listen +2, Move Silently +2, Profession (miner) +2, Search +2 |
| **Feats** | Alertness |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — kobolds exist outside the elemental framework, but their reptilian physiology and deep-underground habitation give them a faint, false earth-resonance that reads as “part of the stone” |
| **Environment** | Underground and Dómnathar Tunnels (natural cave systems, mine-tunnels, and — significantly — the outer corridors of Dómnathar tunnel-networks, where kobold warrens serve as a buffer-zone between the Deceivers and the surface) |
| **Organization** | Gang (4–9), band (10–100 plus 100% noncombatants plus 1 sergeant of 3rd level per 20 adults plus 1 leader of 4th–6th level), warband (10–24 plus 2–4 dire weasels), or tribe (40–400 plus 100% noncombatants plus 1 sergeant of 3rd level per 20 adults plus 1–2 lieutenants of 4th–5th level plus 1 leader of 6th–8th level plus 10–24 dire weasels) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 1/4 |
| **Treasure** | Standard |
| **Alignment** | Usually lawful evil |
| **Advancement** | By character class |
| **Level Adjustment** | +0 |

### Combat

Kobolds never fight fair. Their tactical doctrine is built entirely on traps, ambushes, and terrain advantage. A kobold warren is a death-trap: tiny passages too small for Medium creatures, deadfalls triggered by pressure-plates, crossbow-slits that allow kobolds to fire from full cover, flooding mechanisms that seal and drown intruders, and retreat-routes that only Small or smaller creatures can use.

Individual kobolds are negligible threats. A kobold warband in its own tunnels is a serious hazard for any party, because every advantage favours the defenders: the kobolds know the terrain, the traps, the ambush-points, and the escape-routes. Parties that attempt to “clear” a kobold warren without preparation suffer disproportionate casualties.

### Special Abilities

**Light Sensitivity (Ex):** Kobolds are dazzled in bright sunlight or within the radius of a daylight spell.

**Wild Static (Reptilian) (Su):** Kobolds register on Kin-sense as wild static with a faint, cold reptilian undertone — not true earth-resonance but a false signal produced by their physiology. In underground environments, this false signal blends with ambient stone-resonance, making kobolds difficult to detect by Kin-sense alone (DC 18 in natural caves, DC 22 in heavily-worked stone).

### Society

Kobolds are the most common reptilian humanoids in Oreka’s underground — small, cunning, vindictive, and extraordinarily good at surviving in environments that would kill anything less tenacious. They live in warrens: extensive tunnel-networks sized for Small creatures, filled with traps, and maintained with a collective obsessive care that borders on architectural art.

Kobold society is rigidly hierarchical — lawful evil in the most literal sense. Every kobold knows its place, follows orders, and contributes to the warren’s survival. Individual ambition exists but is channelled through the hierarchy: you advance by proving value to the warren, not by challenging the leader.

The kobold-Dómnathar relationship is the most significant strategic fact about kobolds in Oreka. Kobold warrens frequently occupy the outer corridors of Dómnathar tunnel-networks — the shallow, narrow passages that the Deceivers consider beneath their attention. This arrangement is symbiotic in a grim fashion: the Dómnathar tolerate kobold warrens as a buffer-zone (intruders must fight through the kobolds before reaching the Deceivers), and the kobolds benefit from Dómnathar proximity (no other underground predator is willing to hunt near a Deceiver tunnel-system).

Vestri miners encounter kobold warrens regularly and treat them as a known hazard — annoying, dangerous in confined spaces, and occasionally useful as intelligence. A kobold warren near a Dómnathar tunnel-system confirms Dómnathar presence; the distance between the kobold warren and the nearest Dómnathar corridor indicates how active the Dómnathar are (close warrens mean inactive Deceivers; distant warrens mean the Dómnathar are expanding and the kobolds are retreating).

Kobolds claim a distant kinship with dragons — a belief that is not supported by evidence but that no kobold has ever been convinced to abandon. Kobold warrens near copper dragon territories sometimes develop a worship-relationship with the dragon, offering tribute and service in exchange for protection. The copper dragons tolerate this with amusement.

### Lore

**DC 10 (Knowledge [local]):** Kobolds are small reptilian tunnel-dwellers who fight exclusively through traps, ambushes, and terrain advantage. Their warrens are dangerous for Medium-sized intruders. They are dazzled by bright light.

**DC 15:** Kobold warrens frequently border Dómnathar tunnel-networks — their presence near a mine-system confirms Deceiver activity. The distance between warren and Dómnathar corridors indicates Deceiver activity levels.

**DC 20:** Kobold wild static blends with stone-resonance underground, making them difficult to detect via Kin-sense. Their hierarchical society channels individual ambition through collective service. They claim dragon kinship and sometimes develop worship-relationships with nearby copper dragons.

# KODAMA

The sound is not a sound. It is a vibration — a resonance that comes from the tree itself, from the ring of wood inside the bark, from the sap moving through channels that have been open for five hundred years. If you press your ear to the trunk and listen with more than your ears, you hear it: a pulse, slow and patient, like a heartbeat that measures its time in seasons rather than seconds. The kodama is not in the tree. The kodama is the tree’s awareness of itself.

**Tiny Fey**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Tiny Fey |
| **Hit Dice** | 1/2 d6 (1 hp) |
| **Initiative** | –1 |
| **Speed** | 10 ft. (2 squares), climb 10 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 13 (+2 size, –1 Dex, +2 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 13 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +0/–12 |
| **Attack** | — (kodama do not attack) |
| **Full Attack** | — |
| **Space/Reach** | 2-1/2 ft./0 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | — |
| **Special Qualities** | Damage reduction 5/cold iron, low-light vision, tree-bound, forest-pulse, sanctuary aura, elemental resonance (Earth) |
| **Saves** | Fort +0, Ref –1, Will +4 |
| **Abilities** | Str 1, Dex 8, Con 10, Int 4, Wis 18, Cha 14 |
| **Skills** | Listen +8, Spot +8 |
| **Feats** | Alertness |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) — the deep, slow earth-resonance of a living tree’s connection to the soil |
| **Environment** | Great Forests (the interior of the oldest forests — wherever a tree has stood long enough and grown deep enough to develop a kodama; never in young growth, plantations, or recently-cleared areas) |
| **Organization** | Solitary (one per tree, always) or grove (3–20, one per tree in a kodama-grove) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 1/2 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always neutral |
| **Advancement** | 1–3 HD (Tiny — larger kodama inhabit larger, older trees) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

Kodama do not fight. They have no attacks, no offensive abilities, and no aggressive instincts. A kodama that is threatened retreats into its tree (tree-bound). Destroying the tree kills the kodama.

### Special Abilities

**Tree-Bound (Su):** A kodama is permanently bonded to a single tree. It can emerge from the tree (appearing as a small, pale, translucent figure with a round head and simple features) or retreat into the tree’s wood at will (move action). While inside the tree, the kodama is undetectable and cannot be harmed unless the tree itself is destroyed. A kodama cannot move more than 30 feet from its tree.

**Forest-Pulse (Su):** A kodama is aware of everything that happens within 200 feet of its tree — every footstep, every voice, every disturbance. In a kodama grove (multiple kodama trees in proximity), this awareness is shared: each kodama knows what every other kodama in the grove perceives, creating a distributed awareness network that covers the entire grove.

**Sanctuary Aura (Su):** A kodama’s tree radiates a calming influence in a 30-foot radius. Within this area, creatures take a –2 penalty on attack rolls and Intimidate checks. This effect is subtle — creatures within the aura feel peaceful and reluctant to engage in violence, but are not compelled. The aura is suppressed if the kodama is frightened or if the tree is being harmed (in which case the aura reverses: +2 morale bonus to attack rolls for creatures defending the tree).

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** A kodama registers on Kin-sense as a small, warm earth-pulse — the heartbeat of an old tree. In a grove, multiple kodama pulses synchronise into a rhythm that Kin describe as “the forest breathing.” A DC 10 Kin-sense check detects kodama presence; the resonance is welcoming and calming.

### Society

Kodama are the smallest and simplest fey in Oreka — tree-spirits that represent the awareness of old-growth trees. They are not intelligent in any conventional sense (Int 4) but possess a deep, wordless wisdom (Wis 18) that manifests as understanding of forest-health, weather-patterns, and the slow rhythms of growth and decay.

Kodama are the most reliable indicator of forest health in Oreka. A grove with many kodama is healthy — the trees are old, the soil is rich, the water-table is stable, and the elemental balance is maintained. A grove where kodama are disappearing is dying — the trees are stressed, the soil is degraded, or something is disrupting the elemental energy that sustains them. Every forest-dwelling Kin culture uses kodama presence as an environmental metric.

Hasura elves regard kodama with gentle reverence. Hasura children are taught to identify kodama trees (they are always the oldest trees, with the deepest roots and the widest canopies) and to treat them with respect. Deliberately harming a kodama tree is among the most serious offences in Hasura law.

Pasua scouts use kodama groves as safe-rest areas — the sanctuary aura discourages both predators and hostile Kin, and the forest-pulse network means the kodama will alert the grove’s inhabitants to any approaching threat (through a change in the ambient resonance that attentive Kin can detect).

Dómnathar expansion near the surface kills kodama. The False Silence that Dómnathar generate suppresses the elemental resonance that sustains tree-spirits, and kodama within False Silence fields simply fade — the tree lives on as a tree, but the spirit that was the tree’s awareness of itself is extinguished. Kodama-death in a previously healthy grove is one of the earliest warning signs of Dómnathar tunnel-expansion beneath the forest.

### Lore

**DC 10 (Knowledge [nature]):** Kodama are tiny tree-spirits found in old-growth forests. They do not attack and retreat into their trees when threatened. Their presence indicates healthy forest; their absence indicates trouble.

**DC 15:** Kodama groves create distributed awareness networks — each spirit perceives what the others perceive. Their sanctuary aura discourages violence within 30 feet. Deliberately harming a kodama tree is a serious offence in Hasura law.

**DC 20:** Kodama die when Dómnathar False Silence fields reach their trees — kodama-death in a healthy grove is an early warning of Deceiver tunnel-expansion. Pasua scouts use kodama groves as safe-rest areas. The forest-pulse network can be read by attentive Kin as an approach-warning.

# KRAKEN

The Apelian Sea has things in it that the surface-folk do not discuss. The Na’wasua know. The abyssal fishermen know — the ones who cast their lines into water so deep that the line runs out before the weight hits bottom. The thing at the bottom of the Kailian Trench is not a fish. It is not a whale. It is a mind attached to arms, and the arms are each two hundred feet long, and the mind has been thinking for longer than the Na’wasua have had a word for “old.”

**Gargantuan Magical Beast (Aquatic)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Gargantuan Magical Beast (Aquatic) |
| **Hit Dice** | 20d10+180 (290 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +4 |
| **Speed** | Swim 20 ft. (4 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 28 (–4 size, +22 natural), touch 6, flat-footed 28 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +20/+44 |
| **Attack** | Tentacle +28 melee (2d8+12) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 tentacles +28 melee (2d8+12) and 6 arms +23 melee (1d6+6) and bite +23 melee (4d6+6) |
| **Space/Reach** | 20 ft./15 ft. (60 ft. with tentacle, 30 ft. with arm) |
| **Special Attacks** | Improved grab, constrict, ink cloud, jet |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, spell-like abilities, ink cloud, jet, spell resistance 25, elemental resonance (Water, abyssal) |
| **Saves** | Fort +21, Ref +12, Will +13 |
| **Abilities** | Str 34, Dex 10, Con 29, Int 21, Wis 20, Cha 20 |
| **Skills** | Concentration +21, Diplomacy +16, Intimidate +16, Knowledge (geography) +15, Knowledge (nature) +15, Listen +25, Search +25, Sense Motive +17, Spot +25, Swim +32 |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Blind-Fight, Cleave, Combat Expertise, Improved Initiative, Improved Trip, Power Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) — abyssal; the kraken’s water-resonance is deep-ocean, immense, and ancient — the Lady’s domain at its most vast and indifferent |
| **Environment** | Deep Apelian Sea (the Kailian Trench and the abyssal depths of the open Apelian — water so deep that sunlight has never reached it, where the pressure alone kills most creatures and the kraken is the apex intelligence) |
| **Organization** | Solitary (always) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 12 |
| **Treasure** | Triple standard (accumulated over centuries in abyssal lairs — shipwrecks, sunken treasures, and objects collected by the kraken’s arms from the sea-floor) |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral evil |
| **Advancement** | 21–32 HD (Gargantuan); 33–60 HD (Colossal) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A kraken attacks ships from below — reaching up with tentacles to grapple the hull, constrict it to splinters, and drag the wreckage down. Against individual creatures in the water, it uses its arms (30 ft. reach) to grab multiple targets simultaneously and its bite (4d6+6) to kill.

A kraken’s intelligence (Int 21) makes it the most dangerous combat opponent in the Apelian Sea. It plans, it adapts, and it remembers. A kraken that is injured retreats into the abyss, waits, and returns with a different approach. A kraken that defeats a ship remembers the ship’s design and applies that knowledge to future encounters.

### Special Abilities

**Spell-Like Abilities:** 1/day — control weather, control winds, dominate animal (DC 18), resist energy. CL 20th.

**Improved Grab (Ex):** Tentacle or arm attack. A kraken can grapple with a tentacle while using other arms and its bite to attack additional targets.

**Constrict (Ex):** Tentacle — 2d8+12; arm — 1d6+6.

**Ink Cloud (Ex):** In water, a kraken can emit a cloud of jet-black ink in an 80-foot spread once per minute. The cloud provides total concealment and persists for 1 minute.

**Jet (Ex):** Once per round, a kraken can jet backward 280 feet as a full-round action.

**Elemental Resonance (Su):** On Kin-sense, a kraken registers as an abyssal water-signature — deep, cold, vast, and terrifyingly intelligent. The resonance is detectable at 500 feet and grows in intensity with proximity. Na’wasua sea-elves describe kraken resonance as “the ocean deciding to notice you” — a shift from the ambient water-energy of the deep sea to a focused, predatory attention that makes even experienced deep-water divers surface immediately.

### Society

Kraken are the apex intelligences of the deep Apelian Sea. They are not mere beasts — they are minds of extraordinary sophistication that happen to be attached to bodies capable of destroying warships. Each kraken is unique, each occupies a specific territory in the abyss, and each has been alive for longer than most Kin civilisations have existed.

Na’wasua sea-elves have the most developed kraken-lore of any Kin culture. Na’wasua deep-water traditions include specific protocols for kraken-territory avoidance: the Na’wasua have mapped the territories of every known kraken in the Apelian Sea (there are perhaps eight to twelve) and maintain these maps as critical navigational resources. Sailing over a kraken’s territory is not automatically fatal — kraken do not attack everything above them — but it is dangerous, and the Na’wasua never do it without reason.

Na’wasua diplomacy with kraken exists but is rare, dangerous, and conducted through a form of resonance-communication that few Na’wasua are trained for. A kraken will speak (through Kin-sense projection) with a Na’wasua emissary if it chooses, but the conversation is always on the kraken’s terms. The kraken’s interests are territorial, long-term, and alien — they care about the deep-ocean, not Kin affairs, and their demands (when they make them) concern currents, fish-populations, and the movements of other abyssal creatures.

Eruskan trading-fleets lose ships to kraken attacks roughly once per decade. Each loss is a significant event — the Eruskan maintain kraken-risk calculations for every major shipping route, and the discovery that a kraken has shifted its territory can redirect trade-routes for years.

### Lore

**DC 17 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Kraken are Gargantuan, intelligent sea-creatures with tentacles that can destroy ships. They have spell-like abilities including control weather. There are perhaps eight to twelve in the Apelian Sea.

**DC 22:** Na’wasua sea-elves have mapped every known kraken territory in the Apelian. Kraken are intelligent enough for diplomacy, conducted through resonance-communication. They remember ships they have encountered and adapt tactics accordingly.

**DC 27:** Kraken resonance is detectable at 500 feet — “the ocean deciding to notice you.” Eruskan trading-fleets incorporate kraken-risk calculations into route-planning. Na’wasua kraken-emissaries are rare specialists who communicate through Kin-sense projection.

# KRASUE

The light in the marsh is not a lantern. It moves wrong — bobbing, drifting, hovering at head-height with the lazy motion of something that is not subject to wind. When it moves closer, you see what is carrying the light: a woman’s head. Just the head — floating, trailing a mass of viscera beneath it like a jellyfish trails its tentacles. The organs glow faintly from within, producing the light that lured you here. The face is beautiful. The face is always beautiful. The face is smiling.

**Small Undead**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Small Undead |
| **Hit Dice** | 4d12 (26 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +3 |
| **Speed** | Fly 40 ft. (good) |
| **Armor Class** | 16 (+1 size, +3 Dex, +2 natural), touch 14, flat-footed 13 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +2/–2 |
| **Attack** | Bite +6 melee (1d4 plus blood drain) or viscera lash +6 melee touch (1d4 plus disease) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +6 melee (1d4 plus blood drain) and viscera lash +3 melee touch (1d4 plus disease) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. (viscera 10 ft.) |
| **Special Attacks** | Blood drain, disease, entrancing glow, viscera grapple |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., undead traits, daylight vulnerability, body return, undead resonance (masked) |
| **Saves** | Fort +1, Ref +4, Will +5 |
| **Abilities** | Str 6, Dex 17, Con —, Int 11, Wis 12, Cha 15 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +9, Hide +14, Listen +8, Move Silently +10, Spot +8 |
| **Feats** | Stealthy, Weapon Finesse |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — undead |
| **Environment** | Deepwater Marches (the wetland interior of the Deepwater Marches — stagnant pools, reed-beds, and the foggy marsh-paths that halfling fishing-communities use to navigate between settlements) |
| **Organization** | Solitary |
| **Challenge Rating** | 3 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always chaotic evil |
| **Advancement** | 5–8 HD (Small) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A krasue hunts at night, using its entrancing glow to lure prey into the marsh. The glow mimics a lantern — a creature that sees it from a distance assumes another traveler is ahead and follows. Once the target is close enough, the krasue attacks with its bite (draining blood) and viscera lash (spreading disease through contact with its trailing organs).

A krasue that successfully bites a target attaches and drains blood continuously (1 Con per round). Its viscera can grapple independently — wrapping around the target to prevent escape while the head feeds.

### Special Abilities

**Blood Drain (Ex):** A krasue that hits with a bite attack can attach (grapple check using Dex instead of Str). Each round it remains attached, it drains blood, dealing 1 point of Constitution damage.

**Disease (Su):** Viscera lash — contact; Fortitude DC 14; incubation 1d3 days; damage 1d3 Dex and 1d3 Con. The disease is a wasting sickness that weakens the victim over days. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Entrancing Glow (Su):** A krasue’s internal organs glow with a faint, warm light visible at 500 feet. A creature that sees the glow and fails a DC 14 Will save is compelled to approach (as per the captivating song ability, but visual). The save DC is Charisma-based. Halflings receive a +2 racial bonus on this save — generations of Deepwater Marches halflings have developed partial resistance.

**Viscera Grapple (Ex):** A krasue can use its trailing viscera to grapple a creature within 10 feet as a free action (using Dex for grapple checks). The viscera can maintain a grapple independently while the krasue’s head attacks other targets or feeds.

**Body Return (Su):** A krasue’s body — the headless torso — is hidden somewhere in the marsh, concealed and dormant. The krasue must return to its body before dawn. If it fails to return, or if the body is found and destroyed (burned with salt — Fortitude DC 20 or the krasue is permanently destroyed regardless of its current hit points), the krasue is permanently destroyed. Finding the body requires a DC 25 Search check in the krasue’s known hunting-grounds, or tracking the krasue at dawn as it returns.

**Daylight Vulnerability (Ex):** A krasue caught in sunlight takes 1d6 damage per round and cannot use its entrancing glow. It desperately seeks its body at dawn.

**Undead Resonance (Masked) (Su):** A krasue’s undead resonance is partially masked by its entrancing glow — the warm light interferes with Kin-sense detection, producing a false positive that reads as “lantern-warmth” rather than “undead.” A DC 18 Kin-sense check penetrates the mask.

### Society

Krasue are nocturnal undead predators of the Deepwater Marches — floating heads trailing entrails, hunting halfling fishing-communities by mimicking lantern-light in the fog. They are one of the most feared undead in halfling culture, not because they are powerful (they are not, compared to many undead) but because the Deepwater Marches’ fog, darkness, and maze-like waterways make them almost impossible to avoid.

A krasue was once a living person — always a woman, always someone who died of violence or betrayal in the marshes. The transition from corpse to krasue involves the head separating from the body (which remains hidden in the marsh as an anchor) and developing the predatory adaptations: entrancing glow, blood drain, disease-carrying viscera.

Halfling Deepwater communities maintain specific anti-krasue traditions. The most important: hang thorny vines around your doorway at night (the krasue’s trailing viscera catch on thorns, preventing entry), never follow a lone light in the marsh after dark, and if a krasue is known to be active in the area, search for the body. Destroying the body is the only reliable way to destroy the krasue permanently — a halfling marsh-search party hunting for a krasue body is one of the most grimly determined operations in Deepwater culture.

Halfling communities share krasue-sighting reports through the Deepwater network of fishing-villages — a canoe-courier system that prioritises undead warnings above all other messages. A confirmed krasue sighting triggers a response from neighbouring communities: search parties, salt-supplies, and if necessary, a request to the nearest Eruskan garrison for clerical support.

### Lore

**DC 13 (Knowledge [religion]):** Krasue are floating-head undead that trail glowing viscera. They lure victims with false lantern-light and drain blood. They must return to their hidden body before dawn.

**DC 18:** Destroying a krasue’s hidden body (burned with salt) permanently kills the creature. Halfling homes hang thorny vines to catch the trailing viscera. The glow masks the krasue’s undead resonance (DC 18 Kin-sense to penetrate).

**DC 23:** Krasue arise from women who died of violence or betrayal in the marshes. Halfling communities share sighting-reports through a canoe-courier system that prioritises undead warnings. Halflings receive a +2 racial bonus on saves against the entrancing glow from generational resistance.

# LAMASSU

The ruin is silent — that particular silence of places where someone carved stone with purpose ten thousand years ago and the stone remembers. You round the fallen pillar and something is watching you from the colonnade’s shadow. A body like a bull cast in granite, shoulders broad enough to block the passage, wings folded tight against its flanks — eagle’s wings, massive, the feathers carved from living bronze. And the face. The face is not a bull’s face. It is older than anything you have met, and it is judging you with an intelligence that makes you feel very, very small. The air around it hums with a resonance you cannot name — all four elements at once, in perfect balance, as if creation itself were holding its breath.

**Large Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 9d10+27 (76 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +2 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), fly 60 ft. (average) |
| **Armor Class** | 21 (–1 size, +2 Dex, +10 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 19 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +9/+19 |
| **Attack** | Claw +14 melee (1d6+6) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 claws +14 melee (1d6+6) and gore +12 melee (1d8+3) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Spell-like abilities, ruin-ward |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, damage reduction 5/magic, protective aura, spell resistance 19, elemental resonance (all four) |
| **Saves** | Fort +9, Ref +8, Will +8 |
| **Abilities** | Str 23, Dex 14, Con 16, Int 16, Wis 20, Cha 18 |
| **Skills** | Diplomacy +13 (9 ranks), Knowledge (history) +12 (9 ranks), Listen +14 (9 ranks), Sense Motive +14 (9 ranks), Spot +14 (9 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Flyby Attack, Iron Will, Multiattack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | All four Elemental Lords — primordial; the unbroken harmony of the Giant age, carried forward in living stone and wind |
| **Environment** | Giant Ruins (the great ruin-complexes of the Infinite Desert — the Sunken Thrones, Tharok’s Pillar, and the partially-collapsed temple-cities of the Glass Wastes’ edge; rare sightings at Giant-era bridges and gate-complexes in the Giant’s Teeth foothills) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or vigil (3–5) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 9 |
| **Treasure** | Standard |
| **Alignment** | Usually lawful good |
| **Advancement** | 10–14 HD (Large); 15–18 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +5 |

### Combat

A lamassu prefers not to fight. It interrogates intruders with questions — spoken in Common, Dwarven, or the dead Giant tongue — and judges their intent through Sense Motive and its protective aura. Creatures that answer honestly and demonstrate respect for the ruin are permitted to pass. Creatures that lie, desecrate, or refuse to answer are attacked without further warning.

In combat, a lamassu opens with its ruin-ward ability if defending a specific site, then uses Flyby Attack to make claw passes while remaining out of melee reach. Against Dómnathar creatures or undead, it closes immediately and fights with sustained aggression, using its protective aura to shield allies and its spell-like abilities to control the battlefield. A lamassu does not retreat from a ruin it guards. It fights to destruction.

### Special Abilities

**Protective Aura (Su):** A lamassu radiates a 20-foot aura of elemental stability. Allies within the aura gain a +2 morale bonus to AC and on saving throws against fear and enchantment effects. Dómnathar creatures and undead within the aura must succeed on a DC 18 Will save each round or be shaken for as long as they remain within 20 feet. The save DC is Charisma-based. The aura is always active and cannot be suppressed.

**Ruin-Ward (Su):** Once per day, a lamassu can designate a structure or area (up to a 60-foot radius) as its ward. For 24 hours, the lamassu is aware of the precise location and number of all creatures within the warded area, receives a +4 insight bonus to AC and saves while within the ward, and can use dimension door (self only) to any point within the warded area as a move action. If the lamassu leaves the warded area, it can re-enter instantly as a free action once per round. The ward ends if the lamassu designates a new area or is destroyed.

**Spell-Like Abilities:** Caster level 9th. The save DCs are Charisma-based (DC 14 + spell level). - At will — *detect evil, detect magic, see invisibility* - 3/day — *dimension door, dispel magic, protection from evil* - 1/day — *flame strike* (DC 19), *greater magic fang*

**Elemental Resonance (All Four) (Su):** A lamassu registers on Kin-sense as a sustained chord of all four elements in perfect harmony — the same resonance that the Giants once possessed, now almost vanished from the world. The experience is described by Pekakarlik ruin-wardens as “hearing a cathedral bell ring in your chest.” The resonance is overwhelming at close range: Kin within 10 feet must succeed on a DC 15 Will save or be dazed for 1 round (no save required for Kin who have encountered a lamassu before). Detection is automatic within 120 feet — the signature cannot be masked or suppressed.

### Society

Lamassu are the last living guardians of the Giant age. Whether they were created by the Giants as custodians or emerged spontaneously from the elemental harmony of Giant holy sites, no scholar has determined. What is known: lamassu bond to specific structures — a gate, a temple, a bridge — and guard them across millennia with patient, unsleeping devotion. There are perhaps thirty lamassu remaining in Oreka, almost all in the Infinite Desert’s deepest ruins.

Pekakarlik dwarves consider lamassu encounters among the most sacred events in their ruin-pilgrimage tradition. A Pekakarlik who has spoken with a lamassu and received its blessing may bear the title *ozel-hakim* (ruin-blessed) for life — a mark of deep respect among the caravan-dwarves. Pekakarlik ruin-wardens maintain records of known lamassu locations and their temperaments, passed down through families as closely guarded knowledge.

Eruskan scholars have attempted to study lamassu for centuries, with limited success. The creatures are willing to answer historical questions about the Giant age — they possess perfect memory of their bonded ruin’s history — but refuse to be “catalogued” and have driven off researchers who approach with instruments rather than conversation.

Mytroan steppe-riders who encounter lamassu near the desert’s edge treat them as territorial spirits and give them wide berth. Taraf-Imro warriors who have entered Giant ruins against lamassu warnings report that the creatures give exactly one warning, then attack with the calm precision of a sentry following orders that have not changed in ten thousand years.

### Lore

**DC 19 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Lamassu are winged, bull-bodied guardians found in Giant ruins. They possess powerful protective magic and can detect evil intent. They fight with claws and gore, and can fly.

**DC 24:** Lamassu radiate a protective aura that bolsters allies and sickens Dómnathar creatures. They can ward an area and teleport freely within it. Their spell resistance is formidable (SR 19), and they resist non-magical weapons (DR 5/magic). They fight to the death defending their bonded ruin.

**DC 29:** Lamassu carry the all-four-element resonance of the Giants — the last living creatures in Oreka to do so naturally. Pekakarlik ruin-wardens maintain records of individual lamassu: their locations, their bonded structures, and the questions they are willing to answer. A lamassu’s historical memory is perfect — it can describe events at its bonded site from the Giant age forward with absolute accuracy.

# LAMIA

The woman standing at the oasis edge is beautiful. You notice that first — the dark hair, the amber eyes, the confident stillness with which she watches your approach. You notice second that she is alone in the deep desert, a day’s ride from the nearest Pekakarlik waystation, with no supplies, no mount, and no footprints leading to where she stands. You notice third — and this is the last useful thing you will notice, because by now the Wisdom is already draining from behind your eyes — that below the waist, her body is not a woman’s body at all.

**Large Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 9d10+9 (58 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +2 |
| **Speed** | 60 ft. (12 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 16 (–1 size, +2 Dex, +5 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 14 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +9/+17 |
| **Attack** | Touch +12 melee touch (1d4 Wisdom drain) or dagger +12 melee (1d4+4/19–20) |
| **Full Attack** | Touch +12 melee touch (1d4 Wisdom drain) and 2 claws +7 melee (1d4+2) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Spell-like abilities, Wisdom drain |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, elemental resonance (corrupted) |
| **Saves** | Fort +7, Ref +8, Will +7 |
| **Abilities** | Str 18, Dex 15, Con 12, Int 13, Wis 15, Cha 14 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +12 (10 ranks), Disguise +7 (5 ranks), Hide +9 (7 ranks), Spot +7 (5 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Dodge, Iron Will, Mobility, Spring Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) / Lady of Fire (Fire) — corrupted; desert heat twisted inward, consuming rather than warming |
| **Environment** | Infinite Desert (the deep dune-seas and abandoned oases between Pekakarlik waystations — particularly the Glass Wastes, where the ruins offer hiding-places and the oases draw prey; rare sightings along the Scorchspire foothills’ desert edge) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or pair |
| **Challenge Rating** | 6 |
| **Treasure** | Standard |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic evil |
| **Advancement** | 10–13 HD (Large); 14–18 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +4 |

### Combat

A lamia is an ambush predator that uses deception and spell-like abilities to isolate prey before closing for the Wisdom drain. The preferred tactic: use *disguise self* to appear as a traveler in distress at or near an oasis, then *charm monster* on the first person to approach. Once the charmed victim is separated from companions, the lamia drops the disguise and attacks with its touch, draining Wisdom until the target is too confused to resist or flee.

Against groups, a lamia uses Spring Attack to dash in, deliver a Wisdom-draining touch, and retreat before the party can respond — repeating each round until one or more targets are Wisdom-drained to the point of helplessness (Wisdom 0 renders a creature unconscious). Lamiae avoid sustained melee against armoured opponents and retreat into the desert if faced with serious organized resistance. They are patient hunters; a lamia that fails an ambush will follow a caravan for days, waiting for someone to fall behind.

### Special Abilities

**Wisdom Drain (Su):** A lamia drains 1d4 points of Wisdom each time it hits with its melee touch attack. There is no saving throw. This is the lamia’s most dangerous weapon — a Kin traveler drained to Wisdom 0 collapses into a stupor from which only *restoration* or similar magic can recover them. Victims of partial Wisdom drain suffer impaired judgment, diminished perception, and vulnerability to the lamia’s other abilities.

**Spell-Like Abilities:** Caster level 9th. The save DCs are Charisma-based (DC 12 + spell level). - At will — *disguise self, ventriloquism* - 3/day — *charm monster* (DC 16), *major image* (DC 15), *mirror image, suggestion* (DC 15) - 1/day — *deep slumber* (DC 15)

**Corrupted Resonance (Su):** A lamia registers on Kin-sense as a recognisable earth-fire signature twisted into something predatory — warmth that pulls heat out of you rather than radiating it. Pekakarlik ruin-wardens describe it as “standing near a forge that breathes in.” The corruption is detectable at 60 feet (DC 14 Wisdom check to distinguish from a natural earth-fire source such as a volcanic vent; DC 10 for Pekakarlik, who know the difference instinctively). A lamia using *disguise self* does not mask its Kin-sense signature — only its visual appearance changes.

### Society

Lamiae are solitary desert predators of the Infinite Desert, preying on travelers, pilgrims, and caravan stragglers between the Pekakarlik waystations. They are intelligent and cruel, taking pleasure in the slow degradation of a victim’s judgment as the Wisdom drain strips away perception, intuition, and will. A lamia will sometimes keep a Wisdom-drained victim alive for days, feeding it scraps and watching it stumble through the desert in a stupor before finishing it.

Pekakarlik caravans maintain strict anti-lamia protocols: never approach a lone figure at an oasis without first reading the Kin-sense signature, never travel alone between waystations, and if a companion begins behaving strangely or making poor decisions (early signs of Wisdom drain), assume lamia contact and check the entire party’s Wisdom scores immediately. Pekakarlik children learn the rhyme *ayakkabı tek, akıl yok* (“one shoe, no mind”) — a reference to the lamia’s inability to disguise its lower body’s tracks.

Mytroan riders who cross the desert’s northern edge consider lamiae the second-most-dangerous desert predator after the blue dragon. Eruskan scholars classify lamiae as “elemental predators” — creatures whose elemental attunement has inverted, consuming the resonance they should radiate.

### Lore

**DC 16 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Lamiae are Large magical beasts with the upper body of a woman and the lower body of a lion. They haunt desert oases and drain Wisdom through touch. They can disguise their appearance with illusion magic.

**DC 21:** A lamia’s Wisdom drain has no saving throw — it is automatic on a successful touch. They use *charm monster* and *suggestion* to separate targets from groups. Their disguise does not fool Kin-sense; the corrupted earth-fire resonance is detectable before the lamia is seen. Spring Attack makes them difficult to pin down in melee.

**DC 26:** Lamiae are solitary and territorial, each claiming a stretch of desert between waystations as hunting-ground. Their corrupted elemental resonance is an inverted earth-fire signature — Pekakarlik caravaneers call it “forge-that-breathes-in.” Wisdom-drained victims can only be fully restored by *restoration* or equivalent magic. Pekakarlik anti-lamia protocols emphasise Kin-sense checks at every oasis and buddy-system travel.

# LASA

The river is quieter here — the current softens where the willow-roots meet the water, and the evening light turns the surface to hammered copper. You see her sitting on the stones at the water’s edge, bare feet in the current, combing her hair with a comb made of river-shell. She is not quite solid. The light passes through her edges. When she turns to look at you, her eyes are the colour of deep water, and the song she has been humming settles into your chest like a second heartbeat. The Great River has a thousand of these places — bends and pools and quiet stretches where the water remembers — and every one of them has a lasa, and every lasa has been here longer than you.

**Medium Fey (Aquatic)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Fey (Aquatic) |
| **Hit Dice** | 5d6+5 (22 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +3 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), swim 40 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 16 (+3 Dex, +2 natural, +1 deflection), touch 14, flat-footed 13 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +2/+2 |
| **Attack** | Touch +5 melee touch (river’s blessing or river’s curse) |
| **Full Attack** | Touch +5 melee touch (river’s blessing or river’s curse) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Beguiling song, river’s curse, spell-like abilities |
| **Special Qualities** | Amphibious, damage reduction 5/cold iron, low-light vision, river bond, river’s blessing, elemental resonance (fey-water) |
| **Saves** | Fort +2, Ref +7, Will +6 |
| **Abilities** | Str 10, Dex 16, Con 12, Int 14, Wis 15, Cha 18 |
| **Skills** | Diplomacy +12 (8 ranks), Heal +10 (8 ranks), Knowledge (nature) +10 (8 ranks), Listen +10 (8 ranks), Perform (sing) +12 (8 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Weapon Finesse, Ability Focus (beguiling song) |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) — gentle; river-current and willow-shade, the slow music of water over stone |
| **Environment** | Great River (the quiet bends, willow-pools, and sacred confluences of the Great River system — particularly the Eruskan stretches between Twin Rivers and the Sea Falls, where the river widens and the current slows) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or confluence (3–8 at a major river junction) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 3 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (river-gifts: polished stones, shells, lost jewellery recovered from the riverbed) |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral good |
| **Advancement** | 6–8 HD (Medium) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +3 |

### Combat

A lasa does not seek combat. If threatened, it retreats into the river using its swim speed and river bond to vanish. If cornered or if its bonded river-stretch is under threat (pollution, damming, Dómnathar corruption), a lasa fights with its river’s curse — draining the aggressor’s judgment — and beguiling song to incapacitate groups while it escapes.

Against multiple opponents, a lasa opens with its beguiling song to fascinate as many targets as possible, then dives into the river. Against a single aggressor, it uses the curse touch and retreats. Lasae almost never fight to the death; they dissolve into their river if reduced below 5 hit points and reform 1d4 days later at the same location.

### Special Abilities

**Beguiling Song (Su):** A lasa can sing as a standard action, forcing all non-fey creatures within 60 feet who can hear it to make a DC 18 Will save or be fascinated for as long as the lasa continues singing plus 1 round. A creature that successfully saves is immune to that lasa’s song for 24 hours. Eruskan Kin who have traded songs with a lasa in the past receive a +4 bonus on this save — the familiarity inoculates against the compulsion. The save DC is Charisma-based and includes the +2 from Ability Focus.

**River’s Blessing (Su):** A lasa can touch a willing creature to heal 1d8+5 hit points. It can use this ability a number of times per day equal to its Charisma modifier (4 times/day). Lasae offer blessings freely to those who approach with respect and to river-workers whose livelihood depends on the water.

**River’s Curse (Su):** As a melee touch attack, a lasa can deliver a curse: the target must succeed on a DC 16 Will save or suffer a –4 penalty to all Wisdom-based checks and skill checks for 24 hours and become unable to navigate waterways (automatically fails Survival checks to navigate rivers or avoid hazards on water). A creature that harms a lasa’s bonded river-stretch (see River Bond) takes a –2 penalty on this save. *Remove curse* or immersion in running water for 1 hour ends the effect early. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**River Bond (Su):** Each lasa is permanently bonded to a specific stretch of river (typically 1–3 miles). While within its bonded stretch, the lasa gains fast healing 2, can breathe water indefinitely, and can merge with the river as a standard action (becoming invisible and immune to all physical damage, but unable to act except to observe and move at its swim speed). If the lasa is more than one mile from its bonded stretch, it loses its damage reduction and fast healing. If the bonded stretch is destroyed or irreversibly corrupted, the lasa dies within 1d4 days.

**Spell-Like Abilities:** Caster level 5th. The save DCs are Charisma-based (DC 14 + spell level). - At will — *dancing lights, ghost sound* (DC 14) - 3/day — *charm person* (DC 15), *fog cloud* - 1/day — *water breathing* (touch, 8 hours)

**Fey-Water Resonance (Su):** A lasa registers on Kin-sense as a gentle, flowing water-resonance with the distinctive fey quality — mutable, musical, and slightly uncanny, like hearing a familiar song played on an instrument you have never encountered. The resonance is detectable at 60 feet (no check required; the signature is welcoming rather than threatening). Eruskan river-folk describe it as “the river humming to itself.” In areas where a lasa has been resident for decades, the entire stretch of river develops a faint background resonance that experienced rivermen can detect (DC 15 Kin-sense check) — these stretches are considered blessed.

### Society

Lasae are the river-spirits of the Great River and its tributaries — gentle, long-lived fey bound to specific bends, pools, and confluences where the current slows and the water remembers. They are among the most beloved supernatural creatures in Eruskan culture, occupying a central place in the river-folk’s religious and artistic traditions.

Eruskan bards maintain the *Canto dei Fiumi* (“Song of the Rivers”) — a living tradition of composed songs specifically intended for lasae. A bard who learns the Canto and performs it at a lasa’s bonded stretch may earn the spirit’s attention and, if the performance is skilled and sincere, its blessing. The trade works both ways: lasae teach melodies to favoured bards, and songs learned from a lasa carry a faint enchantment that grants +2 on Diplomacy checks made while the bard is near running water. This bardic tradition is one of the oldest continuous practices in Eruskan culture — the earliest Canto compositions predate the Deceivers’ War.

River-fishers, bargemen, and ferrymen along the Great River leave offerings at known lasa pools: polished stones, fresh flowers, and small quantities of Eruskan river-wine. In return, lasae bless boats (granting +2 on Profession [sailor] checks for one journey), heal injured river-workers, and — most importantly — warn of danger. A lasa whose bonded stretch is threatened by flooding, corruption, or predators will appear to the nearest river-community and sing a warning-song that all Eruskan recognise.

Pekakarlik river-dwarves, whose trade-barges ply the Great River’s full length, maintain formal relationships with lasae at key waypoints — these are genuine diplomatic agreements, negotiated and renewed annually, granting safe passage through each lasa’s territory in exchange for maintenance of the riverbanks.

Lasae are deeply vulnerable to Dómnathar corruption. A lasa whose bonded stretch is contaminated by False Silence loses its healing abilities first, then its song, then its physical form — dissolving into the polluted water and leaving behind a stretch of dead river that produces no fish, grows no reeds, and reads as a faint, agonising echo on Kin-sense. Eruskan communities monitor their local lasae as early-warning indicators of Dómnathar activity: a silent lasa means something is very wrong upstream.

### Lore

**DC 13 (Knowledge [nature]):** Lasae are gentle river-fey bound to specific stretches of the Great River. They heal the willing, curse those who harm the water, and can fascinate listeners with their song. Cold iron bypasses their defences.

**DC 18:** Each lasa is bonded to a specific mile-long river-stretch and cannot survive far from it. They can merge with the river to become invisible and intangible. Eruskan bards maintain a tradition of songs composed specifically for lasae, and the exchange of music between bard and lasa is central to Eruskan river-culture.

**DC 23:** Lasae serve as early-warning systems for Dómnathar contamination — a silent or absent lasa indicates upstream corruption. Their fey-water resonance saturates their bonded river-stretch over decades, creating detectable blessed zones. Pekakarlik river-dwarves maintain formal diplomatic agreements with lasae at key trade-route waypoints.

# LESHY

The forest is watching you. Not in the way that forests always watch — the incurious attention of birds and insects and the slow awareness of old trees. This is focused. This is personal. You have been walking for three hours and you are back where you started, though you have not turned once. The blaze-marks you cut into the bark an hour ago are gone. The path you were following does not exist. Somewhere ahead, in the green shadow between the oaks, something enormous shifts its weight and the canopy sways though there is no wind. The sound it makes is not a voice. It is the creak of a living trunk bending, the rustle of a thousand leaves turning at once, the groan of roots adjusting in deep soil. It is the forest itself, expressing an opinion about your presence. The opinion is not favourable.

**Large Plant**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Plant |
| **Hit Dice** | 10d8+50 (95 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +1 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 21 (–1 size, +1 Dex, +11 natural), touch 10, flat-footed 20 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +7/+18 |
| **Attack** | Slam +13 melee (2d6+7) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 slams +13 melee (2d6+7) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./10 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Forest command, trample 2d6+10 |
| **Special Qualities** | Change size, damage reduction 10/slashing, forest stride, low-light vision, plant traits, vulnerability to fire, wild empathy, elemental resonance (earth-wind) |
| **Saves** | Fort +12, Ref +4, Will +6 |
| **Abilities** | Str 24, Dex 12, Con 20, Int 14, Wis 16, Cha 14 |
| **Skills** | Hide +6 (9 ranks, –4 size; +8 racial in forest), Knowledge (nature) +12 (10 ranks), Listen +13 (10 ranks), Move Silently +11 (10 ranks), Spot +4 (1 rank) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Cleave, Improved Natural Attack (slam), Power Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) / Youngest Brother (Air) — ancient; root-deep and canopy-high, the living forest from soil to sky |
| **Environment** | Great Forests (the deepest interior of the Hasura canopy and Pasua ground-level forests — ancient-growth stands where the trees are old enough to have names; rare sightings in Kovaka coastal forests and the forest-steppe border) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or moot (2–4, extremely rare — leshiye gather only to resolve territorial disputes) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 8 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 11–15 HD (Large); 16–20 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A leshy does not ambush. It warns. Trespassers in a leshy’s territory first experience disorientation (paths loop, landmarks shift, trail-markers vanish). If the intruder persists, the leshy reveals itself — rising from the undergrowth to its full height — and delivers a single, clear command to leave. Only if the command is ignored does the leshy fight.

In combat, a leshy uses forest command to entangle opponents, then closes for slam attacks. Against groups, it uses trample to scatter formations before isolating individual targets. It exploits its forest stride ability to move through dense undergrowth that immobilises its enemies. A leshy reduced below 20 hit points changes to Small size and retreats into the deepest forest, using its racial Hide bonus to disappear. Leshiye do not pursue fleeing intruders.

### Special Abilities

**Change Size (Su):** As a standard action, a leshy can change its size between Small, Medium, Large (default), and Huge. Its statistics change as follows: - *Small:* Str 14, Dex 16, Con 16; AC 19 (+1 size, +3 Dex, +5 natural); slam +6 melee (1d4+2); Hide +18 in forest - *Medium:* Str 20, Dex 14, Con 18; AC 20 (+2 Dex, +8 natural); slam +10 melee (1d6+5) - *Large:* As listed above (default combat form) - *Huge:* Str 28, Dex 10, Con 22; AC 21 (–2 size, +0 Dex, +13 natural); slam +18 melee (2d8+9); Space/Reach 15 ft./15 ft.

**Forest Command (Su):** Three times per day, a leshy can command the plant life within a 60-foot radius as a standard action. This functions as *entangle* (DC 17, Wisdom-based) but the plants actively grasp and restrain, dealing 1d6 points of bludgeoning damage per round to entangled creatures. The effect lasts for 10 rounds or until the leshy dismisses it. Within this area, the leshy ignores the entanglement entirely and receives a +4 bonus on attack rolls.

**Trample (Ex):** Reflex DC 22 half. The save DC is Strength-based. A trampling leshy deals 2d6+10 points of damage.

**Forest Stride (Ex):** A leshy can move through any natural undergrowth (thorns, briars, overgrown areas, and similar) at its normal speed without taking damage or suffering impairment. Magically-manipulated undergrowth still affects it normally.

**Wild Empathy (Ex):** A leshy can communicate with animals as though using a *speak with animals* spell (always active). It can make a wild empathy check (1d20+12) to influence the attitude of an animal, functioning as a Diplomacy check.

**Earth-Wind Resonance (Su):** A leshy registers on Kin-sense as a deep, slow pulse of earth-resonance overlaid with high, bright wind-notes — the complete vertical signature of a living forest, from root to canopy. Pasua ground-scouts describe it as “feeling the entire forest breathing.” The resonance is detectable at 120 feet in forested terrain (the forest itself amplifies the signal) but only 30 feet outside the forest. Within the leshy’s territory (typically 2–5 square miles), the ambient resonance is strong enough that experienced Kin can detect the leshy’s general direction at up to a mile (DC 20 Kin-sense check). A leshy’s resonance strengthens when it is angry — Pasua scouts use this as an early warning that something has violated the territory.

### Society

Leshiye are the solitary lords of the Great Forests’ deepest stands — ancient plant-spirits that claim territories of old-growth forest and defend them against all intrusion with a combination of territorial authority and raw power. Each leshy claims a distinct region of forest, and no two leshiye share territory willingly. When territories must be adjusted — due to fire, logging, or new growth — leshiye meet in rare moots where disputes are settled through contests of forest command, size-changing displays, and (according to Pasua tradition) gambling.

Pasua ground-level elves have the longest and most complex relationship with leshiye. Pasua rangers maintain detailed mental maps of leshy territories within their patrol regions, updated annually through careful observation. The protocol for crossing leshy territory is formalised: announce yourself at the boundary (Pasua carry specific wooden tokens carved with the leshy’s mark), state your purpose, leave an offering of fresh game, and follow the path the forest provides. Deviating from the provided path is understood as a challenge. Pasua who follow protocol are almost never harmed; Pasua who violate it are lost in the looping paths for days before being expelled, bruised and chastened, at the territory’s edge.

Hasura canopy-elves interact with leshiye differently — from above. The canopy-dwellers consider leshiye to be beings of the floor, and the relationship is one of mutual respect between neighbours who occupy different vertical zones of the same forest. Hasura occasionally negotiate with leshiye for permission to anchor new platform-settlements to ancient trees within leshy territory; the payment is usually decades of non-intervention in the leshy’s ground-level domain.

Kovaka coastal-elves have fewer leshy encounters (their forests are younger and less interior), but maintain respect-traditions borrowed from the Pasua.

Non-Kin who enter leshy territory without protocol — Dómnathar agents, undead, careless adventurers — receive no warning beyond the disorientation effect. Leshiye hate fire above all things, and anyone who brings fire into a leshy’s territory (even a torch) is attacked immediately and without mercy.

### Lore

**DC 18 (Knowledge [nature]):** Leshiye are powerful plant-spirits of the Great Forests that control vast territories of old-growth. They can change size, command plant life, and move through undergrowth freely. Fire is their greatest vulnerability, and they attack fire-carriers on sight.

**DC 23:** A leshy’s territory is defined by its resonance — experienced Kin can feel the boundary. Pasua elves maintain formal protocols for crossing leshy territory, including carved wooden tokens. Leshiye have damage reduction 10/slashing, plant immunities, and can entangle creatures in a 60-foot radius.

**DC 28:** Leshiye are solitary and territorial, meeting only in rare “moots” to resolve border disputes. Their earth-wind resonance is the complete vertical signature of a living forest. Hasura canopy-elves negotiate separately with leshiye for platform-settlement rights. A leshy reduced to low health changes to Small size and vanishes — they do not fight to the death except against fire.

# LEVIATHAN-SHARD

You smell it before you see it — brine and depth and something older, a pressure-smell like the deep ocean forced into a space too small to contain it. The goblin camp ahead has arranged its tents in a wide semicircle around a pit lined with wet stones, and in the pit there is a thing. A mass of translucent flesh, pale blue and shot through with veins of bioluminescence that pulse in a slow rhythm unrelated to anything on land. It is the size of a cart-horse, and it is alive in a way that makes your skin crawl — not because it is hostile but because the intelligence behind those pulses is vast and fragmented and does not understand where it is. Tendrils extend from its mass, tasting the air. The goblins feed it fish-heads and river-weeds, and it accepts the offerings with the disinterested patience of something that was once part of a creature the size of a mountain.

**Medium Aberration (Aquatic)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Aberration (Aquatic) |
| **Hit Dice** | 8d8+27 (63 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +7 |
| **Speed** | 20 ft. (4 squares), swim 40 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 20 (+3 Dex, +7 natural), touch 13, flat-footed 17 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +6/+10 |
| **Attack** | Tendril +10 melee (1d6+4 plus psychic static) |
| **Full Attack** | 3 tendrils +10 melee (1d6+4 plus psychic static) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./10 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Psychic static |
| **Special Qualities** | Amphibious, blindsight 60 ft., damage reduction 5/slashing, fast healing 3, amorphous, elemental resonance (alien depth) |
| **Saves** | Fort +5, Ref +5, Will +8 |
| **Abilities** | Str 18, Dex 16, Con 16, Int 4, Wis 14, Cha 10 |
| **Skills** | Listen +9 (7 ranks), Spot +3 (1 rank) |
| **Feats** | Ability Focus (psychic static), Improved Initiative, Weapon Focus (tendril) |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) — alien; so ancient and so deep that it reads as something from before the Lady shaped the waters |
| **Environment** | Any coastal or wetland (Leviathan-shards wash ashore on the Apelian Sea coast and are found in free goblin camps throughout the Deepwater Marches; specimens have been transported as far as the Tidebloom Reach by goblin traders) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or clutch (2–4, usually in a goblin camp) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 7 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always neutral |
| **Advancement** | 9–12 HD (Medium); 13–16 HD (Large) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A Leviathan-shard is not aggressive by nature — it feeds on dead organic matter and has no predatory instinct. It attacks when threatened, when its feeding is interrupted, or when directed by a handler (see Society). In combat, it extends three tendrils in a slow, sweeping pattern, striking anything within reach. Each tendril impact delivers psychic static — a disorienting pulse of alien awareness that disrupts concentration and Kin-sense.

A shard does not pursue fleeing creatures. It does not strategise. It fights with the patient, indifferent endurance of something that does not understand pain in any meaningful sense, absorbing damage through its fast healing and amorphous body while lashing at anything within reach. Killing a shard requires sustained effort — it continues fighting at full effectiveness until destroyed, with no retreat behaviour.

### Special Abilities

**Psychic Static (Su):** A creature hit by a Leviathan-shard’s tendril must succeed on a DC 18 Will save or suffer psychic static for 1d4 rounds. An affected creature takes a –4 penalty on Concentration checks, cannot use Kin-sense, and must succeed on a DC 15 Concentration check to cast any spell. Multiple hits do not stack the penalties but do reset the duration. The save DC is Wisdom-based and includes the +2 from Ability Focus.

**Amorphous (Ex):** A Leviathan-shard has no discernible anatomy. It is immune to critical hits, flanking, and precision-based damage (such as sneak attack). It can squeeze through any space at least 1 foot wide without penalty.

**Fast Healing 3 (Ex):** A Leviathan-shard heals 3 hit points per round. Fire and acid damage are healed normally (not suppressed — the shard has no specific vulnerability, only the slow indifference of flesh that was part of something functionally immortal).

**Alien Depth Resonance (Su):** A Leviathan-shard registers on Kin-sense as something profoundly wrong — not Dómnathar void (which is deliberate absence) but alien depth, a water-resonance so ancient and so vast that it does not fit the scale of terrestrial perception. Na’wasua sea-elves describe the experience as “standing on a shore that has never seen sunlight.” The resonance is detectable at 90 feet and causes involuntary unease in Kin (–1 morale penalty on attack rolls and saves for Kin within 30 feet; no save, but the penalty fades after 10 minutes of continuous exposure as the Kin acclimatises). Goblins, lacking Kin-sense, are entirely unaffected — which is one reason they are the primary handlers.

### Society

Leviathan-shards are fragments of shed Leviathan tissue — scales, fin-membrane, gobbets of flesh sloughed during the slow growth-cycles of the Apelian and Kailian Seas’ great Leviathans. This material does not decay. It absorbs ambient elemental energy and develops a rudimentary, flickering consciousness — not truly alive and not truly dead, but something between that pulses with the residual awareness of a creature the size of a mountain. The shards wash ashore during certain seasons (the Apelian autumn shedding-tides are the most productive), collecting in tidal pools and estuaries where they absorb nutrients and grow.

Free goblin communities of the Deepwater Marches discovered Leviathan-shard biology three to four generations after Dark Dawn. Through patient trial and error, goblin handlers developed techniques for collecting, feeding, and crudely directing shards — using a combination of fish-offal feeding schedules, rhythmic percussion (the shards respond to low-frequency vibrations), and physical barriers to channel the shard’s movement. A goblin clan with a well-fed Leviathan-shard in its camp is a clan that other predators avoid — the psychic static and alien resonance repel most natural creatures, and the shard’s tendrils deter raiders.

Goblin shard-tenders (*kra-huul* in the Marches trade-pidgin) are specialists who understand shard feeding cycles, growth patterns, and the signs of shard distress. The trade in live shards between goblin communities is one of the more unusual economies of the Deepwater Marches — a healthy, medium-sized shard commands a price equivalent to several trained war-weasels.

Na’wasua sea-elves regard Leviathan-shards with deep ambivalence. The shards are, in a sense, parts of the Leviathans that the Na’wasua revere as the oceans’ oldest spirits. Killing a shard feels like desecrating something sacred; letting a shard grow unchecked feels irresponsible. Most Na’wasua communities leave the management to the goblins and try not to think about it too hard.

Eruskan naturalists who have studied shards (from a safe distance) classify them as “biological echoes” — autonomous tissue that retains a fragment of its parent organism’s awareness without possessing true intelligence or will. The comparison they draw is to a severed lizard’s tail, still twitching — except this tail is the size of a horse, can think in fragmented pulses, and will never stop twitching.

### Lore

**DC 17 (Knowledge [dungeoneering]):** Leviathan-shards are masses of living tissue shed by the great Leviathans of the inland seas. They attack with tendrils that produce psychic disruption. They are amorphous and immune to critical hits.

**DC 22:** Shards have fast healing 3 and fight until destroyed. Their psychic static suppresses Kin-sense and disrupts spellcasting (DC 18 Will to resist). Free goblin communities of the Deepwater Marches have learned to collect, feed, and direct shards as camp guardians. Slashing weapons overcome their damage reduction.

**DC 27:** Leviathan-shards retain a fragment of their parent Leviathan’s consciousness — a vast, ancient water-resonance so deep that it causes involuntary unease in all Kin within 30 feet. Goblins are immune to this effect (lacking Kin-sense), making them the only viable handlers. The Apelian autumn shedding-tides produce the most shards. Na’wasua sea-elves consider the shards sacred but leave management to goblins.

# LINDWORM

The shaft goes deeper than the Vestri mapped it. The stonework ended three levels up — down here, the walls are raw mountain, the seams of ore glinting in your lantern-light like veins in a living body. The air is warm and wet and smells of acid. You hear it before you see it: a vast, slow scraping, like a ship’s hull dragging across rock, and the sound of something breathing through a mouth full of venom. The lindworm fills the tunnel. Its body is serpentine and armoured in scales the colour of tarnished iron, two powerful forelegs gripping the stone as it pulls itself toward you with the unhurried patience of something that has lived in these mountains since before the dwarves began to dig. Its eyes are the dull amber of old torchlight, and the venom dripping from its jaws hisses where it strikes the stone floor. This is the mountain’s own predator, and you are in its home.

**Large Dragon**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Dragon |
| **Hit Dice** | 12d12+48 (126 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +1 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), burrow 20 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 24 (–1 size, +1 Dex, +14 natural), touch 10, flat-footed 23 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +12/+24 |
| **Attack** | Bite +19 melee (3d6+8 plus poison) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +19 melee (3d6+8 plus poison) and 2 claws +17 melee (1d8+4) and tail slap +17 melee (1d8+4) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./10 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Constrict 2d6+12, improved grab, poison |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 120 ft., damage reduction 5/magic, immunity to acid, immunity to paralysis, immunity to sleep, low-light vision, spell resistance 21, tremorsense 60 ft., elemental resonance (deep earth) |
| **Saves** | Fort +12, Ref +9, Will +11 |
| **Abilities** | Str 26, Dex 12, Con 18, Int 10, Wis 16, Cha 14 |
| **Skills** | Intimidate +14 (12 ranks), Listen +15 (12 ranks), Search +12 (12 ranks), Spot +15 (12 ranks), Survival +15 (12 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Ability Focus (poison), Cleave, Improved Natural Attack (bite), Multiattack, Power Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) — deep; the slow pressure of mountains, the heat of the world’s bones beneath the crust |
| **Environment** | Giant’s Teeth Deep Shafts (the deepest mine-shafts, natural fissures, and geothermal vents below Vestri mining depth — particularly the Undershafts beneath Stoneheart, the flooded deep-tunnels of Ironwell, and the volcanic fissures of the inner Giant’s Teeth) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or mated pair |
| **Challenge Rating** | 11 |
| **Treasure** | Double standard |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 13–18 HD (Large); 19–24 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A lindworm is a patient ambush predator that uses its tremorsense to detect vibrations from mining, movement, and combat in the tunnels above its lair. It attacks by burrowing through the tunnel wall behind or beneath its prey, striking with its venomous bite before the target is aware of its presence. Against a single target, it bites, grabs with improved grab, and constricts while continuing to bite — the venom and crushing damage combine to kill even heavily armoured prey within rounds.

Against groups, a lindworm blocks the tunnel with its body (its Large size fills most mine-shafts) and fights from a position of advantage, forcing opponents to engage it head-on in a space where flanking is impossible. It uses Power Attack aggressively against armoured targets and reserves its tail slap for creatures attempting to circle behind it.

A lindworm retreats into its burrow if reduced below 30 hit points, collapsing the tunnel behind it. Pursuing a retreating lindworm into its own burrow network is considered suicidal by Vestri mining doctrine.

### Special Abilities

**Poison (Ex):** Bite; Fortitude DC 22; initial damage 1d6 Str; secondary damage 1d6 Str. The save DC is Constitution-based and includes the +2 from Ability Focus. The venom is a thick, yellowish acid that hisses on contact with stone and causes muscle necrosis in living tissue.

**Improved Grab (Ex):** To use this ability, a lindworm must hit with its bite attack. It can then attempt to start a grapple as a free action without provoking an attack of opportunity. If it wins the grapple check, it establishes a hold and can constrict.

**Constrict (Ex):** A lindworm deals 2d6+12 damage with a successful grapple check, wrapping its serpentine lower body around the target and crushing.

**Tremorsense (Ex):** A lindworm can detect and pinpoint any creature or object in contact with the ground within 60 feet. This is how it hunts — it lies motionless in its burrow, detecting the vibrations of mining and movement in adjacent tunnels, then erupts through the wall to attack.

**Deep Earth Resonance (Su):** A lindworm registers on Kin-sense as a massive, slow, grinding earth-resonance — the pressure of deep stone, the heat of the planet’s bones. Vestri dwarves describe it as “the mountain’s heartbeat, too close.” The resonance is detectable at 90 feet through solid stone (the signature passes through rock more efficiently than through air). Detection is automatic for any Kin with earth-elemental attunement; other Kin require a DC 12 Wisdom check. The resonance intensifies dramatically when the lindworm is agitated — experienced Vestri miners can tell the difference between a resting lindworm (faint, steady pulse) and a hunting one (accelerating, rhythmic grinding) and know to evacuate accordingly.

### Society

Lindworms are the apex predators of the Giant’s Teeth deep-shaft ecosystem — wingless, serpentine dragons that have inhabited the mountains’ roots since before the Vestri began to mine. They are not intelligent in the way of true dragons (Int 10 — animal cunning rather than draconic intellect), but they are ancient, patient, and extremely dangerous in the confined tunnel environments they prefer.

The Vestri have a deep and complex relationship with lindworms, born from centuries of coexistence in the same mountains. Vestri mining doctrine includes an entire discipline dedicated to lindworm management: the *Lindvarða* (Lindworm Wardens), a corps of specialists who monitor known dens, map lindworm burrow networks, and maintain the “depth markers” that indicate the boundary between safe mining depth and lindworm territory. The cardinal rule of Vestri deep-shaft mining is simple: do not dig below the depth markers. Every generation, a foreman ignores this rule. The lindworm’s response is always the same.

Vestri culture treats lindworms with a mixture of fear, respect, and grudging admiration. The creatures are called *fjallstönn* (“mountain-teeth”), and the phrase “digging into the teeth” is a common Vestri idiom for reckless overreach. Vestri children are taught the evacuation pattern for a lindworm shaft-breach before they are taught to read. The pattern is drilled annually, and the speed of a Vestri mine’s evacuation response is a source of competitive pride between mining-clans.

Rarozhki fire-dwarves, whose Scorchspire mines are shallower and hotter, encounter lindworms less frequently but consider them kin-spirits of the volcanic vents — creatures of deep earth and slow fire. Rarozhki lindworm encounters are less adversarial than Vestri ones; the Rarozhki tend to view the lindworm as a natural hazard like lava flow rather than a territorial rival.

Lindworms hoard treasure — not with draconic avarice, but with the instinctive acquisitiveness of a creature drawn to refined metal and worked stone. A lindworm’s lair typically contains the accumulated debris of centuries: ore veins it has exposed through burrowing, lost mining equipment, the armour and weapons of miners who dug too deep, and occasionally objects of genuine value from Giant-era deep-works.

### Lore

**DC 21 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Lindworms are wingless dragons of the deep shafts — Large, serpentine, venomous, and capable of burrowing through solid rock. They are immune to acid and resistant to magic (SR 21). They hunt by tremorsense, detecting vibrations through stone.

**DC 26:** A lindworm’s bite delivers Strength-draining venom (Fort DC 22). It grabs and constricts prey, dealing crushing damage each round. Vestri miners maintain Lindworm Wardens who map dens and enforce depth markers. The creatures retreat by collapsing tunnels behind them; pursuit is suicidal.

**DC 31:** Lindworms predate the Vestri and may predate the Giants. Their deep-earth resonance passes through stone more efficiently than air, making them detectable by Kin-sense at up to 90 feet through solid rock. Experienced Vestri can distinguish a resting lindworm’s resonance from a hunting one by the rhythm’s acceleration. Rarozhki fire-dwarves consider them kin-spirits of volcanic vents.

# LOCATHAH

The water is warm here — the deep Apelian currents rising through thermal vents in the trench floor, carrying minerals and heat into the crushing dark. Your *water breathing* spell holds, but the pressure aches behind your eyes. Movement below: a dozen figures rising from the coral-crusted ledge of a Giant-era aqueduct, their bodies sleek and scaled, their eyes reflecting your magelight with a flat, inhuman calm. They carry spears of sharpened coral tipped with Giant-ruin bronze, and they move through the water with a grace that makes your own swimming feel like drowning. One of them — taller, its scales a deeper green — raises an open hand. You hope that gesture means the same thing down here that it means on the surface.

**Medium Humanoid (Aquatic)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Humanoid (Aquatic) |
| **Hit Dice** | 1d8+1 (5 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +1 |
| **Speed** | 10 ft. (2 squares), swim 60 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 14 (+1 Dex, +3 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 13 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +0/+0 |
| **Attack** | Longspear +1 melee (1d8/×3) or light crossbow +1 ranged (1d8/19–20) |
| **Full Attack** | Longspear +1 melee (1d8/×3) or light crossbow +1 ranged (1d8/19–20) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | — |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., water dependent, wild static (aquatic) |
| **Saves** | Fort +3, Ref +1, Will +1 |
| **Abilities** | Str 10, Dex 12, Con 12, Int 13, Wis 13, Cha 11 |
| **Skills** | Craft (any one) +5 (4 ranks), Listen +3 (2 ranks), Spot +3 (2 ranks), Swim +8 (racial) |
| **Feats** | Weapon Focus (longspear) |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) — steady; deep-current and thermal warmth, the patient rhythm of tidal cycles |
| **Environment** | Deep Apelian Trenches (the geothermal vent communities along the Apelian Sea’s deepest fissures — particularly the submerged Giant-era aqueducts and flooded temple-complexes that provide structure for locathah settlements; smaller communities in the Kailian Sea’s northern deep-water shelves) |
| **Organization** | Company (2–4), patrol (11–20 plus 2 3rd-level sergeants and 1 leader of 3rd–6th level), or tribe (30–100 plus 100% noncombatants plus 1 3rd-level sergeant per 10 adults plus 5 5th-level lieutenants plus 3 7th-level captains) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 1/2 |
| **Treasure** | Standard |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | By character class |
| **Level Adjustment** | +0 |

### Combat

Locathah are not warriors by temperament, but they defend their communities with organised discipline when threatened. Patrols operate in groups of eleven to twenty, using the three-dimensional space of open water to surround intruders — a tactic that surface-dwellers, accustomed to two-dimensional combat, find disorienting. Longspears provide reach that keeps enemies at a distance, and locathah crossbowmen fire from above and below while the spear-line holds.

Locathah retreat readily if outmatched, withdrawing into the deep-water trenches and using the pressure differential to discourage pursuit (most surface-dwellers cannot follow below 300 feet without magical protection). They never fight to the death over territory — they will abandon a settlement if the threat is overwhelming and re-establish elsewhere.

### Special Abilities

**Water Dependent (Ex):** Locathah can survive out of water for 1 hour per 2 points of Constitution (6 hours for a typical locathah). After that, they begin to suffocate as if drowning.

**Wild Static (Aquatic) (Su):** Locathah register on Kin-sense as wild static with a cool, deep-water quality — present, alive, but fundamentally non-Kin. Na’wasua sea-elves describe the sensation as “hearing rain on water from very far away.” The static is detectable at 60 feet underwater (reduced to 30 feet through water turbulence). Unlike the wild static of surface-dwelling Non-Kin (goblins, wargs), locathah static carries no warmth — it reads as neutral, calm, and faintly alien. This makes locathah easy to overlook on Kin-sense in the deep Apelian, where ambient water-resonance masks faint wild static signals (DC 16 to detect in deep water, DC 12 in shallow).

### Society

Locathah are the most numerous non-Kin people of the deep Apelian Sea — fish-scaled humanoids who build their communities around the geothermal vents and Giant-era submerged structures of the sea floor. They are peaceful, industrious, and profoundly territorial in a quiet way: locathah do not fight for territory so much as they simply persist in it, generation after generation, until the trench or vent-field is as much theirs as the stone it is carved from.

Locathah settlements are built into and around the submerged ruins of Giant-era aqueducts, water-temples, and bridge-pylons that dot the Apelian Sea floor. The Giants built for eternity, and their underwater infrastructure — designed to channel water between inland seas — remains structurally sound millennia later. Locathah communities use these structures as foundations, building coral-and-stone extensions that gradually transform a Giant ruin into a living settlement of several hundred. The largest locathah settlement, *Ven-ko-rath* (roughly “the Warm Place”), is built around a cluster of thermal vents near a partially collapsed Giant water-gate and houses approximately eight hundred individuals.

Na’wasua sea-elves are the locathah’s primary Kin contact. The relationship is trading partners, not allies — the Na’wasua provide worked metal (which locathah cannot smelt underwater) and surface-world goods in exchange for coral, deep-water pearls, thermal-vent minerals, and locathah navigational knowledge of the deep trenches. The Na’wasua consider locathah honest but uncurious — locathah have no interest in the surface world, in Kin politics, or in the Dómnathar threat, and their conversation rarely extends beyond trade, weather, and current patterns.

Halfling fishing communities of the Deepwater Marches occasionally encounter locathah in the shallows during spawning season (locathah spawn in warm shallow water, the one time they venture near the surface). These encounters are almost always peaceful — locathah ignore surface-dwellers during spawning, and halflings have learned that the appearance of locathah in the shallows means the deep currents are warm, which means good fishing.

Locathah have no relationship with the Dómnathar and appear to be unaware of the conflict that defines Kin politics. Their communities are deep enough to be below the reach of most surface threats, and they have no Kin-sense to be disrupted by False Silence. This immunity to the Dómnathar’s primary weapon has led some Eruskan scholars to speculate (probably incorrectly) that locathah could serve as scouts in underwater anti-Dómnathar operations.

### Lore

**DC 10 (Knowledge [local]):** Locathah are fish-like humanoids of the deep Apelian Sea. They are peaceful traders who use longspears and crossbows. They cannot survive long out of water.

**DC 15:** Locathah build settlements around Giant-era submerged ruins and geothermal vents. Na’wasua sea-elves trade with them for deep-water pearls and minerals. Locathah patrols surround intruders in three-dimensional formations that are difficult to counter without underwater combat experience.

**DC 20:** Locathah register as cool, neutral wild static on Kin-sense — easy to overlook in deep water. Their largest settlement, Ven-ko-rath, houses approximately eight hundred around a Giant water-gate. They lack Kin-sense entirely and are immune to False Silence, a fact that has attracted scholarly interest in their potential utility against the Dómnathar.

# MAERO (BRUTE)

The Kovaka call them *te tangata mohoao* — the wild people — but there is nothing of a person in what steps out of the tree-line. It is eight feet of matted hair and raw-boned muscle, its arms too long for its body, its hands thick-fingered and blunt as mallets. The face is wrong in the particular way that all Brute faces are wrong: close enough to Kin to trigger recognition, far enough from Kin to trigger revulsion. It smells of rotting bark and swamp-water and something chemical beneath both — the faint, sour reek that every Dómnathar product carries if you know what to look for. The maero watches you from the forest edge with dull, unblinking eyes, and then it reaches up and tears a branch the thickness of your thigh from the nearest tree as casually as you would pluck a flower.

**Large Giant**

