| **Advancement** | 3–4 HD (Small) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +3 |

### Combat

Magmin are not tacticians. They engage in melee immediately, slamming into opponents with incandescent fists. Their primary threat is not their damage output but their combustion and melt weapons abilities — anything flammable that touches a magmin ignites, and metal weapons that strike it risk melting. Fighting a magmin in close quarters is a war of attrition that destroys equipment faster than it destroys the magmin.

### Special Abilities

**Combustion (Ex):** Any creature hit by a magmin’s slam must succeed on a DC 12 Reflex save or catch fire. Burning creatures take 1d6 fire damage per round until the fire is extinguished (full-round action, DC 15 Reflex). The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Fiery Aura (Ex):** A magmin radiates intense heat. Any creature within 5 feet takes 1 point of fire damage per round (no save). Flammable materials within 5 feet ignite automatically.

**Melt Weapons (Ex):** Any metal weapon that strikes a magmin must succeed on a DC 12 Fortitude save or melt (becoming useless). Magic weapons apply their enhancement bonus to this save. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Fire Resonance (Su):** A magmin registers on Kin-sense as a small, bright point of pure fire-resonance — warm and uncomplicated, without malice or deception. Rarozhki dwarves describe it as “a candle-flame that walks.” The resonance is detectable at 30 feet and is unmistakable — there is nothing else in Oreka that reads as pure, unalloyed elemental fire at this scale. The warmth it radiates on Kin-sense is actually pleasant at distances beyond 20 feet, which is part of why magmin are so dangerous — they feel welcoming until they are close enough to ignite you.

### Society

Magmin are living fragments of elemental fire given humanoid form — not summoned, not created, but spontaneously generated where volcanic activity intersects with elemental energy. They are simple creatures (Int 8) that exist to burn, explore, and return to magma when cold or tired. They have no culture, no social structure, and no agenda beyond curiosity and the desire to remain warm.

Rarozhki dwarves have learned to coexist with magmin the way one coexists with any natural hazard. Forge-halls near active fissures maintain firebreaks, stone-only construction (no timber within a hundred yards of a known magmin emergence point), and water-reserves for emergency cooling. Individual Rarozhki smiths occasionally develop working relationships with specific magmin — the creatures’ ability to maintain extreme temperatures in forge environments is genuinely useful, and a magmin that has been bribed with obsidian and kept warm is a surprisingly cooperative (if hazardous) forge-companion.

Orean humans of the Giant’s Teeth foothills consider magmin to be minor fire-spirits and leave offerings of polished stone at known emergence points to discourage the creatures from wandering into settlements.

### Lore

**DC 13 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Magmin are Small fire elementals that ignite anything they touch. Their slam attacks set creatures on fire, and metal weapons that strike them may melt. They are immune to fire and vulnerable to cold.

**DC 18:** Magmin radiate a fiery aura that damages creatures within 5 feet. They are spontaneously generated near volcanic activity. Rarozhki dwarves occasionally employ them as forge-assistants.

**DC 23:** Magmin resonance reads as pure, uncomplicated fire on Kin-sense — deceptively welcoming at a distance. Their generation is tied to the intersection of volcanic activity and elemental energy; increases in magmin population signal rising subterranean temperatures.

# MAMLAMBO

The river crossing has been safe for a decade. The Warg packs ford here every season and the Mytroan riders use it as a watering-point on the steppe-circuit. Then the horses stopped drinking. The Wargs crossed upstream, three miles out of their way, and when asked why, the pack-leader said only: “The river has teeth now.” You crouch at the bank and the water looks normal — brown, shallow, running smooth over gravel. You cannot see what is lying on the bottom, because the thing on the bottom has been lying there for weeks, and it has learned what the riverbed looks like, and it is looking back at you.

**Huge Magical Beast (Aquatic)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Huge Magical Beast (Aquatic) |
| **Hit Dice** | 10d10+50 (105 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +2 |
| **Speed** | 20 ft. (4 squares), swim 40 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 21 (–2 size, +2 Dex, +11 natural), touch 10, flat-footed 19 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +10/+26 |
| **Attack** | Bite +16 melee (2d6+8 plus brain drain) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +16 melee (2d6+8 plus brain drain) and tail slap +11 melee (2d6+4) |
| **Space/Reach** | 15 ft./10 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Brain drain, improved grab, swallow whole |
| **Special Qualities** | Amphibious, darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, river camouflage, scent, elemental resonance (corrupted water) |
| **Saves** | Fort +12, Ref +9, Will +5 |
| **Abilities** | Str 27, Dex 14, Con 20, Int 3, Wis 14, Cha 7 |
| **Skills** | Hide +4 (+16 in riverbed), Listen +8, Spot +8, Swim +16 |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Improved Natural Attack (bite), Power Attack, Stealthy |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) — corrupted; stagnant, hungry, the patience of water that has forgotten how to flow |
| **Environment** | River-Steppe Border (the wide, slow-moving river crossings where the Great River’s tributaries meet the Eternal Steppe — the fording-points, gravel shallows, and seasonal flood-pools used by steppe herds and Mytroan caravans) |
| **Organization** | Solitary |
| **Challenge Rating** | 8 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always neutral evil |
| **Advancement** | 11–15 HD (Huge); 16–20 HD (Gargantuan) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A mamlambo is a patient, ambush-only predator. It lies on the riverbed, perfectly camouflaged, for days or weeks at a time, waiting for creatures to enter the water. When a target wades in — a horse drinking, a rider fording, a herder washing — the mamlambo lunges upward, bites, grabs, and drags the victim underwater. Once submerged, it uses its brain drain ability while holding the victim in its jaws, then swallows the remains.

A mamlambo never fights on land if it can avoid it. If attacked on shore, it retreats to the river immediately. It does not pursue targets onto dry ground. It does not need to — it is patient enough to wait for the next creature that enters the water.

### Special Abilities

**Brain Drain (Su):** A creature bitten by a mamlambo must succeed on a DC 20 Fortitude save or take 1d4 Intelligence damage as the mamlambo’s bite dissolves and absorbs neural tissue. A creature reduced to Intelligence 0 by this ability dies. The corpse’s face appears smooth and featureless — the mamlambo consumes the brain and face-tissue through its bite. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Improved Grab (Ex):** Bite attack. A mamlambo that successfully grapples pulls the target underwater on the following round (if in or adjacent to water).

**Swallow Whole (Ex):** A mamlambo can swallow a grabbed Medium or smaller creature with a successful grapple check. A swallowed creature takes 2d6 acid damage plus 1d4 Intelligence damage per round. A swallowed creature can cut its way out with a light slashing weapon by dealing 15 damage to the mamlambo’s interior (AC 15). The mamlambo’s gullet can hold 1 Medium, 2 Small, or 4 Tiny creatures.

**River Camouflage (Ex):** A mamlambo lying motionless on a riverbed receives a +12 racial bonus on Hide checks in water. Its scales shift colour to match the local river substrate — gravel, mud, sand, or stone. Detecting a submerged, motionless mamlambo requires a DC 26 Spot check.

**Corrupted Water Resonance (Su):** A mamlambo registers on Kin-sense as a corrupted water-signature — stagnant, thick, and predatory. The resonance is detectable at 60 feet, but in flowing river water the ambient water-resonance partially masks the signal (DC 18 to detect in moving water; DC 12 in still pools). Wargs — through the Harmony rather than Kin-sense — detect mamlambo more reliably than Kin do. A Warg pack that senses a mamlambo will refuse the crossing and communicate the danger to any allied Kin or goblins.

### Society

Mamlambo are solitary river-predators of the steppe-river border — Huge, serpentine, and terrifyingly patient ambush hunters that claim river crossings as hunting-grounds. They are among the most feared natural predators of the Eternal Steppe’s river margins, not because of their raw power (there are more powerful aquatic creatures in Oreka) but because of their method: the brain drain leaves corpses without faces or brains, which is deeply disturbing to every Kin culture and produces fear disproportionate to the creature’s actual danger.

Warg packs take mamlambo more seriously than almost any other natural predator. The Harmony gives Wargs reliable detection of mamlambo presence, and Warg territorial knowledge includes detailed maps of which crossings are safe and which are claimed. A Warg pack that discovers a mamlambo at a previously-safe crossing communicates this information to every other pack in the region within days — the Warg intelligence network is faster and more reliable than any Kin communication system for this specific threat.

Mytroan steppe-riders rely on Warg intelligence for mamlambo avoidance. The Mytroan-Warg relationship, while complex politically, is unambiguous on this point: if the Wargs say a crossing has teeth, the Mytroans go around. Mytroan caravans carry “crossing-stones” — small river-pebbles enchanted by hedge-wise women to glow faintly warm when a corrupted water-signature is within 100 feet. The enchantment is unreliable (works approximately 60% of the time), but it provides a degree of reassurance at unfamiliar fords.

Eruskan river-traders encounter mamlambo only at the steppe-river border, where the Great River’s tributaries run wide and slow. The Eruskan response to a confirmed mamlambo is practical: hire Mytroan riders and Warg scouts to locate the creature, then use coordinated ranged attacks from the bank to drive it downstream into territory where it is someone else’s problem.

### Lore

**DC 18 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Mamlambo are Huge river-serpents that lie camouflaged on riverbeds and ambush wading creatures. Their bite drains Intelligence and consumes the victim’s face and brain. They do not fight on land.

**DC 23:** A mamlambo’s Hide bonus while submerged is extraordinary (+16 in riverbed). Warg packs detect them more reliably than Kin through the Harmony and share crossing-intelligence across the steppe. Mytroan “crossing-stones” glow near corrupted water-resonance but are unreliable.

**DC 28:** Mamlambo resonance reads as corrupted water — stagnant and predatory — partially masked by flowing water (DC 18 to detect). A mamlambo claims a single crossing and never leaves it. The faceless corpses left by brain drain have produced deep cultural horror across all steppe cultures.

# MANANANGGAL

You find the lower half first. It is standing upright in a Dómnathar-ruined basement, legs together, trunk severed cleanly at the waist, and it is *warm*. Blood pools slowly at the separation point but does not spill — as though the body is waiting for something to return. The cellar smells of vinegar and old blood and the particular sterile absence of a place where Kin-sense dies. You hear wings above you — heavy, wet, membranous wings — and something laughs in the dark with a voice that used to be a woman’s.

**Medium Undead**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Undead |
| **Hit Dice** | 6d12 (39 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +3 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares) (whole form), fly 40 ft. (good) (separated upper half) |
| **Armor Class** | 18 (+3 Dex, +5 natural), touch 13, flat-footed 15 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +3/+6 |
| **Attack** | Tongue +6 melee touch (1d4 plus blood drain) or claw +6 melee (1d6+3) |
| **Full Attack** | Tongue +6 melee touch (1d4 plus blood drain) and 2 claws +4 melee (1d6+1) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. (tongue 10 ft.) |
| **Special Attacks** | Blood drain, horrifying visage |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., undead traits, separation, vulnerability (body destruction), damage reduction 5/slashing, fast healing 2, light sensitivity, elemental resonance (undead/silence breach) |
| **Saves** | Fort +2, Ref +5, Will +7 |
| **Abilities** | Str 16, Dex 17, Con —, Int 12, Wis 14, Cha 16 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +10 (7 ranks), Hide +10 (7 ranks), Listen +9 (7 ranks), Move Silently +10 (7 ranks), Spot +9 (7 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Dodge, Mobility, Multiattack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — undead, Silence Breach-origin |
| **Environment** | Silence Breach Zones (the Kin-sense dead zones near Dómnathar surface-breach points — particularly in the Gatefall Reach and the outer Kinsweave, where the residual metaphysical damage of the Deceivers’ War entry-point creates conditions that sustain this specific form of undead) |
| **Organization** | Solitary |
| **Challenge Rating** | 5 |
| **Treasure** | Standard |
| **Alignment** | Always chaotic evil |
| **Advancement** | 7–10 HD (Medium) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A manananggal hunts at night. Before sunset, it separates — the upper half detaching at the waist and sprouting bat-like wings — and takes flight, leaving the lower half hidden in a secure location. The flying upper body hunts sleeping or isolated victims, using its elongated, tubular tongue to drain blood through windows, tent-flaps, or other openings. It prefers to feed without waking its victim (Hide +10, Move Silently +10).

If discovered, the manananggal uses its horrifying visage to panic opponents, then attacks with claws and tongue. It retreats toward its lower half if reduced below 15 hit points — it must rejoin before dawn or suffer destruction.

### Special Abilities

**Separation (Su):** At dusk, a manananggal can separate its body at the waist as a full-round action. The upper half gains a fly speed of 40 ft. (good) and retains all combat abilities. The lower half is inert, helpless, and has AC 5. The upper half must rejoin the lower half before sunrise or be destroyed (see Vulnerability). While separated, the manananggal can sense the direction and distance to its lower half at any range.

**Blood Drain (Ex):** A manananggal that hits with its tongue attack attaches (automatic grapple, using tongue). Each round it remains attached, it drains blood, dealing 1d4 Constitution damage. A sleeping victim must succeed on a DC 15 Listen check to wake while being drained.

**Horrifying Visage (Su):** Any creature that sees a separated manananggal (the flying upper half with trailing viscera) must succeed on a DC 16 Will save or be frightened for 1d4 rounds. Creatures that succeed are shaken for 1 round. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Vulnerability (Body Destruction) (Ex):** If the manananggal’s lower half is found and destroyed (burned, doused in vinegar then salt, or consecrated), the upper half is immediately and permanently destroyed regardless of its current hit points. If the upper half fails to rejoin the lower half before sunrise, both halves are destroyed. These are the only reliable methods of permanent destruction — a manananggal reduced to 0 hp by normal combat reforms from its lower half in 1d4 nights unless the lower half is also destroyed.

**Light Sensitivity (Ex):** A manananggal in sunlight takes a –2 penalty on attack rolls and checks. Direct sunlight forces the upper half to rejoin the lower half immediately.

**Silence Breach Resonance (Su):** A manananggal registers on Kin-sense as undead — distorted, agonising — but with the specific character of Silence Breach undead: the signature carries a faint echo of Dómnathar void-silence, as though the creature rose in a place where the boundary between Oreka and the Abyss was thin. Detection at 60 feet (DC 14). The resonance intensifies when the creature is separated — the upper half’s signature is stronger and more disturbing than the whole form’s.

### Society

Manananggal are Silence Breach undead — a specific category of undead that arise only in areas where the metaphysical damage from the Dómnathar’s entry into Oreka has weakened the boundary between life and death. They are not Dómnathar creations (the Dómnathar do not create undead — their aesthetic is flesh-warping, not necromancy), but they are consequences of the Dómnathar presence.

A manananggal was always a living person — typically a woman — who died of violence in a Silence Breach zone and rose as this specific form of undead due to the corrupted metaphysical conditions. The transformation preserves intelligence and memory but inverts the personality: a kind woman becomes a cruel predator, a shy woman becomes a brazen hunter.

Hasura border-scouts in the Gatefall Reach consider manananggal one of the Breach’s signature threats. The Hasura anti-manananggal protocol is specific: find the lower half before dawn. Hasura scouts patrol known Breach zones at dusk, watching for the separation-flight, then triangulate the direction of the lower half from the upper half’s flight-path. Destroying the lower half (vinegar, salt, fire) permanently eliminates the creature. The Hasura maintain stocks of vinegar at every border-post specifically for this purpose.

Pasua ground-elves share the Hasura protocols. Eruskan communities near the Kinsweave Breach zones have adopted a simpler approach: garlic, salt, and thorn-vine barriers around windows and doorways at night (the tongue cannot penetrate thorn-vine, and garlic’s strong scent masks the smell of sleeping victims).

### Lore

**DC 15 (Knowledge [religion]):** Manananggal are undead that split at the waist — the upper half flies and hunts, the lower half hides. They drain blood with an elongated tongue and must rejoin before dawn. Destroying the lower half destroys the creature permanently.

**DC 20:** Manananggal arise only in Silence Breach zones. Vinegar and salt applied to the lower half prevent the upper half from reattaching. Hasura border-scouts patrol Breach zones at dusk specifically to intercept the separation-flight and locate the lower half.

**DC 25:** Manananggal carry a unique resonance — undead signature laced with Dómnathar void-echo, marking their origin in areas of metaphysical breach damage. They are not Dómnathar creations but consequences of the Dómnathar presence. The upper half’s resonance is stronger than the whole form’s — a detection advantage for Kin hunting the separated creature.

# MANTICORE

The thing on the ridge has the body of a lion, the face of a man, and a tail bristling with spines the length of crossbow bolts. It has been watching your party for the better part of an hour with the patient, calculating intelligence of a predator that understands geometry. It is not attacking because the range is wrong and it knows the range is wrong. When you cross the open ground between the tree-line and the ridge — that killing-ground of bare earth and low scrub where there is nothing to hide behind — it will fire. It can fire six volleys before you close.

**Large Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 6d10+24 (57 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +2 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), fly 50 ft. (clumsy) |
| **Armor Class** | 17 (–1 size, +2 Dex, +6 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 15 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +6/+15 |
| **Attack** | Claw +10 melee (2d4+5) or tail spike +8 ranged (1d8+2/19–20) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 claws +10 melee (2d4+5) and bite +8 melee (1d8+2); or 6 tail spikes +8 ranged (1d8+2/19–20) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Tail spikes |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, scent, elemental resonance (earth-fire) |
| **Saves** | Fort +9, Ref +7, Will +3 |
| **Abilities** | Str 20, Dex 15, Con 19, Int 7, Wis 12, Cha 9 |
| **Skills** | Listen +5, Spot +9, Survival +3 |
| **Feats** | Flyby Attack, Multiattack, Weapon Focus (tail spike) |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) / Lady of Fire (Fire) — predatory; the dry heat of sun-baked stone, the patience of rock that waits to fall |
| **Environment** | Warm Hills and Marshes (the low, scrub-covered hills between the Eternal Steppe and the Scorchspires — the transitional terrain where grassland gives way to volcanic foothills; secondary populations along the Tidebloom Reach’s drier margins) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or pride (3–6) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 5 |
| **Treasure** | Standard |
| **Alignment** | Usually lawful evil |
| **Advancement** | 7–12 HD (Large); 13–18 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +3 |

### Combat

Manticores are ranged-dominant predators. They prefer to fire tail spikes from elevated positions — ridgelines, cliff-edges, or the air — and avoid melee until the target is weakened. A manticore can fire 6 spikes per round (180 ft. range increment), giving it an effective engagement range that exceeds most ranged weapons. In a pride, manticores fire from multiple angles to deny cover.

A manticore forced into melee fights competently with claws and bite, but it retreats to range at the first opportunity, using Flyby Attack to strafe then climb. Manticores are smart enough (Int 7) to target spellcasters first and to recognise that armoured targets are less efficient than unarmoured ones.

### Special Abilities

**Tail Spikes (Ex):** A manticore’s tail can fire up to 6 spikes per round as a full-attack action (range increment 180 ft., 1d8+2/19–20). The tail can fire 24 spikes per day, regrowing them at a rate of 1 per hour.

**Earth-Fire Resonance (Su):** A manticore registers on Kin-sense as a dry, hot earth-fire signature — the warmth of sun-baked stone. Detectable at 60 feet. The resonance is not inherently threatening (it reads as “large warm predator,” similar to a lion or large cat), which makes manticores harder to distinguish from non-magical predators at a distance. A DC 14 Kin-sense check at 60 feet identifies the resonance as magical-beast-grade rather than animal-grade.

### Society

Manticores are intelligent enough to negotiate and cruel enough to make negotiation unprofitable. They hunt the transitional hills between the steppe and the Scorchspires, claiming territories that overlap with Mytroan caravan routes and Taraf-Imro grazing-land. A manticore pride that establishes itself on a trade-route will demand tribute — livestock, prisoners, or treasure — in exchange for allowing caravans to pass. Prides that receive tribute reliably honour the agreement; prides that do not receive it attack without warning.

Mytroan steppe-riders consider manticore prides a serious threat to caravan logistics. The Mytroan response is pragmatic: pay the tribute if the route is essential, detour if it is not, and hire hunters to eliminate the pride if the tribute demands become unsustainable. Taraf-Imro warriors regard manticore hunts as prestige events — a Taraf-Imro fighter who has taken a manticore carries the tail-spikes as trophies.

### Lore

**DC 15 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Manticores are Large winged predators with a human face and spike-throwing tail. They can fire 6 spikes per round at 180 ft. range. They are intelligent enough to negotiate and demand tribute.

**DC 20:** Manticore prides establish territory on caravan routes and demand payment for passage. They target spellcasters first. Mytroan riders pay tribute to essential-route prides; Taraf-Imro warriors hunt them for prestige.

**DC 25:** Manticore earth-fire resonance mimics that of large natural predators, making them difficult to distinguish at range. Their spikes regrow at 1 per hour (24/day maximum). They are lawful evil — prides that accept tribute honour agreements consistently.

# MAPINGUARI

The jungle went quiet three days ago. Not the quiet of nightfall or the quiet of a predator passing through — the quiet of everything leaving. The birds are gone. The monkeys are gone. The insects are muted. Something enormous is moving through the Deepwater canopy, and the stench reached you before the sound did: a rotting, animal musk so powerful it burns the back of your throat. You see it through the trees — bipedal, shaggy, taller than a man on horseback, with one milky eye set in the centre of its forehead and a mouth that opens vertically in its belly. It moves slowly, deliberately, and the undergrowth dies where it walks.

**Large Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 9d10+45 (94 hp) |
| **Initiative** | –1 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 20 (–1 size, –1 Dex, +12 natural), touch 8, flat-footed 20 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +9/+19 |
| **Attack** | Claw +15 melee (2d6+6) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 claws +15 melee (2d6+6) and belly bite +13 melee (1d8+3 plus disease) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./10 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Belly bite, disease, stench |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., damage reduction 5/slashing, low-light vision, scent, thick hide, blight aura, elemental resonance (earth-corrupted) |
| **Saves** | Fort +11, Ref +5, Will +5 |
| **Abilities** | Str 23, Dex 8, Con 20, Int 4, Wis 14, Cha 7 |
| **Skills** | Listen +8, Spot +8, Survival +8 |
| **Feats** | Cleave, Improved Natural Attack (claw), Multiattack, Power Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) — corrupted; ancient, sick, the resonance of soil that has turned toxic |
| **Environment** | Deepwater Marches (the dense interior jungle of the Marches — the oldest-growth, most inaccessible regions where goblin settlements are sparse and the canopy blocks all sunlight at ground level) |
| **Organization** | Solitary |
| **Challenge Rating** | 7 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always neutral |
| **Advancement** | 10–14 HD (Large); 15–18 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A mapinguari does not ambush — it cannot. Its stench and blight aura announce its presence long before visual contact. It simply walks toward prey with the unstoppable patience of something too durable to need strategy. In combat, it attacks with both claws and its belly mouth simultaneously. The belly bite delivers a wasting disease. The stench sickens creatures within 30 feet, and the blight aura kills plant-life in its wake, leaving a trail of dead undergrowth that marks its path for days.

A mapinguari fights until killed or until its target escapes beyond its tracking ability (Survival +8). It does not retreat. Its thick hide and damage reduction make it extraordinarily durable in melee.

### Special Abilities

**Belly Bite (Ex):** A mapinguari’s vertical belly-mouth can bite any creature it is adjacent to as a secondary natural attack. The belly bite deals 1d8+3 damage and delivers disease (see below).

**Disease (Ex):** Jungle rot — belly bite; Fortitude DC 19; incubation 1d3 days; damage 1d4 Str and 1d4 Con. The disease causes progressive muscle wasting and fever. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Stench (Ex):** A mapinguari exudes a nauseating musk. All living creatures within 30 feet must succeed on a DC 19 Fortitude save or be sickened for 1d6+4 minutes. A creature that successfully saves is immune to that mapinguari’s stench for 24 hours. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Blight Aura (Su):** Plant life within 10 feet of a mapinguari withers and dies. Normal plants are killed instantly; Plant creatures take 1d6 damage per round (no save). This effect leaves a visible trail of dead vegetation that persists for 1d4 weeks — experienced Deepwater trackers can follow a mapinguari’s path long after the creature has passed.

**Thick Hide (Ex):** A mapinguari’s hide is extraordinarily tough. It has DR 5/slashing and +12 natural armour. Piercing weapons (arrows, spears) are largely ineffective against the matted fur and dense subcutaneous layer.

**Corrupted Earth Resonance (Su):** A mapinguari registers on Kin-sense as a deep, sick earth-signature — the resonance of contaminated soil, of ground that produces poison instead of growth. Detectable at 90 feet (the resonance is powerful but unpleasant). Goblin communities of the Deepwater Marches, though lacking Kin-sense, detect mapinguari by their stench and blight trail and give them wide berth.

### Society

Mapinguari are solitary jungle-predators of the deep Deepwater Marches — ancient, slow, and implacable. They are believed to be remnants of a pre-War megafauna population that was corrupted by exposure to Dómnathar chemical residue in the soil after the Lost Third’s passage through the region. Whether this theory is correct or whether mapinguari have always existed in the deep jungle is debated by Eruskan naturalists.

Free goblin communities of the Deepwater Marches treat mapinguari as walking natural disasters. When a mapinguari enters a clan’s territory (detectable days in advance by the blight trail and fleeing wildlife), the entire community relocates until the creature passes. Goblin scouts track mapinguari movements and share information between clans through the same network that communicates Leviathan-shard locations and krasue sightings.

Halfling fishing-communities near the Marches’ coast have little direct contact with mapinguari (the creatures rarely approach the coastline), but halfling folklore includes detailed warnings about “the walking blight” passed down from the earliest post-War settlements.

### Lore

**DC 17 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Mapinguari are Large, shaggy jungle predators with a single eye, a belly mouth, and an overwhelming stench. They are nearly impervious to piercing weapons and kill plant-life in their wake.

**DC 22:** The belly bite delivers a wasting disease (Fort DC 19). The stench sickens all creatures within 30 feet. The blight aura leaves a trail of dead vegetation that lasts weeks. Slashing weapons bypass the damage reduction.

**DC 27:** Mapinguari may be pre-War megafauna corrupted by Dómnathar chemical residue from the Lost Third’s passage. Their corrupted earth-resonance is detectable at 90 feet. Goblin communities evacuate entire territories when a mapinguari approaches, tracking its blight trail through inter-clan networks.

# MAZZIKIN

You cannot see them. That is the point — mazzikin are invisible, bodiless, and everywhere, and the only evidence of their presence is the mischief. Your bootlaces are tied together. Your waterskin is empty though you filled it an hour ago. The goblin trader’s pack has been rearranged so that the heavy items are on top and the fragile items are on the bottom. From somewhere near the ceiling, something giggles — a high, musical laugh that sounds like a child who has never been told no.

**Tiny Fey**

