| **Environment** | Scorchspire Lowlands (the transitional terrain between the Scorchspires’ volcanic slopes and the settled lowlands of Taraf-Imro territory — the scrubland, ash-meadows, and low thorn-forests where volcanic soil meets steppe grass) |
| **Organization** | Solitary |
| **Challenge Rating** | 8 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always neutral |
| **Advancement** | 11–15 HD (Large); 16–20 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A mngwa is a shadow-hunting apex predator. It uses shadow step to close instantly with prey from dim-light concealment, pounces, and rakes — the full-attack sequence (bite + 2 claws + 2 rakes from pounce) in a single devastating round. Targets that survive the initial pounce are grappled and savaged.

Against groups, a mngwa uses shadow form to become incorporeal, passes through the party, and pounces the most isolated target (typically the rearguard). It then shadow-steps back into darkness before the group can respond. A mngwa hunts methodically, picking off stragglers one at a time.

### Special Abilities

**Pounce (Ex):** A mngwa can make a full attack at the end of a charge, including rake attacks.

**Rake (Ex):** 2 rakes at +13 melee, 1d8+3 each, on any round where the mngwa pounces or maintains a grapple.

**Shadow Step (Su):** As a move action, a mngwa can teleport up to 60 feet between two areas of dim light or darkness. Both the origin and destination must be in dim light or darker. This ability leaves no trace and makes no sound.

**Shadow Form (Su):** As a standard action, a mngwa can become incorporeal for up to 3 rounds per encounter. While incorporeal, it gains the incorporeal subtype (immune to non-magical and non-force attacks, can pass through solid objects). It cannot attack while incorporeal. Exiting shadow form is a free action.

**Shadow-Earth Resonance (Su):** A mngwa registers on Kin-sense as a heavy earth-signature darkened by something cold and lightless — not Dómnathar void, not corruption, but shadow-earth: the resonance of stone in places where sunlight has never reached. Detectable at 60 feet, but in dim light the resonance diffuses, becoming directionally ambiguous (DC 18 to pinpoint). Taraf-Imro herders describe it as “the ground getting heavier under your feet.”

### Society

Mngwa are solitary nocturnal predators of the Scorchspire lowlands — enormous grey cats that exist at the intersection of physical and shadow, hunting with abilities that seem to defy natural law. They are not supernatural in origin (they are magical beasts, not outsiders), but their shadow abilities are so alien to normal predator behaviour that the Taraf-Imro have classified them as something outside the usual animal hierarchy.

Taraf-Imro herder-warriors maintain mngwa-protocols that are among the most respected combat traditions in their culture. The protocols: never herd cattle after dark in known mngwa territory; maintain bright fires at all herd-camps (mngwa cannot shadow-step in bright light); if a mngwa is heard or sensed, form a tight circle and keep all torches lit until dawn. Killing a mngwa is considered among the greatest feats a Taraf-Imro warrior can achieve — the creature’s hide is proof of extraordinary skill, and a warrior who wears it earns the title *kisigino cha kivuli* (“shadow’s bane”).

Rarozhki dwarves at the Scorchspire’s lower elevations occasionally encounter mngwa and consider them proof that the volcanic lowlands produce creatures that are fundamentally stranger than anything in the mountains above.

### Lore

**DC 18 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Mngwa are Large grey cats that can teleport between shadows and become incorporeal. They pounce with devastating full-attacks. Bright light prevents their shadow-step ability.

**DC 23:** Shadow step works between any two areas of dim light within 60 feet. Shadow form lasts up to 3 rounds per encounter and makes the mngwa immune to physical attacks. Taraf-Imro herder-warriors maintain fire-based defensive protocols.

**DC 28:** The mngwa’s shadow-earth resonance becomes directionally ambiguous in dim light (DC 18 to pinpoint). They are magical beasts, not outsiders — their shadow abilities are biological rather than planar. Killing one earns the Taraf-Imro title *kisigino cha kivuli*.

# MOHRG

The ruin smelled wrong before you entered it — a sickly-sweet rot that no amount of wind would carry away, layered over the cold-stone scent of the Kinsweave’s abandoned border-settlements. Inside, the bodies are arranged. Not piled, not scattered — *arranged*, in a manner that suggests intelligence, purpose, and a deeply unpleasant sense of humour. In the centre of the arrangement, the thing that made it stands upright: a skeleton wrapped in its own entrails, its ribcage open like a birdcage, and from the hollow of its gut, a purple, writhing tongue extends and tastes the air between you.

**Medium Undead**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Undead |
| **Hit Dice** | 14d12 (91 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +9 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 23 (+5 Dex, +8 natural), touch 15, flat-footed 18 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +7/+12 |
| **Attack** | Slam +12 melee (1d6+7) or tongue +12 melee touch (paralysis) |
| **Full Attack** | Slam +12 melee (1d6+7) and tongue +12 melee touch (paralysis) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Improved grab, paralyzing touch, create spawn |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., undead traits, +4 turn resistance, elemental resonance (undead-war) |
| **Saves** | Fort +4, Ref +9, Will +9 |
| **Abilities** | Str 21, Dex 21, Con —, Int 11, Wis 10, Cha 10 |
| **Skills** | Climb +13 (8 ranks), Hide +19 (14 ranks), Listen +11 (11 ranks), Move Silently +19 (14 ranks), Spot +15 (15 ranks), Swim +9 (4 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Dodge, Improved Initiative, Lightning Reflexes, Mobility, Spring Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — undead |
| **Environment** | Kinsweave Ruins (the abandoned border-settlements, burned villages, and War-era fortifications of the Kinsweave — the region where the northern Deceiver host’s passage left the densest concentration of unburied dead and corrupted ground) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or gang (2–4) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 8 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always chaotic evil |
| **Advancement** | 15–21 HD (Medium) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A mohrg is fast, intelligent, and driven by a compulsion to create more undead. It uses its exceptional Dexterity and Initiative to close range before opponents can react, targeting the most lightly-armoured creature with its paralyzing tongue. Once a target is paralyzed, the mohrg kills it — the corpse rises as a zombie under the mohrg’s control within 1d4 rounds.

Mohrgs use Spring Attack to paralyze-and-retreat, building a zombie horde between engagements. A mohrg that has accumulated zombies sends them forward as a screen while it circles behind the party to tongue-paralyze the spellcaster.

### Special Abilities

**Paralyzing Touch (Su):** A creature hit by the mohrg’s tongue attack must succeed on a DC 17 Fortitude save or be paralyzed for 1d4 minutes. The save DC is Charisma-based (includes +4 turn resistance synergy). *Remove paralysis* or similar magic ends the effect early.

**Create Spawn (Su):** Any humanoid killed by a mohrg rises as a zombie in 1d4 rounds. The zombie is under the mohrg’s control. A mohrg can control up to 14 HD of zombies at a time (equal to its own HD).

**Improved Grab (Ex):** Slam attack. A mohrg that grapples uses its tongue automatically each round.

**Undead War-Resonance (Su):** A mohrg registers on Kin-sense as a powerful, aggressive undead signature — distorted and agonising, with the specific character of War-era undead: rage, violence, and the echo of a death that was not peaceful. Detectable at 60 feet (no check required — mohrg resonance is strong enough to be unmistakable). The resonance intensifies in the presence of living Kin, as though the mohrg’s compulsion to create spawn has a metaphysical component.

### Society

Mohrg are the Kinsweave’s most dangerous undead — War-era remnants that arose from the unburied dead of the Deceivers’ War and have been creating zombie spawn for three hundred years. They are intelligent (Int 11), driven, and capable of basic tactical planning. A mohrg’s “territory” is defined by its zombie horde — the more zombies it controls, the larger the area it can dominate.

Kinsweave border-communities maintain standing bounties on mohrg destruction. The Vestri Stoneguard, whose patrols secure the Kinsweave’s northern border, consider mohrg-hunting a standard rotation duty — unpleasant, dangerous, and necessary. The tactical challenge is neutralising the zombie screen to reach the mohrg itself.

Eruskan scholars classify mohrg as “propagating undead” — undead whose primary threat is not individual combat power but exponential growth through spawn creation. An unchecked mohrg in a populated area produces a crisis within weeks.

### Lore

**DC 18 (Knowledge [religion]):** Mohrg are skeletal undead with a paralyzing tongue. They create zombie spawn from any humanoid they kill. They are fast, intelligent, and tactically sophisticated.

**DC 23:** The paralyzing tongue requires a DC 17 Fort save. Mohrg use Spring Attack to paralyze targets, then return to kill them after moving away. They can control 14 HD of zombies simultaneously.

**DC 28:** Mohrg are War-era undead concentrated in the Kinsweave — products of the mass death during the Deceivers’ War. Their undead resonance intensifies near living Kin. Vestri Stoneguard patrols consider mohrg-clearing a routine but essential border duty.

# MONSTROUS SPIDER

The web is not visible until you are in it. The silk is the colour of shadow and it clings to everything — armour, hair, skin — with an adhesive strength that is entirely out of proportion to its apparent fragility. Something moves at the edge of your torchlight. It has too many legs and too many eyes and it is larger than you want it to be.

**Medium Vermin**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Vermin |
| **Hit Dice** | 2d8+2 (11 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +3 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), climb 20 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 14 (+3 Dex, +1 natural), touch 13, flat-footed 11 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +1/+1 |
| **Attack** | Bite +4 melee (1d6 plus poison) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +4 melee (1d6 plus poison) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Poison, web |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., tremorsense 60 ft., vermin traits, warm static |
| **Saves** | Fort +4, Ref +3, Will +0 |
| **Abilities** | Str 11, Dex 17, Con 12, Int —, Wis 10, Cha 2 |
| **Skills** | Climb +11 (racial), Hide +7 (+11 in web), Spot +4 (racial) |
| **Feats** | Weapon FinesseB |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) — faint; the quiet attunement of small creatures that live in dark places close to stone |
| **Environment** | Any (monstrous spiders are found throughout Oreka — Great Forests, underground cave-systems, Giant ruins, Vestri mines, Dómnathar tunnel-fringes, and any enclosed environment where webs can be anchored; specific subspecies favour specific environments) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or colony (3–8) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 1 (Medium); 2 (Large); 4 (Huge); 7 (Gargantuan) |
| **Treasure** | 1/10th coins; 50% goods |
| **Alignment** | Always neutral |
| **Advancement** | 3–4 HD (Medium); 5–8 HD (Large); 9–14 HD (Huge); 15–20 HD (Gargantuan) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

The stat block above represents a Medium monstrous spider. Larger specimens exist at every size category — Large monstrous spiders (CR 2) haunt the Great Forests’ understory, Huge specimens (CR 4) dominate cave-systems and deep forest, and Gargantuan monstrous spiders (CR 7) are apex predators of the deepest tunnels.

### Combat

Monstrous spiders are ambush predators that fight from webs. A web-spinner constructs a trap-web across a passage or between trees, then waits at the edge for vibrations indicating prey. Once a creature is entangled, the spider moves in to bite and inject venom. Hunting spiders (those without webs) stalk prey using tremorsense and pounce from concealment.

### Special Abilities

**Poison (Ex):** Bite; Fortitude DC 12 (Medium); initial and secondary damage 1d3 Str. The save DC is Constitution-based. Larger specimens have proportionally higher DCs and damage (Large DC 14, 1d4 Str; Huge DC 18, 1d6 Str; Gargantuan DC 22, 1d8 Str).

**Web (Ex):** Web-spinners can cast webs (range increment 10 ft., Escape Artist DC 12 or Strength DC 16 to escape). Webs have 6 hp per 5-ft. section, hardness 0, and are flammable.

**Warm Static (Su):** Monstrous spiders register on Kin-sense as warm static — faint, unreadable background noise, the signature of a non-sapient creature with minimal elemental awareness. Detectable only at close range (15 feet) and easily overlooked in environments with stronger ambient signatures. This makes them functionally invisible to Kin-sense in most natural environments — a significant advantage for an ambush predator.

### Society

Monstrous spiders are mindless predators (Int —), but their ubiquity across Oreka gives them outsized cultural presence. Every Kin culture has spider-traditions:

Pasua and Hasura forest-elves treat Huge and Gargantuan forest-spiders as territorial markers — a mega-spider’s web-territory is avoided the way a leshy’s domain is avoided. Pasua rangers can identify individual mega-spiders by web-pattern.

Vestri miners encounter monstrous spiders at every depth and consider them a routine hazard. Vestri mining-kit includes a short knife specifically designed for cutting web-silk.

Dómnathar tunnel-networks host monstrous spider populations that the Deceivers tolerate or cultivate — House Kethloryn (the spider-prophecy house) actively breeds Gargantuan specimens as tunnel-guardians and living web-barriers.

### Lore

**DC 11 (Knowledge [nature]):** Monstrous spiders are venomous predators found in every environment in Oreka. They range from Medium to Gargantuan. Web-spinners trap prey in adhesive webs; hunters stalk by tremorsense.

**DC 16:** Spider venom causes Strength damage. Webs are flammable (fire is the fastest counter-measure). Pasua rangers identify individual mega-spiders by web-pattern.

**DC 21:** House Kethloryn of the Dómnathar breeds Gargantuan spiders as tunnel-guardians. Monstrous spiders are functionally invisible to passive Kin-sense — their warm static is too faint to detect beyond 15 feet.

# MUD MENDERS

The riverbank is repairing itself. Where the spring flood tore a section away, leaving raw earth and exposed roots, something is working — dozens of small, wet, vaguely humanoid shapes made of river-mud and clay, moving with the busy purposefulness of ants. They are packing mud into the wound, weaving roots through the fill, and smoothing the surface with hands that are more suggestion than anatomy. One of them notices you watching. It stops, tilts its featureless head, and extends a hand that drips with silt — an offer to help, or a request that you not step on the work.

**Small Elemental (Water, Earth)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Small Elemental (Water, Earth) |
| **Hit Dice** | 4d8+8 (26 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +0 |
| **Speed** | 20 ft. (4 squares), swim 30 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 16 (+1 size, +0 Dex, +5 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 16 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +3/+0 |
| **Attack** | Slam +5 melee (1d4+1 plus mudslick) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 slams +5 melee (1d4+1 plus mudslick) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Mudslick |
| **Special Qualities** | Damage reduction 5/—, elemental traits, earth glide, mend terrain, vulnerability to fire, elemental resonance (water-earth gentle) |
| **Saves** | Fort +6, Ref +1, Will +2 |
| **Abilities** | Str 13, Dex 10, Con 14, Int 6, Wis 12, Cha 8 |
| **Skills** | Listen +5, Spot +5, Swim +9 |
| **Feats** | Toughness, Weapon Focus (slam) |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) / Lord of Stone (Earth) — constructive; the intersection of water and earth as building material, the quiet industry of riverbanks repairing themselves |
| **Environment** | Marshes and River Deltas (the Deepwater Marches’ mudflats, the Great River’s flood-plains, and the tidal estuaries where fresh water meets the Apelian — anywhere that river-mud accumulates in sufficient depth and elemental water-earth energy is concentrated) |
| **Organization** | Work-crew (3–8) or colony (9–20) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 3 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always neutral |
| **Advancement** | 5–8 HD (Small); 9–12 HD (Medium) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

Mud menders do not seek combat. They defend their work-sites if attacked, fighting with slow, deliberate slam attacks that coat targets in clinging mud. Their primary defensive strategy is mudslick — coating the ground around them in slippery mud that makes approach difficult — while they retreat toward the nearest body of water, where they dissolve into the mud and reform elsewhere.

### Special Abilities

**Mudslick (Ex):** A creature hit by a mud mender’s slam is coated in clinging mud. The target must succeed on a DC 14 Reflex save or be slowed (as the *slow* spell) for 1d4 rounds as the mud hardens and restricts movement. The save DC is Constitution-based. Additionally, the ground within 10 feet of a mud mender is always slippery (Balance DC 14 to avoid falling prone when moving through).

**Mend Terrain (Su):** Mud menders can repair damaged terrain — eroded riverbanks, collapsed levees, silted channels, damaged marsh-ecosystems — at a rate of 10 cubic feet per hour per mender. A work-crew of eight can rebuild a collapsed riverbank in a single night. This is not magical construction — it is elemental earth-water manipulation, packing and shaping natural materials with supernatural precision. The repaired terrain is indistinguishable from natural formation.

**Earth Glide (Ex):** A mud mender can move through mud, silt, and wet earth as easily as a fish moves through water. It can use this ability to disappear into a riverbank or mudflat in a single round.

**Water-Earth Resonance (Gentle) (Su):** Mud menders register on Kin-sense as a soft, warm water-earth signature — gentle and industrious, like feeling a garden grow. Detectable at 30 feet. The resonance is the most benign signature of any elemental in Oreka — Kin describe it as “comforting,” and halfling marsh-communities consider the presence of mud menders to be a sign of a healthy ecosystem.

### Society

Mud menders are the smallest and most benign elemental beings in Oreka — spontaneously-generated water-earth elementals that exist to repair and maintain the natural infrastructure of marshes, riverbanks, and tidal zones. They are not summoned, not created, and not controlled — they simply appear where the intersection of water and earth elemental energy is strong and the terrain needs mending.

Halfling communities of the Deepwater Marches and Tidebloom Reach consider mud menders essential partners in their wetland way of life. Halfling levee-engineers work alongside mud mender colonies, combining halfling architectural knowledge with the elementals’ supernatural ability to shape mud and clay. The relationship is not formal (mud menders are too simple for negotiation) but it is deeply functional — halflings provide the design, mud menders provide the labour, and the result is wetland infrastructure that is more durable than either could produce alone.

Eruskan river-communities along the Great River’s flood-plains value mud menders for the same reasons. Eruskan farmers consider a mud mender colony on their riverbank to be a blessing — the elementals repair flood-damage faster than human work-crews and do it for free.

Eruskan naturalists classify mud menders as “constructive elementals” — a rare category of elemental being that builds rather than destroys.

### Lore

**DC 13 (Knowledge [the planes]):** Mud menders are Small water-earth elementals that repair riverbanks, levees, and marsh terrain. They are not aggressive and fight only in self-defence. They dissolve into mud when threatened.

**DC 18:** Mud mender work-crews can rebuild a collapsed riverbank in a single night. Their mud-slick ability slows opponents in clinging mud. Halfling wetland-communities work alongside them as construction partners.

**DC 23:** Mud menders generate spontaneously where water-earth elemental energy is concentrated. Their gentle resonance is the most benign elemental signature in Oreka — halflings consider their presence a sign of ecosystem health. They can earth-glide through wet soil at full speed.

# MUMMY

The sarcophagus is not dwarven. It is Giant — carved from a single block of basalt in proportions that no Kin hands shaped, covered in rune-script that predates written Dwarven by millennia. The lid has been moved. From inside, the smell of preservation-resin and dust and something else — something dry and electric that makes the hair on your arms stand up. The thing that climbs out does not rush. It has been waiting for longer than your civilisation has existed, and it has the patience of stone. The wrappings are not cloth — they are strips of treated hide, each inscribed with runes that glow faintly in the dark. Its eyes are empty hollows that see you anyway.

**Medium Undead**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Undead |
| **Hit Dice** | 8d12 (52 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +0 |
| **Speed** | 20 ft. (4 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 20 (+0 Dex, +10 natural), touch 10, flat-footed 20 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +4/+11 |
| **Attack** | Slam +11 melee (1d6+10 plus mummy rot) |
| **Full Attack** | Slam +11 melee (1d6+10 plus mummy rot) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Despair, mummy rot |
| **Special Qualities** | Damage reduction 5/—, darkvision 60 ft., undead traits, vulnerability to fire, +4 turn resistance, elemental resonance (undead-giant) |
| **Saves** | Fort +2, Ref +2, Will +8 |
| **Abilities** | Str 24, Dex 10, Con —, Int 6, Wis 14, Cha 15 |
| **Skills** | Hide +7 (7 ranks), Listen +8 (8 ranks), Move Silently +7 (7 ranks), Spot +8 (8 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Great Fortitude, Toughness |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — undead; but the body was once Giant, and traces of the all-four-element resonance linger in the preservation-runes like an echo in a sealed room |
| **Environment** | Giant Tombs (the sealed burial-complexes and mausoleum-vaults of Giant-era cities throughout the Infinite Desert — the Sunken Thrones, the Dust-Vaults beneath Tharok’s Pillar, and the deep tomb-complexes of the Giant’s Teeth foothills) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, wardens (2–4), or tomb-guard (5–8) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 5 |
| **Treasure** | Standard |
| **Alignment** | Usually lawful evil |
| **Advancement** | 9–12 HD (Medium); 13–18 HD (Large) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +4 |

### Combat

A mummy is slow, powerful, and terrifying. It opens engagement with its despair ability — a supernatural aura of dread that paralyzes weaker-willed opponents — then closes and hammers with its slam. Every blow carries mummy rot, a wasting disease that defies normal healing. A mummy does not chase fleeing opponents beyond its tomb — it returns to its sarcophagus and waits.

### Special Abilities

**Despair (Su):** At the sight of a mummy, creatures within 60 feet must succeed on a DC 16 Will save or be paralyzed with fear for 1d4 rounds. Whether or not the save is successful, the creature is immune to that mummy’s despair for 24 hours. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Mummy Rot (Su):** Slam — supernatural disease; Fortitude DC 16; incubation 1 minute; damage 1d6 Con and 1d6 Cha. Unlike normal diseases, mummy rot continues until the victim reaches Constitution 0 (death) or the disease is removed. *Remove disease* does not cure mummy rot — it requires *remove curse* followed by *remove disease* (in that order). An afflicted creature that dies of mummy rot crumbles to dust and cannot be raised without *resurrection* or more powerful magic. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Undead-Giant Resonance (Su):** A mummy registers on Kin-sense as a distorted undead signature with a faint, fragmentary echo of Giant four-element resonance — the all-element harmony that the Giants once possessed, now frozen in the preservation-runes and slowly degrading. The effect is deeply unsettling: Kin describe it as “hearing the last note of a song that ended ten thousand years ago, played backwards.” Detectable at 60 feet (no check required). Pekakarlik pilgrims who encounter mummies in Giant tombs report that the resonance provokes grief as much as fear — these were once the greatest beings in Oreka, and their undead remnants are a desecration of what they were.

### Society

Mummies in Oreka are exclusively Giant-era undead — the preserved remains of Giant servants, retainers, and (rarely) Giants themselves, bound to their tombs by preservation-runes that were intended to honour the dead but instead trapped them between death and dissolution. They are not created through necromancy — they are the product of Giant funerary magic interacting with millennia of elemental decay.

Pekakarlik dwarves, whose ruin-pilgrimages frequently lead through Giant tombs, treat mummies with a mixture of reverence and caution. A mummy is not an enemy to a Pekakarlik — it is a desecrated sacred thing, a Giant-era tragedy that should be laid to rest. Pekakarlik tomb-teams carry consecrated oils and *remove curse* scrolls specifically for the purpose of releasing mummies from their binding — not destroying them, but freeing them. A Pekakarlik who destroys a mummy without attempting release first is considered to have acted dishonourably.

Eruskan tomb-scholars study mummy-wrappings for the rune-script they carry — these are among the oldest surviving examples of Giant written language, and a single mummy’s wrappings may contain historical information found nowhere else.

### Lore

**DC 15 (Knowledge [religion]):** Mummies are undead found in Giant tombs. Their slam carries mummy rot — a wasting disease that requires *remove curse* before *remove disease*. Their appearance causes paralysing dread. They are vulnerable to fire.

**DC 20:** Mummy rot kills if untreated and prevents resurrection below the *resurrection* spell level. Mummies have DR 5/— and +4 turn resistance. Pekakarlik tomb-teams carry consecrated oils to release mummies rather than destroy them.

**DC 25:** Oreka’s mummies are exclusively Giant-era — products of funerary magic, not necromancy. Their resonance carries a fragmentary echo of Giant four-element harmony. The rune-script on their wrappings is among the oldest surviving Giant writing — of immense scholarly value.

# MUSHUSSU

The ruin-gate is guarded. The guardian is not Giant — it is something the Giants made, or something that lived with the Giants and stayed after they were gone. It has the body of a scaled serpent, the forelegs of a lion, the hind-legs of an eagle, and a neck that arches upward like a crane’s, capped with a horned head whose eyes glow with a faint, steady amber light. It has been sitting in front of this gate for ten thousand years. The bones at its feet suggest that it takes its duties seriously.

**Large Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 10d10+40 (95 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +2 |
| **Speed** | 40 ft. (8 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 22 (–1 size, +2 Dex, +11 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 20 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +10/+20 |
| **Attack** | Bite +15 melee (2d6+6 plus venom) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +15 melee (2d6+6 plus venom) and 2 claws +13 melee (1d6+3) and tail slap +13 melee (1d8+3) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Breath weapon, poison, ruin-sentinel |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., damage reduction 5/magic, low-light vision, scent, spell resistance 18, elemental resonance (all four — fading) |
| **Saves** | Fort +11, Ref +9, Will +7 |
| **Abilities** | Str 23, Dex 14, Con 18, Int 6, Wis 14, Cha 12 |
| **Skills** | Listen +10 (8 ranks), Spot +10 (8 ranks), Survival +10 (8 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Improved Natural Attack (bite), Multiattack, Power Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | All four Elemental Lords — fading; the all-element resonance of the Giant age, attenuated by millennia of isolation, guttering like a candle in its last hours |
| **Environment** | Desert Ruins (the gate-complexes, processional avenues, and entrance-ways of the most intact Giant-era ruin-cities in the Infinite Desert — the Sunken Thrones, Tharok’s Pillar, and the partially-buried temple-complexes of the Glass Wastes) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or gate-vigil (3–5 at a major gate-complex) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 8 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (accumulated offerings and debris from millennia of would-be intruders) |
| **Alignment** | Usually lawful neutral |
| **Advancement** | 11–15 HD (Large); 16–20 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A mushussu fights as a gate-guardian — it does not pursue, does not range, and does not leave its post. It challenges any creature that approaches its designated gate or entrance, and attacks anything that attempts to pass without permission (how permission is granted varies — some mushussu respond to Giant-language commands, others to specific rune-tokens, and some allow passage to any creature that makes a formal request and waits). In combat, it opens with its breath weapon to scatter groups, then engages the closest target with bite and claws. Its venom compounds the damage.

A mushussu fights to the death. It has no retreat behaviour. It has been guarding this gate for ten thousand years, and it will guard it until it is destroyed.

### Special Abilities

**Breath Weapon (Su):** 30-foot cone of searing, elemental-charged wind, usable every 1d4 rounds. 4d6 damage (half fire, half electricity). Reflex DC 19 half. The save DC is Constitution-based. The breath carries the faint, painful resonance of Giant-era elemental energy — Kin who fail the save are dazed for 1 round by the resonance-shock in addition to the damage.

**Poison (Ex):** Bite; Fortitude DC 19; initial damage 1d4 Str; secondary damage 1d4 Con. The venom is a thick, oily substance that smells of heated metal. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Ruin-Sentinel (Su):** A mushussu bonded to a specific gate or entrance cannot be moved from its post by any forced-movement effect (bull rush, grapple repositioning, teleportation). It receives a +4 bonus on saves against enchantment effects while within 60 feet of its bonded site. If killed, a mushussu reforms at its bonded gate in 1d4 months — only *wish* or *miracle* can permanently destroy a gate-bonded mushussu.

**Fading All-Element Resonance (Su):** A mushussu registers on Kin-sense as a fading echo of the all-four-element resonance — the same harmony that lamassu carry, but weaker and flickering, like a candle in its last hours of burning. Pekakarlik ruin-wardens describe it as “the gate itself remembering that it was alive.” Detectable at 90 feet. Unlike lamassu resonance (overwhelming and sustained), mushussu resonance is melancholy — Kin who detect it report a sense of endings, of duty without purpose, of a guard that no longer knows what it guards.

### Society

Mushussu are the last gate-guardians of the Giant cities — composite magical beasts (serpent, lion, eagle) created or adopted by the Giants as sentinels for their most important structures. They predate the Kin; they predate the Shattering; they predate everything except the Giants themselves. Each mushussu is bonded to a specific gate, and it has been guarding that gate since the Giant who placed it there crumbled to dust.

Pekakarlik ruin-wardens maintain careful records of known mushussu locations, their temperaments, and the methods (if any) by which they grant passage. Some mushussu respond to spoken Giant-language — a Pekakarlik who has learned the Giant tongue from lamassu or from rune-study can request passage formally. Others respond to specific rune-tokens that the Pekakarlik have painstakingly recreated from Giant inscription-fragments. And some respond to nothing at all — they guard gates to structures that have been empty for millennia and will guard them until the world ends.

The relationship between mushussu and lamassu is unclear. Lamassu are intelligent, conversational, and willing to answer questions; mushussu are not (Int 6 — they understand commands but do not converse). Whether mushussu were created by the Giants as lesser guardians, or evolved independently and were adopted by the Giants, is debated.

Taraf-Imro warriors who have fought mushussu at ruin-entrances describe them as the most relentless opponents they have faced — a mushussu does not tire, does not retreat, and reforms after death.

### Lore

**DC 18 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Mushussu are composite magical beasts — serpent, lion, and eagle — that guard the gates of Giant ruins. They have a breath weapon (fire/electricity cone), venomous bite, and spell resistance 18. They fight to the death and do not leave their post.

**DC 23:** A mushussu bonded to a gate reforms in 1d4 months after destruction — only *wish* can prevent this. Pekakarlik ruin-wardens maintain records of each mushussu’s temperament and the methods for requesting passage. Some respond to Giant-language commands.

**DC 28:** Mushussu carry a fading echo of Giant four-element resonance — weaker and more melancholy than lamassu resonance. They predate the Kin entirely. The resonance provokes a sense of endings in Kin who detect it — “the gate itself remembering that it was alive.”

# NÄCK

The Sea Falls roar, and beneath the roar there is music. Not the kinnari’s waterfall-song — you have heard that, and it was beautiful in a way that healed. This is beautiful in a way that *takes*. A violin, played from behind the curtain of falling water by hands you cannot see, producing a melody so perfect it hollows you out. Your feet are wet. You have walked into the pool at the falls’ base without deciding to. The water is at your knees. The music is louder. The player steps through the spray — naked, pale, golden-haired, inhuman, and smiling with a mouth that has too many teeth for something that looks so much like an Eruskan boy.

**Medium Fey (Aquatic)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Fey (Aquatic) |
| **Hit Dice** | 7d6+14 (38 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +3 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), swim 50 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 17 (+3 Dex, +4 natural), touch 13, flat-footed 14 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +3/+5 |
| **Attack** | Slam +5 melee (1d6+2) or drowning grasp +5 melee touch (see text) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 slams +5 melee (1d6+2) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Compelling music, drowning grasp, spell-like abilities |
| **Special Qualities** | Amphibious, damage reduction 10/cold iron, fast healing 3 (in water), low-light vision, spell resistance 17, waterfall bond, elemental resonance (fey-water dark) |
| **Saves** | Fort +4, Ref +8, Will +7 |
| **Abilities** | Str 14, Dex 16, Con 14, Int 15, Wis 14, Cha 20 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +15 (10 ranks), Diplomacy +10 (5 ranks), Hide +13 (10 ranks), Listen +12 (10 ranks), Perform (string instruments) +19 (10 ranks, +4 racial), Spot +12 (10 ranks), Swim +12 (10 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Ability Focus (compelling music), Dodge, Weapon Finesse |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) — dark; the pull of deep water, the current beneath the surface that drags you under while the surface stays calm |
| **Environment** | Sea Falls (the great coastal waterfalls along the Pekakarlik sea-fall trade-route — the plunge-pools, mist-caves, and spray-hollows where freshwater meets the Apelian; secondary presence at isolated inland waterfalls in the Great River system, always at falls with deep plunge-pools) |
| **Organization** | Solitary |
| **Challenge Rating** | 5 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (instruments — always instruments, collected over decades, many of exceptional quality; plus coins and jewellery from drowned victims) |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic evil |
| **Advancement** | 8–10 HD (Medium); 11–14 HD (Large) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A näck does not fight — it drowns. Its entire tactical approach centres on compelling music: it plays from concealment (behind the waterfall, within the spray-column), draws victims into the plunge-pool with its melody, then uses drowning grasp once the victim is in deep water. A näck in its element — waist-deep or deeper — is extraordinarily dangerous because its victims must fight the music’s compulsion, the grapple, and the drowning simultaneously.

If forced into open combat (on land or against a prepared group), a näck uses *mirror image* and *fog cloud* to create confusion, then retreats into the waterfall. It never fights on dry ground if it can avoid it. A näck reduced below 10 hit points dives to the bottom of its plunge-pool and remains there until the threat leaves — its fast healing restores it as long as it stays submerged.

### Special Abilities

**Compelling Music (Su):** A näck can play an instrument (typically violin, but some use flute or kantele) as a standard action. All creatures within 120 feet who can hear the music must succeed on a DC 20 Will save or be compelled to move toward the näck by the most direct route, at their normal speed, for as long as the music continues plus 1d4 rounds. A compelled creature takes no other actions and does not avoid hazards (including deep water). A creature that enters water and cannot swim begins drowning normally. A creature that successfully saves is immune to that näck’s music for 24 hours. The save DC is Charisma-based and includes the +2 from Ability Focus. *Silence* or deafness negates this ability.

**Drowning Grasp (Su):** As a melee touch attack, a näck can seize a creature and drag it underwater. This functions as a grapple (using the näck’s grapple modifier of +5, with a +4 circumstance bonus in water for a total of +9). A creature grappled by a drowning grasp cannot hold its breath normally — it begins drowning in 1 round (instead of the usual rounds equal to Constitution score). The näck does not need to breathe and can hold a victim underwater indefinitely. *Freedom of movement* or a successful DC 18 Escape Artist check (or opposed grapple check) breaks the grasp.

**Waterfall Bond (Su):** A näck is bonded to a specific waterfall. Within 120 feet of its bonded falls, it gains fast healing 3, +4 to all saves, and can see and hear through the waterfall’s spray (perfect awareness of anything within the mist-zone). If the näck moves more than one mile from its bonded waterfall, it loses its damage reduction, fast healing, and spell resistance until it returns. If the waterfall is permanently destroyed (dammed, diverted, dried), the näck dies in 1d6 days.

**Spell-Like Abilities:** Caster level 7th. The save DCs are Charisma-based (DC 15 + spell level). - At will — *ghost sound* (DC 15), *prestidigitation* - 3/day — *charm person* (DC 16), *fog cloud, mirror image* - 1/day — *control water*

**Dark Fey-Water Resonance (Su):** A näck registers on Kin-sense as a fey water-signature with a dangerous undertow quality — musical and alluring on the surface, cold and pulling beneath. Detectable at 60 feet. Pekakarlik sea-fall traders describe the sensation as “hearing the kinnari’s song played in a minor key.” The critical distinction between näck and kinnari resonance: kinnari resonance radiates outward (welcoming); näck resonance pulls inward (luring). A DC 14 Kin-sense check distinguishes between the two. Pekakarlik who have encountered both can make this distinction automatically.

### Society

Näckar are the dark fey of Oreka’s waterfalls — the malicious counterpart to the kinnari, occupying the same ecological niche (waterfall-spirit) with opposite intent. Where a kinnari sings to heal and protect, a näck plays to lure and drown. They are solitary, territorial, and patient — a näck that claims a waterfall will drown anyone who enters its pool for decades, building a collection of instruments and waterlogged treasures at the bottom.

Pekakarlik sea-fall traders maintain detailed maps of known näck waterfalls, distinct from kinnari falls, updated with every trading-season. The Pekakarlik protocol is absolute: at an unknown waterfall, test the resonance before approaching the pool. If the resonance pulls inward — walk away. The distinction between kinnari falls and näck falls is taught to Pekakarlik children alongside the lamia protocols and the kappa-bowing trick, part of the comprehensive survival education that makes Pekakarlik traders the most pragmatically cautious people in Oreka.

Eruskan bards have an ambivalent relationship with näckar. The creatures are superb musicians — their violin-playing is, by every technical measure, among the finest in the world — and Eruskan musical tradition includes “näck-melodies,” compositions transcribed from näck performances by bards who listened from safe distance. The ethical status of these compositions is debated in Eruskan bardic circles: is it appropriate to learn from a creature that drowns people? The music itself, separated from its killer, is undeniably beautiful.

Kinnari and näckar never share a waterfall. The presence of one excludes the other absolutely — the resonance-signatures are incompatible. A waterfall that transitions from kinnari-occupied to näck-occupied (or vice versa) is a significant event in Pekakarlik and Eruskan river-lore, usually indicating a major upstream change in elemental conditions.

### Lore

**DC 15 (Knowledge [nature]):** Näckar are dangerous waterfall-fey that lure victims into plunge-pools with irresistible music, then drown them. They are the malicious counterpart to kinnari. Cold iron bypasses their damage reduction.

**DC 20:** A näck’s compelling music forces victims to walk into water (Will DC 20). Its drowning grasp accelerates drowning — victims begin drowning in 1 round instead of the usual time. *Silence* negates the music. The resonance “pulls inward” — the opposite of kinnari resonance.

**DC 25:** Näckar are bonded to specific waterfalls and die if the falls are permanently destroyed. Pekakarlik traders maintain separate maps of näck falls and kinnari falls. Eruskan bards transcribe näck compositions from safe distance, producing “näck-melodies” of controversial beauty.

# NĀGA (OREKA)

The river is deep here — so deep the bottom vanishes into green-black shadow, and the current runs slow and heavy as though the water itself were old. The Pekakarlik rivermen cut their engines and let the barge drift. They have been quiet for the last mile, speaking only in hand-signs, and when you ask why, the barge-master points to the water and puts a finger to his lips. Something vast is coiled on the riverbed below you — a serpentine shape forty feet long, its scales iridescent even in the dim light, and from the forward end of the coils, a face looks up through the water at your barge. Not a snake’s face. A woman’s face, wise and ancient and crowned with a hood of scaled flesh that spreads like a cobra’s, and the expression on that face says: *I see you. You may pass. This time.*

**Huge Magical Beast (Aquatic)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Huge Magical Beast (Aquatic) |
| **Hit Dice** | 12d10+60 (126 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +3 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), swim 50 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 23 (–2 size, +3 Dex, +12 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 20 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +12/+28 |
| **Attack** | Bite +18 melee (2d8+8 plus poison) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +18 melee (2d8+8 plus poison) and tail slap +16 melee (2d6+4) |
| **Space/Reach** | 15 ft./10 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Constrict 2d8+12, improved grab, poison, spells |
| **Special Qualities** | Amphibious, darkvision 60 ft., spell resistance 22, damage reduction 5/magic, elemental resonance (deep water-earth) |
| **Saves** | Fort +13, Ref +11, Will +10 |
| **Abilities** | Str 26, Dex 16, Con 20, Int 18, Wis 18, Cha 17 |
| **Skills** | Concentration +17 (12 ranks), Diplomacy +13 (10 ranks), Knowledge (arcana) +14 (10 ranks), Knowledge (nature) +14 (10 ranks), Listen +14 (10 ranks), Sense Motive +14 (10 ranks), Spellcraft +14 (10 ranks), Spot +14 (10 ranks), Swim +16 (racial) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Combat Casting, Empower Spell, Improved Natural Attack (bite), Multiattack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) / Lord of Stone (Earth) — ancient; the deep riverbed, the slow power of water that has carved stone for millennia |
| **Environment** | Deep Great River (the deepest, oldest stretches of the Great River — the canyon-passages where the river runs through stone gorges hundreds of feet deep, the confluence-pools where major tributaries meet, and the sacred deep-holes that Pekakarlik rivermen mark on their charts with respect-symbols) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or mated pair |
| **Challenge Rating** | 9 |
| **Treasure** | Double standard (river-hoard: Giant-era artefacts, precious metals, gems, and objects of power that have accumulated in the river-deep over millennia) |
| **Alignment** | Usually lawful neutral |
| **Advancement** | 13–18 HD (Huge); 19–24 HD (Gargantuan) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

An Oreka nāga is not aggressive toward river-traffic that behaves respectfully — barges that drift quietly, fishers who do not use nets in the deep-holes, and travellers who make the traditional Pekakarlik hand-sign of respect (palm-down over the gunwale, held for three heartbeats). Creatures that violate these protocols — or that actively pollute, dam, or corrupt the nāga’s river-stretch — are attacked with devastating efficiency.

In combat, a nāga opens with spells (*hold person*, *lightning bolt*) to disable or scatter opponents, then closes with bite and constrict on the most dangerous remaining target. In water, the nāga’s swim speed and grapple modifier make escape nearly impossible. On land (which it avoids), a nāga fights at a disadvantage but compensates with its spell repertoire and raw physical power.

A nāga defending its territory fights to the death. A nāga encountered outside its territory (rare — nāga travel between deep-holes only during the spring flood-season) retreats if seriously injured.

### Special Abilities

**Poison (Ex):** Bite; Fortitude DC 21; initial damage 1d6 Con; secondary damage 1d6 Con. The venom is a clear, odourless liquid that causes rapid internal haemorrhaging. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Improved Grab (Ex):** Bite attack. On a successful grapple, the nāga can constrict.

**Constrict (Ex):** 2d8+12 damage per round. A constricted creature held underwater begins drowning normally.

**Spells:** An Oreka nāga casts spells as a 7th-level sorcerer (6/7/7/5 per day; save DC 13 + spell level). Typical spells known: - 0 — *detect magic, light, mage hand, mending, read magic, resistance* - 1st — *mage armour, magic missile, shield, true strike* - 2nd — *invisibility, mirror image, resist energy* - 3rd — *hold person* (DC 16), *lightning bolt* (DC 16)

**Deep Water-Earth Resonance (Su):** An Oreka nāga registers on Kin-sense as a vast, slow, dual water-earth signature — the weight of the river itself given awareness, the patience of water that has been carving stone since before the Giants. Detectable at 120 feet (the resonance passes through water with almost no attenuation). Pekakarlik rivermen describe it as “the river deciding to pay attention to you.” The resonance is not threatening per se — it is simply *immense*, and the immensity is humbling. Kin within 30 feet of a nāga feel a compulsion to speak quietly and move slowly, not from magical coercion but from the instinctive recognition that they are in the presence of something older and larger than themselves.

### Society

Oreka’s nāga are the deep-river guardians — Huge, intelligent, spell-casting serpents that claim the Great River’s deepest stretches as territory and guard them with the patient authority of creatures that have been in residence since before the Kin began to build boats. They are not the same as the OGL naga variants (guardian, spirit, water, dark); Oreka’s nāga are a distinct species, unique to the Great River system, combining aspects of all four types into a single, culturally-integrated creature.

Pekakarlik rivermen revere nāga as the highest expression of the Lady of the Sea’s authority in freshwater. The Pekakarlik river-protocols — the hand-signs, the quiet drifting, the prohibition on deep-hole netting — are not superstition. They are the accumulated wisdom of millennia of coexistence, and they work. A Pekakarlik barge that follows protocol passes through nāga territory unmolested. A foreign vessel that does not follow protocol learns the consequences.

Pekakarlik river-priests (*nehir-hakim*) maintain relationships with individual nāga, visiting their deep-holes during the spring flood-season to offer gifts (polished gemstones — nāga covet gems with the intensity of dragons) and receive intelligence about river conditions, upstream threats, and the health of the waterway. A nāga that reports corruption or pollution upstream triggers a Pekakarlik mobilisation response that treats the threat as seriously as a Dómnathar incursion.

Eruskan river-cities downstream of nāga territory benefit from their protection — a river-stretch guarded by a nāga is safe from aquatic predators, river-piracy (the nāga sinks pirate vessels with *lightning bolt*), and environmental degradation. Eruskan merchants consider nāga territory the safest water on the Great River and adjust their shipping routes accordingly.

The relationship between nāga and River Serpents (the common water-element beasts of the Great River) is hierarchical: River Serpents defer to nāga absolutely, and nāga tolerate River Serpents in their territory as lesser members of the river’s ecosystem. A deep-hole guarded by a nāga typically also hosts three to five River Serpents.

### Lore

**DC 19 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Oreka nāga are Huge, intelligent river-serpents with spellcasting ability, venomous bite, and constricting coils. They guard the Great River’s deepest stretches and are revered by Pekakarlik rivermen.

**DC 24:** Nāga cast spells as 7th-level sorcerers (including *lightning bolt* and *hold person*). Their venom causes Constitution damage (Fort DC 21). Pekakarlik river-protocols allow safe passage through nāga territory. Nāga covet gemstones and accept them as gifts.

**DC 29:** Pekakarlik river-priests maintain individual relationships with specific nāga, exchanging gems for intelligence about river conditions. Nāga territory is hierarchically above River Serpent territory — River Serpents defer to nāga absolutely. Nāga resonance is the deep river itself made aware — “the river deciding to pay attention to you.”

# NAK

The dock is old Pekakarlik construction — heavy timber pylons driven into the estuary-mud, planked with salt-treated oak, worn smooth by a century of barge-keels and bare feet. At the dock’s end, where the pylons meet the water, something lives between the pilings. The children see it first — they always do — a crocodilian shape the size of a large dog, long-snouted and dark-scaled, watching the dock-traffic from the shadows between the timbers with bright, unblinking eyes. It is not a crocodile. Crocodiles do not hang upside-down from dock-pylons. Crocodiles do not grin.

**Medium Magical Beast (Aquatic)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Magical Beast (Aquatic) |
| **Hit Dice** | 4d10+8 (30 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +2 |
| **Speed** | 20 ft. (4 squares), swim 40 ft., climb 20 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 17 (+2 Dex, +5 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 15 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +4/+7 |
| **Attack** | Bite +7 melee (1d6+3 plus grab) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +7 melee (1d6+3 plus grab) and tail slap +2 melee (1d4+1) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Improved grab, drag under, dock ambush |
| **Special Qualities** | Amphibious, darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, scent, pylon-cling, elemental resonance (water-brackish) |
| **Saves** | Fort +6, Ref +6, Will +2 |
| **Abilities** | Str 16, Dex 14, Con 14, Int 5, Wis 12, Cha 8 |
| **Skills** | Climb +11, Hide +8 (+14 in dock structures), Listen +5, Spot +5, Swim +11 |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Stealthy |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) — brackish; the murky, salt-tinged water where river meets sea, neither fully fresh nor fully salt |
| **Environment** | Pekakarlik Docks (the timber-pylon dock-complexes of Pekakarlik coastal and estuarine trading-posts — the pilings, jetties, and harbour structures where river-barges meet sea-going vessels along the Apelian coast) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or colony (3–8) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 3 |
| **Treasure** | None (nak do not hoard, but shiny objects dropped in the water near a nak colony accumulate on the estuary-bed) |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 5–8 HD (Medium); 9–12 HD (Large) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A nak is a dock-ambush predator. It clings to the underside of pier-planking or between pylons (pylon-cling), waiting for small prey — rats, fish, gulls, dock-cats — to come within reach. It strikes upward or sideways with its bite, grabs, and drags the prey underwater. Against Kin-sized targets, nak are opportunistic: they grab unattended equipment, pull fishing-lines, and snatch food from dock-edges, but rarely attack a person unless the nak is Large (advanced) or the target is a child or small halfling wading alone.

A colony of nak defending a dock-section fights cooperatively — one bites and grabs while others slap with tails, creating confusion. They retreat into the water if seriously threatened.

### Special Abilities

**Improved Grab (Ex):** Bite attack against a creature of the nak’s size or smaller.

**Drag Under (Ex):** A nak that successfully grapples a creature in or adjacent to water can drag it underwater as a move action. The nak receives a +4 bonus on grapple checks while fully submerged.

**Pylon-Cling (Ex):** A nak can cling to any wooden or stone surface, including the underside of docks, piers, and bridge-spans, indefinitely. It can fight while clinging (no penalty). This ability, combined with its climb speed, allows a nak to move through the three-dimensional structure of a Pekakarlik dock-complex with the ease of a spider in its web.

**Dock Ambush (Ex):** A nak hiding in a dock-structure receives a +6 racial bonus on Hide checks (total +14 in dock structures). A nak that attacks from a concealed position within a dock-structure receives a +2 circumstance bonus on the first attack roll.

**Brackish Water Resonance (Su):** A nak registers on Kin-sense as a faint, murky water-signature — detectable at 30 feet, reading as “something alive in the pilings.” Pekakarlik dock-workers describe it as “the dock sweating.” The resonance is easily lost in the ambient noise of busy harbour areas (DC 16 to detect in an active dock, DC 12 at an abandoned one). This makes nak functionally undetectable by Kin-sense in working harbours.

### Society

Nak are the dock-predators of Pekakarlik coastal trading-posts — crocodilian magical beasts that have colonised the pylon-forests of Pekakarlik harbour infrastructure and adapted to life in the narrow, shadowed spaces between timbers. They are not dangerous to adult Kin under normal circumstances (Medium nak target rats and fish, not people), but they are persistent nuisances that steal catches, damage nets, gnaw mooring-lines, and occasionally bite toes.

Pekakarlik dock-communities have a grudging tolerance for nak. The creatures eat harbour-rats in prodigious numbers, which provides a genuine service — a dock without nak is a dock with a rat problem. Pekakarlik harbour-masters maintain an informal population-management approach: too many nak and the fishing-losses become unacceptable; too few and the rats multiply. The ideal is a colony of four to six per major dock-section.

Halfling coastal settlements near Pekakarlik ports have adopted nak-management practices from their dwarven neighbours. Halfling children are taught not to dangle feet off dock-edges at dusk (peak nak feeding-time) and not to leave fish-heads on the planking (which attracts additional nak).

Na’wasua sea-elves consider nak to be minor water-spirits of the shore-zone — unremarkable, part of the dock-ecosystem, and not worth thinking about. The Na’wasua attitude is shared by most Kin who spend time in harbours: nak are like seagulls with teeth, an accepted hazard of maritime life.

### Lore

**DC 13 (Knowledge [nature]):** Nak are crocodilian dock-predators found in Pekakarlik harbours. They cling to pylons, ambush small prey, and drag catches underwater. They eat rats, making them a mixed blessing.

**DC 18:** Nak can cling to any surface and fight while hanging upside-down. They receive a +14 Hide bonus in dock structures. Pekakarlik harbour-masters manage nak populations rather than eliminate them, maintaining 4–6 per dock-section for rat control.

**DC 23:** Nak resonance is nearly undetectable in active harbours (DC 16 Kin-sense). They are brackish-water specialists — never found in purely fresh or purely salt water, only in the estuary-zone where the two mix. Advanced Large nak can be genuinely dangerous.

# NANG TANI

The banana grove is older than the halfling settlement that tends it. The trees are tall and thick-trunked, their broad leaves casting the kind of shade that turns midday into twilight, and the air beneath them is sweet with the smell of ripening fruit and damp earth. You notice one tree at the grove’s heart that is different — not larger, but *present* in a way the others are not. A green silk ribbon is tied around its trunk, and at its base, a scattering of fresh flowers, a small clay cup of honey-water, and a garland of jasmine. At dusk, when the light goes green-gold through the canopy, you see her — standing against the trunk as though she grew from it, a woman in green with hair the colour of new leaves and an expression of patient, protective attention directed at the settlement below.

