| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A noble salamander is a commander as well as a combatant. It directs average salamanders in coordinated attacks while engaging the strongest enemy personally. Its +3 longspear (a weapon of its own forging, burning with sovereign-level heat) deals devastating fire damage, and its spell-like abilities (*dispel magic*, *burning hands*, *fireball*, *wall of fire*) provide area control.

### Special Abilities

**Heat (Ex):** As average salamander, but 1d8 fire damage.

**Constrict / Improved Grab (Ex):** Tail; 2d8+3 plus 1d8 fire per round. On a successful tail attack against a Large or smaller creature.

**Spell-Like Abilities:** Caster level 15th. Save DCs are Charisma-based (DC 14 + spell level). - 3/day — *burning hands* (DC 15), *fireball* (DC 17), *flaming sphere* (DC 16), *wall of fire* (DC 18) - 1/day — *dispel magic, summon monster VII* (huge fire elemental only)

**Sovereign Forge Resonance (Su):** A noble salamander’s resonance is fire at absolute authority — detectable at 120 feet. Rarozhki master-smiths describe it as “standing inside the Lady of Fire’s own forge.” The resonance is qualitatively different from average salamander resonance (which is working-fire) — this is *commanding* fire, fire that expects obedience from metal.

### Society

Noble salamanders rule the Scorchspire forge-colonies as tyrant-smiths — master craftsmen whose authority derives from their absolute command over fire and metal. Each noble controls a court of 3–10 average salamanders, directing forge-work, military operations, and the colony’s interactions with the Material Plane.

The Ember Vault — the name Rarozhki give to the deepest Scorchspire forge-chambers — is contested territory between noble salamanders and Rarozhki master-smiths. The competition is professional as much as territorial: both cultures produce extraordinary metalwork, and each considers the other’s methods inferior. Noble salamanders scorn Rarozhki reliance on mundane tools; Rarozhki scorn salamander reliance on brute supernatural heat rather than technique. The rivalry has produced some of the finest weapons in Oreka, forged in competitive spite.

### Lore

**DC 20 (Knowledge [the planes]):** Noble salamanders rule fire-outsider colonies in the deepest Scorchspires. They are powerful combatants with spell-like abilities and carry master-forged weapons. DR 15/magic, SR 22.

**DC 25:** Noble salamanders and Rarozhki master-smiths maintain a competitive rivalry. The Ember Vault is contested territory. Noble salamanders can summon huge fire elementals once per day.

**DC 30:** Sovereign forge resonance is fire at absolute authority — qualitatively different from average salamander resonance. The rivalry has produced some of Oreka’s finest weapons. Noble salamanders consider mortal metalworking inferior but covet mortal-mined rare ores.

# SALT MEPHIT

The salt flat shimmers in the heat. The crust is thin here — thin enough that your boot punches through with each step, revealing the damp brine beneath. Something crunches to your left, and a shape rises from the salt-crust like a man rising from shallow water: small, angular, encrusted with crystalline deposits, with a face that is all sharp edges and a grin that contains too many teeth. It smells like a low-tide beach on a hot day. It is looking at your waterskin with the focused intensity of a creature that knows exactly what you cannot afford to lose.

**Small Outsider (Earth, Extraplanar)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Small Outsider (Earth, Extraplanar) |
| **Hit Dice** | 3d8+6 (19 hp) |
| **Initiative** | –1 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), fly 40 ft. (average) |
| **Armor Class** | 16 (+1 size, –1 Dex, +6 natural), touch 10, flat-footed 16 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +3/–2 |
| **Attack** | Claw +3 melee (1d3–1 plus desiccation) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 claws +3 melee (1d3–1 plus desiccation) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Breath weapon, desiccation, summon mephit |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., fast healing 2 (in arid environments), DR 5/magic, elemental resonance (earth — crystalline desiccation) |
| **Saves** | Fort +5, Ref +2, Will +3 |
| **Abilities** | Str 9, Dex 8, Con 15, Int 6, Wis 11, Cha 14 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +8 (3 ranks), Hide +9 (3 ranks), Listen +6 (3 ranks), Move Silently +5 (3 ranks), Spot +6 (3 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Power Attack, Toughness |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) — crystalline desiccation; the resonance of salt-deposits, of water removed from earth until only the mineral skeleton remains, earth at its driest and most hostile to life |
| **Environment** | Desert Salt Flats (the vast salt-pan expanses of the Infinite Desert — specifically the dried lake-beds and mineral-flat zones where ancient water-sources evaporated millennia ago, leaving crystalline wastelands) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, gang (2–4), or pack (5–12) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 3 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 4–6 HD (Small) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +3 |

### Combat

Salt mephits are annoying rather than dangerous — their individual combat ability is trivial, but their desiccation effect and breath weapon can be debilitating in desert environments where water is already scarce. They target waterskins, water-casks, and other water-containers with gleeful malice, using their desiccation touch to evaporate water-supplies rather than attacking creatures directly.

### Special Abilities

**Breath Weapon (Su):** 10-foot cone of desiccating salt-crystals, 1d4 damage plus target must succeed on a DC 13 Fortitude save or be tormented by salt in wounds (–2 penalty on attack rolls and skill checks for 3 rounds). Usable once per day. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Desiccation (Su):** A salt mephit’s touch evaporates water. Unattended water within 5 feet of a salt mephit evaporates at 1 gallon per round. A creature struck by a salt mephit’s claw must succeed on a DC 13 Fortitude save or take 1 point of nonlethal damage from dehydration in addition to the claw damage. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Summon Mephit (Sp):** Once per day, a salt mephit can attempt to summon another salt mephit with a 25% chance of success. Caster level 6th.

**Crystalline Desiccation Resonance (Su):** Salt mephits register on Kin-sense as earth stripped of moisture — dry, sharp, crystalline. Detectable at 15 feet. Pekakarlik caravan-scouts describe it as “the ground being thirsty” — a hostile absence of water in the earth-resonance that warns of both the mephit’s presence and the salt-flat’s dangers.

### Society

Salt mephits are minor earth-outsiders of the Infinite Desert’s salt flats — small, mean-spirited creatures that delight in making desert travel worse than it already is. They are not a significant threat to armed groups but are a genuine danger to unprepared travellers, because their desiccation effect destroys water-supplies in an environment where water is life.

Pekakarlik caravan-routes through salt-flat zones include mephit-deterrent protocols: water-containers are sealed with wax and stored in central wagons (rather than carried individually, where they’re vulnerable to mephit touch), and caravan-guards carry salt-ward torches (mundane torches treated with alchemical compounds that produce acrid smoke mephits find repellent).

### Lore

**DC 13 (Knowledge [the planes]):** Salt mephits are Small earth-outsiders found on desert salt flats. They desiccate water on touch and are more nuisance than threat. Their breath weapon scatters salt-crystals that irritate wounds.

**DC 18:** Salt mephits target water-supplies rather than creatures. Pekakarlik caravans seal water-containers with wax and use salt-ward torches as deterrents. They gain fast healing 2 in arid environments.

**DC 23:** Salt mephit resonance is crystalline desiccation — earth stripped of all moisture. They can summon additional mephits. Large packs of 5–12 near water-sources can be genuinely dangerous to small parties.

# SAND WRAITH

The ruin ahead is half-buried — the upper columns of what was once a Giant plaza project from the dune like the ribs of a vast skeleton, and the sand between them moves in patterns that have nothing to do with the wind. A shape gathers in the air above the columns: tall, vaguely humanoid, composed entirely of swirling sand and grit. Dim amber light burns where its eyes should be. The sound it produces is less a voice than a sustained, low howl of desert wind forced through a space too narrow for it. The Pekakarlik Sand Warden beside you raises one hand, palm outward — the greeting-sign — and murmurs a name in a language older than any you speak. The shape pauses. The howl shifts pitch. The Warden lowers his hand. “This one is mourning,” he says. “We go around.”

**Medium Undead (Elemental, Incorporeal)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Undead (Elemental, Incorporeal) |
| **Hit Dice** | 5d12 (32 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +3 |
| **Speed** | Fly 30 ft. (perfect) |
| **Armor Class** | 15 (+3 Dex, +2 deflection), touch 15, flat-footed 12 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +2/— |
| **Attack** | Desiccating touch +5 melee touch (1d6 plus desiccation) |
| **Full Attack** | Desiccating touch +5 melee touch (1d6 plus desiccation) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Desiccating touch, sand shriek |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., incorporeal traits, undead traits, sand form, elemental resonance (all four — fragmented Giant echo), Kin-sense signature |
| **Saves** | Fort +1, Ref +4, Will +6 |
| **Abilities** | Str —, Dex 16, Con —, Int 8, Wis 14, Cha 15 |
| **Skills** | Hide +11 (5 ranks), Listen +10 (5 ranks), Search +7 (5 ranks), Spot +10 (5 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Improved Initiative |
| **Elemental Affinity** | All four Elemental Lords (fragmented); strongest resonance with the Lord of Stone — a Sand Wraith’s elemental signature is the shattered remnant of a Giant’s full four-element harmony, broken and looping like a record stuck in a groove |
| **Environment** | The Infinite Desert (Giant ruins, dune-seas; thickest concentration at the Sunken Thrones, Tharok’s Pillar, and the deep dune-seas; rare sightings at the Apelian Sea’s submerged Giant piers in the Deepwater Marches) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or mourning (3–6) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 5 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 6–10 HD (Medium); 11–15 HD (Large) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

Sand Wraiths attack with their desiccating touch, draining moisture from living creatures with terrible speed. They prefer to isolate single targets, circling a group with slow, drifting patience until one member separates or falls behind. If reduced to half hit points, a Sand Wraith disperses into its sand form and reforms 1d4 rounds later at the nearest Giant ruin within one mile. Sand Wraiths never willingly pursue targets beyond the boundaries of the ruin complex or dune-sea they haunt; their territorial attachment to Giant sites appears to be absolute.

### Special Abilities

**Desiccating Touch (Su):** A Sand Wraith’s touch attack deals 1d6 damage and forces the target to make a DC 14 Fortitude save or take 1d4 Constitution damage as moisture is violently extracted from the body. Creatures reduced to 0 Constitution by this ability crumble to dust. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Sand Shriek (Su):** Once per day, a Sand Wraith can unleash a piercing shriek in a 30-foot cone. All creatures in the area must succeed on a DC 14 Will save or be shaken for 1d4 rounds. Creatures with Kin-sense who fail the save also experience a flash of the wraith’s last memory — a glimpse of the Giant city as it was before the desert took it. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Sand Form (Su):** As a standard action, a Sand Wraith can disperse into a cloud of sand and dust, becoming effectively invisible in desert terrain (Spot DC 25 to detect). While in sand form, the wraith cannot attack but moves at double speed and is immune to all physical damage. It can reform as a standard action.

**Fragmented Giant Resonance (Su):** A Sand Wraith registers on Kin-sense as a faint, distorted echo of all four elements — the remnant of a Giant’s full elemental harmony, shattered and looping. Detectable at 60 feet. Pekakarlik pilgrims describe the sensation as “hearing a song you loved, played on a broken instrument, in a language you’ve forgotten.” The distorted signature makes precise location difficult (concealment, 20% miss chance) unless the Kin succeeds on a DC 15 Wisdom check. Sand Wardens on the Pilgrim Road can distinguish passive wraiths (those simply drifting) from aggressive ones (those guarding a specific ruin entrance) by the pitch of the howl.

### Society

Sand Wraiths are the Infinite Desert’s most iconic undead — incorporeal spirits of swirling sand and dust that drift through the Giant ruins and dune-seas, drawn to the places where the Giants once lived and worked. Whether they are the ghosts of Giants, elemental echoes of their passing, or something else entirely, no scholar has determined. The wraiths refuse to answer, in their wordless, howling way.

Pekakarlik Dwarves consider Sand Wraiths sacred and do not attack them unless attacked first, viewing them as the mourning spirits of the Giants who built the cities the Pekakarlik now maintain. Pekakarlik Sand Wardens — the specialised guides who lead pilgrimages through the deep desert — can read a Sand Wraith’s behaviour (passive drifting vs. aggressive guarding) and adjust their route accordingly. A mourning (group of 3–6) blocking a ruin entrance is taken seriously — the Wardens divert rather than challenge.

Mytroan caravans that cross the desert’s edge consider Sand Wraiths ill omens — a sighting near a caravan route means the desert is “restless” and conditions will worsen. Taraf-Imro warriors regard Sand Wraiths with warrior’s respect — as worthy opponents, neither to be feared nor pitied.

Pekakarlik tradition holds that a Sand Wraith can be pacified by performing the Giant mourning rite at the ruin’s central rune-circle, though the rite has not been successfully completed in living memory. Eruskan bard-scholars speculate that Sand Wraiths are the residual rune-magic of Giant architecture given pseudo-life — not ghosts of Giants but echoes of the magic that built their cities, still running on empty long after the builders departed.

### Lore

**DC 15 (Knowledge [religion]):** Sand Wraiths are incorporeal undead found in the Infinite Desert’s Giant ruins. Their touch drains moisture from living tissue. They are territorial and will not pursue beyond their ruin’s boundaries.

**DC 20:** Sand Wraiths can disperse into sand form when damaged, reforming at the nearest ruin. Their shriek induces fear and, in Kin-sense users, a flash of the wraith’s last memory. Pekakarlik consider them sacred and do not attack unprovoked.

**DC 25:** Sand Wraith resonance is a fractured echo of the Giants’ full four-element harmony. Pekakarlik tradition holds they can be pacified by performing the Giant mourning rite at the ruin’s rune-circle. Sand Wardens distinguish passive from aggressive wraiths by the pitch of the howl.

# SATYR

The music reaches you before the musician does. It is coming from deep in the forest — a pipe-melody that winds between the trees like smoke, changing key with each turn of the path, and you find yourself walking toward it without having decided to. The undergrowth parts. The clearing opens. He is sitting on a fallen oak, legs crossed — the legs of a goat, furred and hooved, below the bare-chested torso of a man who looks like he has never done anything more strenuous than smile. He is playing a set of reed-pipes, and the melody is the reason you left the path, and he knows it. He looks up. The smile widens. The music does not stop.

**Medium Fey**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Fey |
| **Hit Dice** | 5d6+5 (22 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +1 |
| **Speed** | 40 ft. (8 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 15 (+1 Dex, +4 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 14 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +2/+2 |
| **Attack** | Head butt +2 melee (1d6) or shortbow +3 ranged (1d6/×3) |
| **Full Attack** | Head butt +2 melee (1d6) and dagger –3 melee (1d4/19–20) or shortbow +3 ranged (1d6/×3) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Pipes |
| **Special Qualities** | Damage reduction 5/cold iron, low-light vision, elemental resonance (earth-air — forest-edge revelry) |
| **Saves** | Fort +2, Ref +5, Will +5 |
| **Abilities** | Str 10, Dex 13, Con 12, Int 12, Wis 13, Cha 13 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +9 (5 ranks), Diplomacy +3 (0 ranks), Hide +13 (5 ranks), Knowledge (nature) +9 (5 ranks), Listen +15 (5 ranks), Move Silently +13 (5 ranks), Perform (wind instruments) +9 (5 ranks), Spot +15 (5 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Dodge |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone / Youngest Brother (Earth/Air) — forest-edge; the resonance of where cultivated land meets wildwood, earth-under-leaves meeting wind-through-branches, the boundary between the tamed and the untamed expressed as music |
| **Environment** | Great Forests (the mid-forest zones between deep canopy and forest-edge — specifically the clearings, stream-banks, and meadow-openings where sunlight reaches the ground and the forest is at its most welcoming and most deceptive) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or band (3–5) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 2 (without pipes); 4 (with pipes) |
| **Treasure** | Standard |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic neutral |
| **Advancement** | 6–10 HD (Medium) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +2 |

### Combat

A satyr does not fight. A satyr *avoids* fighting — through music, through deception, through the simple expedient of being faster than you in forest terrain. If forced into melee, a satyr is a mediocre combatant: the head butt is serviceable, the dagger is backup, and DR 5/cold iron provides some protection, but a satyr that is standing and fighting has already exhausted every preferable option.

The pipes are the satyr’s real weapon — three distinct melodies that charm, frighten, or put targets to sleep. A satyr opens with charm to defuse hostility, escalates to fear if charm fails, and uses sleep as a last resort before fleeing.

### Special Abilities

**Pipes (Su):** A satyr can play one of three melodies on its pipes as a standard action. Each affects all creatures within 60 feet that can hear. DC 13 Will save negates (Charisma-based). Satyrs with Perform ranks of 10+ increase the DC by +2. - *Charm:* Affected creatures are charmed as *charm person* for 1 hour. - *Fear:* Affected creatures are frightened for 1d4 rounds. - *Sleep:* Affected creatures with 4 HD or fewer fall asleep for 1 minute.

**Forest-Edge Resonance (Su):** A satyr registers on Kin-sense as the boundary between cultivated and wild — earth and air mixing in the zone where the forest is at its most inviting. Detectable at 30 feet. Pasua scouts describe satyr resonance as “the forest being in a good mood” — warm, musical, and slightly untrustworthy. Hasura elves detect satyrs through the canopy-resonance network and consider them harmless neighbours.

### Society

Satyrs are the Great Forests’ most personable inhabitants and, for precisely that reason, the most underestimated. They are fey — chaotic, self-interested, and fundamentally concerned with their own pleasure — but their pleasure is social: music, conversation, wine, celebration, the company of interesting people. A satyr that encounters travellers in the forest wants to be entertained, not to fight, and will go to considerable lengths to ensure the encounter is enjoyable for everyone involved. The problem is that a satyr’s definition of “enjoyable” does not always align with the traveller’s, and the pipes ensure the satyr’s definition prevails.

Pasua elves have the most regular contact with satyrs. Pasua patrol-routes through the mid-forest zones inevitably cross satyr territory, and the relationship is one of exasperated tolerance — satyrs are harmless, amusing, and occasionally useful (their knowledge of forest conditions and creature movements is excellent), but they are also unreliable, easily distracted, and constitutionally incapable of taking anything seriously. Pasua scouts who need information from a satyr know to bring wine — the bribe is traditional and effective.

Hasura elves in the canopy above satyr territory view them with affectionate detachment. Hasura poets draw on satyr music traditions, and some Hasura festivals include satyr attendance (or at least satyr proximity — satyrs don’t attend formal events so much as they attend the margins of formal events, providing unsanctioned entertainment).

Tanuki groves and satyr clearings occasionally overlap, producing cultural exchanges that the rest of the forest describes with a mixture of fondness and concern. Tanuki communal warmth and satyr hedonistic energy are highly compatible, and joint satyr-tanuki celebrations are legendary, loud, and best avoided by anyone with responsibilities the following morning.

### Lore

**DC 12 (Knowledge [nature]):** Satyrs are Medium fey of the Great Forests. They play enchanting pipes that can charm, frighten, or put listeners to sleep. They prefer revelry to combat. DR 5/cold iron.

**DC 17:** Satyr pipes affect all creatures within 60 feet. Pasua scouts bribe satyrs with wine for forest intelligence. Satyrs are harmless but unreliable. Skilled pipers (Perform 10+) increase the save DC.

**DC 22:** Satyr resonance is forest-edge — the boundary between cultivated and wild. Tanuki-satyr cultural overlap produces legendary joint celebrations. Hasura elves consider satyrs harmless neighbours and draw on their music traditions.

# SEA CAT

The Apelian shallows are not empty — you knew this — but you were watching for serpents and sharks, and the thing that surfaces thirty feet from the boat is neither. It has the forelimbs, mane, and head of a great lion, and the hind-body and tail of a fish, and it moves through the water with a power and grace that a lion on land cannot match. Its roar carries across the water — not the deep bass of a terrestrial lion but a sharper, higher sound, pitched to carry over waves — and the fishing-crew is already pulling in the nets, because when a sea cat claims a stretch of water, the fish are no longer yours.

**Large Magical Beast**

