| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Undead |
| **Hit Dice** | 1d12 (6 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +5 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 13 (+1 Dex, +2 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 12 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +0/+1 |
| **Attack** | Claw +1 melee (1d4+1) or short sword +1 melee (1d6+1/19–20) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 claws +1 melee (1d4+1) or short sword +1 melee (1d6+1/19–20) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | — |
| **Special Qualities** | Damage reduction 5/bludgeoning, darkvision 60 ft., immunity to cold, undead traits, elemental resonance (none — animated bone) |
| **Saves** | Fort +0, Ref +1, Will +2 |
| **Abilities** | Str 13, Dex 13, Con —, Int —, Wis 10, Cha 1 |
| **Skills** | — |
| **Feats** | Improved Initiative |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — skeletons are animated objects, not elemental beings; they have no resonance, no signature, and no connection to the elemental system — they are bones made to move by magic, nothing more |
| **Environment** | Any (wherever the dead are raised — battlefields, crypts, Dómnathar tunnels, necromantic workshops, cursed sites where ambient death-energy animates remains without a spellcaster’s intervention) |
| **Organization** | Any |
| **Challenge Rating** | 1/3 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always neutral evil |
| **Advancement** | — |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

Skeletons fight without intelligence, without fear, and without retreat. They follow the instructions of whoever animated them and continue fighting until destroyed. DR 5/bludgeoning means slashing and piercing weapons are largely ineffective — maces, hammers, and clubs are the appropriate tools.

### Special Abilities

**Animated Bone Resonance (Su):** Skeletons register on Kin-sense as nothing — animated objects without elemental connection. This absence is detectable as “dead space that is moving” — distinct from the void-signature of Dómnathar (which is active, hungry absence) and from natural emptiness (which is passive). The distinction matters: a skeleton’s absence is *mechanical*, the blank non-signature of an object being moved by external force.

### Society

Skeletons have no society — they are animated weapons, tools of necromancy. In Oreka, the cultural context of skeletons varies by region and by source of animation.

Dómnathar tunnel-networks use skeletal troops as expendable labour and perimeter security. Dómnathar-animated skeletons are typically goblinoid or Kin-race remains — the psychological impact of facing skeletons wearing the armour of your own people is a deliberate Dómnathar terror-tactic.

Natural-animation skeletons — those raised by ambient death-energy rather than deliberate necromancy — occur at sites of mass death: battlefields, plague-graves, and locations where the elemental field has been so disrupted by death that the residual energy animates the dead without intent. The Battle of Dark Dawn’s aftermath produced skeletal risings for decades — bones pulled from the earth by the sheer weight of death that soaked the field.

Eruskan burial traditions include specific protections against skeletal animation: bodies are cremated rather than buried, and the ashes are scattered in the Great River (where the river serpents’ water-resonance prevents undead formation).

### Lore

**DC 11 (Knowledge [religion]):** Skeletons are mindless undead animated by necromancy. They follow their creator’s commands without deviation. Bludgeoning weapons bypass their damage reduction; slashing and piercing are largely ineffective.

**DC 16:** Skeletons can animate spontaneously at sites of mass death. Eruskan cremation and river-scattering traditions prevent skeletal animation. Dómnathar use skeletal troops as expendable perimeter security.

# SKINWALKER

The Mytroan camp-fire is burning low, and the herder on watch is the last one awake. The horse at the picket-line is nervous — stamping, pulling at its tether, nostrils flared. The herder watches the horse and does not watch the darkness behind him, and that is the mistake. Something comes out of the steppe on four legs — a wolf, large and dark, moving with a wolf’s easy lope — and then it stops, and the wolf *unfolds*. The hind-legs straighten. The forelegs become arms. The spine elongates. The snout shortens. In the space of three heartbeats, the wolf is a man — naked, dark-eyed, wearing the wolf’s skin draped across his shoulders like a cloak. And then the man reaches for the sleeping herder’s face, and the herder’s face begins to change.

**Medium Monstrous Humanoid (Shapechanger)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Monstrous Humanoid (Shapechanger) |
| **Hit Dice** | 8d8+24 (60 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +3 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares); 50 ft. in animal form |
| **Armor Class** | 18 (+3 Dex, +5 natural), touch 13, flat-footed 15 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +8/+11 |
| **Attack** | Claw +11 melee (1d6+3) or bite +11 melee (1d8+3, animal form only) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 claws +11 melee (1d6+3) and bite +9 melee (1d6+1); or bite +11 melee (1d8+3) and 2 claws +9 melee (1d4+1, animal form) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Face-theft, curse of the skin, spell-like abilities |
| **Special Qualities** | Alternate form (wolf, horse, eagle), darkvision 60 ft., damage reduction 10/silver, scent, fast healing 3, elemental resonance (earth-air — stolen, shifting) |
| **Saves** | Fort +5, Ref +9, Will +9 |
| **Abilities** | Str 16, Dex 17, Con 16, Int 14, Wis 16, Cha 16 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +14 (8 ranks), Disguise +14 (8 ranks, +10 with face-theft), Hide +14 (8 ranks), Listen +14 (8 ranks), Move Silently +14 (8 ranks), Spot +14 (8 ranks), Survival +14 (8 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Ability Focus (face-theft), Multiattack, Track |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone / Youngest Brother (Earth/Air) — stolen, shifting; a skinwalker’s resonance is not its own — it is a corrupted fragment of whatever creature’s form it has most recently worn, earth and air twisted into something that mimics life without possessing it |
| **Environment** | Eternal Steppe (the open grasslands, river-valleys, and camp-grounds of Mytroan territory — specifically the edges of Mytroan settlements and herding-routes, where the steppe meets the dark and the boundary between human space and wild space is thinnest) |
| **Organization** | Solitary |
| **Challenge Rating** | 7 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (accumulated through impersonation — a skinwalker in stolen form takes the victim’s possessions) |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic evil |
| **Advancement** | 9–12 HD (Medium); 13–16 HD (Large — the eldest specimens) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A skinwalker is an ambush predator that attacks from deception — approaching in animal form (wolf, horse, or eagle), shifting to humanoid form to attack, then using face-theft to assume the victim’s appearance and escape into the community. It avoids prolonged combat, preferring to strike, steal, and vanish.

Face-theft is the skinwalker’s defining weapon: by touching a sleeping or helpless creature’s face, it copies that creature’s appearance, gaining +10 on Disguise checks and the victim’s Kin-sense signature. The original victim’s face becomes blank — featureless smooth skin where the features were — until the skinwalker is killed or the curse is broken.

DR 10/silver and fast healing 3 make the skinwalker durable against unprepared attackers. Mytroan warriors carry silver weapons specifically for skinwalker encounters.

### Special Abilities

**Face-Theft (Su):** As a full-round action, a skinwalker can touch the face of a sleeping, unconscious, or helpless creature and steal its appearance. The skinwalker gains the victim’s exact physical appearance and Kin-sense signature (including racial resonance). The victim’s face becomes blank — smooth, featureless skin. The theft lasts until the skinwalker voluntarily drops the disguise, steals another face, or is killed (which restores all stolen faces). A DC 22 Will save negates. The save DC is Charisma-based (+2 Ability Focus).

**Curse of the Skin (Su):** A creature whose face has been stolen suffers the effects of a curse: –4 on all Charisma-based checks, inability to be recognised by those who knew them, and the loss of their Kin-sense signature (they register as blank — not void, but absent, as though their elemental identity has been removed). *Remove curse* (DC 20) restores the face without requiring the skinwalker’s death.

**Alternate Form (Su):** A skinwalker can assume the form of a wolf, horse, or eagle as a standard action. In animal form it gains the animal’s movement speed and natural attacks, retains its own HP, saves, and special abilities, and registers on Kin-sense as the animal’s Harmony signature — nearly undetectable as a skinwalker without a DC 20 Kin-sense check.

**Spell-Like Abilities:** Caster level 8th. Save DCs are Charisma-based. - At will — *disguise self* - 3/day — *fear* (DC 17), *bestow curse* (DC 17)

**Stolen Resonance (Su):** A skinwalker’s Kin-sense signature is never its own — it always reflects the form it is currently wearing. In animal form, it radiates the animal’s Harmony. In stolen-face form, it radiates the victim’s racial resonance. In its natural form (featureless humanoid with grey skin and empty eyes), it registers as a shifting, unstable echo of earth and air — DC 15 to detect, recognisable by Mytroan steppe-shamans as “the steppe wearing a person’s shape.”

### Society

Skinwalkers are the Eternal Steppe’s most feared shapeshifters — solitary predators that steal the faces of their victims and infiltrate Mytroan communities wearing the appearances of trusted members. They are the Mytroan cultural nightmare: the terror that the person beside you at the fire is not the person you think they are.

Mytroan anti-skinwalker traditions are the most elaborate identity-verification protocols of any Kin culture. Mytroan bands returning from patrol are challenged with questions only the real person would know — personal details, shared memories, specific knowledge of family and history. Silver weapons are maintained by every warrior and used in ritual testing: a skinwalker flinches from silver contact (the DR 10/silver is detectable as a physical reaction).

Mytroan steppe-shamans are the primary skinwalker-detection specialists. Shamans trained in Kin-sense analysis can detect the “shifting” quality of a skinwalker’s stolen resonance — the subtle instability where the mimicked signature doesn’t quite settle. This detection requires a DC 20 Kin-sense check and prolonged observation (at least 1 minute of focused attention).

The Mytroan word for skinwalker — *yüz hırsızı* (“face-thief”) — is among the gravest insults in the Mytroan language. Accusing someone of being a skinwalker is a declaration of absolute distrust that can split bands and shatter alliances.

### Lore

**DC 17 (Knowledge [nature]):** Skinwalkers are shapeshifting predators of the Eternal Steppe that steal faces from sleeping victims. They can assume wolf, horse, or eagle forms. DR 10/silver, fast healing 3. Silver weapons are the traditional countermeasure.

**DC 22:** Face-theft copies both the victim’s appearance and Kin-sense signature. The victim’s face becomes blank until the skinwalker dies or the curse is lifted. Mytroan bands use personal-knowledge challenges and silver-contact tests for identification.

**DC 27:** Skinwalker resonance is always stolen — never its own. Mytroan shamans can detect the instability in stolen resonance with prolonged observation (DC 20). The term *yüz hırsızı* is among the gravest insults in the Mytroan language.

# SPECTRE

The Ashen Hollows are the places where fire died — the volcanic valleys of the Scorchspire foothills where eruptions once poured lava and now pour nothing, where the ground is cold and grey and the trees are petrified stumps. Nothing lives here. That is the first sign that something dead does. The shape that rises from the grey earth is not smoke — it is darker than smoke, more defined, and it moves with the deliberate purpose of something that remembers being alive and hates you for still being so. Its face is a rictus of fury frozen in shadow, and where it passes, the temperature drops, not to cold but to *absence* — the heat of life draining away into something that has none.

**Medium Undead (Incorporeal)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Undead (Incorporeal) |
| **Hit Dice** | 7d12 (45 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +7 |
| **Speed** | 40 ft. (8 squares), fly 80 ft. (perfect) |
| **Armor Class** | 15 (+3 Dex, +2 deflection), touch 15, flat-footed 12 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +3/— |
| **Attack** | Incorporeal touch +6 melee touch (1d8 plus energy drain) |
| **Full Attack** | Incorporeal touch +6 melee touch (1d8 plus energy drain) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Energy drain, create spawn |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., incorporeal traits, undead traits, +2 turn resistance, sunlight powerlessness, unnatural aura, elemental resonance (fire — extinguished, inverted) |
| **Saves** | Fort +2, Ref +5, Will +7 |
| **Abilities** | Str —, Dex 16, Con —, Int 14, Wis 14, Cha 15 |
| **Skills** | Hide +13 (7 ranks), Intimidate +12 (7 ranks), Knowledge (religion) +12 (7 ranks), Listen +14 (7 ranks), Search +12 (7 ranks), Spot +14 (7 ranks), Survival +9 (7 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Blind-Fight, Improved Initiative |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of Fire (Fire) — extinguished; the resonance of fire that has gone out, heat that has been removed, the Lady of Fire’s domain inverted into its opposite — not cold (which is the absence of heat) but the *memory* of heat, the agonising awareness of warmth that no longer exists |
| **Environment** | Ashen Hollows (the dead volcanic valleys of the Scorchspire foothills — places where volcanic activity ceased, where the Lady of Fire’s presence once burned and now does not, leaving a residue of elemental grief that produces the most powerful incorporeal undead in the region) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or gang (2–4) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 7 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always lawful evil |
| **Advancement** | 8–14 HD (Medium) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A spectre is an energy-drain predator — faster, more intelligent, and more aggressive than a shadow, with the ability to drain actual levels rather than merely ability scores. Its incorporeal touch deals 1d8 damage plus two negative levels, and any humanoid killed by a spectre rises as a new spectre under the killer’s control.

Spectres are tactically sophisticated (Int 14). They attack at night (sunlight renders them powerless), targeting spellcasters first (the most dangerous opponents and the most devastating level-drain targets), and use their fly speed (80 ft., perfect) to maintain air superiority against melee-only parties.

The unnatural aura (30-foot radius) causes animals to panic, depriving the party of mounts and animal companions before combat begins.

### Special Abilities

**Energy Drain (Su):** A spectre’s incorporeal touch inflicts two negative levels. The DC to remove the negative levels is 15. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Create Spawn (Su):** Any humanoid killed by a spectre’s energy drain rises as a spectre 1d4 rounds later under the control of the spectre that created it. The new spectre retains none of its former abilities.

**Sunlight Powerlessness (Ex):** A spectre caught in sunlight cannot attack and flees. It is not destroyed but is effectively helpless.

**Unnatural Aura (Su):** Animals will not voluntarily approach within 30 feet. Animals within the aura panic (as *fear*) and remain panicked for the duration of the spectre’s presence.

**Extinguished Fire Resonance (Su):** A spectre registers on Kin-sense as fire that has been extinguished — the Lady of Fire’s resonance inverted, heat replaced by the memory of heat. Detectable at 60 feet. Rarozhki fire-smiths describe it as “the forge going cold while you’re still standing in it” — the visceral wrongness of a fire-signature that radiates *loss* instead of warmth. The resonance is unique to the Ashen Hollows — spectres formed elsewhere do not carry it; only those born from the grief of extinguished volcanic energy.

### Society

Spectres in Oreka are concentrated in the Ashen Hollows — the dead volcanic valleys where the Lady of Fire’s presence once burned and no longer does. The Hollows are the Scorchspires’ graveyard: places where volcanic activity ceased centuries or millennia ago, leaving landscapes of petrified forests, cold lava-flows, and grey ash-fields. The elemental grief of these locations — fire-resonance that remembers being alive — produces spectres of unusual power and malice.

Rarozhki Dwarves who operate near the Ashen Hollows treat them as exclusion zones. Rarozhki volcanic-cartography maps Hollow boundaries with the same precision applied to active volcanic zones — a living volcano is dangerous; a dead volcano is haunted. Rarozhki border-patrols carry sunlight-producing magical items (typically *daylight* wands or alchemical sunrods) as standard equipment when operating near Hollows.

Taraf-Imro warriors who range through the Scorchspire foothills encounter spectres and fight them with a combination of positive-energy channelling (Taraf-Imro warrior-traditions include basic turn undead training for senior fighters) and tactical discipline — keeping formation to prevent spectres from isolating individuals.

### Lore

**DC 17 (Knowledge [religion]):** Spectres are powerful incorporeal undead that drain levels through touch. Two negative levels per hit. Humanoids killed by spectres rise as new spectres. Sunlight renders them powerless but does not destroy them.

**DC 22:** The unnatural aura panics animals within 30 feet. Spectres are tactically intelligent and target spellcasters first. Rarozhki map Ashen Hollow boundaries as exclusion zones.

**DC 27:** Ashen Hollow spectres carry extinguished fire-resonance — the Lady of Fire’s domain inverted into grief. Taraf-Imro senior warriors receive basic turn undead training for spectre encounters. Only Hollow-born spectres carry this unique resonance.

# SPIDER EATER

The thing drops from the canopy — thirty feet of membranous wing spanning between a body like a wasp’s, a head like a horse’s, and a stinger the length of your forearm. It is not falling. It is diving, and the target is not you but the giant spider in the web between the oaks. The stinger drives into the spider’s abdomen with surgical precision, deposits something, and the creature is airborne again before the spider can react. In three days, the spider’s body will burst open. The larva inside will be hungry.

**Large Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 4d10+16 (38 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +3 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), fly 60 ft. (good) |
| **Armor Class** | 14 (–1 size, +3 Dex, +2 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 11 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +4/+10 |
| **Attack** | Sting +5 melee (1d8+2 plus poison) |
| **Full Attack** | Sting +5 melee (1d8+2 plus poison) and bite +0 melee (1d8+1) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Implant, poison |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., freedom of movement, low-light vision, scent, elemental resonance (air — canopy-predator) |
| **Saves** | Fort +8, Ref +7, Will +2 |
| **Abilities** | Str 15, Dex 17, Con 19, Int 2, Wis 12, Cha 10 |
| **Skills** | Listen +10 (4 ranks), Spot +11 (4 ranks, +4 racial) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Dodge |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Youngest Brother (Air) — canopy-predator; the resonance of the Great Forest’s upper airspace, wind filtered through leaves and channelled between tree-trunks |
| **Environment** | Great Forests (the mid-canopy and upper-canopy zones of the Great Forests — specifically the zones where giant spider populations are dense enough to support spider eater breeding cycles) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or pair |
| **Challenge Rating** | 5 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always neutral |
| **Advancement** | 5–7 HD (Large); 8–12 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A spider eater is a specialist predator — its entire biology is built around hunting giant spiders and implanting larvae in them. Against non-spider targets, it attacks only in self-defence or if extremely hungry, using its sting (which delivers a paralytic poison) and bite.

Against spiders, a spider eater is devastatingly efficient: dive from above (Flyby Attack if feat is taken at advancement), sting to deliver the implant, and withdraw before the spider can react. Freedom of movement makes it immune to web entanglement — the spider’s primary defence is useless.

### Special Abilities

**Implant (Ex):** A spider eater can implant an egg in a paralysed or helpless creature (preferably a spider). The egg hatches in 1d4 weeks, and the larva devours the host from within (dealing 2d6 damage per day until the host dies). *Remove disease* kills the egg.

**Poison (Ex):** Sting; Fortitude DC 16; initial damage paralysis for 1d8+5 minutes; no secondary damage. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Canopy-Predator Resonance (Su):** Spider eaters register on Kin-sense as upper-canopy wind — the Youngest Brother’s domain filtered through forest architecture. Detectable at 30 feet. Hasura elves in the canopy recognise spider eater resonance and consider the creatures beneficial (they control giant spider populations that would otherwise threaten Hasura canopy-settlements).

### Society

Spider eaters are the Great Forests’ aerial specialist-predators — large, fast-flying creatures that control giant spider populations through parasitic reproduction. Their ecological role is critical: without spider eaters, giant spider populations would expand unchecked, overwhelming the mid-canopy and threatening both Hasura canopy-settlements and Pasua ground-routes.

Hasura elves consider spider eaters allies and never hunt them. Hasura canopy-settlements near spider eater nesting-sites benefit from dramatically reduced spider-web density in the surrounding canopy. Pasua scouts value spider eaters for the same reason — a forest section with active spider eater populations is safer to traverse than one without.

### Lore

**DC 15 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Spider eaters are Large, flying predators that hunt giant spiders. Their sting delivers paralytic poison. They implant eggs in paralysed prey — the larvae consume the host from within. *Remove disease* kills the egg.

**DC 20:** Spider eaters are immune to web entanglement (freedom of movement). Hasura elves consider them beneficial allies that control spider populations. They nest in the upper canopy.

**DC 25:** Spider eater resonance is upper-canopy wind. Their ecological role is critical to forest health. A forest section with active spider eater populations has dramatically reduced giant spider density.

# SPIRIT NAGA

The waterway ahead is wrong. The current runs sluggishly, the colour is off — a faint yellow-green tinge beneath the surface — and the reeds along the bank are wilted despite adequate water. Something has corrupted this stretch of river, and the corruption has a voice. It speaks from the water: a woman’s voice, cultured, persuasive, and utterly, chillingly reasonable, explaining why you should come closer, why you should listen, why resistance to the inevitable is wasteful. The voice belongs to a creature coiled in the corrupted water — fifteen feet of scaled serpent-body supporting a human-like face with eyes that glow faint green and a smile that promises understanding it has no intention of delivering.

**Large Aberration**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Aberration |
| **Hit Dice** | 9d8+36 (76 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +1 |
| **Speed** | 40 ft. (8 squares), swim 20 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 19 (–1 size, +1 Dex, +9 natural), touch 10, flat-footed 18 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +6/+14 |
| **Attack** | Bite +9 melee (2d4+6 plus poison) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +9 melee (2d4+6 plus poison) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Charming gaze, poison, spells |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., elemental resonance (water — corrupted current) |
| **Saves** | Fort +7, Ref +6, Will +9 |
| **Abilities** | Str 18, Dex 13, Con 18, Int 16, Wis 17, Cha 18 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +16 (9 ranks), Concentration +16 (9 ranks), Diplomacy +12 (5 ranks), Listen +14 (9 ranks), Spellcraft +15 (9 ranks), Spot +14 (9 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Ability Focus (charming gaze), Combat Casting, Eschew Materials, Lightning Reflexes |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) — corrupted; the resonance of water that has been claimed and twisted by an intelligence that uses the Lady’s domain for its own purposes — river-current directed by will rather than gravity, water that serves a master |
| **Environment** | Corrupted Waterways (stretches of river, creek, or lake where a spirit naga has established territorial dominance — the water itself changes, becoming sluggish, discoloured, and hostile to normal aquatic life; most commonly found along Great River tributaries and the smaller waterways of the Kinsweave and Deepwater Marches) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or nest (2–4) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 9 |
| **Treasure** | Double standard |
| **Alignment** | Usually chaotic evil |
| **Advancement** | 10–13 HD (Large); 14–18 HD (Huge) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A spirit naga is a sorcerer-predator that fights with spells, charm, and poison in combination. It opens with charming gaze to neutralise the strongest-willed opponent, then casts offensive spells (*lightning bolt*, *fireball*) to damage the party while its charmed puppet fights on the naga’s behalf. Its bite delivers Constitution-damaging poison, used against targets that resist charm.

### Special Abilities

**Charming Gaze (Su):** 30 feet, DC 20 Will save or be charmed as *charm person* (caster level 9th). The save DC is Charisma-based (+2 Ability Focus).

**Poison (Ex):** Bite; Fortitude DC 18; initial and secondary damage 1d6 Con. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Spells:** A spirit naga casts spells as a 7th-level sorcerer (and can also cast spells from the cleric list as arcane spells): - 0 — *daze, detect magic, mage hand, message, ray of frost, read magic, resistance* - 1st (7/day) — *charm person* (DC 15), *cure light wounds, divine favour, magic missile, shield of faith* - 2nd (7/day) — *cat’s grace, invisibility, hold person* (DC 16) - 3rd (5/day) — *displacement, lightning bolt* (DC 17)

**Corrupted Current Resonance (Su):** A spirit naga registers on Kin-sense as water *claimed* — river-current no longer flowing naturally but directed by an intelligence. Detectable at 60 feet. The resonance extends through the corrupted waterway itself — Kin-sense users wading in naga-controlled water feel the corruption as a subtle wrongness, “water that knows you’re there and is deciding what to do about it.” Pekakarlik river-navigators describe the sensation as “the river getting a personality.”

### Society

Spirit nagas are territorial water-predators that claim stretches of waterway and corrupt them through sustained magical presence. They are intelligent, manipulative, and patient — a spirit naga establishes itself in a remote tributary, extends its corrupted influence over months or years, and eventually dominates a stretch of waterway long enough to threaten the communities downstream.

Pekakarlik river-navigators are the Kin culture most directly affected by spirit nagas. A spirit naga on a Great River tributary corrupts the water-quality, drives away river serpents (which will not tolerate corrupted water), and threatens Pekakarlik trade-routes that depend on clean, navigable waterways. Pekakarlik anti-naga response is coordinated and ruthless: when a spirit naga is identified, the Pekakarlik assemble a river-clearing team — experienced fighters, a Kin-sense specialist to track the corrupted resonance to the naga’s lair, and a cleric or spellcaster capable of countering the charming gaze.

Eruskan river-cities downstream of naga-corrupted tributaries experience water-quality degradation that affects public health. Eruskan civic authorities maintain bounties on spirit nagas — significant rewards for confirmed naga kills.

River serpents and spirit nagas are natural enemies. A river serpent will attack a spirit naga on sight — the corruption of the Lady of the Sea’s domain is an existential affront. A waterway stretch occupied by a spirit naga is, by definition, a stretch without river serpent protection.

### Lore

**DC 19 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Spirit nagas are Large aberrations that corrupt waterways. They charm with their gaze, cast spells as 7th-level sorcerers, and deliver Constitution-damaging poison. They are intelligent and manipulative.

**DC 24:** Spirit nagas corrupt water through sustained magical presence, driving away river serpents and threatening downstream communities. Pekakarlik assemble specialised river-clearing teams. Charming gaze DC 20 requires strong-willed front-line fighters.

**DC 29:** Corrupted current resonance extends through the claimed waterway — Kin-sense detects the wrongness in the water itself. River serpents and spirit nagas are natural enemies. Eruskan cities maintain bounties on spirit nagas.

# STIRGE

The first one lands on your neck before you feel it. That is the thing about stirges — they are small, they are quiet, and they latch on before you know they are there. The proboscis is thin as a needle and slides into your skin with a precision that a surgeon would envy. By the time you slap at it, the first pint is already gone. The second stirge lands on your arm. The third is on the horse. There are more in the air — a dozen, two dozen, darting and hovering like oversized mosquitoes with the wingspans of crows and the hunger of something that has not eaten in a week.

**Tiny Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Tiny Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 1d10 (5 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +4 |
| **Speed** | 10 ft. (2 squares), fly 40 ft. (average) |
| **Armor Class** | 16 (+2 size, +4 Dex), touch 16, flat-footed 12 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +1/–11 (+1 when attached) |
| **Attack** | Touch +7 melee touch (attach) |
| **Full Attack** | Touch +7 melee touch (attach) |
| **Space/Reach** | 2½ ft./0 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Attach, blood drain |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, scent, elemental resonance (none — vermin-analogue) |
| **Saves** | Fort +2, Ref +6, Will +1 |
| **Abilities** | Str 3, Dex 19, Con 10, Int 1, Wis 12, Cha 6 |
| **Skills** | Hide +14 (0 ranks, +8 size), Listen +4 (0 ranks), Spot +4 (0 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Weapon FinesseB |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — stirges have no elemental resonance; they are blood-feeding parasites that register on Kin-sense as barely-there biological noise, too small and too simple to carry elemental identity |
| **Environment** | Deepwater Marches (the warm, humid marshlands and swamp-forests of the Deepwater Marches — specifically the stagnant pools, reed-beds, and dense undergrowth where stirge swarms breed in standing water) |
| **Organization** | Colony (2–4), flock (5–8), or storm (9–14) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 1/2 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always neutral |
| **Advancement** | — |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A stirge has one tactic: attach and drain. It makes a touch attack to latch onto exposed skin, then drains 1d4 Constitution per round. A single stirge is an annoyance; a storm of 9–14 is a genuine threat — multiple simultaneous Constitution drains can incapacitate or kill even experienced combatants.

### Special Abilities

**Attach (Ex):** A stirge that hits with a touch attack latches onto the target. An attached stirge is effectively grappling but has a +12 racial bonus on grapple checks (already included). An attached stirge can be removed with a successful grapple check or by dealing damage to it (AC 12 while attached).

**Blood Drain (Ex):** An attached stirge drains blood, dealing 1d4 Constitution damage per round. A stirge that drains 4 points of Constitution detaches and flies away, sated.

### Society

Stirges are the Deepwater Marches’ most ubiquitous blood-parasites — tiny, numerous, and relentless. They are not dangerous individually, but their numbers make them a persistent environmental hazard that every culture operating in the Deepwater Marches has developed countermeasures for.

Halfling marsh-communities treat stirge management as routine pest-control — stirge-breeding pools are identified and drained or treated with herbal insecticides, and sleeping-shelters are equipped with fine-mesh netting. Halfling children learn stirge-avoidance before they learn to swim.

Pasua scouts crossing the Deepwater Marches carry stirge-repellent (a pungent herbal compound rubbed on exposed skin) and wear high-collared, tight-cuffed clothing. The Pasua term for stirge translates as “flying leech.”

### Lore

**DC 10 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Stirges are Tiny blood-draining flying creatures. They latch on and drain Constitution. Individually weak, dangerous in swarms. Found in marshes and wetlands.

**DC 15:** Halfling communities drain breeding-pools and use fine-mesh netting. A stirge detaches after draining 4 Constitution. Pasua scouts carry herbal repellent.

# STONE GIANT

The boulder moves. Not falls — *moves*, with the deliberate precision of something thrown by hands that know exactly where it will land. The second boulder follows three seconds later, and it lands exactly where the first would have driven you if you’d run. You look up. The figure on the cliff is sixty feet away and thirty feet tall, grey-skinned, long-armed, with a face like weathered granite and eyes that are calculating the trajectory of the third rock.

**Large Giant (Earth)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Giant (Earth) |
| **Hit Dice** | 14d8+56 (119 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +2 |
| **Speed** | 40 ft. (8 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 25 (–1 size, +2 Dex, +11 natural, +3 hide armour), touch 11, flat-footed 23 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +10/+22 |
| **Attack** | Greatclub +17 melee (2d8+12) or rock +11 ranged (2d8+8) |
| **Full Attack** | Greatclub +17/+12 melee (2d8+12) or rock +11 ranged (2d8+8) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./10 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Rock throwing (range 180 ft.) |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, rock catching, elemental resonance (earth — Giant remnant) |
| **Saves** | Fort +13, Ref +6, Will +7 |
| **Abilities** | Str 27, Dex 15, Con 19, Int 10, Wis 12, Cha 11 |
| **Skills** | Climb +11 (14 ranks), Hide +6 (14 ranks, +8 in rocky terrain), Listen +12 (14 ranks), Spot +12 (14 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Combat Reflexes, Iron Will, Point Blank Shot, Power Attack, Precise Shot |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) — Giant remnant; the resonance of the original Giants’ earth-attunement, diminished and fragmented but recognisably derived from the same source — the Lord of Stone’s domain expressed through beings that carry the Giants’ bloodline in diluted, feral form |
| **Environment** | Giant’s Teeth (the high mountain valleys, cliff-dwellings, and cave-systems of the Giant’s Teeth range — specifically the zones above Vestri mining-depth and below the snow-line, in the rock-country where stone giants can use their stone-throwing and rock-catching abilities to maximum tactical advantage) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, gang (2–5), band (6–9 plus 35% noncombatants), or tribe (21–30 plus 50% noncombatants) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 8 |
| **Treasure** | Standard |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | By character class |
| **Level Adjustment** | +4 |

### A Note on Stone Giants in Oreka

Stone giants in Oreka are **not Brutes**. They are the last surviving natural descendants of the original Giants — the Firstborn who shaped the world during the Age of Giants and vanished during the Thalorien (the Fading). Stone giants carry a diluted but genuine version of the Giants’ elemental heritage, and their presence in the Giant’s Teeth is the strongest remaining evidence that the original Giants were real beings of flesh and stone rather than purely mythological figures.

The distinction from Brutes is absolute and critical: Brutes (Hrokk, Goreham, Charjaw, Fogwrack) are Dómnathar-manufactured war-creatures that *look* like giants but are artificial, feral, and elementally void. Stone giants are natural beings with genuine elemental resonance, cultural traditions, and an ancestral connection to the world’s geological history.

### Combat

Stone giants fight from elevated positions, using rock throwing (180-foot range, 2d8+8 damage) with tactical precision — they calculate trajectories that account for cover, movement, and the tendency of targets to dodge in predictable directions. A stone giant on a cliff-face above an enemy is among the most difficult tactical problems in Oreka: attacking uphill against a creature that can throw boulders with the accuracy of a siege engine.

In melee, stone giants are straightforward — greatclub attacks with Str 27 deal devastating damage, and rock catching (they can catch thrown boulders, siege stones, and similar projectiles) makes ranged counter-attack difficult.

### Special Abilities

**Rock Throwing (Ex):** Range 180 feet. 2d8+8 damage.

**Rock Catching (Ex):** A stone giant can catch Small, Medium, or Large rocks (or similar projectiles) as a free action once per round with a DC 20 Reflex save.

**Giant Remnant Resonance (Su):** A stone giant registers on Kin-sense as the original Giants’ earth-resonance — diminished and fragmented, but recognisably derived from the Firstborn’s connection to the Lord of Stone. Detectable at 120 feet. The sensation is profoundly affecting for earth-attuned Kin: Vestri Dwarves describe encountering stone giant resonance as “hearing your grandfather’s voice in the mountain” — familiar, ancestral, and laden with the grief of something great that has been diminished. Stone giant resonance is the strongest evidence available through Kin-sense that the original Giants were real.

### Society

Stone giants live in small tribal communities in the high Giant’s Teeth — cliff-dwellings carved into mountain-faces, cave-complexes reinforced with dry-stone walls, and open-air camps on sheltered plateaus. They are the last natural Giant-descended people in Oreka, and their way of life reflects a culture in long, slow decline — a people who remember (through oral tradition) that they were once part of something vast and have accepted, with the patient resignation of stone, that the vastness is gone.

Vestri Dwarves maintain the most complex relationship with stone giants. The Vestri mine the same mountains that stone giants inhabit, and territorial disputes over specific valleys and cliff-faces are ongoing. However, the relationship is not purely adversarial — Vestri and stone giants have coexisted for millennia, and some Vestri mining-communities maintain trade-relationships with neighbouring stone giant tribes (Vestri metalwork for stone giant raw ore and gemstones).

The Vestri relationship with stone giants is deeply complicated by the Vestri awareness of what stone giants *represent*. The Vestri venerate the original Giants as the world’s builders, and stone giants — diminished, feral, but undeniably descended from the Firstborn — are living relics of that venerated past. Killing a stone giant weighs heavily on Vestri conscience in a way that killing a Brute (which is a Dómnathar manufacturing abomination) does not.

Orean mountain-communities occasionally encounter stone giant hunting-parties in the foothills and maintain cautious distance. Orean tradition includes stone giants in the category of “the old ones” — beings from before Kin-memory that belong to the mountains in ways the Kin do not.

### Lore

**DC 18 (Knowledge [nature]):** Stone giants are Large, intelligent natural giants of the Giant’s Teeth. They throw boulders with devastating accuracy (180-foot range) and can catch thrown projectiles. They are NOT Brutes — they are genuine descendants of the original Giants.

**DC 23:** Stone giants carry diluted Giant-remnant resonance — the strongest remaining evidence of the original Giants’ elemental heritage. Vestri mining-communities maintain trade-relationships with some tribes. The Vestri relationship is complicated by veneration of the original Giants.

**DC 28:** Stone giant resonance is the Firstborn’s earth-attunement, diminished but recognisable. Earth-attuned Kin find the sensation profoundly moving. Stone giant oral traditions include memories of the Thalorien. Their culture represents the last living connection to the Age of Giants.

# STORM WISP

The air crackles. A blue-white sphere of light — no larger than a fist, but bright enough to leave afterimages — darts between the trees, pauses, darts again. It moves like a dragonfly: sudden direction-changes, instantaneous stops, bursts of speed that defy any creature with mass. Your arm-hair stands up. The taste of metal fills your mouth. The Pasua scout beside you grins. “Wisp,” she says. “Don’t touch. Don’t touch *anything metal*.”

**Tiny Elemental (Air, Extraplanar)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Tiny Elemental (Air, Extraplanar) |
| **Hit Dice** | 3d8 (13 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +7 |
| **Speed** | Fly 60 ft. (perfect) |
| **Armor Class** | 17 (+2 size, +3 Dex, +2 deflection), touch 17, flat-footed 14 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +2/–8 |
| **Attack** | Electric touch +7 melee touch (1d6 electricity) |
| **Full Attack** | Electric touch +7 melee touch (1d6 electricity) |
| **Space/Reach** | 2½ ft./0 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Electric touch, static burst |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., electricity immunity, natural invisibility, wind dependent, gaseous form, earth/acid vulnerability, elemental resonance (air — raw static), the Harmony |
| **Saves** | Fort +1, Ref +6, Will +2 |
| **Abilities** | Str 4, Dex 17, Con 10, Int 4, Wis 12, Cha 13 |
| **Skills** | Hide +14 (3 ranks), Listen +7 (3 ranks), Move Silently +9 (3 ranks), Spot +7 (3 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Improved Initiative, Weapon Finesse |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Youngest Brother (Air) — raw; the purest, most unrefined expression of the Youngest Brother’s domain, wind as playful electrical discharge, the air-element at its most mischievous and least controlled |
| **Environment** | Great Forests (primary — the forest canopy and clearings during storm season) and Eternal Steppe (secondary — open grasslands during thunderstorms); anywhere with frequent storms and sustained wind |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or swirl (3–6) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 2 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 4–6 HD (Tiny); 7–9 HD (Small — transition toward Storm Herald) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

Storm wisps do not fight tactically — they react to stimuli. They are drawn to campfires, metal equipment, and living creatures, and deliver painful but usually non-lethal electric shocks through contact. A swirl of 3–6 wisps is more dangerous, as their static bursts can chain.

A storm wisp does not intentionally attack Kin — the shocks are more mischief than malice. However, the damage is real, and metal armour or weapons conduct the electricity with enhanced effect (–2 on saves against static burst for creatures wearing metal).

### Special Abilities

**Electric Touch (Su):** 1d6 electricity damage. On a critical hit (19–20), the target must succeed on a DC 13 Fortitude save or be stunned for 1 round. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Static Burst (Su):** Once per day, a storm wisp can release a 10-foot-radius burst of electrical energy dealing 2d6 electricity damage (DC 13 Reflex save for half). Metal armour or weapons impose –2 on the save. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Natural Invisibility (Su):** Storm wisps are naturally invisible during calm weather. During storms, rain, or high winds, they become visible as crackling blue-white spheres. *See invisibility* or *true seeing* reveals them at all times.

**Wind Dependent (Ex):** In completely calm, windless conditions, storm wisps take 1 point of damage per round and cannot use static burst.

**Gaseous Form (Su):** At will, a storm wisp can become ionised air (as *gaseous form*) retaining fly speed. It cannot attack in this form.

**Raw Static Resonance (Su):** Storm wisps register on Kin-sense as raw air-element crackle — faint, intermittent, like the feeling before a lightning strike. Detectable at 15 feet per wisp; a swirl of six generates a combined field at 90 feet. Pasua elves and Mytroan wind-callers find the sensation delightful; earth-attuned Kin (Vestri, Pekakarlik) find it itchy and distracting.

### Society

Storm wisps are the common tier of the Storm Wisp Elemental Sovereign family — tiny, mischievous air-elementals that represent the Youngest Brother’s domain at its most playful and least controlled. They are the most commonly encountered Elemental Sovereign creatures and the most deeply integrated into everyday Kin life during storm-season.

Pasua elves have the warmest relationship with storm wisps. Pasua charm-singers have songs that soothe agitated wisps, and Pasua scouts consider a swirl of wisps in the canopy a sign of healthy forest-air. The Pasua term for storm wisps translates as “the Brother’s laughter” — affectionate, slightly exasperated.

Mytroan wind-callers on the Eternal Steppe treat storm wisps as weather-omens. Storm wisp activity precedes thunderstorms by hours, and Mytroan herders who observe wisp-behaviour can predict storm intensity and direction with remarkable accuracy. Some Mytroan clans claim specific wisps as guardian-spirits, though whether a wisp with Int 4 can meaningfully serve as a guardian is debatable.

Storm wisps are the youngest form of a family that includes Storm Heralds (Large, CR 8 — vaguely avian shapes of compressed wind and lightning) and Gale Sovereigns (Gargantuan, CR 15 — living, thinking storms that remember the Age of Giants). This lifecycle means every storm wisp is a potential Gale Sovereign, though the transition takes millennia.

### Lore

**DC 12 (Knowledge [arcana] or [nature]):** Storm wisps are Tiny air-elementals — crackling spheres of blue-white energy found during storm season. Their touch delivers electrical shocks. They are naturally invisible in calm weather.

**DC 17:** Storm wisps are mischievous, not malicious. Metal armour conducts their electricity (–2 saves). Pasua charm-songs soothe agitated wisps. They take damage in windless conditions.

**DC 22:** Storm wisps are the common tier of the Storm Wisp Elemental Sovereign family, which includes Storm Heralds and Gale Sovereigns. Mytroan wind-callers use wisp-behaviour to predict thunderstorms. The raw static resonance is the Youngest Brother’s most unrefined expression.

# SUPAY

The mine-shaft is old — older than the Vestri tunnels above it, older than the Orean settlements in the foothills, old enough that the tool-marks on the walls were made by hands larger than any Kin’s. The air at the bottom of the shaft is not stale. It is *warm*, the wrong kind of warm — not geothermal warmth but the warmth of a presence, of something breathing in the dark. The Orean miners who mapped this shaft went no further than this landing, and the reason is carved into the wall in Old Orean: a single glyph that means “he is below.” *He*. Not *it*. The miners knew what lived down here, and they gave it a pronoun of respect.

**Large Outsider**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Outsider |
| **Hit Dice** | 14d8+70 (133 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +2 |
| **Speed** | 40 ft. (8 squares), burrow 20 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 26 (–1 size, +2 Dex, +15 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 24 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +14/+26 |
| **Attack** | Claw +21 melee (2d6+8 plus death-mark) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 claws +21 melee (2d6+8 plus death-mark) and bite +19 melee (1d8+4) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./10 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Death-mark, earth command, spell-like abilities |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 120 ft., damage reduction 10/good, spell resistance 24, tremorsense 60 ft., earth glide, fire resistance 20, cold resistance 20, elemental resonance (earth — sovereign depth, underworld authority) |
| **Saves** | Fort +14, Ref +11, Will +14 |
| **Abilities** | Str 26, Dex 14, Con 20, Int 18, Wis 20, Cha 20 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +22 (14 ranks), Diplomacy +22 (14 ranks), Intimidate +22 (14 ranks), Knowledge (history) +21 (14 ranks), Knowledge (religion) +21 (14 ranks), Knowledge (the planes) +21 (14 ranks), Listen +22 (14 ranks), Sense Motive +22 (14 ranks), Spot +22 (14 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Awesome Blow, Cleave, Improved Bull Rush, Multiattack, Power Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) — sovereign depth; the resonance of the deepest earth, the stone that has never seen light, the Lord of Stone’s domain at its most absolute and most ancient — not the worked-stone of mines or the living-stone of mountains but the primordial substrate beneath everything |
| **Environment** | Deep Caverns (the deepest natural cave-systems beneath the Giant’s Teeth foothills — specifically the ancient mine-shafts and subterranean chambers that Orean mountain-communities have mapped and sealed, where the earth is old enough to have its own ruler) |
| **Organization** | Solitary (always — a supay claims a domain and rules it alone) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 10 |
| **Treasure** | Double standard (mineral wealth — gemstones, precious metals, and rare ores accumulated over centuries of domain-rule; a supay’s treasure-hoard is a geological deposit that the supay considers its personal property) |
| **Alignment** | Usually lawful neutral |
| **Advancement** | 15–21 HD (Large); 22–28 HD (Huge — the eldest domain-rulers) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A supay fights to defend its domain — the subterranean territory it has claimed and ruled for centuries. It does not pursue intruders who retreat; it does not venture to the surface; it does not attack creatures that enter its domain with respectful intent. A supay that determines visitors are miners or explorers rather than invaders will parley, and its terms are consistent: you may enter, but you may not take. The minerals in the supay’s domain are the supay’s property, and removing them without permission is theft, punished by death.

When combat is unavoidable, a supay is devastating. Earth command allows it to reshape the terrain — closing tunnel-mouths, opening fissures beneath targets’ feet, and collapsing ceilings. Earth glide lets it move through stone as a fish moves through water, attacking from walls, floors, and ceilings with no warning. The death-mark ensures that creatures the supay has struck cannot hide — it knows where they are, anywhere in its domain, until the mark fades.

### Special Abilities

**Death-Mark (Su):** A creature struck by a supay’s claw must succeed on a DC 22 Will save or be death-marked for 24 hours. The supay knows the exact location of any death-marked creature within 1 mile. A death-marked creature takes –2 on saves against the supay’s spell-like abilities. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Earth Command (Su):** Three times per day, a supay can reshape stone within 60 feet as a standard action. Effects include: close a tunnel-mouth (as *wall of stone*), open a 10-foot-deep fissure beneath a target (DC 22 Reflex save or fall, taking 1d6 damage), collapse a 10-foot section of ceiling (4d6 damage, DC 22 Reflex save for half). The save DCs are Charisma-based.

**Earth Glide (Su):** A supay can move through stone as easily as a fish swims through water. It leaves no tunnel and creates no vibration (tremorsense does not detect it while earth-gliding). It can attack from within stone, emerging to strike and re-entering in the same round.

**Spell-Like Abilities:** Caster level 14th. Save DCs are Charisma-based (DC 15 + spell level). - At will — *detect magic, stone shape, meld into stone* - 3/day — *transmute rock to mud* (DC 20), *wall of stone* (DC 20), *spike stones* (DC 19) - 1/day — *earthquake* (DC 23), *imprisonment* (DC 24, earth-variant — the target is entombed in stone)

**Sovereign Depth Resonance (Su):** A supay registers on Kin-sense as the deepest earth — the Lord of Stone’s domain at its most absolute, stone that has never been touched by light or tool. Detectable at 120 feet through stone, 60 feet in open air. Earth-attuned Kin (Vestri, Orean) describe the sensation as “the mountain reminding you who owns it” — not hostile but *authoritative*, the unquestionable dominion of something that was here first and will be here last.

### Society

Supay are the sovereign rulers of the deep earth beneath the Giant’s Teeth foothills — powerful outsiders that claim subterranean domains and govern them with the absolute authority of territorial lords. Each supay is unique, each claims a specific domain (typically an ancient cave-system or sealed mine-complex), and each has ruled that domain for centuries or millennia.

Orean mountain-communities have the oldest and deepest supay-traditions. Orean mining-culture includes specific protocols for entering supay domains: approach is announced (striking a specific rhythm on the tunnel-wall), intent is stated clearly (in Old Orean, the traditional language of supay-communication), and offerings are made (precious metals, gemstones, or rare ores brought *into* the domain as gifts, not taken *out*). A supay that accepts the offering permits passage and limited resource-extraction; one that rejects the offering commands the intruders to leave, and refusal means death.

Orean theology integrates supay as the Lord of Stone’s appointed wardens of the deep earth — beings that ensure the mineral wealth beneath the mountains is not exhausted by surface-folk. This theological framework supports the Orean cultural practice of sustainable mining: take only what is needed, replace what you can, and always ask permission.

Vestri Dwarves who mine deep enough to encounter supay domains maintain a different relationship — more transactional, less theological. Vestri deep-shaft engineers negotiate with supay on commercial terms: specific quantities of ore in exchange for specific tributes, with clear boundaries and formal agreements. The Vestri respect supay as territorial powers, not as spiritual authorities.

Dómnathar tunnel-networks occasionally encroach on supay domains, and the results are consistently catastrophic — for the Dómnathar. A supay defending its domain against Dómnathar incursion fights with the full power of earthquake and imprisonment, collapsing tunnel-sections and entombing Dómnathar troops in stone. Several Dómnathar Houses have learned to route around known supay domains rather than attempt to tunnel through them.

### Lore

**DC 20 (Knowledge [the planes]):** Supay are Large outsiders that rule deep subterranean domains. They reshape stone at will, glide through earth, and fight with devastating power. DR 10/good, SR 24. They do not attack respectful visitors.

**DC 25:** Supay permit limited resource-extraction in exchange for tribute. Orean mining-protocols include ritual announcement, formal permission-requests, and offerings. Death-mark ensures struck creatures cannot hide within the supay’s domain.

**DC 30:** Supay resonance is sovereign depth — the Lord of Stone’s deepest authority. Dómnathar Houses route around known supay domains. The *imprisonment* variant entombs targets in stone. Supay have governed their domains for centuries or millennia.

# SVARTÁLFAR SHADE

The dwarf-hall is empty. It has been empty for a long time — the forge-fires are cold, the tool-racks bare, the sleeping-quarters stripped of everything portable. The Vestri who abandoned this hall took everything they could carry and left everything they could not, and what they could not carry included their dead. The shade drifts through the doorway of the memorial-chamber with the slow, deliberate movement of something that is still performing a duty it was assigned a very long time ago. It is translucent — the suggestion of a dwarf in Vestri forge-armour, carrying a tool that might be a hammer and might be a weapon, with a face that expresses nothing because the shade has forgotten what it was supposed to feel. It is not hostile. It is not friendly. It is *present*, in the way that the walls are present and the cold forge is present, and it will be here until the hall falls or the world ends, because this is its post and no one has relieved it.

**Medium Undead (Incorporeal)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Undead (Incorporeal) |
| **Hit Dice** | 4d12 (26 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +1 |
| **Speed** | Fly 30 ft. (perfect) |
| **Armor Class** | 14 (+1 Dex, +3 deflection), touch 14, flat-footed 13 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +2/— |
| **Attack** | Incorporeal touch +3 melee touch (1d4 plus forge-chill) |
| **Full Attack** | Incorporeal touch +3 melee touch (1d4 plus forge-chill) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Forge-chill, duty-call |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., incorporeal traits, undead traits, duty-bound, hall-tethered, +2 turn resistance, elemental resonance (earth — fading Vestri) |
| **Saves** | Fort +1, Ref +2, Will +6 |
| **Abilities** | Str —, Dex 13, Con —, Int 8, Wis 14, Cha 16 |
| **Skills** | Craft (any one) +6 (4 ranks), Hide +8 (4 ranks), Listen +9 (4 ranks), Search +6 (4 ranks), Spot +9 (4 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Iron Will |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) — fading; the resonance of Vestri earth-attunement diminished by death but not extinguished — a candle’s afterglow where a forge-fire once burned, recognisably dwarven, recognisably diminished |
| **Environment** | Abandoned Dwarf Halls (the sealed, evacuated, or forgotten mining-halls and forge-complexes of the Vestri Dwarven infrastructure — specifically the halls abandoned during the centuries of contraction following the Fall of Aldenheim, where Vestri dead were left in memorial-chambers when the living withdrew) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or garrison (3–8) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 3 |
| **Treasure** | None (the shade carries nothing; the hall may contain residual Vestri equipment too heavy or too damaged to evacuate) |
| **Alignment** | Usually lawful neutral |
| **Advancement** | 5–8 HD (Medium) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A svartálfar shade does not attack without provocation. It is duty-bound — tethered to the abandoned hall it guards, compelled to defend the hall’s contents and memorial-chambers against intruders. A creature that enters the hall without hostile intent and does not disturb the memorial-dead is ignored. A creature that loots, damages, or disrespects the hall or its dead is attacked.

When provoked, a shade fights with methodical, passionless efficiency — incorporeal touch delivers forge-chill (Strength damage that represents the sapping of vitality by cold, unworked stone), and duty-call summons other shades in the hall to converge on the threat. A garrison of 3–8 shades coordinating through duty-call can overwhelm a party that entered expecting empty halls.

### Special Abilities

**Forge-Chill (Su):** A svartálfar shade’s incorporeal touch deals 1d4 damage plus 1d4 Strength damage. The Strength damage represents heat and vitality draining into the shade — the forge-fire that the shade remembers, pulling warmth from the living to sustain a memory of work that will never be completed. DC 15 Fortitude save negates the Strength damage. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Duty-Call (Su):** As a standard action, a svartálfar shade can emit a silent pulse that alerts all other svartálfar shades within 500 feet to the presence of intruders. Alerted shades converge on the caller’s location at fly speed. This is not a compulsion — it is a communication, and shades that are engaged elsewhere may choose not to respond.

**Duty-Bound (Su):** A svartálfar shade cannot willingly leave the abandoned hall it guards. It can be turned but not destroyed by turning — a turned shade retreats to the deepest chamber of the hall and remains there until the turning effect ends. *Hallow* cast within the hall gives the shade permanent rest (destroying it peacefully); *desecrate* cast within the hall enrages the shade, removing its lawful neutral restraint and making it hostile to all living creatures.

**Hall-Tethered (Su):** A svartálfar shade exists only within its hall. It cannot pass through the hall’s outer walls or exits. If the hall is destroyed (collapsed, flooded, or otherwise rendered structurally non-existent), the shade dissipates permanently.

**Fading Vestri Resonance (Su):** A svartálfar shade registers on Kin-sense as fading dwarven earth-resonance — the Lord of Stone’s domain as experienced by a Vestri soul that has not fully departed. Detectable at 30 feet. Vestri Dwarves who detect svartálfar shade resonance describe it as “hearing the forge-song through a closed door” — recognisably Vestri, recognisably diminished, and profoundly melancholy. The resonance is not hostile — it is *loyal*, the residual duty-sense of a dwarf who died at their post and has not been relieved.

### Society

Svartálfar shades are the duty-bound dead of the Vestri Dwarves — incorporeal remnants of dwarves who died in halls that were subsequently abandoned, left behind when the living withdrew. They are not malicious, not tormented, and not hostile by nature. They are *on duty*. The hall is their post, the memorial-dead are their charge, and they will guard both until relieved, destroyed, or the hall ceases to exist.

The phenomenon is unique to the Vestri. Vestri cultural values — duty, craftsmanship, loyalty to one’s post — are so deeply embedded that Vestri dead in abandoned halls sometimes fail to *stop working*. The shade is not a curse or a necromantic creation; it is the natural consequence of a dwarf whose sense of duty outlasted their body.

Vestri Dwarves who encounter svartálfar shades in abandoned halls treat them with solemn respect. The standard Vestri protocol is to announce oneself by name and purpose (in formal Vestri, using the cadences of military reporting), identify the dead in the memorial-chambers (by name if possible, by regiment if not), and formally relieve the shade of its duty. A shade that is formally relieved — told by a living Vestri authority that its watch is over and its dead are honoured — dissipates peacefully, the duty fulfilled at last.

This protocol does not always work. Some shades have been on duty so long that they no longer recognise living Vestri — the dialect has changed, the uniforms have changed, and the shade’s diminished Int 8 cannot process the differences. These shades must be laid to rest through *hallow* or through the patient, repeated application of the relief-protocol until the shade’s residual recognition responds.

The Fall of Aldenheim produced the largest concentration of svartálfar shades in Oreka — the sealed lower halls of Aldenheim contain an unknown number of shades guarding memorial-chambers that no living Vestri has entered in centuries. Vestri tradition holds that the shades of Aldenheim are still on duty, still guarding the dead, still waiting to be relieved.

### Lore

**DC 13 (Knowledge [religion]):** Svartálfar shades are incorporeal undead found in abandoned Vestri dwarf-halls. They guard the halls and their memorial-dead. They do not attack unless provoked by looting or disrespect.

**DC 18:** Shades can be formally relieved of duty by a living Vestri authority, causing them to dissipate peacefully. Their forge-chill touch drains Strength. Duty-call summons other shades in the hall. *Hallow* grants permanent rest; *desecrate* enrages them.

**DC 23:** Svartálfar shade resonance is fading Vestri earth-attunement — recognisably dwarven, recognisably diminished. They are unique to Vestri culture, born from duty-sense that outlasts death. The sealed Aldenheim lower halls contain an unknown number of shades still on duty.

# TANIWHA

The cave-pool is still — perfectly still, in the way that only deep water in enclosed stone can be. The Kovaka dive-master kneels at the pool’s edge and presses her palm flat against the water’s surface without breaking it. She holds the position for thirty seconds. Then she withdraws her hand and nods. “It’s home,” she says. “Be respectful.” The water stirs. Something vast moves beneath the surface — a shape that the torchlight catches in fragments: a scaled ridge, a limb thick as a tree-trunk, a head that breaks the surface with a sound like a door opening in a cathedral. It is a lizard — or it was, before it became something older and more sacred. Its eyes reflect the torchlight with a luminous green intelligence, and its jaws could close around a canoe. It regards you. The Kovaka dive-master bows. You bow too, because the alternative is unthinkable.

**Huge Magical Beast (Aquatic)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Huge Magical Beast (Aquatic) |
| **Hit Dice** | 12d10+72 (138 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +1 |
| **Speed** | 20 ft. (4 squares), swim 60 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 24 (–2 size, +1 Dex, +15 natural), touch 9, flat-footed 23 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +12/+30 |
| **Attack** | Bite +20 melee (2d8+10) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +20 melee (2d8+10) and tail slap +18 melee (2d6+5) |
| **Space/Reach** | 15 ft./10 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Improved grab, swallow whole, tidal surge |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., water sense 200 ft., water breathing, damage reduction 10/magic, spell resistance 22, pool-ward, elemental resonance (water-earth — cave-pool sovereign), the Harmony |
| **Saves** | Fort +14, Ref +9, Will +8 |
| **Abilities** | Str 30, Dex 12, Con 22, Int 10, Wis 18, Cha 16 |
| **Skills** | Hide +8 (12 ranks, +8 in water), Listen +19 (12 ranks), Spot +19 (12 ranks), Swim +18 (0 ranks, +8 racial) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Cleave, Improved Natural Attack (bite), Multiattack, Power Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea / Lord of Stone (Water/Earth) — cave-pool sovereign; the resonance of underground water in shaped stone, the Lady’s domain enclosed by the Lord’s architecture — water that has been held in stone so long that the two elements have merged into something inseparable |
| **Environment** | Cave Pools (the deep, still pools within Kovaka coastal cave-systems — specifically the limestone caverns and sea-caves where underground freshwater meets tidal salt-water, creating the brackish cave-pools that taniwha claim as permanent territories) |
| **Organization** | Solitary |
| **Challenge Rating** | 9 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (accumulated on the pool-bottom — offerings from Kovaka communities, lost equipment from drowned explorers, and natural mineral deposits polished smooth by centuries of water-contact) |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 13–18 HD (Huge); 19–24 HD (Gargantuan — the eldest pool-sovereigns) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A taniwha fights to defend its pool — the cave-pool territory it has claimed and inhabited for decades or centuries. It does not pursue intruders who flee the pool-chamber, and it does not attack creatures that approach the pool with visible respect (the Kovaka palm-press greeting). A taniwha that determines visitors are hostile — or that determines they intend to pollute, dam, or otherwise alter the pool — attacks with the full devastating power of a Huge aquatic apex predator.

Underwater, a taniwha is nearly unbeatable. Water sense (200-foot blindsight while submerged) means nothing in the pool escapes its awareness. The bite grapples Medium or smaller creatures, leading to swallow whole. Tidal surge pushes multiple opponents away from the pool-centre (the taniwha’s preferred fighting position).

### Special Abilities

**Improved Grab (Ex):** On a successful bite against a Large or smaller creature.

**Swallow Whole (Ex):** A taniwha can swallow a Medium or smaller creature. Swallowed creatures take 2d8+10 crushing plus 4 acid damage per round. The gizzard has AC 17 and 20 hp.

**Tidal Surge (Su):** Three times per day, the taniwha generates a pressurised wave in a 30-foot cone. Creatures in the cone take 4d6 bludgeoning damage and are pushed back 20 feet (DC 22 Reflex save for half damage, negates push). The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Pool-Ward (Su):** A taniwha’s presence purifies the water within its pool over 1d4 days. Pollutants, diseases, and magical contaminants are neutralised. The pool-ward is passive and constant. Additionally, the taniwha is aware of any creature that enters the pool’s water — this awareness has no range limit within the pool itself.

**Water Sense (Ex):** Blindsight 200 feet while submerged.

**Cave-Pool Sovereign Resonance (Su):** A taniwha registers on Kin-sense as water-in-stone — the dual resonance of underground water held in geological architecture. Detectable at 60 feet. Kovaka coastal elves describe it as “the cave remembering rain” — the sensation of ancient water and ancient stone existing in perfect equilibrium. The resonance extends through the pool’s water — any creature touching the pool-water can detect the taniwha’s presence.

### Society

Taniwha are the cave-pool sovereigns of Kovaka coastal territory — Huge, long-lived, intelligent aquatic predators that claim specific cave-pools and guard them for centuries. They are not servants of the Kin, not hostile by nature, and not mindless — they are territorial rulers whose authority over their pools is absolute and whose relationship with the Kovaka elves who share their coastal habitat is one of the most formalised creature-Kin arrangements in Oreka.

Kovaka coastal communities maintain taniwha relationships as a matter of survival and reverence. The cave-pools that taniwha inhabit are freshwater sources of extraordinary purity (the pool-ward effect), and Kovaka settlements are frequently built near taniwha pools specifically to access the purified water. In exchange, Kovaka maintain the cave-systems, prevent pollution of the water-sources feeding the pool, and make regular offerings (fresh fish, polished stone, occasionally worked-metal objects).

Kovaka dive-masters — the specialised swimmers who serve as the primary point of contact between Kovaka communities and aquatic creatures — learn the taniwha palm-press greeting as a fundamental skill: palm flat on the water’s surface, held motionless, signalling peaceful intent. A taniwha that accepts the greeting allows entry; one that does not accepts it (the water ripples violently) means *leave now*.

The taniwha and the ponaturi are natural enemies. Ponaturi inhabit flooded Giant ruins — the underwater structures that taniwha consider an affront to clean water. A taniwha that discovers ponaturi in its pool-system attacks without hesitation, and a single taniwha can clear a ponaturi colony of a dozen in hours.

### Lore

**DC 19 (Knowledge [nature]):** Taniwha are Huge, intelligent aquatic guardians of cave-pools. They purify water through passive presence. They are territorial but not hostile to respectful visitors. DR 10/magic, SR 22.

**DC 24:** Kovaka dive-masters use the palm-press greeting to establish peaceful contact. Taniwha and ponaturi are natural enemies. Swallow whole and tidal surge are the primary combat abilities.

**DC 29:** Taniwha resonance is water-in-stone — detectable through the pool-water itself. Kovaka settlements are built near taniwha pools for purified water. The eldest taniwha have guarded their pools for centuries.

# TENDRICULOS

The Deepwood is dense — dense enough that sunlight reaches the forest floor only in thin, scattered beams, and the undergrowth is a tangle of moss, root, and fallen branch. The mound ahead looks like a compost-heap, green with new growth. It is not a compost-heap. The vines that compose it are moving, slowly, independently, and the opening at the mound’s centre — the one that looks like a hollow in the vegetation — is lined with thorns the length of daggers, and it is a mouth.

**Huge Plant**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Huge Plant |
| **Hit Dice** | 9d8+54 (94 hp) |
| **Initiative** | –1 |
| **Speed** | 20 ft. (4 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 16 (–2 size, –1 Dex, +9 natural), touch 7, flat-footed 16 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +6/+22 |
| **Attack** | Bite +12 melee (2d8+8) or tendril +12 melee (1d6+8) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +12 melee (2d8+8) and 2 tendrils +7 melee (1d6+4) |
| **Space/Reach** | 15 ft./15 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Improved grab, swallow whole, paralysis |
| **Special Qualities** | Low-light vision, plant traits, regeneration 10 (bludgeoning and fire), elemental resonance (earth — ravenous growth) |
| **Saves** | Fort +12, Ref +2, Will +4 |
| **Abilities** | Str 28, Dex 9, Con 22, Int 3, Wis 8, Cha 3 |
| **Skills** | Hide +1 (0 ranks, +8 in dense vegetation), Listen +1 (0 ranks), Move Silently +1 (0 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Iron Will, Power Attack, Stealthy |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) — ravenous growth; the resonance of earth-fertility pushed to destructive excess, soil so rich and so hungry that everything planted in it grows beyond control and consumes everything around it |
| **Environment** | Deepwood (the densest, darkest zones of the Great Forests — the old-growth interiors where the canopy blocks nearly all light and the undergrowth is so thick that navigation is by sound and touch rather than sight) |
| **Organization** | Solitary |
| **Challenge Rating** | 6 |
| **Treasure** | 1/10th coins; 50% goods; 50% items (found inside — undigested equipment from swallowed victims) |
| **Alignment** | Always neutral |
| **Advancement** | 10–16 HD (Huge); 17–27 HD (Gargantuan) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A tendriculos is a sit-and-wait predator that lurks in dense vegetation, disguised as a mound of growth (Hide +8 in vegetation). Its tendrils grab targets at 15-foot reach, pulling them toward the central maw. The bite delivers paralysis (DC 20 Fortitude save or paralysed 3d6 rounds), and a paralysed creature is swallowed whole on the following round.

Regeneration 10 makes the tendriculos extremely durable — only bludgeoning and fire damage are not regenerated. Slashing weapons, piercing weapons, and most magical damage are regenerated within rounds. A party without fire or heavy blunt weapons faces an effectively unkillable plant.

### Special Abilities

**Paralysis (Ex):** Bite; DC 20 Fortitude save or paralysed for 3d6 rounds. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Improved Grab (Ex):** On a successful tendril or bite attack against a Large or smaller creature.

**Swallow Whole (Ex):** A tendriculos can swallow a paralysed or grappled Medium or smaller creature. Swallowed creatures take 2d6 acid damage plus 2d6 bludgeoning per round. Interior AC 14, 15 hp. The tendriculos can hold 1 Large, 2 Medium, or 8 Small creatures.

**Regeneration 10 (Ex):** Bludgeoning and fire damage are not regenerated.

**Ravenous Growth Resonance (Su):** A tendriculos registers on Kin-sense as earth-fertility gone wrong — the Lord of Stone’s growing-aspect pushed to destructive hunger. Detectable at 30 feet, but easily confused with dense forest ambient-resonance (DC 22 to distinguish). Pasua scouts describe it as “the forest getting greedy” — a concentration of earth-growth resonance so intense it feels predatory.

### Society

Tendriculos are the Deepwood’s apex plant-predators — stationary ambush organisms that consume any animal that wanders within tendril-reach. They are not intelligent in any meaningful sense (Int 3) and have no social behaviour.

Pasua scouts who patrol the Deepwood treat tendriculos as environmental hazards comparable to quicksand or cliff-edges. Pasua Deepwood-protocols include the tendriculos-check: before camping in dense undergrowth, drive a wooden stake into any suspicious mound of vegetation and observe the reaction. A tendriculos reacts to the stimulus within seconds.

Hasura elves in the canopy above the Deepwood are largely unaffected by tendriculos (the creatures cannot reach the canopy) but warn Pasua scouts about new tendriculos growth observed from above.

### Lore

**DC 16 (Knowledge [nature]):** Tendriculos are Huge, carnivorous plants that swallow prey whole. Their bite paralyses. Regeneration 10 makes them nearly unkillable — only bludgeoning and fire damage stick. Found in the densest Deepwood zones.

**DC 21:** Tendriculos disguise as compost-mounds in dense vegetation. Pasua stake-test identifies them. Swallowed creatures take acid and crushing damage. They cannot be killed by slashing or piercing weapons alone.

**DC 26:** Tendriculos resonance is ravenous earth-growth — fertility pushed to predatory excess. DC 22 to distinguish from ambient Deepwood resonance. Hasura canopy-watchers track new tendriculos growth from above.

# TENGU

The Hasura canopy-platform is a hundred feet above the forest floor, and the creature standing at the edge of the platform should not be able to stand there — the branch is too narrow for anything larger than a squirrel. But the tengu stands with the casual balance of something born to the air, its taloned feet gripping the bark with an ease that makes the Hasura sentinel beside you look clumsy by comparison. It is man-shaped — roughly — with a raven’s head, a raven’s beak, and wings folded against its back that it wears like a cloak. Its eyes are black and bright and sharp, and the sword at its hip is the finest blade you have ever seen. It looks at you. It looks at the sentinel. It says something in Hasura that makes the sentinel laugh and then immediately look embarrassed. The tengu grins — which, on a raven’s beak, is a remarkable expression.

**Medium Outsider (Air)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Outsider (Air) |
| **Hit Dice** | 8d8+16 (52 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +4 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), fly 60 ft. (good) |
| **Armor Class** | 20 (+4 Dex, +6 natural), touch 14, flat-footed 16 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +8/+10 |
| **Attack** | Masterwork katana +13 melee (1d10+3/19–20) or talon +10 melee (1d4+2) |
| **Full Attack** | Masterwork katana +13/+8 melee (1d10+3/19–20) and wing buffet +8 melee (1d4+1) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Spell-like abilities, wind gust |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., damage reduction 5/cold iron, spell resistance 19, feather fall (constant), elemental resonance (air — canopy-wind, high-dwelling) |
| **Saves** | Fort +8, Ref +10, Will +8 |
| **Abilities** | Str 14, Dex 19, Con 14, Int 16, Wis 15, Cha 16 |
| **Skills** | Balance +15 (8 ranks), Bluff +14 (8 ranks), Craft (weaponsmithing) +14 (8 ranks), Diplomacy +14 (8 ranks), Hide +15 (8 ranks), Knowledge (nature) +14 (8 ranks), Listen +13 (8 ranks), Move Silently +15 (8 ranks), Sense Motive +13 (8 ranks), Tumble +15 (8 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Combat Expertise, Dodge, Weapon Finesse, Weapon Focus (katana) |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Youngest Brother (Air) — canopy-wind; the resonance of wind in the highest forest, air channelled through branch-architecture into currents that only canopy-dwellers know, the Youngest Brother’s domain at its most refined and most playful |
