| **Special Attacks** | Dread-touch, poison, drowning aura, three-faced gaze |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., damage reduction 5/good, spell resistance 18, water breathing, drowned-place bond, elemental resonance (water — drowned malice, stagnant death) |
| **Saves** | Fort +9, Ref +9, Will +9 |
| **Abilities** | Str 16, Dex 17, Con 16, Int 14, Wis 16, Cha 18 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +15 (8 ranks), Hide +14 (8 ranks), Intimidate +15 (8 ranks), Knowledge (local) +13 (8 ranks), Listen +14 (8 ranks), Move Silently +14 (8 ranks), Sense Motive +14 (8 ranks), Swim +22 (8 ranks, +8 racial) |
| **Feats** | Ability Focus (three-faced gaze), Multiattack, Stealthy |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) — drowned malice; the resonance of water in places where it should not be — flooded cellars, submerged streets, drowned foundations — the Lady of the Sea’s domain claiming territory that was built for air, converting civilisation to ruin through patient inundation |
| **Environment** | Drowned Places (the flood-damaged, water-logged, and permanently submerged structures of Eruskan river-cities — specifically the cellars, undercrofts, and lower storeys of buildings that have been partially or fully claimed by the Great River’s seasonal floods and never reclaimed by the living) |
| **Organization** | Solitary |
| **Challenge Rating** | 6 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (accumulated from the drowned building’s former contents — water-damaged coins, corroded metalwork, and sodden trade-goods) |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral evil |
| **Advancement** | 9–12 HD (Medium); 13–16 HD (Large — tuchulcha of the largest drowned structures) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A tuchulcha fights from within its drowned place — the flooded structure it has claimed as territory. It lurks below the water’s surface, invisible in the dark, stagnant water (Hide +14, +4 in murky water), and attacks when victims wade in. The drowning aura is the opening: a 30-foot radius effect that makes breathing difficult, sapping strength and inducing panic. The three-faced gaze follows: three simultaneous fear effects from three faces, targeting up to three different creatures.

In the water, a tuchulcha has decisive advantages — swim 40 ft., water breathing, and familiarity with its drowned territory. It drags grappled victims under the surface and holds them there.

### Special Abilities

**Dread-Touch (Su):** A tuchulcha’s claw attack deals 1d6+3 damage plus 1d4 Wisdom damage. The Wisdom damage manifests as drowning-terror — the sensation of water closing over the victim’s head even on dry ground. DC 18 Will save negates the Wisdom damage. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Poison (Ex):** Serpent bite; Fortitude DC 17; initial damage 1d4 Dex; secondary damage 1d4 Dex. The save DC is Constitution-based.

**Drowning Aura (Su):** A tuchulcha constantly radiates a 30-foot aura that makes breathing difficult. Living creatures within the aura must succeed on a DC 18 Fortitude save each round or become fatigued (if already fatigued, they become exhausted). The save DC is Charisma-based. Creatures that can breathe water are immune.

**Three-Faced Gaze (Su):** As a standard action, a tuchulcha can direct the gaze of all three faces simultaneously at up to three different targets within 30 feet. Each target must succeed on a DC 20 Will save or be affected: - *Human face:* Frightened for 1d4 rounds (fear of civilisation lost to water) - *Serpent face:* Paralysed for 1 round (the serpent’s cold fixation) - *Vulture face:* Sickened for 1d4 rounds (the carrion-stench of inevitable decay)

A single creature can be targeted by multiple faces simultaneously. The save DC is Charisma-based (+2 Ability Focus).

**Drowned-Place Bond (Su):** A tuchulcha is permanently bonded to the drowned structure it inhabits. It cannot leave the structure’s footprint (including the flooded space above and below). If the structure is drained of water (through pumping, magical evaporation, or *control water*), the tuchulcha takes 2d6 damage per round until water returns. A structure permanently drained destroys the tuchulcha in 1d4 hours.

**Drowned Malice Resonance (Su):** A tuchulcha registers on Kin-sense as water in the wrong place — the Lady of the Sea’s domain claiming built-space, stagnant, malicious, and patient. Detectable at 30 feet. Eruskan river-folk describe it as “the cellar wanting you to drown” — not natural water but water with *intent*, water that remembers being a floor and has decided to become a grave.

### Society

Tuchulcha are outsider spirits of drowned places — entities that manifest in structures permanently claimed by water, inhabiting the flooded cellars and submerged undercrofts of Eruskan river-cities where the Great River’s seasonal floods have turned civilised space into underwater territory.

Eruskan river-cities, built along the Great River’s banks and tributaries, experience regular flooding. Most flood-damage is temporary — the water recedes, the cellars are pumped, and life resumes. But some buildings are lost permanently — their foundations undermined, their lower storeys filled with water that never drains, their contents reduced to silt and ruin. These permanently drowned places attract tuchulcha — or perhaps *become* tuchulcha, the distinction is debated by Eruskan scholars.

Eruskan civic authorities maintain drowned-place registries — catalogues of permanently flooded structures within each river-city, classified by tuchulcha risk. Buildings known to harbour tuchulcha are sealed above the water-line, marked with warning-glyphs, and listed on civic maps. Entry is prohibited except for authorised clearance-teams.

Eruskan clearance protocol for tuchulcha is drainage-based: pump the water out. A tuchulcha without water is dying, and a dying tuchulcha cannot maintain its drowning aura or three-faced gaze. The logistics of pumping a flooded cellar while under attack from a fear-inducing outsider make this protocol challenging in practice, which is why Eruskan cities prefer to seal and avoid rather than confront.

The relationship between tuchulcha and the Great River’s river serpents is adversarial. River serpents purify water; tuchulcha corrupt it. A river serpent will not enter a tuchulcha-claimed structure (the stagnant, malicious water is antithetical to the serpent’s nature), but the serpent’s presence in the river outside prevents the tuchulcha’s corruption from spreading beyond the drowned building.

### Lore

**DC 16 (Knowledge [the planes]):** Tuchulcha are three-faced outsiders that inhabit flooded structures in Eruskan river-cities. Their drowning aura makes breathing difficult, and their three-faced gaze inflicts fear, paralysis, and sickness. They cannot leave their drowned places.

**DC 21:** Draining the water from a tuchulcha’s structure kills it. Eruskan cities maintain drowned-place registries. The three faces target different creatures simultaneously. Dread-touch inflicts drowning-terror Wisdom damage.

**DC 26:** Tuchulcha resonance is water-in-the-wrong-place — stagnant, malicious, patient. River serpents prevent corruption from spreading beyond the structure. Eruskan prefer to seal and avoid rather than confront. The drowned-place bond cannot be broken except by permanent drainage.

# UGALLU

The desert edge is where the sand meets the stone — where the Infinite Desert’s dune-fields break against the Giant’s Teeth foothills like waves against a cliff. The creature standing on the ridge-line where sand becomes rock has the body of a lion and the head of a man, and the head is wrong. Not wrong the way a sphinx’s head is wrong (a sphinx looks composed, deliberate, *designed*); wrong the way a storm-cloud is wrong — massive, heavy-browed, bearded, with a mouth that could swallow a shield and eyes that contain the focused, predatory intelligence of something that has been hunting this border between desert and mountain since before the Giants vanished. It is bigger than a lion should be. It is older than the dunes. And it is watching the caravan trail below with the patient, proprietary attention of a creature that considers everything on that trail to be food, tribute, or trespass.

**Large Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 8d10+32 (76 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +2 |
| **Speed** | 40 ft. (8 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 19 (–1 size, +2 Dex, +8 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 17 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +8/+18 |
| **Attack** | Claw +13 melee (1d6+6) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 claws +13 melee (1d6+6) and bite +11 melee (1d8+3) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Pounce, roar, improved grab |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, scent, damage reduction 5/magic, desert stride, elemental resonance (earth-fire — desert-edge sovereign), the Harmony |
| **Saves** | Fort +10, Ref +8, Will +5 |
| **Abilities** | Str 22, Dex 15, Con 18, Int 8, Wis 16, Cha 14 |
| **Skills** | Hide +7 (8 ranks, +4 in rocky desert), Listen +14 (8 ranks), Spot +14 (8 ranks), Survival +14 (8 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Multiattack, Power Attack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone / Lady of Fire (Earth/Fire) — desert-edge sovereign; the resonance of the transition zone where the Infinite Desert’s sun-baked sand meets the Giant’s Teeth’s volcanic stone — the Lord and Lady’s domains in arid, predatory equilibrium |
| **Environment** | Desert Edge (the ridge-lines, rock-shelves, and boulder-fields at the transition between the Infinite Desert and the Giant’s Teeth foothills — specifically the caravan-routes and pass-mouths where travellers cross from sand to stone) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or pair (mated) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 6 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (accumulated from caravan-tolls and kills — coins, equipment, and trade-goods scattered across the ugallu’s ridge-line territory) |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 9–12 HD (Large); 13–16 HD (Huge — the eldest desert-edge lords) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

An ugallu is a territorial ambush-predator that attacks from elevated ground. It waits on ridge-lines above caravan-routes, selects a target, and charges downhill with devastating pounce — full attack at the end of a charge. The roar (60-foot cone, shaken 1d4 rounds) scatters caravan-guards, isolating the target for a focused kill.

Against groups, the ugallu uses its roar first, then pounces the most vulnerable target (pack-animals preferred — an ugallu that takes a horse or camel drags it away and does not press the attack further). Against lone travellers, the ugallu may demand tribute — it is intelligent enough (Int 8) to recognise that a living merchant who pays toll is more useful than a dead one.

### Special Abilities

**Pounce (Ex):** An ugallu can make a full attack at the end of a charge.

**Roar (Su):** Three times per day, an ugallu can release a thunderous roar in a 60-foot cone. Creatures in the cone must succeed on a DC 16 Will save or be shaken for 1d4 rounds. Animals (including mounts and pack-beasts) take –4 on this save. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Improved Grab (Ex):** On a successful bite against a Medium or smaller creature.

**Desert Stride (Ex):** An ugallu moves through sand, scree, and rocky desert-terrain at full speed without penalty.

**Desert-Edge Sovereign Resonance (Su):** An ugallu registers on Kin-sense as the desert-edge itself — hot stone and dry sand in predatory equilibrium, the Lord of Stone and the Lady of Fire’s domains meeting in arid transition. Detectable at 60 feet. Pekakarlik desert-scouts describe it as “the ridge deciding you owe it something” — territorial, proprietary, and ancient. The resonance is strongest at dawn and dusk, when the desert-edge temperature-differential creates shimmering air.

### Society

Ugallu are the territorial lords of the desert-edge — the transition zone between the Infinite Desert and the Giant’s Teeth where caravan-routes funnel through narrow passes and ridge-gaps. Each ugallu claims a specific stretch of border-terrain and guards it with the proprietary authority of a toll-collector that predates civilisation.

The ugallu relationship with Pekakarlik caravans is transactional. Pekakarlik desert-traders who operate the caravan-routes between the oasis-towns and the mountain-passes have maintained ugallu-toll protocols for centuries: when approaching a known ugallu territory, the caravan-master leaves an offering at the ridge-base (typically a goat, a haunch of preserved meat, or — for particularly aggressive ugallu — a bolt of cloth or a copper vessel). If the offering is accepted (the ugallu takes it and does not attack), the caravan passes. If rejected (the ugallu roars), the caravan-master increases the offering or reroutes.

The lamassu — the Giant-remnant guardian-beasts that inhabit the Giant ruins — and the ugallu maintain a relationship of territorial respect. Lamassu protect the ruins; ugallu control the approaches. Caravans that have paid toll to an ugallu and then made offering at a lamassu shrine are operating under a double-protection system that has kept the desert-edge trade-routes functional despite the absence of any centralised authority.

Orean mountain-communities on the Giant’s Teeth side of the desert-edge consider ugallu part of the landscape. Orean herders who graze livestock near ugallu territory factor the toll into their seasonal planning — lose a goat to the ugallu, keep the rest safe, because an ugallu that is fed does not hunt nearby herds.

### Lore

**DC 16 (Knowledge [nature]):** Ugallu are Large, lion-bodied, human-headed predators of the desert-edge. They control caravan-routes through territorial roaring and pounce-ambush. DR 5/magic. They are intelligent enough to accept tribute instead of attacking.

**DC 21:** Pekakarlik caravans maintain ugallu-toll protocols — offerings at ridge-bases to secure passage. The roar scatters animals at –4 to saves. Ugallu and lamassu maintain complementary territorial control of the desert-to-mountain transition.

**DC 26:** Ugallu resonance is desert-edge — the Lord of Stone and Lady of Fire in arid equilibrium. Strongest at dawn and dusk. The oldest ugallu have controlled their stretches of border-terrain for centuries and remember the Giant-era trade-routes.

# UNICORN

The forest clearing is lit from within — not by sunlight (the canopy is too thick) but by something else, a quality of light that has no visible source and no shadow. The creature standing in the clearing is a horse — or it looks like a horse, the way a cathedral looks like a building. It is white, impossibly white, the white of fresh snow before anyone has walked on it, and its mane falls like water. The horn is the colour of old ivory, spiralling from the centre of its forehead with the mathematical precision of a seashell, and it radiates a warmth that has nothing to do with temperature. It regards you. Its eyes are dark and calm and contain an assessment that you feel rather than understand: not whether you are dangerous, but whether you are *good*.

**Large Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 4d10+20 (42 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +3 |
| **Speed** | 60 ft. (12 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 18 (–1 size, +3 Dex, +6 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 15 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +4/+11 |
| **Attack** | Horn +11 melee (1d8+8) |
| **Full Attack** | Horn +11 melee (1d8+8) and 2 hooves +3 melee (1d4+2) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | — |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, scent, magic circle against evil, spell-like abilities, immunity to poison/charm/compulsion, wild empathy, elemental resonance (earth — forest-heart purity), the Harmony |
| **Saves** | Fort +9, Ref +7, Will +6 |
| **Abilities** | Str 20, Dex 17, Con 21, Int 10, Wis 21, Cha 24 |
| **Skills** | Jump +21 (4 ranks), Listen +13 (4 ranks), Move Silently +9 (4 ranks), Spot +13 (4 ranks), Survival +8 (4 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Skill Focus (Survival) |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lord of Stone (Earth) — forest-heart; the resonance of the deepest, purest forest-earth — soil that has never been ploughed, turned, or contaminated, the Lord of Stone’s domain expressed as the foundation of untouched wilderness |
| **Environment** | Great Forests (the deepest, most pristine zones of the Great Forests — specifically the old-growth interiors where Kin settlements have never reached, where the forest-floor has been undisturbed for millennia, and where the elemental purity of the earth is absolute) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or grace (3–6) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 3 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always chaotic good |
| **Advancement** | 5–8 HD (Large) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +4 (cohort) |

### Combat

A unicorn does not seek combat but fights with fierce, concentrated aggression when defending the innocent or when its forest-territory is threatened by evil. The horn attack (1d8+8, treated as magic and good-aligned for overcoming DR) is devastating for CR 3 — the unicorn’s Str 20 and the horn’s piercing focus deliver damage comparable to creatures twice its Challenge Rating.

A unicorn’s constant *magic circle against evil* (10-foot radius) provides significant defensive benefit to nearby allies, and its spell-like abilities (*cure light wounds* 3/day, *cure moderate wounds* 1/day, *neutralize poison* 1/day, *greater teleport* within forest 1/day) make it an exceptional emergency healer and escape-enabler.

### Special Abilities

**Magic Circle Against Evil (Su):** Constant, 10-foot radius. As the spell.

**Spell-Like Abilities:** Caster level 5th. - 3/day — *cure light wounds* (DC 18) - 1/day — *cure moderate wounds* (DC 19), *neutralize poison* (DC 21), *greater teleport* (within its forest only, self plus willing rider)

**Wild Empathy (Ex):** As the druid class feature. +18 bonus (HD + Cha modifier).

**Forest-Heart Purity Resonance (Su):** A unicorn registers on Kin-sense as the purest earth-resonance in the Great Forests — soil that has never been violated, the Lord of Stone’s domain at its most untouched and most sacred. Detectable at 120 feet. The sensation is described by every Kin culture that has experienced it in nearly identical terms: “the forest remembering what it was before we came.” The resonance actively repels corruption — undead, Dómnathar, and evil outsiders within 120 feet of a unicorn’s resonance suffer –2 on attack rolls and saves (no save; the purity of the resonance is antithetical to corrupted existence).

### Society

Unicorns are the Great Forests’ purest inhabitants — magical beasts of absolute goodness that dwell in the deepest, most pristine forest-zones and serve as living markers of ecological and spiritual health. A forest that contains unicorns is a forest that has not been corrupted. A forest that has lost its unicorns is a forest in decline.

Pasua elves have the deepest unicorn-traditions. Pasua scouts who encounter unicorn sign (hoof-prints that leave no impression, the inexplicable quality of light in a clearing, the sensation of being assessed) consider it among the most auspicious events in the scouting calendar. A Pasua scout who has *seen* a unicorn carries a social prestige that no other achievement can match — it means the forest itself has judged them and found them worthy.

Hasura elves in the canopy above unicorn-territory maintain a policy of absolute non-interference. Hasura canopy-settlements near unicorn ranges are built with additional care to minimise impact on the forest-floor below — the unicorn’s presence is a guarantee of the canopy’s health, and the Hasura will do nothing to drive them away.

The unicorn’s horn — in legend and in reality — neutralises poison. Eruskan apothecary-traditions include (largely fictional) unicorn-horn remedies, and the black-market trade in “unicorn horn” (invariably fake — narwhal tooth, carved ivory, or alchemically treated horse-bone) is a persistent problem in Eruskan river-cities. Actual unicorn horn has never been successfully harvested, because killing a unicorn to take its horn immediately destroys the horn’s magical properties.

Unicorn Paragons are not documented — the unicorn *is* the paragon-level expression of forest-heart purity. Where other creatures have Paragons that serve as elevated guardians, the unicorn serves that function at its base form.

### Lore

**DC 13 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Unicorns are Large, intelligent, always-good magical beasts found in the deepest forests. Their horn attacks overcome evil DR. They radiate *magic circle against evil* and can heal, cure poison, and teleport within their forest.

**DC 18:** Unicorn resonance repels corruption — undead and evil outsiders within 120 feet take –2 on attacks and saves. Pasua scouts consider sighting a unicorn the highest honour. Killing a unicorn destroys the horn’s magical properties.

**DC 23:** Unicorn resonance is the purest earth-signature in the Great Forests — untouched soil, forest-heart purity. Their presence is a living indicator of ecological health. A forest losing its unicorns is a forest under spiritual threat. Unicorns serve a paragon-equivalent function without a distinct Paragon form.

# UTHIKOLOSHE

The river-crossing is shallow — knee-deep, cold, and fast-moving. The Warg pack-scout wades in without hesitation and stops. The water around his ankles has darkened — not with mud but with something else, a shadow that has no source and no shape, a presence in the water that is cold in a way that river-water in summer should not be. The scout backs out slowly. “Uthikoloshe,” he says to the pack-leader. His voice is flat. “In the water. We go around.” The pack-leader looks at the river — the perfectly ordinary-looking river — and nods without argument, and the pack adds six miles to the day’s travel without complaint, because the Warg know what an uthikoloshe is, and the Warg do not argue with what the Warg know.

**Medium Outsider (Shadow)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Outsider (Shadow) |
| **Hit Dice** | 7d8+14 (45 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +5 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), swim 40 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 18 (+1 Dex, +7 natural), touch 11, flat-footed 17 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +7/+10 |
| **Attack** | Claw +10 melee (1d6+3 plus drowning shadow) |
| **Full Attack** | 2 claws +10 melee (1d6+3 plus drowning shadow) and bite +8 melee (1d4+1) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Drowning shadow, river-curse, spell-like abilities |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., damage reduction 5/cold iron, spell resistance 17, water breathing, shadow-water, vulnerability to sunlight on dry land, elemental resonance (water-shadow — drowned darkness, river-malice) |
| **Saves** | Fort +7, Ref +6, Will +8 |
| **Abilities** | Str 16, Dex 13, Con 14, Int 12, Wis 16, Cha 16 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +13 (7 ranks), Hide +11 (7 ranks, +4 in water), Intimidate +13 (7 ranks), Knowledge (nature) +11 (7 ranks), Listen +13 (7 ranks), Move Silently +11 (7 ranks), Spot +13 (7 ranks), Swim +21 (7 ranks, +8 racial) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Improved Initiative, Multiattack |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) — shadow-current; the resonance of water in shadow, river-current that flows through the darkest places, the Lady of the Sea’s domain where her light does not reach — not corrupted water (like a spirit naga’s domain) but *shadowed* water, water that has become a medium for darkness |
| **Environment** | Warg Territory (the rivers, streams, and water-crossings of Warg pack territory on the Eternal Steppe — specifically the fords, shallow crossings, and river-bends where Warg packs cross between seasonal grazing-grounds, where the water is accessible and the uthikoloshe can ambush wading creatures) |
| **Organization** | Solitary |
| **Challenge Rating** | 6 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (accumulated on the river-bottom — equipment, weapons, and trade-goods from drowned victims, corroded by water-exposure) |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral evil |
| **Advancement** | 8–10 HD (Medium); 11–14 HD (Large — the eldest river-lords) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

An uthikoloshe fights from water — always water. It lurks beneath the surface of rivers and streams, concealed by its shadow-water ability (the water around it darkens, but the uthikoloshe is invisible within the darkened zone). When a creature wades into the claimed crossing, the uthikoloshe attacks from below — claws delivering drowning shadow (Constitution damage that manifests as the sensation of lungs filling with water) and grappling to drag the victim under.

On dry land, the uthikoloshe is significantly weakened — vulnerability to sunlight deals 1d4 damage per round in direct sun. An uthikoloshe that is dragged or driven onto dry land in daylight fights desperately to return to water.

### Special Abilities

**Drowning Shadow (Su):** An uthikoloshe’s claw attack deals 1d6+3 damage plus 1d4 Constitution damage. The Constitution damage manifests as drowning-sensation — the victim’s lungs feel heavy, breathing becomes laboured, and the victim’s skin takes on a faint blue-grey tinge. DC 16 Fortitude save negates the Constitution damage. The save DC is Charisma-based. A creature reduced to 0 Constitution by drowning shadow dies and appears to have drowned, regardless of whether it was in water at the time.

**River-Curse (Su):** Once per day, an uthikoloshe can curse a creature within 30 feet that is touching water. The cursed creature becomes unable to cross running water — any attempt to wade, swim, or be carried across a river, stream, or creek provokes paralyzing terror (DC 16 Will save or be paralysed for 1d4 rounds at the water’s edge). The curse lasts until removed by *remove curse* (DC 18) or *break enchantment*. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Shadow-Water (Su):** An uthikoloshe’s presence darkens the water within 30 feet — the water becomes opaque and black, as though a cloud of ink has been released. Within this darkened zone, the uthikoloshe has total concealment (50% miss chance). Creatures in the shadow-water that rely on sight are effectively blind. The uthikoloshe sees normally within its own shadow-water.

**Spell-Like Abilities:** Caster level 7th. Save DCs are Charisma-based (DC 13 + spell level). - At will — *darkness, obscuring mist* - 3/day — *chill touch* (DC 14), *cause fear* (DC 14) - 1/day — *control water*

**Vulnerability to Sunlight on Dry Land (Ex):** An uthikoloshe on dry land in direct sunlight takes 1d4 damage per round. In water, even in full sunlight, it is unaffected — the water shields it. At night or in shade on dry land, it is also unaffected.

**Drowned Darkness Resonance (Su):** An uthikoloshe registers on Kin-sense as water-in-shadow — the Lady of the Sea’s domain darkened, river-current flowing through places where light cannot reach. Detectable at 30 feet in water, 15 feet on land. Warg pack-scouts describe it as “the river going cold inside” — not the healthy cold of deep water but the *wrong* cold of water that has something hiding in it.

### Society

Uthikoloshe are shadow-water outsiders of the Warg territories — solitary, malevolent predators that claim specific river-crossings and prey on creatures that attempt to ford. They are the dark counterpart of the tokoloshe: where tokoloshe are annoying, petty, and ultimately harmless camp-followers, uthikoloshe are lethal, patient, and territorial. The naming similarity is deliberate — Warg oral tradition holds that uthikoloshe are “what tokoloshe become when the river gets inside them,” though the two creatures are not actually related (tokoloshe are fey, uthikoloshe are shadow-outsiders).

Warg pack-scouts are the primary line of defence against uthikoloshe. Warg packs cross rivers constantly — the nomadic steppe-lifestyle requires frequent fording — and every pack-scout is trained to identify uthikoloshe-signs before wading in. The signs are consistent: water that darkens without apparent cause, an unexpected chill in summer rivers, the sensation of Kin-sense reading “cold inside” from a river that should register as neutral. When a pack-scout identifies a claimed crossing, the pack reroutes — no argument, no hesitation. The detour cost is always less than the drowning cost.

Warg anti-uthikoloshe tactics, when confrontation is unavoidable, are based on forcing the creature onto dry land in daylight. Pack-warriors with nets, hooks, and rope attempt to drag the uthikoloshe from the water while ranged attackers with fire-arrows target the shadow-water zone. A coordinated Warg team of six to eight warriors can extract and kill an uthikoloshe, but casualties are common — the drowning shadow’s Constitution damage and the river-curse’s paralysis make the extraction dangerous.

Goblin communities within Warg packs have their own uthikoloshe-traditions. Goblin river-lore, which is older and more detailed than Warg river-lore on this subject, includes specific appeasement rituals for claimed crossings — offerings of blood (typically from a small animal) poured into the river upstream of the crossing. Whether the offerings actually appease the uthikoloshe or merely distract it is debated; goblin shamans claim the former, Warg pack-leaders suspect the latter.

### Lore

**DC 16 (Knowledge [the planes]):** Uthikoloshe are Medium shadow-outsiders that inhabit river-crossings in Warg territory. They darken water in a 30-foot radius, attack from concealment, and deal Constitution damage that manifests as drowning-sensation. Vulnerable to sunlight on dry land.

**DC 21:** Shadow-water grants total concealment. River-curse prevents the victim from crossing running water. Warg pack-scouts identify claimed crossings by Kin-sense “cold inside” reading. Forcing the uthikoloshe onto dry land in daylight is the primary kill-tactic.

**DC 26:** Uthikoloshe resonance is water-in-shadow — the Lady of the Sea’s domain darkened. Not related to tokoloshe despite the naming similarity. Goblin river-lore includes appeasement rituals for claimed crossings. A creature killed by drowning shadow appears to have drowned regardless of location.

# VAMPIRE SPAWN

The tomb-air is dry and still and old, and the thing that steps out of the sarcophagus-shadow is not what you expected. You expected bone. You expected rot. What you get is a person — pale, sharp-featured, dressed in the remnants of burial-finery that has held together through centuries of absolute darkness. Its eyes are open and aware and utterly, coldly hungry, and when it smiles, the canines are longer than they should be, and the smile does not contain a single molecule of warmth. It is not a person. It was a person, once, and what it is now is a person-shaped hole in the world through which something else is looking.

**Medium Undead**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Undead |
| **Hit Dice** | 4d12+3 (29 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +6 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 15 (+2 Dex, +3 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 13 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +2/+5 |
| **Attack** | Slam +5 melee (1d6+4 plus energy drain) |
| **Full Attack** | Slam +5 melee (1d6+4 plus energy drain) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Blood drain, dominate, energy drain |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., damage reduction 5/silver, fast healing 2, gaseous form, resistance to cold 10 and electricity 10, spider climb, +2 turn resistance, undead traits, elemental resonance (none — dead hunger) |
| **Saves** | Fort +1, Ref +5, Will +5 |
| **Abilities** | Str 16, Dex 14, Con —, Int 13, Wis 13, Cha 14 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +6 (4 ranks), Climb +8 (4 ranks), Hide +10 (4 ranks), Listen +8 (4 ranks), Move Silently +10 (4 ranks), Search +5 (4 ranks), Sense Motive +5 (4 ranks), Spot +8 (4 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Improved Initiative, Toughness |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — a vampire spawn has no elemental resonance; it is dead matter animated by hunger, a body that feeds to sustain a semblance of existence without possessing any of the elemental connections that defined it in life |
| **Environment** | Giant Tomb Complexes (the sealed burial-chambers, sarcophagus-halls, and crypt-networks of the Giant-era tomb complexes scattered through the Giant’s Teeth and Infinite Desert — places where the original Giants entombed their dead with rituals that preserved the bodies in conditions that, when combined with subsequent necromantic contamination, produced vampiric undead) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or pack (3–6) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 4 |
| **Treasure** | Standard (burial goods — Giant-era grave-offerings, jewellery, and ceremonial equipment that has survived centuries of sealed-tomb preservation) |
| **Alignment** | Always chaotic evil |
| **Advancement** | — |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A vampire spawn is a fast, aggressive melee combatant — more dangerous than its CR 4 suggests because of the energy drain. Each slam delivers one negative level, and the blood drain (1d4 Constitution per round while grappling) can kill quickly. Fast healing 2, DR 5/silver, and gaseous form (escape at 0 hp) make them difficult to put down permanently.

Vampire spawn fight in packs when possible (3–6 emerging from separate sarcophagi simultaneously), using dominate to neutralise the strongest-looking opponent while the pack converges on the remaining party members. Spider climb allows them to attack from walls and ceilings in the high-vaulted Giant tomb-chambers.

### Special Abilities

**Energy Drain (Su):** A vampire spawn’s slam attack inflicts one negative level. The DC to remove the negative level is 14. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Blood Drain (Ex):** A vampire spawn can drain blood from a pinned opponent, dealing 1d4 Constitution damage per round. Each round of blood drain heals the vampire spawn 5 hit points.

**Dominate (Su):** A vampire spawn can crush the will of a humanoid within 30 feet as a standard action. The target must succeed on a DC 14 Will save or fall under the spawn’s influence (as *dominate person*, caster level 5th). The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Gaseous Form (Su):** When reduced to 0 hit points, a vampire spawn automatically assumes gaseous form and flees to its sarcophagus. It reforms in 1d10 hours with 1 hp unless destroyed (see vulnerabilities).

**Vulnerabilities:** Sunlight deals 1d4 damage per round and prevents fast healing. A wooden stake through the heart while in its sarcophagus paralyses it. Holy water deals 2d4 damage. Garlic repels (10 feet, Will DC 14 to overcome). Cannot enter a dwelling without invitation.

**Dead Hunger Resonance (Su):** A vampire spawn registers on Kin-sense as nothing — no elemental signature, no distortion, no void. Just absence. The effect is subtler than a wraith’s active negation or a shadow’s Dómnathar void — it is the passive emptiness of something that should have resonance and does not. Detectable at 30 feet as “a person-shaped gap in the room.” Vestri tomb-explorers describe it as “standing next to someone who isn’t there.”

### Society

Vampire spawn in Oreka are concentrated in the Giant tomb complexes — the elaborate burial-facilities the original Giants constructed for their dead during the Age of Giants. The tombs preserved bodies under conditions of perfect darkness, stable temperature, and ritual energy that, over millennia, interacted with the ambient death-energy of the Giant era to produce vampiric undead.

The vampire spawn in Giant tombs are not Giant-created (the Giants did not practice necromancy) and are not Dómnathar-created (though the Dómnathar have certainly exploited them). They are a natural consequence of extremely long-term preservation combined with the elemental disruption caused by the Thalorien — the Giants’ Fading destabilised the metaphysical environment of the tombs, and the preserved dead rose.

Pekakarlik desert-archaeologists who excavate Giant tomb complexes in the Infinite Desert encounter vampire spawn as the primary tomb-guardian threat. Pekakarlik tomb-protocols are precise: never open a sealed sarcophagus without sunlight access (carry *daylight* scrolls or polished-mirror sun-reflectors), always carry silver weapons, and always station a cleric at the tomb-entrance. The Pekakarlik term for vampire spawn is *kanatlı açlık* (“winged hunger”), despite the fact that vampire spawn in Oreka do not have wings — the term refers to the gaseous form’s escape-flight.

Vestri tomb-exploration teams in the Giant’s Teeth encounter vampire spawn in the deeper tomb-complexes and maintain similar silver-and-sunlight protocols. The Vestri relationship with Giant tombs is complicated by the same veneration that complicates their relationship with stone giants — these are the Firstborn’s resting-places, and clearing them of undead is treated as a sacred duty rather than a treasure-hunt.

### Lore

**DC 14 (Knowledge [religion]):** Vampire spawn are undead that drain energy and blood. One negative level per slam. DR 5/silver, fast healing 2. They flee in gaseous form at 0 hp and reform unless destroyed in their sarcophagi. Sunlight, garlic, and holy water are countermeasures.

**DC 19:** Vampire spawn dominate humanoids within 30 feet. In Giant tombs, packs of 3–6 emerge simultaneously from separate sarcophagi. Spider climb allows ceiling-attacks in high-vaulted chambers. Pekakarlik carry silver weapons and *daylight* scrolls as standard tomb-equipment.

**DC 24:** Giant-tomb vampire spawn arose from Thalorien-era metaphysical disruption, not deliberate necromancy. Their resonance is passive emptiness — no signature at all. The Vestri treat tomb-clearance as sacred duty. Gaseous form returns to a specific sarcophagus — destroying the sarcophagus denies the escape.

# VANTH

The battlefield is three days old. The crows have come and gone. The burial-detail has done what it can. And yet something remains — a figure standing at the field’s edge where the dead are thickest, motionless, masked, carrying a staff that is neither weapon nor walking-stick but something between. It is the height of a tall man but too thin, wrapped in a cloak the colour of old bronze, and its face is a mask — featureless, smooth, with no eyes and no mouth but a surface that somehow conveys an expression of infinite, patient attention. It is not looking at you. It is looking at the dead. It is counting.

**Medium Outsider**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Outsider |
| **Hit Dice** | 6d8+12 (39 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +3 |
| **Speed** | 30 ft. (6 squares), fly 40 ft. (good) |
| **Armor Class** | 18 (+3 Dex, +5 natural), touch 13, flat-footed 15 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +6/+8 |
| **Attack** | Deathstaff +8 melee (1d8+3 plus soul-weight) |
| **Full Attack** | Deathstaff +8/+3 melee (1d8+3 plus soul-weight) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Soul-weight, death gaze, spell-like abilities |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 120 ft., damage reduction 5/magic, immunity to death effects, spell resistance 17, deathsense, spirit sight, elemental resonance (all four — grave-stillness, equilibrium of endings) |
| **Saves** | Fort +7, Ref +8, Will +9 |
| **Abilities** | Str 14, Dex 16, Con 14, Int 14, Wis 18, Cha 16 |
| **Skills** | Diplomacy +12 (6 ranks), Knowledge (history) +11 (6 ranks), Knowledge (religion) +11 (6 ranks), Listen +13 (6 ranks), Search +11 (6 ranks), Sense Motive +13 (6 ranks), Spot +13 (6 ranks), Survival +13 (6 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Combat Reflexes, Iron Will |
| **Elemental Affinity** | All four Elemental Lords — grave-stillness; the resonance of all four elements settling into equilibrium, the moment where fire cools, water stills, wind falls silent, and earth receives — not the harmonious balance of the qilin or the learned wisdom of the simurgh, but the quiet cessation that follows the end of a life, when the elements that comprised a living being return to the world |
| **Environment** | Battlefields (the sites of mass Kin death — battlefields, massacre-sites, plague-graves, and disaster-zones, specifically within the first days or weeks after death, when the recently dead have not yet been fully committed to the earth and the boundary between life and death is thinnest; most commonly documented at Eruskan military engagements) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or vigil (2–4) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 5 |
| **Treasure** | None (a vanth carries nothing but its deathstaff, and the staff cannot be taken — it dissolves if the vanth is destroyed) |
| **Alignment** | Always true neutral |
| **Advancement** | 7–10 HD (Medium); 11–14 HD (Large — the greater vanth, which appear at the largest mass-death sites) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A vanth does not attack the living unless attacked first or unless the living interfere with its purpose — the counting and shepherding of the dead. A vanth that is attacked defends itself with methodical efficiency but without malice: the deathstaff delivers physical damage plus soul-weight (Wisdom damage that forces the target to confront the reality of their own mortality), and the death gaze can incapacitate attackers who meet the vanth’s eyeless mask.

A vanth never pursues. If its attackers disengage, the vanth returns to its work without comment. It does not hold grudges, does not seek revenge, and does not remember individual living creatures — the living are beneath its professional attention.

### Special Abilities

**Soul-Weight (Su):** A vanth’s deathstaff delivers 1d8+3 damage plus 1d4 Wisdom damage. The Wisdom damage manifests as a sudden, crushing awareness of mortality — the target experiences, for one instant, the absolute certainty of their own eventual death. DC 16 Will save negates the Wisdom damage. The save DC is Charisma-based. Creatures immune to fear are immune to soul-weight.

**Death Gaze (Su):** 30 feet. Creatures that meet the vanth’s featureless mask must succeed on a DC 16 Fortitude save or be paralysed for 1d4 rounds by the sudden cessation of vitality — the body temporarily shuts down in proximity to the vanth’s purpose. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Deathsense (Su):** A vanth can detect all dead and undead creatures within 500 feet. It knows the exact number, location, and manner of death of every corpse in range. Against undead, it knows the undead’s type and HD.

**Spirit Sight (Su):** A vanth can see incorporeal creatures, ethereal creatures, and souls that have not yet departed. This is constant and not magical (it cannot be dispelled).

**Spell-Like Abilities:** Caster level 6th. Save DCs are Charisma-based (DC 13 + spell level). - At will — *detect undead, gentle repose, speak with dead* (DC 16) - 3/day — *halt undead* (DC 16), *invisibility* (self only) - 1/day — *dismissal* (against undead only, DC 17)

**Grave-Stillness Resonance (Su):** A vanth registers on Kin-sense as all four elements simultaneously settling into stillness — the quiet that follows death, when the elemental energies of a living being return to the world. Detectable at 60 feet. The sensation is not frightening but profoundly solemn — Eruskan soldiers describe it as “the battlefield going to sleep.” Kin within the resonance range instinctively lower their voices, slow their movements, and feel the weight of the dead around them. The resonance does not suppress Kin-sense but makes all other readings muted, as though the world has turned down its volume.

### Society

Vanth are psychopomps — outsiders that appear at sites of mass death to count, catalogue, and shepherd the dead. They are not divine servants (they serve no specific deity), not undead (they are fully alive in the outsider sense), and not hostile (they are professionally indifferent to the living). They are the world’s undertakers — entities that exist to ensure that the dead are properly *ended*, that the elemental energies of the deceased return to the four Lords, and that the boundary between life and death remains intact.

Eruskan military culture has the most developed vanth-traditions, because the Eruskan — as the Kin culture most engaged in organised warfare — produce the most battlefields. Eruskan soldiers who survive a major battle expect vanth to appear within hours. The Eruskan military term for a vanth is *il contabile* (“the accountant”), reflecting the creature’s visible behaviour: methodical, systematic movement across the battlefield, pausing at each body, conducting some invisible assessment, and moving on.

Eruskan burial-detail protocols account for vanth presence. Burial-teams are instructed to work around vanth rather than disturb them — a vanth that has not completed its count will remain at the battlefield indefinitely, and interfering with the count produces the only aggressive response a vanth is known to display. The Eruskan saying *“****let the accountant finish****”* means “don’t interfere with something that is doing necessary work you don’t understand.”

Vanth also appear at plague-graves, disaster-sites, and — rarely — at individual deaths that the vanth considers significant for reasons it does not explain. An Eruskan noble whose deathbed is attended by a vanth is considered to have died a death of consequence, though whether the consequence is positive or negative is a matter the vanth does not clarify.

The relationship between vanth and undead is adversarial. A vanth’s purpose is to ensure the dead remain dead; undead are, by definition, a violation of that purpose. A vanth that detects undead at a battlefield will pause its counting work, address the undead with *halt undead* and *dismissal*, and — if those measures fail — attack with its deathstaff. Vanth do not destroy undead with particular efficiency (they are not clerics), but their implacable, emotionless hostility toward the undead is absolute and unwavering.

### Lore

**DC 15 (Knowledge [the planes] or [religion]):** Vanth are Medium outsiders that appear at battlefields and mass-death sites. They are neutral, non-hostile, and count the dead. They attack only if interfered with or if undead are present. Their deathstaff deals Wisdom damage.

**DC 20:** Vanth detect all dead and undead within 500 feet. They can speak with dead and halt undead at will. Eruskan military protocols require burial-teams to work around vanth. Interfering with a vanth’s count provokes the only hostile response.

**DC 25:** Vanth resonance is grave-stillness — all four elements settling into cessation. They see incorporeal and ethereal creatures at all times. They are hostile to all undead on principle. The deathstaff dissolves when the vanth is destroyed — it cannot be taken as a trophy or weapon.

# VODYANOY

The river-pool beneath the bridge is deep — deeper than the river should be at this point, the bottom invisible even in clear water. Something lives in the depth, and the Eruskan rivermen know what it is because the bridge has been here for four hundred years and the thing below the bridge has been here longer. It surfaces at dusk. It is man-shaped — roughly — with a face like a catfish given human proportions: wide-mouthed, bearded with trailing whisker-tendrils, and green-skinned, covered in a mucus that catches the torchlight with an iridescent sheen. It is fat in the way that a prosperous merchant is fat — comfortably, deliberately, as though the fatness is a statement of authority. It sits on a submerged rock and regards the bridge above with proprietary satisfaction. The bridge is above *its* pool. The rivermen who cross the bridge do so because *it* permits them. And the fish in its pool are the finest in the river because *it* says so.

**Large Fey (Aquatic)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Large Fey (Aquatic) |
| **Hit Dice** | 10d6+40 (75 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +1 |
| **Speed** | 20 ft. (4 squares), swim 40 ft. |
| **Armor Class** | 19 (–1 size, +1 Dex, +9 natural), touch 10, flat-footed 18 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +5/+15 |
| **Attack** | Slam +10 melee (1d8+6) or trident +10 melee (2d6+9) |
| **Full Attack** | Trident +10/+5 melee (2d6+9) or 2 slams +10 melee (1d8+6) |
| **Space/Reach** | 10 ft./10 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Drowning grasp, river-command, spell-like abilities |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., damage reduction 10/cold iron, spell resistance 20, water breathing, amphibious, pool-sovereignty, fast healing 5 (in water), elemental resonance (water — river-lord, deep-pool authority) |
| **Saves** | Fort +7, Ref +8, Will +10 |
| **Abilities** | Str 22, Dex 12, Con 18, Int 16, Wis 16, Cha 18 |
| **Skills** | Bluff +17 (10 ranks), Craft (fishing) +16 (10 ranks), Diplomacy +17 (10 ranks), Intimidate +17 (10 ranks), Knowledge (nature) +16 (10 ranks), Listen +16 (10 ranks), Sense Motive +16 (10 ranks), Spot +16 (10 ranks), Swim +27 (10 ranks, +8 racial) |
| **Feats** | Ability Focus (drowning grasp), Cleave, Power Attack, Weapon Focus (trident) |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Lady of the Sea (Water) — river-lord; the resonance of a specific stretch of river claimed by an intelligence that manages it — not corrupted water (like a spirit naga’s domain) and not shadowed water (like an uthikoloshe’s crossing) but *governed* water, river that has a master who keeps it healthy, productive, and under absolute personal control |
| **Environment** | Great River / Kailian Deep (the deep pools, bridge-hollows, and river-bends of the Great River and its major tributaries, and the freshwater deeps of the Kailian Sea coast — specifically the pools beneath bridges, dams, and river-structures where the water is deep enough and permanent enough to sustain a vodyanoy’s territorial claim) |
| **Organization** | Solitary or court (1 vodyanoy plus 2–4 water fey attendants — lasa, water mephits, or small water elementals) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 7 |
| **Treasure** | Double standard (accumulated on the pool-bottom — centuries of bridge-tolls, offerings, drowned trade-goods, and river-salvage, all corroded by water-exposure but including a surprising number of well-preserved items in the deepest mud-layers) |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral |
| **Advancement** | 11–15 HD (Large); 16–20 HD (Huge — the eldest river-lords of the deepest pools) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A vodyanoy fights from its pool — always its pool. It does not pursue beyond its claimed stretch of river. Within the pool, it is devastating: Str 22, trident (2d6+9), drowning grasp (grapple-and-submerge), and river-command (control the current itself) give it overwhelming tactical advantages in its home water. Fast healing 5 in water makes it nearly unkillable unless dragged onto dry land.

Against intruders who have offended its authority (crossing the bridge without acknowledgement, polluting the pool, fishing without permission), the vodyanoy opens with river-command — capsizing boats, creating whirlpools, and flooding the riverbank. If the intruders apologise and make offerings, the vodyanoy *may* accept. If they persist, drowning grasp follows.

### Special Abilities

**Drowning Grasp (Su):** A vodyanoy that successfully grapples a creature can drag it underwater as a move action. A submerged, grappled creature must hold its breath or begin drowning (Constitution check DC 10, +1 per subsequent round). The vodyanoy’s grapple bonus is +15 (+17 in water, where it gains +2 from aquatic advantage). The save DC for the initial grapple is Strength-based.

**River-Command (Su):** Three times per day, a vodyanoy can command the water in its pool. Effects include: - *Capsize:* A watercraft of up to 30 feet in length must succeed on a DC 18 Reflex save (captain’s Profession [sailor] check) or capsize. - *Whirlpool:* 20-foot-radius, 10-foot-deep; creatures within must succeed on a DC 18 Swim check each round or be pulled to the centre and held underwater. - *Flood:* The river rises 5 feet along a 60-foot stretch of bank for 1 minute, flooding low-lying areas.

The save DCs are Charisma-based.

**Pool-Sovereignty (Su):** A vodyanoy’s pool is its domain — within the pool, it is aware of every creature, object, and change in water-quality. The pool’s fish population is unusually healthy and abundant (the vodyanoy manages the ecosystem with fey precision). The vodyanoy can communicate with all aquatic animals within its pool at will (as *speak with animals*, aquatic only, constant).

**Spell-Like Abilities:** Caster level 10th. Save DCs are Charisma-based (DC 14 + spell level). - At will — *control water, create water, water breathing* (on others) - 3/day — *fog cloud, quench* (DC 17), *sleet storm* (DC 17) - 1/day — *ice storm* (DC 18)

**River-Lord Resonance (Su):** A vodyanoy registers on Kin-sense as governed water — the Lady of the Sea’s domain under personal management, river-current that has a master. Detectable at 60 feet. Eruskan rivermen describe it as “the pool having an opinion about you” — not hostile but proprietary, the sensation of being assessed by something that considers you a guest in its territory and is deciding whether you’re welcome. The resonance extends through the pool-water — any creature touching the water can detect the vodyanoy’s presence and general disposition (content, irritated, hostile).

### Society

Vodyanoy are the river-lords of the Great River system — powerful, territorial, long-lived fey that claim specific pools and river-stretches and govern them with the absolute, proprietary authority of landed aristocrats. They are the water-equivalent of the supay’s deep-earth sovereignty: beings that consider the water their personal property and everything in it (fish, plants, sunken objects, drowned travellers) their personal wealth.

Eruskan river-culture has the deepest vodyanoy relationships. The Great River’s vodyanoy have inhabited their pools since before the Eruskan settled the river-cities, and Eruskan river-tradition includes elaborate vodyanoy-acknowledgement protocols: rivermen who cross a vodyanoy bridge leave offerings (traditionally a fresh fish, a copper coin, or a measure of ale poured into the water); fishermen who wish to fish in a vodyanoy pool request permission (by speaking aloud to the water, addressing the vodyanoy by its known name or by the generic title *signore del pozzo* — “lord of the pool”); and boat-crews who navigate vodyanoy stretches maintain respectful silence while passing through.

The vodyanoy’s pool-sovereignty makes it an ecological asset: a stretch of river governed by a vodyanoy is invariably healthier, more productive, and more fish-rich than ungoverned stretches. Eruskan fishermen who maintain good relations with their local vodyanoy catch more and better fish than those who do not. This creates an economic incentive for maintaining the traditional protocols — a fisherman who offends a vodyanoy loses access to the finest fishing-water in the region.

River serpents and vodyanoy coexist peacefully. Both serve the Lady of the Sea’s domain, though in different capacities: river serpents are sacred wardens (protecting the river’s elemental health), while vodyanoy are territorial lords (managing the river’s practical ecology). A river-stretch that has both a river serpent and a vodyanoy is the healthiest, most productive, and most dangerous stretch of water in its region.

Lasa — the small river-fey of Eruskan tradition — often serve as attendants in vodyanoy courts, carrying messages between the vodyanoy and Eruskan communities and serving as intermediaries when the vodyanoy is too irritated for direct negotiation.

### Lore

**DC 17 (Knowledge [nature]):** Vodyanoy are Large, territorial fey that inhabit deep river-pools. They demand acknowledgement from those who cross their territory. DR 10/cold iron, SR 20, fast healing 5 in water. They can capsize boats and create whirlpools.

**DC 22:** Vodyanoy pool-sovereignty produces exceptionally healthy, fish-rich water. Eruskan rivermen maintain traditional offering-protocols. River-command capsizes boats, creates whirlpools, and floods banks. Drowning grasp drags grappled creatures underwater.

**DC 27:** Vodyanoy resonance is governed water — detectable through the pool itself. They coexist peacefully with river serpents. Lasa serve as attendants and intermediaries. Vodyanoy consider everything in their pool (including sunken treasure and drowned travellers) their personal property.

# WATER ELEMENTAL

The river rises. Not floods — the water level does not change — but a column of river-water pulls itself upright, shaping limbs and a torso and something that might be a head from the current itself. It stands on the river’s surface like a person stands on a floor, and within its translucent body you can see river-debris turning slowly: pebbles, weeds, a small fish swimming in confused circles. When it moves, the sound is rain on stone.

Water elementals are living currents — portions of Oreka’s rivers, seas, and lakes given purpose and form. They range from knee-high ripples to towering columns of pressurised water that can crush stone. In Oreka, they are the Lady of the Sea’s most direct expression — water given will.

