| **Initiative** | +2 |
| **Speed** | 50 ft. (10 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 14 (+2 Dex, +2 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 12 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +1/+2 |
| **Attack** | Bite +3 melee (1d6+1) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +3 melee (1d6+1) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Trip |
| **Special Qualities** | Low-light vision, scent, elemental resonance (species Harmony) |
| **Saves** | Fort +5, Ref +5, Will +1 |
| **Abilities** | Str 13, Dex 15, Con 15, Int 2, Wis 12, Cha 6 |
| **Skills** | Hide +2 (0 ranks), Listen +3 (0 ranks), Move Silently +3 (0 ranks), Spot +3 (0 ranks), Survival +1 (0 ranks, +4 tracking by scent) |
| **Feats** | Track, Weapon Focus (bite) |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Species Harmony — wolves carry the species-specific resonance of their kind, distinct from elemental Kin-sense but part of the world’s ecological web |
| **Environment** | Forests / Steppe (the Great Forests’ edges and the Eternal Steppe — anywhere pack-hunting in open or semi-open terrain is viable) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or pack (7–16) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 1 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always neutral |
| **Advancement** | 3 HD (Medium); 4–5 HD (Large) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

Wolves are pack-hunters that trip prey and overwhelm through numbers. A wolf that hits with its bite can attempt a trip as a free action. Packs coordinate to isolate the weakest target.

### Special Abilities

**Trip (Ex):** Free action on successful bite.

**Species Harmony Resonance (Su):** Wolves register on Kin-sense through species-specific Harmony — distinct from elemental resonance, operating on a biological frequency that Kin perceive as “animal presence” rather than elemental identity. Detectable at 15 feet per wolf; a large pack generates a combined presence detectable at significant range.

### Society

Wolves are Oreka’s most widespread pack-predator — found in every region with sufficient prey-density, from the Great Forest edges to the open steppe. They are natural animals with no supernatural abilities, serving as the ecological baseline against which all other canine creatures (worgs, winter wolves, cù sìth) are measured.

Mytroan steppe-clans have the closest wolf-relationship. Mytroan herding-culture manages wolf predation through territorial understanding rather than extermination — wolf-packs that avoid Mytroan herds are left alone; packs that raid are hunted.

Warg packs maintain complex social relationships with wolf-packs in their territory. Wargs are intelligent; wolves are not. The dynamic is not alliance but coexistence — Wargs occasionally adopt orphaned wolf-pups, and wolf-packs instinctively defer to Warg presence.

### Lore

**DC 10 (Knowledge [nature]):** Wolves are Medium pack-predators found across Oreka. They trip prey through coordinated attacks. Packs of 7–16 are the standard hunting unit.

**DC 15:** Mytroan manage wolf-predation through territorial understanding. Wargs and wolves coexist — Wargs occasionally adopt wolf-pups. Wolf Harmony resonance is the ecological baseline for canine creatures.

# WORG

The wolf is too large, too intelligent, and looking at you with an expression that wolves do not have. Wolves assess threats. This creature is assessing *you* — your armour, your weapons, the way you hold your sword. It understands equipment. It understands threat-hierarchy. And when it speaks — growling, accented Common — it says: “Move. Or I move you.”

**Medium Magical Beast**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Magical Beast |
| **Hit Dice** | 4d10+8 (30 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +2 |
| **Speed** | 50 ft. (10 squares) |
| **Armor Class** | 14 (+2 Dex, +2 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 12 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +4/+7 |
| **Attack** | Bite +7 melee (1d6+4) |
| **Full Attack** | Bite +7 melee (1d6+4) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Trip |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, scent, elemental resonance (wild static — non-Kin intelligence) |
| **Saves** | Fort +6, Ref +6, Will +3 |
| **Abilities** | Str 17, Dex 15, Con 15, Int 6, Wis 14, Cha 10 |
| **Skills** | Hide +4 (4 ranks), Listen +6 (4 ranks), Move Silently +6 (4 ranks), Spot +6 (4 ranks), Survival +4 (4 ranks, +8 tracking by scent) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Track |
| **Elemental Affinity** | Wild Static — worgs are intelligent non-Kin creatures that register on Kin-sense as unreadable presence, the same wild-static signature shared by all non-Kin sapients (goblins, goblinoids, Wargs); recognisable, alive, but not elementally identifiable |
| **Environment** | Any (worgs range across all of Oreka’s temperate and cold regions — Eternal Steppe, Great Forest edges, mountain foothills, and the margins of every settled area) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or pack (6–11) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 2 |
| **Treasure** | 1/10th coins; 50% goods; 50% items |
| **Alignment** | Usually neutral evil |
| **Advancement** | 5–6 HD (Medium); 7–8 HD (Large) |
| **Level Adjustment** | +1 |

### Combat

Worgs fight as intelligent wolves — coordinated pack-tactics, trip attacks, and the ability to communicate and plan. A worg pack does not charge blindly; it flanks, isolates, and overwhelms. Worgs speak Common and Goblin, and occasionally negotiate (demanding food, warning trespassers, or offering to sell information about the territory ahead).

### Special Abilities

**Trip (Ex):** Free action on successful bite.

**Wild Static Resonance (Su):** Worgs register on Kin-sense as wild static — the non-Kin intelligent-creature signature. Detectable at 30 feet. Distinct from wolf Harmony (which is animal-biological) — worg static is the unreadable presence of a sapient mind that exists outside the elemental system.

### Society

Worgs are the intelligent wolf-analogue of Oreka — sapient, language-speaking magical beasts that occupy the ecological and social niche between natural wolves and the Warg people. They are not Wargs (Wargs are a distinct intelligent people with their own culture, settlements, and political structures) but they interact with Warg society as affiliated predators, occasional allies, and permanent neighbours.

Warg packs and worg packs maintain the most complex inter-species relationship of any non-Kin pairing in Oreka. Wargs recognise worgs as kin (lowercase) — related intelligent canines that share the same wild-static resonance and the same territorial instincts. Worg packs that range through Warg territory are tolerated if they respect Warg hunting-rights and avoided if they become aggressive.

Goblin communities use worgs as mounts and war-companions. The goblin-worg relationship is symbiotic: goblins provide hands, tools, and fire; worgs provide speed, strength, and tactical intelligence. Goblin worg-riders are among the most mobile light-cavalry units in Oreka — faster than Mytroan horse-riders in broken terrain and capable of coordinating attacks through shared language.

### Lore

**DC 12 (Knowledge [arcana]):** Worgs are intelligent, speech-capable wolves. They speak Common and Goblin. They fight with pack-tactics and trip attacks. They are not Wargs — they are a separate species.

**DC 17:** Worg-Warg relations are complex — affiliated but not subordinate. Goblin worg-riders are among Oreka’s most mobile light-cavalry. Worg wild-static resonance identifies them as non-Kin sapients.

# WRAITH

The burned city is dark — dark in the way that fire-ruins are dark, the charred beams absorbing torchlight, the collapsed roofs creating pockets of absolute blackness that no flame seems to penetrate. Something moves in the blackness — not a shadow (shadows are passive, projected by light) but something that moves *as* darkness, a shape of concentrated absence that slides between the ruins with deliberate, predatory intent. Where it passes, the air goes cold, and the coldness is not temperature but *meaning* — the warmth of life being pulled away, drawn into something that has none.

**Medium Undead (Incorporeal)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **Size/Type** | Medium Undead (Incorporeal) |
| **Hit Dice** | 5d12 (32 hp) |
| **Initiative** | +7 |
| **Speed** | Fly 60 ft. (good) |
| **Armor Class** | 15 (+3 Dex, +2 deflection), touch 15, flat-footed 12 |
| **Base Attack/Grapple** | +2/— |
| **Attack** | Incorporeal touch +5 melee touch (1d4 plus 1d6 Constitution drain) |
| **Full Attack** | Incorporeal touch +5 melee touch (1d4 plus 1d6 Constitution drain) |
| **Space/Reach** | 5 ft./5 ft. |
| **Special Attacks** | Constitution drain, create spawn |
| **Special Qualities** | Darkvision 60 ft., daylight powerlessness, incorporeal traits, +2 turn resistance, undead traits, unnatural aura, elemental resonance (none — fire-grief, burned absence) |
| **Saves** | Fort +1, Ref +4, Will +6 |
| **Abilities** | Str —, Dex 16, Con —, Int 14, Wis 14, Cha 15 |
| **Skills** | Diplomacy +6 (5 ranks), Hide +11 (5 ranks), Intimidate +10 (5 ranks), Listen +12 (5 ranks), Search +10 (5 ranks), Spot +12 (5 ranks), Survival +10 (5 ranks) |
| **Feats** | Alertness, Blind-Fight, Improved Initiative |
| **Elemental Affinity** | None — a wraith’s resonance is burned absence, the elemental signature of fire-death — not the extinguished-fire of the Ashen Hollow spectres but the *burned-away* identity of creatures that died in fire, their elemental connections consumed along with their bodies |
| **Environment** | Burned Cities (the fire-ruined settlements, razed towns, and burned-out strongholds scattered across Oreka — specifically the Reckoning-era burned cities of the Kinsweave and Tidebloom Reach, where the Dómnathar’s surface campaigns used fire as a primary destruction-tool, and where the mass fire-death produced concentrations of wraith-spawning energy) |
| **Organization** | Solitary, pair, or gang (3–5 wraiths, sometimes led by 1 dread wraith) |
| **Challenge Rating** | 5 |
| **Treasure** | None |
| **Alignment** | Always lawful evil |
| **Advancement** | 6–10 HD (Medium) |
| **Level Adjustment** | — |

### Combat

A wraith is an incorporeal Constitution-drain predator — faster and more aggressive than a shadow, less powerful than a spectre. Its incorporeal touch drains 1d6 Constitution (DC 14 Fortitude save negates), and any humanoid killed by the drain rises as a wraith under the killer’s control in 1d4 rounds.

Wraiths fight from the air (fly 60 ft.), pass through walls and barriers, and target the weakest-Constitution party members first (the fastest kill, the quickest spawn). Daylight renders them powerless — wraiths caught in sunlight cannot attack and flee.

### Special Abilities

**Constitution Drain (Su):** Incorporeal touch drains 1d6 Constitution (DC 14 Fortitude negates). On each successful drain, the wraith gains 5 temporary hit points. The save DC is Charisma-based.

**Create Spawn (Su):** Any humanoid killed by a wraith’s Constitution drain rises as a wraith 1d4 rounds later under the control of the wraith that created it.

**Daylight Powerlessness (Ex):** Helpless in natural sunlight; flees at full speed.

**Unnatural Aura (Su):** Animals within 30 feet panic.

**Burned Absence Resonance (Su):** A wraith registers on Kin-sense as fire-death — elemental identity consumed by flame, leaving a charred void where resonance should be. Detectable at 30 feet. Distinct from the spectre’s extinguished-fire (which is grief) — a wraith’s resonance is *destruction*, the aftermath of elemental connections burned away. Eruskan who have entered Reckoning-era ruins describe wraith resonance as “standing in a house that remembers burning.”

### Society

Wraiths in Oreka are concentrated in the burned cities of the Reckoning — the settlements destroyed by Dómnathar surface campaigns during the Deceivers’ War, where fire was used as a primary weapon and the mass fire-death of civilian populations produced the specific metaphysical conditions that generate wraiths.

The Kinsweave border-kingdoms contain the highest density of wraith-haunted ruins. The razed towns and burned-out strongholds of the Reckoning are listed on civic maps as exclusion zones, marked with warning-posts, and avoided after dark. Kinsweave community-watches maintain night-patrols specifically to detect wraith incursion from nearby ruins.

Tidebloom Reach’s drowned villages — Hillmeet and Foxfen — harbour both wraiths and dread wraiths, a combination that makes the ruins among the most dangerous undead sites in Oreka.

The relationship between wraiths and the dread wraiths that sometimes lead them is hierarchical: dread wraiths control wraith-gangs of 3–5, using them as expendable scouts and first-wave attackers while the dread wraith targets high-value opponents.

### Lore

**DC 15 (Knowledge [religion]):** Wraiths are incorporeal undead that drain Constitution. Humanoids killed by wraiths rise as new wraiths. Daylight renders them helpless. They are most common in fire-ruined settlements.

**DC 20:** Wraith resonance is burned absence — fire-death that consumed elemental identity. Kinsweave border-kingdoms maintain exclusion zones around Reckoning-era ruins. Dread wraiths lead wraith-gangs.

**DC 25:** Wraiths are specifically a product of mass fire-death — the Dómnathar’s use of fire during the Reckoning created the conditions for wraith-generation. Tidebloom’s Hillmeet and Foxfen harbour combined wraith and dread wraith populations.

# WYVERN

The shape in the sky resolves as it banks — two legs, two wings, a barbed tail longer than its body, and a head that is all jaw and no subtlety. It is not a dragon. It does not have a dragon’s intelligence, a dragon’s breath, or a dragon’s treasure-hoard ambition. What it has is a tail-stinger loaded with enough venom to drop a horse, a wingspan that lets it carry that horse into the sky, and the single-minded predatory focus of a creature that has identified you as the right size for dinner.

**Large Dragon**

